584,2,C002_S1.txt,0,Supplemental Information for “Codebook LLMs: Evaluating LLMs as Measurement Tools for Political Science Concepts” Andrew Halterman (Michigan State University) Katherine A.
585,2,C002_S1.txt,1,Keith (Williams College) A Glossary for Applied Researchers We direct applied researchers to Grimmer et al.
586,2,C002_S1.txt,2,(2022)’s textbook for general and technical overviews of the text-as-data ﬁeld.
587,2,C002_S1.txt,3,"In this glossary section, we deﬁne terms related to our work and LLMs that may not be present in Grimmer et al. or new to applied readers. • Ablation: A evaluation approach where components of a system are removed one at a time to understand their contribution."
588,2,C002_S1.txt,4,"In the context of our codebook ablation, we can remove (ablate) one component at a time (e.g., the Negative Clariﬁcation)."
589,2,C002_S1.txt,5,We re-run the entire prediction step with the ablated codebook and check the performance.
590,2,C002_S1.txt,6,A decrease in performance compared to the full-codebook baseline indicates that the abalated component is important for good performance. • Adaptation/Low-rank Adaptation (LoRA) : A technique for e!ciently updating large language models for new tasks.
591,2,C002_S1.txt,7,"Rather than modifying all of a model’s parameters (which could be billions of parameters), LoRA approximates these changes using smaller matrices."
592,2,C002_S1.txt,8,"As an analogy, think about how singular value decomposition approximates a large matrix with two smaller matrices."
593,2,C002_S1.txt,9,"Similarly, the full weight matrix is decomposed into two smaller matrices."
594,2,C002_S1.txt,10,"In the case of Mistral 7B, our rank 16 LoRa has only 0.5% of the weights of the full weight matrix."
595,2,C002_S1.txt,11,"During training, the weights in the full weight matrix remain unchanged–only the weights in the “low rank” approximation of the weights are updated."
596,2,C002_S1.txt,12,"At inference time, the low rank matrices are multiplied by the full weight matrix."
597,2,C002_S1.txt,13,(2022). • Self-Attention: A mechanism introduced in the Transformer architecture of Vaswani et al.
598,2,C002_S1.txt,14,(2017) and thus a key component in LLMs.
599,2,C002_S1.txt,15,"For each self-attention layer and head and for each token (typically a word), the model computes three vectors—a query, key, and value—and uses these to calculate “attention weights” that determine how much each other token inﬂuences 27 the current token’s representation (embedding)."
600,2,C002_S1.txt,16,"These weights are computed as normalized dot products between query and key vectors, then used to create a weighted sum of value vectors."
601,2,C002_S1.txt,17,"The main text discusses previous empirical results that LLMs attend more to words at the beginning or end of the prompt, putting less weight on words in the middle. • Classiﬁcation Head : An additional component added to BERT-style models to perform classiﬁcation tasks (Devlin et al., 2019)."
602,2,C002_S1.txt,18,"While the base BERT model learns (via pretraining) contextual representations of text, and the classiﬁcation head is a smaller (logistic regression) model that takes BERT’s text representations and converts them into speciﬁc class predictions."
603,2,C002_S1.txt,19,This is similar to how one might ﬁrst create features from text (like topic model scores) and then use those features in a logistic regression for classiﬁcation.
604,2,C002_S1.txt,20,The classiﬁcation head is typically trained along with the main model to predict numerical class labels (like 0 or 1). • F ew-shot: An approach where the model sees a small number of examples before making predictions.
605,2,C002_S1.txt,21,"In the context of LLMs, few-shot learning typically occurs through “in-context learning”, where examples are included in the prompt rather than used to update the model’s parameters."
606,2,C002_S1.txt,22,This is similar to showing a human coder several correctly coded examples along- side the codebook before asking them to code new documents.
607,2,C002_S1.txt,23,This di”ers from traditional machine learning approaches where models are updated using training examples.
608,2,C002_S1.txt,24,"(2020). • Lexical Overlap Heuristics : A heuristic (or “shortcut”) observed in some LLMs, where they make predictions based on matching words rather than “understanding” meaning."
609,2,C002_S1.txt,25,"For example, a model might label any text containing the word “protest” as a protest event with- out considering context."
610,2,C002_S1.txt,26,This is a familiar problem with dictionary-based approach that can misclassify texts by matching words without understanding their usage.
611,2,C002_S1.txt,27,(2023). • instruction tuning : A method for adapting language models to better follow speciﬁc instruc- tions by training them on examples of tasks paired with instructions.
612,2,C002_S1.txt,28,"Instead of training the model to simply predict the next word in a piece of text or to classify inputs into predeﬁned categories (like in traditional supervised learning), instruction tuning teaches the model to generate appropriate responses to instructions."
613,2,C002_S1.txt,29,"In our context, this means training the model to read a codebook and document, then generate the correct category label as text."
614,2,C002_S1.txt,30,We point readers to Wang et al.
615,2,C002_S1.txt,31,(2023) (which we found to be one of the more accessible instruction 28 tuning papers). • Language Modeling Objective/Loss : The usual objective/loss function for training LLMs.
616,2,C002_S1.txt,32,"The LLM predicts the next word in a sequence, the predicted token is compared to the true next token, and the model’s parameters to improve these predictions."
617,2,C002_S1.txt,33,The “loss” measures how far o” the model’s predictions are from the correct next word.
618,2,C002_S1.txt,34,"This is similar to how regression models are trained by minimizing the squared distance between predictions and ac- tual values, but instead of predicting continuous numbers, language models predict probability distributions over possible next words. • Quantization: A technique for compressing the numerical precision of a model to make it smaller in memory."
619,2,C002_S1.txt,35,"Instead of storing numbers with high precision (like 2.493827), quantization might round them to simpler values (like 2.5)."
620,2,C002_S1.txt,36,This reduces memory and computational requirements while maintaining most of the model’s performance.
621,2,C002_S1.txt,37,(2024). • W eights: The numerical parameters in a language model.
622,2,C002_S1.txt,38,These weights are adjusted dur- ing training (both pretraining or ﬁnetuning) to improve the model’s performance.
623,2,C002_S1.txt,39,"This is analogous to how the coe!cients in a regression model are optimized to minimize prediction error. • Zero-shot: Describes when an LLM makes predictions using only the input prompt, without seeing any examples (that is zero labeled examples)."
624,2,C002_S1.txt,40,"In our case, this means giving the model just the codebook deﬁnitions and asking it to classify documents."
625,2,C002_S1.txt,41,This is analogous to giving a human coder only a codebook and asking them to begin coding immediately (given their previous experience and no background).
626,2,C002_S1.txt,42,B Ethics We acknowledge the real-world harm associated with the events reported in the documents in the datasets we use.
627,2,C002_S1.txt,43,"We believe quantitative study of these events is important to mitigate future harm, but we also acknowledge that it should be paired with qualitative work, hopefully that which also connects with and advocates for the people a”ected by the events (D’Ignazio & Klein, 2020)."
628,2,C002_S1.txt,44,"We also acknowledge that all our results focus on English-language codebooks and text documents (Bender, 2019)."
629,2,C002_S1.txt,45,"Our conclusions may not hold on non-English language texts. 29 Justiﬁable concerns exist about the use of LLMs, speciﬁcally their environmental cost and the provenance of their training data."
630,2,C002_S1.txt,46,"Given the lack of transparency in LLM pretraining data (see Section F), we cannot know the exact mix of text in the pretraining data."
631,2,C002_S1.txt,47,The question of whether pretraining LLMs on copyrighted text is fair use is an open question that we hope for more clarity on.
632,2,C002_S1.txt,48,The (marginal) CO 2 costs from using pretrained LLMs is also a concern.
633,2,C002_S1.txt,49,All experiments were conducted on a server with a single Nvidia RTX 4090 with 24GB of VRAM.
634,2,C002_S1.txt,50,Using a generous estimate of 200 hours of GPU compute time and an emission factor of 0.50 kg/kWh yields an estimated 40kg of emitted CO 2 from our experiments.
635,2,C002_S1.txt,51,"This is slightly less than the CO 2 emitted by an average internal combustion vehicle making two Ann Arbor–East Lansing round trips (Lacoste et al., 2019)."
636,2,C002_S1.txt,52,"C Comparison with NLP/CS tasks Here, we provide more details for readers interested in the NLP/computer science literature on how the codebook measurement task di”ers from existing techniques and datasets in NLP/CS."
637,2,C002_S1.txt,53,"C.1 Machine Reading Comprehension In NLP, the closest task to our codebook task is machine reading comprehension , also known as question answering ."
638,2,C002_S1.txt,54,The task of machine reading comprehension presents text passages to NLP models and then requires the models to answer questions about the passages.
639,2,C002_S1.txt,55,"Popular machine reading comprehension datasets include Stanford Question Answering Dataset (SQuAD) (Rajpurkar et al., 2016) and SQuAD 2.0 (Rajpurkar et al., 2018) which consist of hun- dreds of thousands of Wikipedia-based question-answer pairs."
640,2,C002_S1.txt,56,The answer to every question is an extractive span (a segment of text from the text passage).
641,2,C002_S1.txt,57,Other variants of machine reading com- prehension datasets require models to answer questions about news articles (Trischler et al.
642,2,C002_S1.txt,58,"(2017)’s NewsQA), ﬁnd and reason over multiple supporting documents to answer questions (Yang et al."
643,2,C002_S1.txt,59,"(2018)’s HotPotQA), or contain questions derived from Google search users’ queries (Kwiatkowski et al."
644,2,C002_S1.txt,60,"In contrast with our codebook task, machine reading comprehension questions are usually factoid 30 questions (general world knowledge) or extractive questions (a simple question whose answer is a direct quote from the provided passage), not questions constrained by context-speciﬁc deﬁnitions crafted by domain experts in codebooks."
645,2,C002_S1.txt,61,"Our work builds on these NLP literatures, but is distin- guished from previous work by our focus on codebook-speciﬁc constructs and requiring reasoning over both long documents and long codebook instructions with many categories."
646,2,C002_S1.txt,62,"C.2 LLM Benchmarks New generative LLMs, especially instruction tuned LLMs, are evaluated on a small set of widely used benchmark datasets."
647,2,C002_S1.txt,63,"MMLU (Massive Multitask Language Understanding, Hendrycks et al."
648,2,C002_S1.txt,64,(2021)) asks multiple choice questions covering a range of academic and professional domains.
649,2,C002_S1.txt,65,"Good performance requires rea- soning and knowledge, but the instructions/questions are concise and do not require reasoning over complex instructions or long passages, as our task requires."
650,2,C002_S1.txt,66,"IFEval (Instruction-Following Evaluation, Zhou et al."
651,2,C002_S1.txt,67,"(2023)) measures the ability of LLMs to comply with very speciﬁc instructions about their output (e.g., limiting the response to a set number of words, using bullet points in the response, answering only in lowercase, etc.)."
652,2,C002_S1.txt,68,"This benchmark is a useful test of LLM compliance, which we identify as a key limitation for current models in carrying out the codebook measurement task."
653,2,C002_S1.txt,69,"However, the benchmark does not evaluate the ability of LLMs to reason over long, detailed instructions in the face of ambiguity."
654,2,C002_S1.txt,70,"ARC (AI2 Reasoning Challenge, Clark et al."
655,2,C002_S1.txt,71,"(2018)) asks multiple choice questions about grade- school-level science, requiring subject matter knowledge and limited reasoning."
656,2,C002_S1.txt,72,"However, it does not require the LLM to interpret complex instructions."
657,2,C002_S1.txt,73,"GPQA (Graduate-Level Google-Proof Q&A benchmark, Rein et al."
658,2,C002_S1.txt,74,(2023)) asks very di!cult ques- tions written by domain experts in STEM that are challenging even for PhDs in the ﬁeld.
659,2,C002_S1.txt,75,"They require careful domain-speciﬁc reasoning, but the questions are relatively straightforward and do not require long-context reasoning."
660,2,C002_S1.txt,76,"ZeroScrolls (Shaham et al., 2023) is a collection of tasks that require reasoning over long contexts, including long document summarization and question-answering that involves multi-step reasoning over multiple paragraphs."
661,2,C002_S1.txt,77,"Long context reasoning is an important aspect of the codebook mea- 31 surement task, but our task also requires attention to long, complex instructions, which this set of evaluations does not directly measure."
662,2,C002_S1.txt,78,Performance on math and coding benchmarks is less relevant to our codebook measurement tasks and we omit a discussion of the standard benchmarks here.
663,2,C002_S1.txt,79,"D Further illustration of codebook-LLM measurement Here, we provide a second example to motivate the codebook-LLM measurement tasks."
664,2,C002_S1.txt,80,Asking an LLM to label whether a news story describes a “protest” invites potential measurement prob- lems.
665,2,C002_S1.txt,81,"While all deﬁnitions of protests include a shared core (claim-making or demands for political or social change outside of formal political channels), speciﬁc projects use di”erent deﬁnitions of protests, categorize protests at varying levels of granularity, and apply di”erent exclusion criteria."
666,2,C002_S1.txt,82,"For example, the BFRS dataset on political violence in Pakistan (Bueno de Mesquita et al., 2015) excludes all non-violent protests, while making a distinction between a “riot” and a “violent po- litical demonstration”."
667,2,C002_S1.txt,83,"In contrast, the common automated event data ontology CAMEO (Gerner et al., 2002) collapses these two into a single “riot” category, while also coding other non-violent protest tactics."
668,2,C002_S1.txt,84,"CAMEO excludes resignations and complaints by elites as a form of protest, while the Electoral Contestation and Violence (ECA V) dataset (Daxecker et al., 2019), which focuses ex- clusively on subnational protests in the context of elections, includes these as protests."
669,2,C002_S1.txt,85,Applying these di”erent operationalizations of “protest” to the same corpus should not produce the same measurements.
670,2,C002_S1.txt,86,D.1 Dataset preprocessing We make several changes to the original datasets as part of our preprocessing pipeline.
671,2,C002_S1.txt,87,The original news stories used to code the BFRS dataset from the English-language Dawn newspaper in Pak- istan were not obtainable.
672,2,C002_S1.txt,88,"Instead, we rely on the short, free-text English language summary of the event written by annotators that is provided in the structured BFRS dataset."
673,2,C002_S1.txt,89,"In most cases, using the hand-written summary makes the task easier, as the summary focuses on the main event corresponding to the gold-standard label. 4 4In some cases, the summary omits details that are necessary for determining the true label."
674,2,C002_S1.txt,90,"However, in Table 5, we ﬁnd this is not a major concern in practice; only 4% of our BFRS sample lacked the necessary context. 32 The CCC dataset provides hyperlinks to the sources used to code each event. 5 We obtain the original English language source text using a scraper provided by (Halterman & Radford, 2021)."
675,2,C002_S1.txt,91,"To make the dataset comparable to the other two datasets, we limit their corpus to events that have (1) a single event type, and (2) a single news source."
676,2,C002_S1.txt,92,"Omitting stories with multiple event types yields a single-label classiﬁcation task that matches the other two datasets, while limited to events with a single source avoids the need for the LLM to perform a challenging cross-document inference task."
677,2,C002_S1.txt,93,We also omit events where the original text is not obtainable via the scraper.
678,2,C002_S1.txt,94,We obtain the labeled Manifesto quasi-sentences from the Manifesto Project through their API 6.
679,2,C002_S1.txt,95,"In total, the Manifesto Project provides more than 1 million labeled quasi-sentences across several dozen languages."
680,2,C002_S1.txt,96,"The Manifesto Project employs a large team of extensively trained native language speakers to annotate each quasi-sentence in each manifesto (Merz et al., 2016)."
681,2,C002_S1.txt,97,"For this work, we use a sample of 13 manifestos from English-speaking countries."
682,2,C002_S1.txt,98,"BFRS and CCC both label standalone, complete news stories, while Manifesto passages are often sub-sentence fragments (quasi-sentences)."
683,2,C002_S1.txt,99,Prototype manual analysis of LLM errors revealed that identifying the correct label for some Manifesto passages was impossible without context from the preceding passes.
684,2,C002_S1.txt,100,"Thus, in our empirical pipeline, we input the Manifestos’ target quasi-sentence (which is labeled) as well as the quasi-sentence just prior to the target one as context."
685,2,C002_S1.txt,101,"D.2 Contamination insulation Contamination of evaluation datasets—when an evaluation dataset is part of the LLMs training data and thus does not adequately represent generalization performance on an unseen set of examples—is a major concern in NLP research (Balloccu et al., 2024; Golchin & Surdeanu, 2024; Li & Flanigan, 2024; “Speak, Memory: An Archaeology of Books Known to ChatGPT/GPT-4”, n.d., inter alia )."
686,2,C002_S1.txt,102,"We believe that our datasets are insulated from contamination, that is, they are unlikely to appear in their complete form in LLM pre-training or instruction tuning data."
687,2,C002_S1.txt,103,The BFRS dataset is not available online and was provided directly to us by the authors of the dataset.
688,2,C002_S1.txt,104,"The structured CCC dataset includes hyperlinks to the sources used, but not the raw text."
689,2,C002_S1.txt,105,"Instead, we scrape the original news stories, where available, and combine them with the structured data."
690,2,C002_S1.txt,106,"The Manifesto corpus is the most at risk of training contamination, though we note that it has the lowest performance 5https://github.com/nonviolent-action-lab/crowd-counting-consortium 6urlhttps://manifesto-project.wzb.eu/information/documents/api 33 Class Precision Recall F1-score Support CARA V AN 0.17 0.50 0.25 2 DEMONSTRATION 0.02 0.18 0.04 17 MARCH 0.60 0.22 0.32 109 PROTEST 0.77 0.79 0.78 647 RALLY 0.61 0.41 0.49 232 Macro avg 0.35 0.34 0.32 1009 Weighted avg 0.70 0.63 0.65 1009 Table SI 1: Zero-shot performance of Mistral-7B on the development set of CCC (new codebook format)."
691,2,C002_S1.txt,107,"Here, “support” is the number of examples in the development set."
692,2,C002_S1.txt,108,"The original manifestos and the Manifesto Project codebook (Version 2020a from July 22, 2020) are available on the internet and likely to present in the LLM pre-training data, but the sentence-level annotations are provided through an API that requires registration."
693,2,C002_S1.txt,109,"E Detailed zero-shot results In Tables SI 1, SI 2, and SI 3, we provide per-class performance and support information for the three datasets in the zero-shot condition."
694,2,C002_S1.txt,110,"For space, we include only results for Mistral-7B."
695,2,C002_S1.txt,111,"F LLM details Here, we provide greater justiﬁcation of our choice of the four LLMs we examine, along with other parameters we experimented with."
696,2,C002_S1.txt,112,"Because the landscape and performance of LLMs is constantly changing, we select four well performing open-weight LLMs between 7 billion and 12 billion pa- rameters."
697,2,C002_S1.txt,113,Our purpose in the paper is to demonstrate our framework for using and evaluating LLMs to conduct codebook-based measurement.
698,2,C002_S1.txt,114,"We want to ensure that our framework is general- izable to multiple models, but we re-emphasize that our objective is not to identify a single “best” LLM."
699,2,C002_S1.txt,115,"We intentionally choose“local” LLMs, whose weights can be downloaded to a local machine and updated."
700,2,C002_S1.txt,116,"In our conception, “local” involves both open weights, but also a model small enough to run on a commodity GPU."
701,2,C002_S1.txt,117,"Others have emphasized the importance of local models for scientiﬁc research and how local models are reproducible in a way that “closed”, API-based models which are constantly changing and do not have version control (e.g., ChatGPT) are not (Palmer et al., 2024; 34"
702,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,0,"Multi-Perspective LLM Annotations for Valid Analyses in Subjective Tasks Navya Mehrotra⋆ Johns Hopkins University nmehrot2@jh.edu Adam Visokay⋆ University of Washington avisokay@uw.edu Kristina Gligori ´c Johns Hopkins University gligoric@jhu.edu Abstract Large language models are increasingly used to annotate texts, but their outputs reflect some human perspectives better than others."
703,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,1,Exist- ing methods for correcting LLM annotation error assume a single ground truth.
704,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,2,"However, this assumption fails in subjective tasks where disagreement across demographic groups is meaningful."
705,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,3,"Here we introduce PERSPECTIVE- DRIVENINFERENCE, a method that treats the distribution of annotations across groups as the quantity of interest, and estimates it using a small human annotation budget."
706,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,4,We contribute an adaptive sampling strategy that concentrates human annotation effort on groups where LLM proxies are least accurate.
707,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,5,"We evaluate on po- liteness and offensiveness rating tasks, showing targeted improvements for harder-to-model de- mographic groups relative to uniform sampling baselines, while maintaining coverage. 1 Introduction LLMs are promising tools for reducing annota- tion burden in computational social science (CSS) (Ziems et al., 2024; Manning et al., 2024)."
708,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,6,"Yet, LLM annotations can be wrong (Dillion et al., 2023), encode particular positionalities (Santy et al., 2023), and reproduce stereotypes (Shrawgi et al., 2024)."
709,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,7,"Methods like Prediction-Powered Inference (An- gelopoulos et al., 2023a) and design-based su- pervised learning (Egami et al., 2023) offer a re- pair (Hullman et al., 2026), addressing these limi- tations by combining potentially inaccurate LLM proxies with a small set of ground truth human labels, yielding valid downstream inference even when the LLM proxy is imperfect."
710,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,8,"However, these repair methods assume a ground truth exists."
711,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,9,"In many CSS settings, ground truth ⋆Equal contribution. does not exist."
712,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,10,"Reasonable people disagree about whether language is toxic, empathetic, or polite, and that disagreement is not error to be corrected, but a signal to be preserved."
713,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,11,Collapsing annotator disagreement into a majority label discards the very variation that matters for understanding how people use and perceive language.
714,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,12,"A common method to address is persona prompt- ing (Truong et al., 2025): conditioning LLMs on demographic attributes to simulate the perspectives of specific groups."
715,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,13,"However, persona prompting does not always improve performance of large lan- guage models (Zheng et al., 2024; Sun et al., 2025): it can exaggerate group differences (Cheng et al., 2023), misrepresent minority viewpoints (Wang et al., 2025a), and in many settings performs no better than a generic prompt (Zheng et al., 2024; Sun et al., 2025; Xu and Jurgens, 2026)."
716,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,14,"Here, we introduce PERSPECTIVE-DRIVENIN- FERENCE, a framework for valid corpus inference in subjective annotation tasks where no single ground truth exists (illustrated in Figure 1)."
717,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,15,"Our goal is not to train LLMs to make more accurate predictions, but to leverage their annotations to con- duct robust downstream statistical inference that faithfully retains annotator disagreement."
718,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,16,"Framework.We formalize multi-perspective corpus inference as estimation of a vector es- timand (one entry per demographic group), rather than a single scalar, and show how stan- dard PPI-based correction extends to this set- ting. 2."
719,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,17,"Sampling method.We develop a sampling strategy that concentrates the human annota- tion budget on demographic groups for which LLM annotations are predicted to be less reli- able, with the goal of improving inference for underrepresented or poorly modeled perspec- tives. arXiv:2603.21404v1 [cs.CL] 22 Mar 2026 Corpus with n texts Estimate Θ* = (Θ*g1, ..., Θ*gk) 1."
720,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,18,Collect LLM annotations Ĥᵢ for all n (zero/few-shot/persona) 2.
721,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,19,Burn-in uniform sampling collect initial human annotations Hᵢ at random 3.
722,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,20,"Adaptive loop Predict LLM error (Ĥᵢ − Hᵢ)² from  demographic features Sample and collect next human  annotations Hᵢ, across groups Make estimates IPW correction and Θ* per group iterate Figure 1:Overview of the PERSPECTIVE-DRIVENINFERENCE.Starting from a corpus of n texts, we collect LLM annotations, initialize human annotation via uniform sampling, and then enter an adaptive loop that predicts LLM error from demographic features, sampling human annotations across groups."
723,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,21,The core idea is to prioritize human annotation for texts where LLMs poorly represent the target demographic group.
724,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,22,"Once the annotation budget is exhausted, we apply inverse probability weighting (IPW) to produce group-level estimatesθ ∗. 3."
725,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,23,"Evaluation.We evaluate PERSPECTIVE- DRIVENINFERENCEon three datasets: polite- ness ratings, offensiveness ratings, and syn- thetic binary annotations, finding improved accuracy for targeted demographic groups, while maintaining coverage. 2 Background Annotators’ backgroundA growing body of NLP literature views annotation disagreement not as noise, but valuable signal (Uma et al., 2021; Hovy, 2015)."
726,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,24,"Prior work has shown considerable heterogeneity in annotator preferences on subjec- tive tasks, ranging from toxicity (Sap et al., 2022) and sexism detection (Tahaei and Bergler, 2024), to theory of mind modeling (Fan et al., 2025) and counterspeech generation (Mun et al., 2024), with demographic axes like gender (Biester et al., 2022) and race (Lee et al., 2024) shifting annotations sys- tematically (Al Kuwatly et al., 2020)."
727,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,25,"Modeling this disagreement explicitly, rather than collaps- ing it into majority vote, has become a concern in NLP (Fleisig et al., 2023; Xu and Jurgens, 2026; Xu et al., 2025)."
728,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,26,"Recent efforts push toward char- acterizing how demographic factors shape human preferences in LLM outputs (Movva et al., 2025; Wang et al., 2025b; Chen et al., 2025), and using that understanding to build systems that represent multiple perspectives (Sorensen et al., 2020; Feng et al., 2024; Röttger et al., 2022)."
729,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,27,"What is different about our work is that we ask: how can we effi- ciently leverage limited budgets of human input, given that models do not capture different perspec- tives equally well (Sen et al., 2025; Santurkar et al., 2023)?"
730,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,28,"In doing so, our goal is not to use LLMs to make better predictions, but to use LLM anno- tations as inputs to downstream analyses, while preserving diverse perspectives on subjective tasks."
731,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,29,"Valid inference with proxy annotationsCorpus- level inference from text has roots in literary anal- ysis (Yavuz, 2019) and causal inference in NLP (Feder et al., 2022)."
732,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,30,"Early work formalized the task of inferring document class prevalence under un- certainty (Keith and O’Connor, 2018)."
733,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,31,"A separate thread examined whether annotations themselves are valid (Valentino et al., 2021; Ruder et al., 2025), and how annotation error and genuine label vari- ation can be disentangled (Weber-Genzel et al., 2024; Baledent et al., 2022)."
734,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,32,"More recent work in CSS turns to downstream inference under annota- tion imperfection, using LLM outputs as surrogates for human labels and developing statistically rig- orous methods for correction (Wang et al., 2020; Egami et al., 2023; Angelopoulos et al., 2023b)."
735,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,33,"We contribute to this line of work by complicating the assumption that a ground truth exists at all: in subjective tasks, disagreement is constitutive, and we show how these repair methods apply in settings where no single correct label can be defined, and the target estimand is a vector, rather than a scalar."
736,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,34,"Adaptive samplingActive learning methods re- duce annotation cost by selecting the most informa- tive instances for labeling (Baldridge and Osborne, 2004; Arora et al., 2009), with established tools to support these workflows (Lin et al., 2019; Tsvigun et al., 2022; Nghiem and Ananiadou, 2018)."
737,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,35,"Work in the multi-annotator setting specifically targets instances where annotators are likely to disagree (Baumler et al., 2023), and recent methods allo- cate annotation effort between humans and LLMs based on uncertainty (Li et al., 2023; Rouzegar and Makrehchi, 2024; Zhang et al., 2023)."
738,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,36,"Most related to our approach is sampling based on LLM anno- tation confidence (Gligoric et al., 2025), and strati- fied PPI (Fisch et al., 2024), which improves infer- ence efficiency by partitioning samples into strata."
739,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,37,"In contrast, our stratification is alongperspectives rather than strata with data subsets: we sample human annotators to cover the distribution of view- points, not to reduce label uncertainty around a single ground truth. 3 Methods 3.1 Problem setup We have a corpus of n independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.) text instances T1, . . . , Tn."
740,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,38,"We consider aperspective-awaresetup: each instance is annotated by multiple annotators, each coming from a particular perspective."
741,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,39,"Specifically, each ob- servation is a (text, annotator) pair (Ti, di), where di ∈ D encodes the demographic profile of the annotator (e.g., gender, race, age, education level)."
742,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,40,The human annotation Hi therefore captures the judgment of an annotator with demographics di on text Ti.
743,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,41,Note that we focus on demographic fea- tures as a proof of concept.
744,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,42,"In principle, di features could include any axis along which human per- spectives vary, informed by theoretical background knowledge, or exploratory analyses."
745,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,43,"We partition annotators into K demographic groups G={g 1, . . . , gK}."
746,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,44,"We wish to estimate avectorof group-specific quantities θ∗ = (θ∗ g1, . . . , θ∗ gK), where each θ∗ gk =E[H i |d i ∈g k] is the ex- pected annotation value within demographic group gk, i.e., the group mean."
747,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,45,"Note that, beyond the group means, the framework applies for standard statistics such as group medians or regression coef- ficients (Angelopoulos et al., 2023b)."
748,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,46,"For instance, θ∗ gk can be the fraction of texts rated as polite by annotators in group gk, or their mean perceived offensiveness rating."
749,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,47,Estimating θ∗ separately per group reveals how a quantity of interest differs across demographic perspectives.
750,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,48,"In addition to human annotations, we have ac- cess to LLM annotations ˆHi for all n instances."
751,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,49,These serve as a cheap but potentially inaccurate proxy for human judgments.
752,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,50,We define theLLM errorfor instanceias( ˆHi −H i)2.
753,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,51,"Our goal is to estimate θ∗ with a valid confi- dence interval at a pre-specified level(1−α) , us- ing only nhuman ≪n human annotations in total."
754,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,52,"Two challenges make this goal difficult: (i) rare demographic groups are likely to receive too few annotations under uniform sampling, yielding im- precise group-level estimates; and (ii) LLM anno- tations may be systematically biased for certain demographic perspectives. 3.2 Perspective-driven inference To overcome these challenges, we combine LLM annotations withadaptivesampling of human an- notations, to produce an unbiased estimate ˆθPDI of each θ∗ gk, together with a valid confidence interval."
755,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,53,"The adaptive design concentrates the human an- notation budget on demographic groups for which LLM annotations areleast reliable, improving pre- cision for poorly-modeled groups."
756,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,54,"Adaptive sampling ruleWe collect a human an- notation Hi for observation (Ti, di) with probabil- ity πi."
757,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,55,Let ξi =1{H i collected} denote the corre- sponding indicator.
758,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,56,"Motivated by active inference (Zrnic and Candès, 2024; Gligoric et al., 2025), we set πi ∝derri(di), normalized so thatPn i=1 πi =n human."
759,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,57,The func- tion derri is a black-box predictor of the LLM squared error trained on annotator demographics.
760,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,58,"Crucially, Hi is unknown before annotation, so π∗ i is not directly measurable."
761,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,59,"Instead, we approxi- mate it by learning a predictor of the LLM error from annotator demographic features."
762,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,60,"As annotations are collected, we use{(dj,( ˆHj − Hj)2)}j<i, ξj =1 as feature–label pairs to fit derri via a black-box classifier (gradient-boosted regres- sion tree, XGBoost)."
763,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,61,"That is, we train a model to predict the squared LLM error from the annota- tor’s demographic profile, and then allocate human annotations to groups with high predicted error."
764,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,62,"To bootstrap the sampling rule, we first collect nburnin annotations uniformly at random (referred to as theburn-inphase)."
765,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,63,"Within each batch b, we normalize the predicted errors into a discrete probability vector, and smooth it with the uniform distribution over the batch to prevent zero-probability allocations."
766,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,64,We refinederri after each batch using all annotations collected so far.
767,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,65,"Perspective-driven estimatorAfter collecting human annotations according to πi, we estimate each group mean θ∗ gk via an inverse-probability- weighted (IPW) rectified estimator (Appendix, Sec."
768,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,66,"We form a valid (1−α) -level confidence interval for each θ∗ gk via bootstrap (Zrnic and Can- dès, 2024). 3.3 Baselines LLM only (zero-shot)This baseline prompts the LLM with the task description and text Ti di- rectly, with no examples, and treats the resulting annotation as ground truth."
769,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,67,"No human annota- tion budget is required, but the estimate may be biased if the LLM misrepresents certain demo- graphic perspectives, or is inaccurate, depending on which demographics LLMs default to during annotation (Schäfer et al., 2025)."
770,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,68,LLM only (few-shot)This baseline augments the zero-shot prompt with a small number of ran- domly chosen labeled examples.
771,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,69,"The few-shot ex- amples may improve accuracy relative to zero-shot prompting, but demographic bias can persist."
772,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,70,LLM only (persona prompt)This baseline in- structs the LLM to adopt a specific demographic persona before annotating.
773,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,71,"Persona prompting is designed to steer the LLM toward a particular de- mographic perspective, but fidelity to that perspec- tive is not guaranteed."
774,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,72,"PPI (uniform sampling)This baseline uses the same rectified estimator as PDI but collects human annotationsuniformly at randomrather than adap- tively, i.e., πi =n human/n for all i."
775,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,73,It is a special case of ˆθPDI with uniform πi and optimally chosen λ.
776,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,74,"Since uniform sampling ignores group mem- bership, minority demographic groups may receive few annotations."
777,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,75,This baseline corresponds to the estimator of Angelopoulos et al.
778,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,76,"For both PPI and PDI, for each model, we use the LLM variant (zero-shot, few-shot, or persona) that achieves the highest coverage for the LLM-only estimator, selected separately for each model. 3.4 Evaluation DatasetsWe evaluate on both real-world and synthetic data."
779,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,77,"For real-world data, we use two annotation tasks from POPQUORN (Pei and Jur- gens, 2023), a large-scale dataset that collects de- mographically diverse human annotations via Pro- lific."
780,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,78,"POPQUORN contains 45,000 annotations from 1,484 annotators across multiple tasks."
781,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,79,"We used the politeness rating and offensiveness rating subsets, taking 1,000 unique annotations from each task."
782,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,80,"For additional robustness experiments, we construct a synthetic dataset of N= 10,000 items drawn from two demographic groups with selected label rates and group-specific LLM error rates (see Appendix, Section H for details)."
783,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,81,"Annotation tasksIn the politeness task, anno- tators rate how polite a statement would be in an email from a colleague on a Likert scale from 1.0 (not polite at all) to 5.0 (very polite)."
784,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,82,"In the of- fensiveness task, annotators rate how offensive a statement would be as a Reddit comment on the same scale."
785,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,83,Synthetic annotations are binary.
786,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,84,"Inference tasksOur goal is to estimate the vec- tor θ∗ = (θ ∗ g1, . . . , θ∗ gK), where each θ∗ gk is the mean annotation rating within demographic group gk."
787,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,85,"For the politeness task, θ∗ gk is the mean per- ceived politeness rating among annotators in group gk; for the offensiveness task, it is the mean per- ceived offensiveness rating."
788,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,86,"We stratify separately by gender, age, and education, yielding K groups per demographic axis, used as features in the black box classifier."
789,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,87,"Descriptive statisticsAnnotation ratings vary significantly across demographic groups in both real-world datasets, motivating the multi- perspective estimation."
790,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,88,We verify this using chi- squared tests on ratings.
791,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,89,"In the offensiveness dataset, we find significant variation by gender (χ2(4) = 13.305 , p= 0.0099 ), with men rat- ing statements as more offensive on average than women (1.77 vs. 1.58), as well as by age (χ2(28) = 90.261, p <0.001 ) and education ( χ2(16) = 49.837, p <0.001 )."
792,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,90,"The politeness dataset shows the same pattern such that ratings differ signifi- cantly by gender, age, and education."
793,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,91,"Since the dif- ferences between age groups are most pronounced in both politeness and offensiveness ratings (Fig- ure 2), we focus on age strata in the evaluation."
794,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,92,"For illustration, tables 7 and 8 list example texts, along with annotations."
