820,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,118,"PDI allocates 33% more annotations to Age 50+ than PPI (12.2 vs. 9.2), reflecting error-driven upsampling toward the hardest subgroup."
821,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,119,"CoverageFirst, we find that coverage consis- tently falls below 90% for several LLM-only meth- ods on older age groups (Table 1)."
822,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,120,Zero-shot GPT- 5.2 misses the target for Age 35–49 (coverage = 0.800).
823,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,121,"For Age 50+, both the few-shot variant (coverage = 0.750) and the persona variant (cover- age = 0.850) fall short."
824,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,122,"In contrast, PDI maintains coverage above 90% across all three age groups, reaching 0.950 for Age 50+."
825,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,123,"DeltaAveraged across age groups, the LLM-only methods are comparable to PPI and non-rectified baselines: zero-shot and few-shot GPT-5.2 pro- duce average deltas of 7.48 and 7.52 percentage points, respectively, versus 6.35 for PPI and 7.10 for PDI."
826,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,124,"Again, the critical divergence appears for Age 50+: The few-shot variant is inaccurate for this group (coverage = 0.750), producing the worst delta at 16.31%."
827,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,125,"In contrast, PDI achieves the low- est delta for Age 50+ at 11.23%, outperforming PPI (13.63%) and all three LLM-only variants."
828,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,126,Upsampling liftThe lower delta for Age 50+ un- der PDI reflects error-driven upsampling.
829,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,127,"Because the error classifier accurately identifies this group as high-error, PDI directs a disproportionate share of the annotation budget there (Table 2)."
830,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,128,"Averaged across 20 trials, PPI allocates 9.2 annotations to Age 50+ under uniform sampling; PDI allocates 12.2, a 33% increase."
831,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,129,"This confirms that the pre- dicted error signal is useful: the classifier correctly identifies where annotation effort matters most, and the resulting upsampling translates into improved coverage and accuracy for the most challenging subpopulation."
832,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,130,"Crucially, this reallocation does not compro- mise overall validity—averaged across all three age groups, PDI maintains 0.933 coverage. 4.2 Offensiveness For the offensiveness task, the persona variant re- sults in the smallest mean prediction error for GPT- 5.2."
833,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,131,"As with politeness, age is the demographic axis with the greatest variation in performance, and Age 50+ again emerges as the hardest subgroup (Table 3)."
834,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,132,CoverageThe coverage for offensiveness is sub- stantially worse than for politeness.
835,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,133,"All three LLM- only methods fail: averaged across age groups, zero-shot GPT-5.2 achieves only 11.7% coverage, the persona variant 13.3%, and few-shot variant only 53.3% (substantially below the 90% cover- age across every age group)."
836,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,134,"For age 35–49, the persona variant achieves 0% coverage."
837,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,135,"In contrast, both PPI and PDI maintain 95.0% average coverage across all three age groups, including Age 50+."
838,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,136,"DeltaThe LLM-only delta values reflect the same breakdown: zero-shot and persona produce average deltas above 19 percentage points, and even the best LLM-only variant (few-shot, 14.21%) falls far short of PPI (3.86%) and PDI (6.04%)."
839,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,137,For A vg (Age) Age 18–34 Age 35–49 Age 50+ MethodCov.∆Cov.∆Cov.∆ Cov. ∆ GPT-5.2 (zero shot) 11.7 20.11 15.0 14.05 5.0 18.38 15.0 27.90 GPT-5.2 (few shot) 53.3 14.21 65.0 8.01 60.0 10.06 35.0 24.54 GPT-5.2 (persona) 13.3 19.68 25.0 13.12 0.0 17.50 15.0 28.40 PPI 95.0 3.86 100.0 2.38 95.0 3.57 90.0 5.64 PDI 95.0 6.04 95.0 7.31 95.0 5.57 95.0 5.24 Table 3:Offensiveness.Coverage (Cov.) and delta ( ∆) by age group on the offensiveness task (GPT-5.2).
840,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,138,Values below the 90% coverage are highlighted .
841,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,139,Bold indicates best performance for Age 50+.
842,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,140,Group PDI samples PPI samples Gender Woman 152.3 143.7 Man 47.6 56.4 Race White 164.7 162.9 Black/Afr.
843,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,141,"Am. 6.8 9.0 Asian 17.4 20.2 Age Age 18–34 85.1 87.0 Age 35–49 89.2 91.4 Age 50+ 25.8 21.6 Education College degree 102.4 103.2 HS diploma 67.5 68.5 Grad. degree 12.2 11.4 Table 4: Average number of human annotations allo- cated per group by PDI and PPI, averaged across 20 trials (total budget n= 200 per trial, offensiveness task)."
844,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,142,"PDI allocates 19% more annotations to Age 50+ than PPI (25.8 vs. 21.6), reflecting error-driven upsam- pling toward the hardest subgroup."
845,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,143,"Age 50+, all three LLM-only variants exceed 24% delta, with persona reaching 28.40%."
846,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,144,"PDI achieves the lowest delta for Age 50+ at 5.24%, outperform- ing PPI (5.64%), while also maintaining coverage."
847,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,145,"Upsampling liftAs with politeness, the PDI per- formance for Age 50+ is supported by error-driven upsampling (Table 4)."
848,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,146,"PDI allocates on average 25.8 annotations to Age 50+ across 20 trials, com- pared to 21.6 under uniform PPI sampling (a 19% increase)."
849,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,147,"The upsampling lift closes the delta gap with PPI while preserving validity: averaged across all three age groups, PDI maintains coverage. 4.3 Synthetic data To understand the impact of the human annotation budget, size of the burn-in, group skew, and LLM error, we analyze PDI on synthetic data, under con- trolled conditions."
850,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,148,"The simulated data consist of N= 10,000 items drawn from two demographic groups: a large group (Group 1, N1 = 9,000, 90%) and a small group (Group 2, N2 = 1,000, 10%)."
851,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,149,"Each item carries a binary human label Yi ∈ {0,1} and a binary LLM prediction ˆYi."
852,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,150,"LLM predic- tions are generated by flipping the true label in- dependently with group-specific error rates (see Appendix, Sec."
853,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,151,"Overall, we find that adaptive sampling is advantageous over uniform sampling when the budget of human annotations is at least 20%, as sufficient labels are needed to learn the sampling rule (Figure 3), while the choice of precise batch size is not consequential, as long as it is under 50% of the complete budget (Figure 4)."
854,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,152,"As expected, the stronger the disparity in LLM performance between groups and the more severe the group skew, the more PERSPECTIVE-DRIVEN INFERENCEdeviates from uniform sampling (Fig- ures 5 and 6)."
855,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,153,"These differences are particularly pronounced for group sizes under 10%, and for error differences above 20%, where upsampling is particularly valuable, when compared to uniform sampling. 4.4 Limitations of persona prompting Lastly, overall across the experiments, we find that persona prompting is not a reliable method."
856,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,154,"Across models, it is the highest-variance prompting strat- egy and frequently the worst (Appendix, Sec."
857,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,155,"Persona prompting sometimes matches few-shot performance, but it can also shift predictions sys- tematically in the wrong direction, suggesting the effect depends heavily on model-specific patterns, rather than on the demographic content of the per- sona itself."
858,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,156,"Persona prompting is the most common method for capturing demographic perspectives with LLMs, yet it fails precisely for the groups it is meant to represent, and in several cases leaves cov- erage at zero."
859,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,157,"The results confirm that conditioning an LLM on a demographic label is not a substitute for human annotation from that group, and under- score why a correction framework that treats LLM outputs as potentially inadequate proxies (rather than steerable perspectives) can be useful. 5 Discussion Overall, our results show that correcting LLM an- notation error can be important when the target estimand is a distribution over perspectives rather than a single ground truth."
860,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,158,LLM-only methods fail for specific groups that are poorly modeled by persona prompting (such as Age 50+).
861,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,159,PDI ad- dresses this by directing human annotation effort where it matters most.
862,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,160,"The gains can be substantial: for offensiveness, PDI reduces delta for Age 50+ to 5.24%, while LLM-only variants exceed 24%."
863,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,161,Coverage holds across all groups.
864,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,162,"Practitioners should expect the largest gains over uniform sam- pling when LLM performance disparities between groups are large, and groups are skewed."
865,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,163,The evaluation therefore demonstrates that PDI can be viewed as a targeted subgroup-improvement method (rather than a universally superior alterna- tive to uniform PPI).
866,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,164,"On aggregate metrics, PDI does not consistently outperform uniform PPI."
867,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,165,"But PDI is designed for settings where the main con- cern is not average performance across all groups, but better inference for those groups that are hardest for LLM proxies to capture."
868,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,166,"Our findings support this interpretation, with PDI showing its clearest benefits on harder-to-model groups, such as Age 50+, while maintaining coverage."
869,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,167,The framework may generalize beyond the tasks studied here.
870,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,168,"More broadly, corpus inference prob- lems where annotator identity shapes labels are promising candidates for this approach."
871,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,169,The de- mographic axes we use are a proof of concept.
872,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,170,"In practice, the stratification could follow any theo- retically motivated partition, including ideological orientation, professional background, or lived ex- perience (Orlikowski et al., 2025)."
873,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,171,The key require- ment is that the error predictor receives informative features.
874,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,172,"Instead, where demographic proxies are weak, the adaptive gains will be smaller, and the method degrades to uniform PPI."
875,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,173,The problem we study also appears in three high-stakes settings that have received attention in NLP.
876,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,174,"In RLHF, preference labels reflect the per- spectives of whoever provided feedback, yet mod- els are trained as if those preferences were univer- sal (Movva et al., 2025; Wang et al., 2025b; Chen et al., 2025)."
877,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,175,"In LLM-as-judge evaluation, a single model scores outputs according to implicit stan- dards that may not generalize across demographic groups (Dong et al., 2024)."
878,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,176,"In LLM simulations, the task is often to predict distributions of opinions as self-reported in survey answers (Krsteski et al., 2025; Suh et al., 2025), and LLM predictions do not represent each respondent equally well."
879,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,177,"All three settings involve collapsing perspective-dependent judgments into a scalar, discarding variation that is not noise."
880,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,178,"Extending our framework to these settings is a natural direction, and one with impli- cations for how models are trained or evaluated."
881,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,179,"Lastly, several limitations remain."
882,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,180,"Our evalua- tion uses two tasks, and performance on tasks with subtler demographic structure is a promising av- enue for future work."
883,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,181,"The burn-in phase requires uniform samples before adaptation begins, which may be inefficient when the human budget is very small."
884,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,182,"The error predictor is a gradient-boosted tree trained on demographic features alone; richer features, including linguistic properties of the text, could improve predictions and allocate the budget more efficiently. 6 Conclusion LLMs are widely used as annotation proxies, but their outputs do not represent all demographic per- spectives equally."
885,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,183,"We introduced a framework that treats the distribution of group-specific annotations as the estimand of interest, and allocates a lim- ited human annotation budget adaptively to where LLM error is highest."
886,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,184,"Across two subjective rat- ing tasks, PDI maintains valid coverage and re- duces estimation error for the hardest subpopula- tions, while maintaining validity."
887,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,185,"The framework is task-agnostic and can extend to any setting where annotator identity shapes labels, including RLHF, LLM-as-judge evaluation, and survey simulation."
888,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,186,"Correcting for LLM bias at the aggregate level is not enough; valid inference requires knowing whoseperspective the model fails to capture, and directing human effort there."
889,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,187,"Limitations First, we stratify by gender, age, and education in- dependently, but these axes correlate in practice."
890,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,188,An annotator who is older and identifies as a par- ticular gender occupies an intersection that our per- axis treatment does not capture.
891,3,C003_P1_pdf.txt,189,Modeling intersec- tional subgroups directly would require larger an- notation budgets and raises challenges for the error predictor when intersectional cells are sparse.
892,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,0,ARTICLE LLMs as annotators: the effect of party cues on labelling decisions by large language models Sebastián Vallejo Vera 1 ✉ & Hunter Driggers 1 Human coders can be biased.
893,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,1,We test whether Large Language Models (LLMs) replicate those biases when used as text annotators.
894,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,2,"By replicating an experiment conducted by Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer ( 2018), we ﬁnd evidence that LLMs use political information, and speci ﬁcally party cues, to evaluate political statements."
895,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,3,"Not only do LLMs use relevant information to contextualize whether a statement is positive, negative, or neutral based on the party cue, they also re ﬂect the biases of the human-generated data upon which they have been trained."
896,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,4,"We also ﬁnd that unlike humans, who are only biased when faced with statements from extreme parties, some LLMs exhibit signi ﬁcant bias even when prompted with statements from center-left and center-right parties."
897,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,5,"The implications of our ﬁndings are discussed in the conclusion. https://doi.org/10.1057/s41599-025-05834-4 OPEN 1 University of Western Ontario, London, ON, Canada. ✉email: sebastian.vallejo@uwo.ca HUMANITIES AND SOCIAL SCIENCES COMMUNICATIONS | (2025) 12:1530 | https://doi.org/10.1057/s41599-025-05834-4 1 1234567890():,; Introduction T he increasing sophistication of large language models (LLMs) has allowed for their more prominent presence in political science research."
898,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,6,One particular area that has received signi ﬁcant attention in the ﬁeld is the use of LLMs as annotators.
899,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,7,"Research has shown promising results, with LLMs often outperforming human coders (Gilardi et al. 2023) and providing comparable accuracy when labeling political text (Overos et al. 2024), across multiple languages (Heseltine and Clemm von Hohenberg, 2024)."
900,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,8,"While researchers have evaluated the performance of LLMs as annotators across various domains, there is still insuf ﬁcient information on how the known biases of LLMs (see Gallegos et al. 2024) can affect their performance."
901,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,9,"For human text annotators, studies show that political cues, such as party, affect their coding decisions (Benoit et al. 2016; Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer, 2018; Laver and Garry, 2000)."
902,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,10,"In this article, we test whether this is also true for LLMs."
903,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,11,"We replicate the experimental design of Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer (2018), who tested human coder bias by having annotators evaluate policy statements on immigration that were modi ﬁed by party cues."
904,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,12,"We use the same treatment (i.e., the same policy statement with different party cues) to evaluate how two LLM families, OpenAI ’s ChatGPT and Meta ’s LLaMa, determine the sentiments behind policy statements (i.e., positive, negative, or neutral)."
905,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,13,"Our results show important differences in internal consistency across LLM models, low agreement between LLM and human coders and, most importantly, signi ﬁcant dis- crepancies that are conditioned by party cue (i.e., treatment)."
906,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,14,This behavior remains even when we explicitly tell LLMs to not take party labels into consideration.
907,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,15,"These results are re ﬂective of the way LLMs embed certain tokens (e.g., party names) with infor- mation, as well as how embedding interacts with highly polarized contexts (e.g., immigration) where there are clear expectations about the position of each party."
908,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,16,The output mirrors human behavior when evaluating political statements.
909,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,17,"However, our analysis suggests that LLMs are more sensitive to partisan context than human coders."
910,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,18,"In our conclusion, we discuss the implica- tions and limitations of our results with respect to the use of LLMs as political text annotators."
911,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,19,"Bias in annotation Numerous political behavior studies have shown that individuals ’ perceptions can be biased based on characteristics that are rele- vant to political preference formation: gender, education, racial identity, and partisanship."
912,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,20,"Since annotators are not immune to their political contexts, similar biases have been observed in coding tasks."
913,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,21,"In a wide-ranging meta-analysis, Webb Williams et al."
914,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,22,"( 2023) show various sources of annotator bias, including partisanship and gender, when completing subjective and objec- tive coding tasks. 1 Other research ﬁnds that partisanship can affect reactions of disgust (Ahn et al. 2014) and responses on opinion surveys (Bullock and Lenz, 2019; Schaffner and Luks, 2018)."
915,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,23,"In the study that we replicate in this paper, Ennser- Jedenastik and Meyer ( 2018) show that human coders use heuristics from party labels when judging political statements."
916,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,24,Research on LLMs has also explored biases and incongruities in their responses.
917,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,25,"Despite promises and fanfare from LLM devel- opers, studies have shown multiple sources of errors (Hicks et al. 2024), as well as political bias in their output (Rotaru et al. 2024; Urman and Makhortykh, 2025; Walker and Timoneda, 2024)."
918,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,26,"( 2024), for example, ﬁnd that LLMs tend to align more with left-of-center viewpoints, a result similar to the one obtained by Rozado ( 2024) when probing LLMs with political orientation tests."
919,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,27,"More broadly, studies on LLMs have con- sistently found biases based on contextual and cultural factors (Gallegos et al. 2024), leading to the misrepresentation of certain social groups (Yang et al. 2022), gender stereotyping (Dong et al. 2024), and the reinforcement of normativity (Bender et al. 2021)."
920,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,28,"Despite the known limitations of LLMs, most research on LLMs as annotators has focused solely on accuracy, comparing their performance with that of human annotators."
921,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,29,"Relevant political science research has shown that LLMs outperform human annotators, at a fraction of the price, with minimal effects on downstream performance (see Braylan et al. 2022; Gilardi et al. 2023; Heseltine and Clemm von Hohenberg, 2024; Overos et al. 2024)."
922,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,30,"Although the results of these studies provide promising avenues for the application of LLM as coders, less attention has been paid to the effect of known LLM biases on performance."
923,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,31,"In this article, we test the possible biases in LLM annotation resulting from political cues."
924,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,32,"We argue that LLMs use political contextual information to evaluate statements and produce responses.2 As a simpli ﬁed explanation, Transformer-based LLMs assign representations (i.e., embeddings) to tokens by relating their co-occurrences with other tokens in the text."
925,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,33,"To do this on a large scale, LLMs are fed enormous amounts of text from various sources.3 These corpora are not created in a vacuum, instead reﬂecting social realities."
926,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,34,"Thus, if certain parties (e.g., far-right parties) are often mentioned in certain contexts (e.g., dis- criminatory practices), LLMs are more likely to associate these parties with those contexts."
927,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,35,"When LLMs annotate text, they will use high-information tokens (i.e., political parties) to guide their responses, just as humans use party cues as a heuristic to evaluate statements (Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer, 2018)."
928,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,36,"In the remain- der of the paper, we ﬁrst analyze differences in output across LLM models and consistency in output within each model across multiple iterations of the same prompt; then, we evaluate to what degree party cues affect the output of LLMs when used as annotators."
929,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,37,"Replication setup To test possible biases in LLMs as annotators, we adapt Ennser- Jedenastik and Meyer ( 2018)’s experiment on party cues and human annotators."
930,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,38,"In their study, Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer (2018) enlisted ten coders to classify 200 policy statements on immigration and migrant integration from Austrian election manifestos produced between 1986 and 2013."
931,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,39,"The authors removed all party labels, references to previous or subsequent sentences, and gender-sensitive language."
932,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,40,"They then randomly assigned a party cue (i.e, the treatment) to each statement: Green Party (Grüne - Extreme Left), Social Democrats (SPÖ - Center Left), People ’s Party (ÖVP - Center Right), or Freedom Party (FPÖ - Extreme Right)."
933,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,41,The control statement was the version without a party cue.
934,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,42,"An example of a statement without a party cue is “We stand for a modern and objective immigration policy, ” while a randomly treated statement would be “We [Greens/Social Democrats/Christian Democrats/Freedomites ( ‘Freiheitliche’)] stand for a modern and objective immigration policy. ” Each coder received 200 statements with randomly assigned conditions and were subsequently asked whether the statement conveyed a positive or negative stance on immigration, or if the statement was neutral or unclear."
935,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,43,"The coding question that appeared below each statement was “Does this statement convey a positive or a negative stance on immigration and multiculturalism –or is the statement neutral or unclear, respectively? ”."
936,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,44,"Coders were also provided with examples for negative and positive messages towards immigration and multiculturalism: “By positive state- ments on immigration and cultural diversity we mean, for example, approval of immigration to Austria and the acceptance of refugees, appreciation of other cultures in Austria or demands ARTICLE HUMANITIES AND SOCIAL SCIENCES COMMUNICATIONS | https://doi.org/10.1057/s41599-025-05834-4 2 HUMANITIES AND SOCIAL SCIENCES COMMUNICATIONS | (2025) 12:1530 | https://doi.org/10.1057/s41599-025-05834-4 for the opening of the labor market to foreign workers ”; and “By negative statements on immigration and cultural diversity we mean, for example, demands for less immigration, skepticism towards other cultures and religions (Islam), the desire for pre- ferential treatment of Austrians in the labor market or for restrictive asylum laws ”."
937,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,45,"Finally, Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer (2018) tested whether the party cue had an effect on annotation."
938,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,46,"They found that human coders were more likely to evaluate statements with the Greens party cue (i.e., extreme left) positively, and more likely to evaluate statements with the FPÖ party cue (i.e., extreme right) negatively, with no effect from statements with centrist-party cues (e.g., SPÖ and ÖVP)."
939,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,47,We reproduce the results of their experiment in Table 2.
940,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,48,"For our analysis, we use the exact same statements and instructions that were given to human annotators. 4 We test two LLM families: OpenAI ’s ChatGPT (ChatGPT-3.5 Turbo and ChatGPT-4o), and Meta ’s LLaMa (LLaMa 3-70B and LLaMa 3.1- 70B).5 Each LLM is prompted using the same text that an annotator would have read in Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer (2018)’s study (including the examples of positive and negative statements)."
941,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,49,"Each prompt is run in a fresh instance of the LLM client, making each response independent from the previous one."
942,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,50,"Given the independence of each instance, rather than randomly assigning one party cue to each statement (i.e., prompt), we show each LLM all 200 statements with each party cue, including the control."
943,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,51,"In total, each LLM labels 1000 statements (200 state- ments x 5 party cues)."
944,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,52,"Since the output from LLMs is stochastic, we increase the determinism of answers by setting the tempera- ture to 0 for all runs. 6 Additionally, we replicate each run (200 statements) 10 times, allowing us to measure within model consistency.7 To evaluate coding bias, we follow Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer ( 2018) and use an ordered logistic regression to estimate the effect of the treatment on the labeling decisions of the LLMs."
945,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,53,"To that end, we estimate the following model: yijk ¼ cuej þ contenti þ ϵijk where yijk is the response of LLM k to statement i with party cue treatment j."
946,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,54,"LLMs categorize each statement as negative, neutral/ unclear, or positive."
947,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,55,"Our main variable of interest is cuej, an indi- cator variable that takes the value of the four party labels (i.e., Greens, SPÖ, ÖVP, and FPÖ), with the no label statements as the reference category."
948,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,56,"Following Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer (2018), we control for content-related factors using either ﬁxed effects at the sentence level or random intercepts at the statement level."
949,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,57,"Inter-LLM and inter-coder reliability We begin with Fig. 1, which plots the distribution of positive, negative, and neutral labels for statements containing no party cues (i.e., control group) of LLMs and human coders."
950,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,58,"Following a similar distribution as human coders, LLaMa 3 and LLaMa 3.1 models are more likely to label statements as positive."
951,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,59,The same is not true for OpenAI models: ChatGPT-3.5 and ChatGPT-4o predict positive and negative labels at similar rates.
952,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,60,"The former is least likely to predict neutral labels, while the latter is most likely to do so."
953,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,61,"To further evaluate some of these discrepancies, Table 1 compares statements at different degrees of agreement."
954,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,62,Statement where there is high agreement require no additional information or context to determine their valance.
955,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,63,"For example, the statement ‘We want to create incentives to encourage people with a migration background to participate in teacher training courses ’ has a clear positive sentiment towards immigrants and their integration in Austrian society."
956,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,64,There seems to be greater dis- agreement between LLMs and human coders in statements where context about the Austrian immigration system is required to make a decision.
957,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,65,"Take, for example, the following statement: ‘We believe it is sensible to prepare an annual needs assessment regarding the number and quali ﬁcations of potential immigrants and use this as a basis for migration ’, labeled as neutral by LLMs and negative by humans."
958,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,66,"Knowledge of the anti-immigration rhetoric in Austrian politics might allow coders to pick up on certain telling elements: deciding on the ‘type of immigrants ’ and ‘how many ’ have been issues of anti-immigration policy (Kolbe, 2021)."
959,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,67,"In the Discussion Section, we show that statements labeled as neutral when there is no party cues are more likely to change their label when prompted with the same statement that includes a party cue (see Figure F.1 in Appendix F), suggesting that, similar to humans, LLMs use heuristics from party labels when judging political statements."
960,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,68,"They do so, however, at a higher rate than humans."
961,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,69,We now turn to the task of describing inter-LLM and inter- coder reliability.
962,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,70,We describe within-model consistency by looking at inter-run reliability.
963,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,71,"To this end, we estimate Krip- pendorff’s Alpha, an inter-coder reliability (ICR) score, for each model across the multiple runs (ten in total)."
964,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,72,Within model Krippendorff’s Alpha scores by party cue (treatment) are shown in Fig. 2.
965,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,73,"Overall, within model consistency is relatively high, with most scores close to or above.8. 8 There are important differences across LLM families: LLaMa models are highly consistent across runs, with an average Alpha close to 1.0, while OpenAI models are less consistent."
966,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,74,"Within models, however, there are no statis- tically signi ﬁcant differences resulting from party cues."
967,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,75,Fig. 1 Distribution of labels by coder with bias-corrected bootstrapped 95% con ﬁdence intervals (5000 samples) for statements containing no party cues .
968,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,76,"HUMANITIES AND SOCIAL SCIENCES COMMUNICATIONS | https://doi.org/10.1057/s41599-025-05834-4 ARTICLE HUMANITIES AND SOCIAL SCIENCES COMMUNICATIONS | (2025) 12:1530 | https://doi.org/10.1057/s41599-025-05834-4 3 Finally, Fig. 3 depicts ICR scores between LLMs and the human annotators from Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer ( 2018)."
969,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,77,"Since every LLM labels each statement ten times, we adjudicate discrepancies following majority rules. 9 In terms of ICR, the best performing LLMs are LLaMa 3.1 and ChatGPT-4o, with an average Krippendorff ’s Alpha of 0.56 and 0.55, respectively; the worst performing LLM is ChatGPT-3.5 Turbo with a Krip- pendorff ’sA l p h ao f0 . 4 3 .10 There are also differences in the variation of agreement between humans and LLMs across party cues."
970,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,78,"For the LLaMa family models, the agreement with human coders across party cues is similar, and we ﬁnd no statistically signiﬁcant differences."
971,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,79,"That is not the case for ChatGPT-4o, where there is a Krippendorff ’s Alpha of 0.68 when labeling statements with the center-left SPÖ label, but 0.37 when labeling statements with the extreme-right FPÖ label, a statistically signi ﬁcant difference at the 95% con ﬁdence level."
972,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,80,"In Figure D.1 (see Appendix D), we also show the estimates of Krippendorff ’s Alpha for each run from every LLM when compared to human coders."
973,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,81,"As expected, given the lower within-model consistency of ChatGPT models, there is greater variation in ICR scores across runs when compared to models from the LLaMa family."
974,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,82,"Note, however, that there are no overall performance gains from using a djudicated labels, nor labels from a speci ﬁcr u n ."
975,4,C004_P1_pdf.txt,83,"Replication results In Models 1 and 2 from Table 2, we reproduce the results from Ennser-Jedenastik and Meyer ( 2018), who estimate an ordered logistic regression model where the dependent variable is the label Table 1 Labels for statements about immigration and multiculturalism."
