1929,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,90,"Research ethics of reusing data All personal and identifiable information was removed from the transcripts to protect participants' privacy and confidentiality before conducting data analysis, following our standardized qualitative study protocol (Zhang et al., )."
1930,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,91,"In addition, we applied for and obtained Institutional Review Board (IRB) approval for an amendment allowing the reuse of transcripts collected for a traditional qualitative study for use in the present context."
1931,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,92,"Considering potential ethical concerns and privacy protection, we chose to exclude the transcripts or data from ethnic minority women in this exploratory study."
1932,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,93,The reuse of the transcript data was approved as a study amendment by the IRB committee at the University of South Carolina (#Pro00115169).
1933,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,94,"Interview transcript and structure Given the structure of an interview, the raw interview transcript typically follows a question‐and‐answer structure that allows researchers to consider a variety of responses from different participants to the same question, thereby identifying diverse opinions and lived experiences."
1934,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,95,"To facilitate GenAI's coding, we first reformatted the text into structured, analyzable data by matching each question with its corresponding answer."
1935,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,96,"Each question–answer pair (hereafter referred to as a ) was assigned a unique identifier (ID#), making the data computer‐readable and facilitating efficient data management and query."
1936,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,97,"Figure illustrates the reformatting process from raw text into structured data, where interviewers' questions were aligned with participants' responses."
1937,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,98,These structured data were saved in.
1938,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,99,"CSV files, with each participant's responses organized accordingly."
1939,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,100,Reformatting raw text data into structured computer‐readable data.
1940,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,101,Each interviewers' question is matched with its corresponding participants' answer as a dialogue.
1941,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,102,"Coding of semistructured interview with GenAI In this study, we aimed to investigate the potential of utilizing ChatGPT for thematic analysis in inductive coding for semistructured interviews."
1942,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,103,"Specifically, through carefully designed instructions and question prompts, ChatGPT generated a set of codes by identifying and summarizing key points mentioned by each participant following thematic analysis approach."
1943,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,104,"Braun and Clarke's six‐phase coding framework widely adopted for thematic analysis of inductive coding was employed in the present study (Braun & Clarke, )."
1944,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,105,"The framework involves the following steps: Familiarizing: Read the data thoroughly, transcribe if necessary, and jot down initial ideas."
1945,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,106,"Generating initial codes: Systematically code features across the dataset, collating relevant data."
1946,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,107,"Searching for themes: Organize codes into potential themes, gathering relevant data for each theme."
1947,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,108,"Reviewing themes: Check the application of themes, in relation to the coded extracts and the entire dataset, generating a thematic “map” of the analysis."
1948,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,109,"Defining and naming themes: Refine themes and the overall narrative, generating clear definitions and names."
1949,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,110,"Producing the report: Conduct the final analysis, select compelling examples, relate the analysis to the research question and literature, and produce a scholarly report."
1950,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,111,"In this study, we used ChatGPT 4 to simulate the thematic analysis procedure from the second step to the fourth step."
1951,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,112,"The specific methods included , which are illustrated in Figure ."
1952,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,113,"During the development and testing of the proposed workflow, we first interacted with the ChatGPT 4 model through its web‐based chatbot interface."
1953,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,114,This allowed us to iteratively refine prompts utilized for analysis and roughly evaluate model performance in generating appropriate codes.
1954,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,115,"Once the prompt structure was established, we leveraged the ChatGPT API to automate the inductive coding process at scale."
1955,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,116,The workflow of using ChatGPT for inductive coding.
1956,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,117,"In‐depth interviews often feature a deep, conversational nature where participants might address supporting points for one question while responding to another, either unintentionally or to reinforce their viewpoints."
1957,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,118,"As a result, the same perspective might be repeated across different responses and intersect with multiple interview questions."
1958,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,119,"Given this complexity, we performed to locate participants' responses to specific questions."
1959,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,120,We first instructed ChatGPT to determine whether a specific question was asked during the interview.
1960,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,121,"When the question was identified, ChatGPT provided the dialogue ID, allowing researchers to observe participants' responses to the question."
1961,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,122,"This step ensured that only relevant sections of the dialogue are further coded, enhancing the accuracy and efficiency of the analysis."
1962,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,123,The prompt template used for dialogue filtering was illustrated in Figure .
1963,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,124,"The prompt instructed ChatGPT to identify if a specific interview question is present within the dialogue and, if so, to return the ID of the relevant dialogue."
1964,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,125,"If no relevant content was found, it returned a 0."
1965,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,126,"By doing so, for each question, we identified all relevant dialogue from each participant for each question."
1966,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,127,The prompt template used for dialogue filtering.
1967,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,128,"If the given question is asked in the interview transcript, returns the row number of the dialogue, else then returns 0."
1968,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,129,"After identifying the dialogues for each question, we instructed ChatGPT to perform by summarizing and extracting key topics from the dialogues."
1969,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,130,Figure illustrates the prompt template used for generating codes.
1970,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,131,"In this phase, responses to specific questions from all interview transcripts were collected."
1971,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,132,ChatGPT was then tasked to extract and generate codes from the collected responses.
1972,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,133,This process enabled the identification of themes and topics across participants' responses.
1973,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,134,The prompt template used for code generation.
1974,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,135,"After GenAI generated a set of codes reflecting the key topics in response to each question, we further aggregated these codes into categories and developed themes."
1975,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,136,The first task was to merge codes with similar semantic meanings.
1976,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,137,"While ChatGPT generated the most fitting code for each participant's response, slight variations in expressions resulted in many repetitive codes that were redundant for analysis and required manual aggregation."
1977,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,138,The second task was to synthesize codes based on their conceptual meanings.
1978,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,139,The codes were combined and grouped into categories based on their definitions and scope in the conceptual system.
1979,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,140,The process of ensured that the extracted codes were concise and useful for identifying themes in subsequent qualitative data analysis.
1980,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,141,Reviewing the generated and aggregated codes was crucial to ensure the accuracy and applicability of the generated themes.
1981,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,142,"Although ChatGPT is often efficient at identifying general themes present in dialogue, it may lack domain‐specific knowledge."
1982,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,143,"Thus, two evaluation approaches were performed to assess the validity of the generated codes: a human‐centered approach and a machine‐based approach."
1983,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,144,It is important to emphasize that the purpose of presenting these evaluation methods is not to position one as superior to the other.
1984,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,145,"Rather, our goal is to assess and characterize the performance of ChatGPT through both lenses, recognizing that each approach has its own advantages and limitations."
1985,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,146,"Human‐centered approach We engaged domain experts in maternal health, with relevant background knowledge in manual coding of the interview transcripts."
1986,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,147,"One faculty member and one doctoral student in public health, both with extensive experiences in qualitative studies, independently developed the codes after reviewing all the transcripts."
1987,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,148,The disagreements were sufficiently discussed and resolved before finalizing the codes assigned to each participant's response.
1988,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,149,The domain experts reviewed and compared the ChatGPT‐generated codes with the human‐generated codes.
1989,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,150,"If the ChatGPT‐generated codes were the same as and/or aligned with the human‐generated codes, they were marked as “accepted.” Two domain experts independently marked each code as accepted and discussed any disagreements."
1990,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,151,The accuracy rate for each response to a question was the number of “accepted” codes divided by the total number of codes generated by ChatGPT.
1991,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,152,Machine‐based metric approach We also compared the human‐generated codes and ChatGPT‐generated codes and quantified the differences by assessing their semantic similarity.
1992,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,153,"The underlying hypothesis is that if ChatGPT performs effectively, the semantic content of its generated codes should closely resemble that of human‐generated codes."
1993,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,154,"In particular, we utilized a cutting‐edge text embedding method, Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT), to convert the codes into high‐dimensional vectors (Devlin et al., )."
1994,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,155,No preprocessing was conducted since the codes (whether generated by humans or ChatGPT) consisted of only a few words or paraphrases.
1995,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,156,These high‐dimensional feature vectors captured the semantic meanings of the input codes.
1996,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,157,"We calculated the cosine similarity between the two high‐dimensional vectors using the following formula. represents the high‐dimensional vector of a GenAI‐generated code, represents the high‐dimensional vector of a human‐defined code, represents the cosine similarity of ranges from 0 to 1, and the higher the , the more similar the two codes."
1997,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,158,Inductive coding performance We first show several examples of the codes generated by ChatGPT.
1998,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,159,Table lists the ChatGPT‐generated codes for three example questions.
1999,6,C006_P1_v2.txt,160,Each question was coded based on the participants' direct responses to the questions.
