2204,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,0,"Research Synthesis Methods (2026), 17: 332–347 doi:10.1017/rsm.2025.10044 RESEARCH ARTICLE Compact large language models for title and abstract screening in systematic reviews: An assessment of feasibility, accuracy, and workload reduction Antonio Sciurti 1, Giuseppe Migliara2, Leonardo Maria Siena1, Claudia Isonne1, Maria Roberta De Blasiis1, Alessandra Sinopoli3, Jessica Iera1,4, Carolina Marzuillo1, Corrado De Vito1,P a o l oVillari1 and V alentinaBaccolini1 1Department of Public Health and Infectious Diseases, University of Rome La Sapienza, Italy 2Department of Life Sciences, Health, and Health Professions, Link Campus University, Italy 3Department of Prevention, Local Health Authority Rome 1, Italy 4Department of Infectious Diseases, Istituto Superiore di Sanità, Italy Corresponding author: Leonardo Maria Siena; Email: leonardo.siena@uniroma1.it Received: 12 May 2025; Revised: 14 July 2025; Accepted: 15 August 2025; published online 13 November 2025 Keywords: artiﬁcial intelligence; Gemma 2 9B; GPT-4o mini; large language models; Llama 3.1 8B; title and abstract screening Abstract Systematic reviews play a critical role in evidence-based research but are labor-intensive, especially during title and abstract screening."
2205,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,1,"Compact large language models (LLMs) offer potential to automate this process, balancing time/cost requirements and accuracy."
2206,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,2,"The aim of this study is to assess the feasibility, accuracy, and workload reduction by three compact LLMs (GPT-4o mini, Llama 3.1 8B, and Gemma 2 9B) in screening titles and abstracts."
2207,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,3,"Records were sourced from three previously published systematic reviews and LLMs were requested to rate each record from 0 to 100 for inclusion, using a structured prompt."
2208,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,4,"Predeﬁned 25-, 50-, 75-rating thresholds were used to compute performance metrics (balanced accuracy, sensitivity, speciﬁcity, positive and negative predictive value, and workload-saving)."
2209,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,5,Processing time and costs were registered.
2210,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,6,"Across the systematic reviews, LLMs achieved high sensitivity (up to 100%) and low precision (below 10%) for records included by full text."
2211,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,7,"Speciﬁcity and workload savings improved at higher thresholds, with the 50- and 75-rating thresholds offering optimal trade- offs."
2212,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,8,"GPT-4o-mini, accessed via application programming interface, was the fastest model ( ~40 minutes max.) and had usage costs ($0.14–$1.93 per review)."
2213,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,9,Llama 3.1-8B and Gemma 2-9B were run locally in longer times (~4 hours max.) and were free to use.
2214,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,10,LLMs were highly sensitive tools for the title/abstract screening process.
2215,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,11,"High speciﬁcity values were reached, allowing for signiﬁcant workload savings, at reasonable costs and processing time."
2216,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,12,"Conversely, we found them to be imprecise."
2217,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,13,"However, high sensitivity and workload reduction are key factors for their usage in the title/abstract screening phase of systematic reviews."
2218,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,14,"Highlights What is already known? • Large language models (LLMs) have shown potential to automate the title/abstract screening process of systematic reviews, but practical aspects of their usage, such as costs and processing time, should be considered."
2219,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,15,This article was awarded Open Data and Open Materials badges for transparent practices.
2220,7,C007_P1_pdf.txt,16,"See the Data availability statement for details. © The Author(s), 2025."
