2313,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,17,"Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. 07 Apr 2026 at 13:19:28, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use. 1006 Emilova Doneva et al. such as randomized controlled trials (RCTs) or animal studies—before screening, potentially reducing the number of references to review and making the process more efﬁcient."
2314,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,18,"However, there has been no direct comparison of how well GPT performs this task compared to more established models like bidirectional encoder representations from transformer (BERT)."
2315,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,19,"We introduce a new dataset of abstracts, labeled by humans according to 14 different study types."
2316,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,20,"Using this dataset, we evaluated how well different GPT and BERT models classify these study types."
2317,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,21,"Our results show that BERT models are particularly effective at this task, making them a good choice for sorting abstracts before systematic review."
2318,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,22,"In fact, BERT models consistently outperformed the newer GPT models in this speciﬁc task."
2319,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,23,"Potential impact for RSM readers Using BERT models to pre-screen abstracts could reduce the workload of systematic reviews, especially for larger collections of references."
2320,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,24,"And importantly, while GPT models have advanced features and are trained on massive datasets, they were consistently outperformed by the more traditional BERT models for this type of classiﬁcation."
