2369,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,73,A random sample from the validation dataset was used to select the most promising GPT prompts (see Section 2.3.2).
2370,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,74,"To ensure that all classes are present across all parts of the split, we employed a stratiﬁcation strategy which ensured that all classes were present across all dataset splits."
2371,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,75,"Each dataset record included the following ﬁelds: title, abstract, author keywords, and journal name."
2372,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,76,"Note that we did not include MeSH terms, as empirical evaluations for a similar task have shown no positive impact on performance.13 2.3."
2373,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,77,"Setup We employed two generative LLMs developed by OpenAI: GPT-3.5-turbo and GPT-4-turbo- preview. 23,24 These models have been trained on publicly available data (e.g., Common Crawl, a public dataset of web page data [ https://commoncrawl.org] and Wikipedia) and licensed third-party data.23,24 GPT models generate text by predicting the next word in a sequence, based on the context of the previous words."
2374,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,78,"GPT-4 is an advancement over GPT-3.5, featuring a larger model size, enhanced performance (including in the domain of medicine), 25,26 and more extensive training data."
2375,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,79,"We utilized the OpenAI chat-completion API to obtain responses from both models. 27 Each abstract’s classiﬁcation was run in an independent session, and since the API currently does not have a memory function, there is no transfer of information or bias from one abstract to another."
2376,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,80,"The classiﬁcation task was structured as a question-answering problem, where GPT was prompted to identify the most suitable study type from a predeﬁned study type set based on the paper’s title, abstract, journal name and, when available, keywords."
2377,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,81,The analysis was conducted with the temperature parameter set at 0 to reduce the randomness of responses (compared to higher values producing more creative and random outputs).
2378,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,82,"Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. 07 Apr 2026 at 13:19:28, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use. 1010 Emilova Doneva et al."
2379,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,83,"Furthermore, to deal with variation in GPT responses, we conﬁgured the output format of the API call to a speciﬁc structured output type (“json_object”)."
2380,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,84,"Additionally, we used a fuzzy matching approach to account for minor differences between model outputs and expected labels. 2.3.2."
2381,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,85,Prompting strategy We pre-deﬁned three prompting strategies: 1.
2382,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,86,"Zero-shot28,29 The model is given the classiﬁcation prompt without any additional context, examples, or speciﬁc instructions, relying solely on its pre-trained knowledge. 2. contextual clues (CC)30 The model is provided with our detailed annotation guidelines (see Section a of the Supplementary Material and Table S1 in the Supplementary Material for the full version and Section b of the Supplementary Material and Table S2 in the Supplementary Material for the shortened version)."
2383,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,87,"These guidelines outline the classiﬁcation criteria and labeling conventions, enabling the model to use these information to create an output. 3. chain-of-thought (CoT) 30,31 The model is instructed to generate a chain of thought (step-by-step reasoning) before providing its ﬁnal classiﬁcation."
2384,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,88,This process encourages explicit reasoning and can improve accuracy by making the decision process more transparent.
2385,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,89,"For prompt engineering, i.e., designing the input instructions given to the model, we followed OpenAI’s Prompt Engineering Guidelines 30 and other published recommendations. 32 Prompts are summarized in Table 2 and detailed in Section j of the Supplementary Material."
2386,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,90,"We tested both, 1) classiﬁcation into one of 14 categories (multi-class) or 2) just two (“Animal” versus “Other,” binary) due to the following reasons: First, it allowed us to compare the performance of BERT-based and GPT-based models on a simpler binary classiﬁcation task."
2387,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,91,"Second, it allowed us to construct a hierarchical classiﬁcation pipeline, i.e., a two-step approach where binary classiﬁcation is followed by more detailed classiﬁcation (i.e., a form of the Chain-of-Thought-prompting-strategy)."
2388,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,92,"We also brieﬂy explored in-context learning (few-shot) 31 as a prompting strategy, i.e., giving the model a few examples in the prompt (Table S10 in the Supplementary Material)."
2389,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,93,"The selection of few-shot examples was based on,33,34 as follows: 1."
2390,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,94,"Random Few-Shots : In this approach, the classiﬁcation examples (few-shots) were randomly selected from the training split. 2."
2391,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,95,"K-Nearest Neighbor (K-NN) : Here, the few-shot examples were chosen based on the closest neighbors to each test example from the training split. 2.3.3."
2392,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,96,Experiments We ﬁrst tested the prompting strategies on random samples of 50 abstracts from the validation dataset.
2393,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,97,"To compare GPT with BERT performance, we re-ran all the prompts on the test set (enriched with keywords), see Table S8 in the Supplementary Material."
2394,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,98,"In addition, we tested them on the test split without keywords (Table S9 in the Supplementary Material)."
2395,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,99,"Due to relatively high API costs of GPT-4, we decided to only run the most promising prompts (based on their performance with GPT-3.5) and at least one prompt of each prompting strategy on GPT- 4."
2396,8,C008_P1_pdf.txt,100,"In total, we tested eight selected prompts on GPT-4 (Table3). 2.4."
