2410,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,0,"Nature | Vol 650 | 26 February 2026 | 857 Article Synthesizing scientific literature with  retrieval-augmented language models Akari Asai1,2, Jacqueline He1,7, Rulin Shao1,7, Weijia Shi1, Amanpreet Singh2,  Joseph Chee Chang2, Kyle Lo2, Luca Soldaini2, Sergey Feldman2, Mike D’ Arcy2,  David Wadden2, Matt Latzke2, Jenna Sparks2, Jena D."
2411,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,1,"Hwang2, Varsha Kishore1,2,  Minyang Tian3, Pan Ji4, Shengyan Liu3, Hao Tong3, Bohao Wu3, Yanyu Xiong5,  Luke Zettlemoyer1, Graham Neubig6, Daniel S."
2412,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,2,"Weld1,2, Doug Downey2, Wen-tau Yih1,  Pang Wei Koh1,2 & Hannaneh Hajishirzi1,2 ✉ Scientific progress depends on the ability of researchers to synthesize the growing  body of literature."
2413,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,3,Can large language models (LLMs) assist scientists in this task?
2414,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,4,"Here we introduce OpenScholar, a specialized retrieval-augmented language model  (LM)1 that answers scientific queries by identifying relevant passages from 45 million  open-access papers and synthesizing citation-backed responses."
2415,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,5,"T o evaluate  OpenScholar, we develop ScholarQABench, the first large-scale multi-domain  benchmark for literature search, comprising 2,967 expert-written queries and  208 long-form answers across computer science, physics, neuroscience and  biomedicine."
2416,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,6,"Despite being a smaller open model, OpenScholar-8B outperforms  GPT-4o by 6.1% and PaperQA2 by 5.5% in correctness on a challenging multi-paper  synthesis task from the new ScholarQABench."
2417,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,7,"Although GPT-4o hallucinates citations  78–90% of the time, OpenScholar achieves citation accuracy on par with human  experts."
2418,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,8,"OpenScholar’s data store, retriever and self-feedback inference loop improve  off-the-shelf LMs: for instance, OpenScholar-GPT-4o improves the correctness  of GPT-4o by 12%."
2419,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,9,"In human evaluations, experts preferred OpenScholar-8B and  OpenScholar-GPT-4o responses over expert-written ones 51% and 70% of the time,  respectively, compared with 32% for GPT-4o."
2420,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,10,"We open-source all artefacts, including  our code, models, data store, datasets and a public demo."
2421,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,11,"Synthesizing knowledge from the scientific literature is essential for  discovering new directions, refining methodologies and supporting  evidence-based decisions, yet the rapid growth of publications makes  it increasingly difficult for researchers to stay informed."
2422,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,12,"Effective syn- thesis requires precise retrieval, accurate attribution and access to  up-to-date literature."
2423,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,13,"LLMs can assist but suffer from hallucinations2,3,  outdated pre-training data4 and limited attribution."
2424,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,14,"In our experiments,  GPT-4o fabricated citations in 78–90% of cases when asked to cite recent  literature across fields such as computer science and biomedicine."
2425,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,15,Retrieval-augmented LMs5– 7 mitigate some of these issues by incor- porating external knowledge at inference time and have encour - aged systems for literature search and synthesis8– 10.
2426,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,16,"However, most  rely on black-box application programming interfaces (APIs) or  general-purpose LMs and lack open, domain-specific retrieval data  stores (processed corpora with retrieval indices) tailored to scientific  domains."
2427,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,17,"Evaluations for literature synthesis are also limited, typically  focusing on narrow, single-discipline studies8,9 or simplified tasks such  as multiple-choice question answering10."
2428,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,18,"T o address the challenges of accurate, comprehensive and transpar- ent scientific literature synthesis, we introduce OpenScholar (Fig. 1, top),  to our knowledge the first fully open, retrieval-augmented LM specifi- cally designed for scientific research tasks."
2429,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,19,"OpenScholar integrates  a domain-specialized data store (OpenScholar DataStore, OSDS),  adaptive retrieval modules and a new self-feedback-guided generation  mechanism that enables iterative refinement of long-form outputs."
2430,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,20,"OSDS is a fully open, up-to-date corpus of 45 million scientific papers  and 236 million passage embeddings, offering a reproducible foun- dation for training and inference."
2431,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,21,"OpenScholar retrieves from OSDS  using trained retrievers and rerankers, generates cited responses and  iteratively refines them by means of a self-feedback loop to improve  factuality, coverage and citation accuracy."
2432,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,22,"This same pipeline is used  to generate high-quality synthetic data, enabling the training of a com- pact 8B model (OpenScholar-8B) and retrievers without relying on  proprietary LMs."
2433,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,23,"T o evaluate OpenScholar, we introduce ScholarQABench (Fig. 1,  middle), to our knowledge the first multidisciplinary benchmark for  open-ended scientific synthesis."
2434,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,24,"Unlike previous benchmarks focused  on short-form outputs, multiple-choice formats or domain reasoning  tasks10– 12, ScholarQABench requires long-form responses grounded in  up-to-date literature from numerous papers."
2435,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,25,"It includes 3,000 research  Received: 16 February 2025 Accepted: 17 December 2025 Published online: 4 February 2026 Open access  Check for updates 1University of Washington, Seattle, WA, USA. 2Allen Institute for AI, Seattle, WA, USA. 3University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign, Urbana, IL, USA. 4University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, Chapel  Hill, NC, USA. 5Stanford University, Stanford, CA, USA. 6Carnegie Mellon University, Pittsburgh, PA, USA. 7These authors contributed equally: Jacqueline He, Rulin Shao. ✉e-mail: hannaneh@  cs.washington.edu 858 | Nature | Vol 650 | 26 February 2026 Article questions and 250 expert-written answers across computer science,  physics, biomedicine and neuroscience, authored by experienced PhD  students and postdocs to reflect real-world literature review practices."
2436,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,26,"T o overcome the difficulties of evaluating long-form, comprehensive  responses13– 16, ScholarQABench introduces a rigorous evaluation pro- tocol combining automatic metrics (for example, citation accuracy)  with human rubric-based assessments of coverage, coherence, writing  quality and factual correctness to enable reliable assessments of the  detailed long-form answers of LMs."
2437,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,27,"Our expert analysis shows that the  proposed multifaceted evaluation pipeline achieves high agreement  with expert judgements, reliably capturing coverage, coherence, writ- ing quality and factual correctness in long-form scientific answers."
2438,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,28,"We evaluated proprietary and open models (for example, GPT-4o,  Llama 3.1 8B and 70B) with and without retrieval capabilities, as well  as specialized systems such as PaperQA2 (ref. 10), on ScholarQA - Bench."
2439,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,29,"Although GPT-4o demonstrated strong general performance,  it struggled with citation accuracy and coverage, often producing inac- curate or non-existent citations."
2440,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,30,"OpenScholar outperformed both  LM-only and retrieval-augmented pipelines, surpassing proprietary  and open-source systems."
2441,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,31,"Notably, using fully open-source check- points, OpenScholar-8B outperformed PaperQA2, built on proprietary  LMs, and production systems such as Perplexity Pro, achieving 6% and  10% improvements, respectively."
2442,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,32,"Furthermore, OpenScholar’s use of  smaller, efficient retrievers substantially reduced costs."
2443,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,33,The Open- Scholar pipeline can also enhance off-the-shelf LMs.
2444,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,34,"For example, when  using GPT-4o as the underlying model, OpenScholar-GPT-4o achieves  a 12% improvement in correctness compared with GPT-4o alone."
2445,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,35,"Fur- thermore, although expert human performance exceeds that of GPT-4o  and other competitive baselines, OpenScholar systems match or sur- pass expert humans in both answer correctness and citation accuracy."
