2451,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,41,"OpenScholar system overview Citation accuracy Citation correctness By model Coverage Relevance Organization By model and human Usefulness By human Evaluation ScholarQABench Data Scholar-Multi Multi Discipline Multi-paper tasks Scholar-Neuro Neuroscience Scholar-CS Computer science Scholar-Bio Biomedicine Scholar-Multi Multidiscipline Single-paper tasks PubMed QA Biomedicine SciFact Biomedicine QASA Computer science Fig. 1 | Overview of OpenScholar, ScholarQABench and evaluation results."
2452,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,42,"OpenScholar consists of a specialized data store  (OSDS), retrievers and LMs and iteratively improves responses using self-  feedback inference with retrieval."
2453,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,43,"Middle, overview of ScholarQABench."
2454,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,44,"ScholarQABench consists of 2,200 expert-written questions across several  scientific disciplines and we introduce automatic and human evaluation  protocols for ScholarQABench."
2455,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,45,"Bottom, automatic and human evaluation  results: experimental results from the ScholarQABench computer science  subset (Scholar-CS, 100 questions) show that OpenScholar with our trained  8B or GPT-4o substantially outperforms other systems and is preferred over  experts more than 50% of the time in human evaluations."
2456,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,46,Our human evaluations  were conducted by 16 experts with PhDs across 108 questions from Scholar-Multi.
2457,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,47,"Nature | Vol 650 | 26 February 2026 | 859 verification, as well as the value of combining diverse retrieval pipelines  and training domain-specialized retrieval systems."
2458,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,48,"As well as automatic evaluations on ScholarQABench, we conducted  detailed expert assessments with 16 scientists from fields such as com- puter science, physics and biomedicine."
2459,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,49,These experts performed pair- wise and fine-grained evaluations of the outputs of OpenScholar against  108 expert-written responses to literature synthesis queries in Scholar- QABench.
2460,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,50,"OpenScholar, when paired with GPT-4o and our trained 8B  model, consistently outperformed expert-written responses, with win  rates of 70% and 51%, respectively."
2461,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,51,"By contrast, vanilla GPT-4o (that  is, without retrieval) struggled with information coverage and was  rated as less helpful than human experts, achieving only a 31% win rate  against human responses."
2462,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,52,"Overall, these findings demonstrate that  OpenScholar can produce high-quality outputs that are not only on par  with expert-written answers but, in some cases, above par, particularly  in terms of coverage and organization."
2463,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,53,"We also released the first public  demo for scientific literature synthesis, powered by OpenScholar-8B."
2464,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,54,"Since launch, the demo has been used by more than 30,000 users and  has collected nearly 90,000 user queries across diverse scientific fields."
2465,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,55,"OpenScholar performance on ScholarQABench We first provide an overview of our key results of OpenScholar on our  newly created expert-annotated benchmark, ScholarQABench."
2466,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,56,Table 1  shows scores for several aspects of the main baselines.
2467,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,57,Baseline models We compare three settings.
2468,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,58,(1) Parametric LMs (no retrieval): Llama   3.1 8B/70B (ref. 17) and GPT-4o (gpt-4o-2024-05-13 (ref. 18)) generate  answers and a list of paper titles.
2469,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,59,"We verify that the titles exist and, when  they do, fetch their abstracts as citations."
2470,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,60,"(2) Retrieval-augmented gen- eration (RAG) baselines: using our OSDS (RAGOSDS), we retrieve the top  N passages and concatenate them with the input, following stand - ard RAG pipelines 2,18."
2471,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,61,"(3) Our method (OpenScholar): a custom  inference pipeline with a trained 8B model (OpenScholar-8B)  and with Llama 3.1 70B and GPT-4o back ends (OpenScholar-70B,  OpenScholar-GPT-4o)."
2472,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,62,"For multi-paper tasks, we also test Perplexity  Pro."
2473,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,63,"We use the paid subscription version; because there is no API, we  collect final predictions through selenium, and cannot extract citations,  and PaperQA2 (ref. 10)."
2474,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,64,"As the data store of PaperQA2 is not public, we  use OSDS as its retrieval source."
2475,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,65,"Main results On single-paper tasks, OpenScholar consistently outperforms  other models."
2476,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,66,OpenScholar-8B and OpenScholar-70B outperform  Llama 3.1 8B and 70B with and without retrieval augmentation in terms  of final accuracy and citation accuracy (Table 1).
2477,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,67,OpenScholar-70B  even matches or outperforms GPT-4o on PubMedQA and QASA.
2478,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,68,We  also found that OpenScholar models consistently show substantial  improvements in terms of citation accuracy compared with standard  RAG baselines (RAGOSDS).
2479,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,69,"In multi-paper tasks, we report the Scholar-CS rubric score—the  number of expert-annotated answer rubrics satisfied by the response  of a model (see Methods for scoring details)—as our primary measure of  correctness."
2480,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,70,We also evaluate overall writing quality with a LLM judge  (‘LLM’) on Scholar-Multi and track citation accuracy across all datasets.
2481,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,71,"OpenScholar-8B, OpenScholar-70B and OpenScholar-GPT-4o, which  use the OpenScholar pipeline with our fine-tuned Llama 3.1 8B-based  LM and off-the-shelf Llama 3.1 70B and GPT-4o as the generator  LM, respectively, demonstrate strong performance."
2482,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,72,"Specifically,  OpenScholar-GPT-4o provides a 12.7-point improvement over GPT-4o  alone in the Scholar-CS rubric score and a 5.3 improvement over stand- ard RAG."
2483,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,73,"When combined with trained OpenScholar-8B, OpenScholar  greatly outperforms the pipeline that uses off-the-shelf Llama 3.1 8B,  showcasing the benefits of domain-specific training."
2484,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,74,"Furthermore,  OpenScholar-8B shows better rubric performance by a substantial  margin than proprietary systems such as GPT-4o, Perplexity Pro or  PaperQA2, which use GPT-4o models for passage reranking, summa- rization and answer generation."
2485,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,75,"Although we found that PaperQA2  matches or even outperforms OpenScholar in citation accuracy, its  responses often rely on only one or a few papers, summarizing each  retrieved snippet individually."
2486,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,76,This leads to limited coverage and  contributes to its lower performance on the Scholar-CS rubric and  LLM judge scores.
2487,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,77,These findings highlight the importance of balanc- ing both precision and recall in effective literature synthesis.
2488,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,78,"Nota- bly, by making use of efficient retrieval pipelines with lightweight  Table 1 | Results of ScholarQABench Single-paper performance Multi-paper performance Cost Pub Sci QASA CS Multi Bio Neu CS Model Acc."
