2492,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,82,PaperQA2 is based on GPT-4o and its pricing is dependent on  the number of PDF files used during inference.
2493,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,83,"For the 8B and 70B model costs, although evaluations were conducted on our local machines, we estimated costs based on Together AI pricing.  *We used Perplexity Pro (which requires a monthly subscription at US$20) and divided this cost by 9,000, which is the maximum number of queries allowed under the Pro subscription."
2494,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,84,"Because  the Perplexity user interface does not provide snippets for each citation, we were unable to evaluate its citation accuracy. 860 | Nature | Vol 650 | 26 February 2026 Article bi-encoders, cross-encoders and in-house models, OpenScholar-8B and  OpenScholar-GPT-4o achieve much lower costs—orders of magnitude  cheaper than PaperQA2—while maintaining high performance."
2495,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,85,"Limitations of parametric LMs On both single-paper and multi-paper tasks, we observe that non-  retrieval augmented baselines struggle—retrieval is almost always  conducive to achieving better performance—and models without any  retrieval often struggle to generate correct citations and show limited  coverage on multi-paper tasks."
2496,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,86,Table 2 presents statistics on the cited  papers in the outputs of four models.
2497,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,87,We report the number of fully  fabricated citations (‘No. of hallucinated’) by verifying whether the  cited paper titles exist using the Semantic Scholar API.
2498,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,88,"Across mod- els, the share of cited papers that actually exist is very low: despite  plausible-looking reference lists, 78–98% of titles are fabricated, with  the worst rates in biomedicine."
2499,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,89,"This mirrors previous findings that  LLMs hallucinate on long-tail, underrepresented knowledge2,19 and we  suggest that the effect is amplified in scientific areas undercovered  on the open web."
2500,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,90,"Repeating the analysis on GPT-5, which was released  in August 2025, lowers title-level hallucination to 39% but fabricated  citations remain common."
2501,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,91,"Examples of model responses, as well as a  list of paper titles, are available in Supplementary Tables 19 and 20."
2502,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,92,"We also noticed that, even when citations refer to real papers, most of  them are not substantiated by the corresponding abstracts, resulting  in near-zero citation accuracy."
2503,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,93,We also observe that such models generate responses with limited  coverage.
2504,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,94,"On Scholar-Multi, non-retrieval models (Llama 3.1 8B, 70B  and GPT-4o) consistently exhibit much lower average scores com - pared with retrieval-augmented models."
2505,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,95,"This discrepancy is primarily  driven by substantially lower coverage scores; for instance, Llama 3.1 8B  achieves a coverage score of 3.45, whereas Llama 3.1 8B + OSDS (a stand- ard RAG baseline) improves the coverage score to 4.01."
2506,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,96,"These results  suggest that relying on the parametric knowledge of models alone is  particularly difficult in scientific domains, especially for smaller LMs."
2507,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,97,Human performance on ScholarQABench We also analysed expert performance on this challenging literature  synthesis task.
2508,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,98,"Specifically, we evaluated human-written answers on the  two subsets of ScholarQABench with long-form human annotations:  Scholar-CS and Scholar-Multi."
2509,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,99,"For both, we applied the same evaluation  pipeline used for model-generated responses to assess rubric and cita- tion accuracy."
2510,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,100,"For Scholar-Multi, rubric evaluation is not available, but  we conducted expert evaluations on both human and model responses  and compare the results in the next section."
2511,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,101,"Table 3 compares human per- formance with OpenScholar-GPT-4o, OpenScholar-8B, PaperQA2 and  GPT-4o (no retrieval)."
2512,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,102,Our analysis shows that human-written answers  remain strong baselines for quality and relevance.
2513,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,103,"On rubric-based  evaluations, human responses outperform GPT-4o without retrieval by  9.6 points and OpenScholar-8B by 2.9 points."
2514,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,104,"PaperQA2 demonstrates  high citation accuracy but its scores for rubrics, organization, coverage,  and relevance are lower."
2515,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,105,"By contrast, OpenScholar-GPT-4o achieves  even higher rubric scores than human experts and OpenScholar-8B  matches expert-level citation accuracy."
2516,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,106,"We found that OpenScholar  tends to produce more comprehensive responses than humans  or other baseline systems, citing a greater number of papers, as  reflected in both answer length and citation count."
2517,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,107,"In Supplemen - tary Information Section 6, we present a detailed human analysis  of model-written and human-written answers and further examine  key factors for improving scientific literature synthesis."
2518,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,108,Ablations and analysis Ablations of inference components.
2519,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,109,We ablate inference com - ponents by removing: (1) reranking (use top N OSDS results only);  (2) feedback (generate once then attribute); and (3) citation verification  (omit the final check).
2520,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,110,"For OpenScholar-8B, we also ablate training by  swapping in off-the-shelf Llama 3.1 8B with the same inference pipeline  (as in OpenScholar-GPT-4o)."
2521,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,111,"Extended Data Table 2 shows notable  drops in both correctness and citation accuracy for all removals, with  the largest losses from removing reranking."
2522,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,112,Feedback removal hurts  GPT-4o more than our trained 8B (probably because the latter learned  feedback patterns during training) and skipping post-hoc attribu - tion reduces both citation accuracy and final correctness.
2523,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,113,The gap  between trained versus vanilla OpenScholar-8B underscores the value  of domain-specific training.
2524,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,114,"We also compare OSDS-only (dense retrieval),  S2-only (Semantic Scholar keyword API), web-only (You.com) and their  combination."
2525,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,115,"T o isolate retrieval, we use our 8B LM without self-feedback  or citation verification and rerank to the top 15 with OpenScholar  reranker."
2526,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,116,"On Scholar-CS (Extended Data Table 2), web-only performs  worst (45.9 correctness, 12.6 citation F1), S2-only improves especially  on citations (47.9/39.1) and the combined pipeline is best (49.6/47.6)."
2527,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,117,"Tailored, literature-focused retrieval (dense + API + reranking)  yields the strongest factuality and attribution."
2528,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,118,We analyse how the number of retrieved passages (top N) affects  performance.
2529,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,119,"We compare standard RAG and OpenScholar with our  trained 8B model and Llama 3.1 8B, evaluating generation and citation  accuracy on Scholar-CS."
2530,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,120,Extended Data Figs. 3 and 4 summarize the  results.
2531,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,121,"Although Llama 3.1 is trained to accept up to 128,000 tokens,  its performance degrades beyond a certain context size: increasing top  N from 5 to 10 improves correctness but larger N harms both correct- ness and citation accuracy."
2532,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,122,"This suggests that, despite long-context  capacity, smaller LMs may struggle to effectively use many passages  without specialized training."
2533,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,123,"By contrast, our trained 8B model remains  strong up to N = 20 and larger models (for example, Llama 3.1 70B) are  more robust to longer contexts."
2534,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,124,"Expert evaluation of OpenScholar’s effectiveness T o complement automatic metrics and examine the strengths and limits  of OpenScholar, we ran expert evaluations comparing human-written  answers with those generated by LLM systems."
2535,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,125,"This study involved more  than 100 literature review questions and more than 15 participants,  including PhD students, research scientists and university professors  with expertise in the relevant fields."
2536,9,C009_P1_pdf.txt,126,"In total, we curated more than  400 fine-grained expert evaluations of expert and model answers."
