3509,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,330,"To view a copy of this licence, visit http:// creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/. © The Author(s) 2026, modified publication 2026 Article Methods OpenScholar OpenScholar (detailed in Extended Data Fig. 1) is a new retrieval-  augmented LM designed to ensure reliable, high-quality responses  to a range of information-seeking queries about scientific literature."
3510,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,331,Task formulation and challenges.
3511,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,332,"Given a scientific query x, the task  is to identify relevant papers, synthesize their findings and generate a  response y that effectively addresses the query."
3512,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,333,"This response should be  accompanied by a set of citations, C = c1, c2,…, c K, in which each citation  ci corresponds to an existing scientific paper."
3513,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,334,"Each ci in C corresponds  to specific passages from scientific literature and should be provided  as an in-line citation, linked to the relevant spans of text in y, following  standard practice in scientific writing."
3514,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,335,"These citations allow researchers  to trace the output back to the original literature, ensuring transpar- ency and verifiability."
3515,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,336,"However, this task presents several challenges: (1) retrieving high-  recall, high-precision scientific content from a vast, domain-specific cor- pus; (2) synthesizing accurate, non-hallucinated responses grounded  in the retrieved evidence; and (3) producing citation-aware outputs  that align generated text with appropriate references at a fine-grained  level."
3516,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,337,"A further challenge lies in the scarcity of resources: to our knowl- edge, there is limited availability of large-scale, up-to-date scientific  corpora, especially those suitable for dense retrieval, as well as a lack of  supervised training data for both retrieval and generation in scientific  domains."
3517,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,338,"T o address these challenges, Open- Scholar introduces several key innovations that extend the standard  RAG (refs. 1,5) model for scientific literature synthesis."
3518,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,339,"Specifically,  OpenScholar combines domain-specialized retrieval, citation-aware  generation and a new self-feedback inference mechanism, all built on  top of a fully open and large-scale scientific data store."
3519,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,340,"Formally, OpenScholar consists of three key components: a data  store D, a retriever R and a generator LM G."
3520,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,341,"In standard retrieval-  augmented inference pipelines, the process begins with R, which  retrieves a set of passages P = {p1, p2,…, p N} from D—a large-scale corpus  of previously published scientific papers—based on semantic relevance  to the input query x."
3521,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,342,These passages serve as context for the next step.
3522,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,343,The generator LM G then takes both the retrieved passages P and the  input query x to produce the output y along with corresponding  citations C.
3523,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,344,"Formally, this process can be represented as:  CDyG xR x,= (, (, )), in which each ci in C corresponds to a specific passage from P."
3524,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,345,OpenScholar introduces new technical contributions to address the  aforementioned challenges.
3525,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,346,"(1) T o address the lack of large-scale,  up-to-date scientific corpora, we construct OSDS, a database of 45 mil- lion scientific papers with precomputed dense embeddings, represent- ing, to our knowledge, the largest and most up to date scientific paper  data store available."
3526,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,347,"(2) T o enable high-recall, high-precision retrieval  and support LM training in scientific domains, we design a retrieval  pipeline that integrates both our trained OpenScholar retriever and  OpenScholar reranker, optimized on scientific data to select the top  N passages for the generator G—and complementary retrieval APIs— ensuring broader coverage and improved relevance."
3527,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,348,"(3) T o improve  factuality and evidence grounding, we introduce iterative self-feedback  inference with retrieval and citation verification, in which the LM first  produces an initial draft y0 with G and then iteratively refines it using  retrieval-augmented self-feedback."
3528,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,349,"(4) T o enhance citation accuracy  and overall output quality, we use this inference pipeline to generate  high-quality training data, enabling the training of specialized LMs  that produce more accurate and citation-aware long-form answers."
3529,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,350,OpenScholar retrieval pipeline.
3530,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,351,"Extended Data Fig. 1 (top left) shows  our retrieval pipeline, consisting of a data store D, a bi-encoder retriever  θ bi and a cross-encoder reranker θcross."
3531,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,352,"We first select initial candidate  paragraphs using D and θ bi, as well as external APIs, and then refine and  identify the top N relevant paragraphs using θcross."
3532,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,353,Scientific paper collection and data store construction.
3533,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,354,"Although  previous work often used a small subset of scientific papers, such as  arXiv papers from 2023 to 2024 (ref. 9), it is important to have a diverse  set of papers to improve the quality and coverage of model generation23."
3534,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,355,"For this, we use peS2o (ref. 24) as our retrieval source, which consists of  open-access academic papers from S2ORC (ref. 25)."
3535,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,356,"We built our data  store using peS2o v3, which includes 45 million papers up to October  2024."
3536,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,357,"For evaluations, we use peS2o v2, which consists of papers up to  January 2023, as our main benchmarks and models were constructed  before the curation of peS2o v3."
3537,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,358,"Our data store, which we call OSDS,  consists of 236 million passages."
3538,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,359,"T o our knowledge, this is the largest  open-sourced data store for scientific literature."
3539,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,360,We retrieve passages from three sources:  (1) the OSDS using our trained retriever; (2) publicly available abstracts  from papers returned through the Semantic Scholar API (ref. 26) based  on search keywords; and (3) publicly available texts from papers  retrieved through a web search engine using the original query x.
3540,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,361,"For (1), we first generate embeddings of each passage in the OSDS  D using the passage bi-encoder θ bi, which processes text chunks (for  example, queries or passages) into dense vectors27 offline."
3541,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,362,Off-the-shelf  retrieval models often struggle in out-of-domain scenarios 28.
3542,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,363,"To  overcome this limitation, we develop θ bi by continually pre-training  Contriever29 on the peS2o data store in an unsupervised fashion to  improve domain-specific retrieval performance."
3543,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,364,"During inference, we  encode the query using θ bi and retrieve the top 70 passages through  a nearest-neighbour search27."
3544,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,365,"Following previous work23, we split the  main text of each paper into discrete, 256-word text blocks (as deter- mined by white space) and concatenate the paper title to each block to  formulate passages in D."
3545,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,366,"Although semantic segmentation can be used  to split scientific articles into meaningful sections, we found that not all  papers in our data store consistently retain such semantic or discourse  structures."
3546,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,367,"Furthermore, applying segmentation models post hoc  would be computationally expensive at this scale."
3547,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,368,"Therefore, following  common practice in this area27,29, we divide articles into fixed-length  chunks to ensure scalability and simplicity."
3548,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,369,"Therefore, several text  chunks from the same paper can be retrieved at inference time."
3549,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,370,"For (2), we first generate keywords from the query x using a genera- tor LM."
3550,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,371,"These keywords are then used to retrieve the top 10 papers for  each, as ranked by citation count, through the Semantic Scholar search  API."
3551,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,372,"This approach addresses a limitation of the Semantic Scholar API,  which cannot effectively handle long, question-like search queries."
3552,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,373,"If  the full text is available in HTML format (for example, ar5iv), we retrieve  the entire text and include all passages from the paper as candidate  documents."
3553,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,374,"Otherwise, we only consider the abstract."
3554,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,375,"For (3), we obtain the top 10 search results using the You.com retrieval  API, restricting the search to academic platforms such as arXiv and  PubMed."
3555,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,376,"Similarly to (2), if the papers are open access, we extract and  add their full texts to the candidate pool; otherwise, we include only  their abstracts."
3556,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,377,T op N paragraph reranking and finalization.
3557,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,378,"After the initial stage,  we have gathered more than a hundred or even a thousand relevant  passages per query."
3558,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,379,"However, passages retrieved by the bi-encoder  may include unhelpful context owing to deep interactions between a  query and passages, as they are encoded separately30."
3559,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,380,"Feeding a large  number of documents that might include irrelevant content to LLMs  can cause efficiency and performance issues, even with state-of-the-art  models31,32."
3560,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,381,"T o overcome these challenges, we use a cross-encoder  reranker33,34, denoted as θ cross."
3561,10,C010_S1_pdf.txt,382,"For each candidate paragraph, the  cross-encoder reranker jointly encodes and computes the relevance  score between the input query and each of the passages."
3562,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,0,"The Rise of Large Language Models and the Direction and Impact of US Federal Research Funding Yifan Qian1,2,3,4, Zhe Wen1,2,3,4, Alexander C."
3563,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,1,"Furnas1,2,3,4, Yue Bai1,2,3,4, Erzhuo Shao1,2,3,5, and Dashun Wang1,2,3,4,5,* 1Center for Science of Science and Innovation, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL, USA 2Ryan Institute on Complexity, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL, USA 3Northwestern Innovation Institute, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL, USA 4Kellogg School of Management, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL, USA 5McCormick School of Engineering, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL, USA *Correspondence to: dashun.wang@kellogg.northwestern.edu Abstract Federal research funding shapes the direction, diversity, and impact of the US scientific enterprise."
3564,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,2,"Large language models (LLMs) are rapidly diffusing into scientific practice, holding substantial promise while raising widespread concerns."
3565,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,3,"Despite growing attention to AI use in scientific writing and evaluation, little is known about how the rise of LLMs is reshaping the public funding landscape."
3566,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,4,"Here, we examine LLM involvement at key stages of the federal funding pipeline by combining two complementary data sources: confidential National Science Foundation (NSF) and National Institutes of Health (NIH) proposal submissions from two large US R1 universities, including funded, unfunded, and pending proposals, and the full population of publicly released NSF and NIH awards."
3567,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,5,"We find that LLM use rises sharply beginning in 2023 and exhibits a bimodal distribution, indicating a clear split between minimal and substantive use."
3568,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,6,"Across both private submissions and public awards, higher LLM involvement is consistently associated with lower semantic distinctiveness, positioning projects closer to recently funded work within the same agency."
3569,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,7,The consequences of this shift are agency-dependent.
3570,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,8,"LLM use is positively associated with proposal success and higher subsequent publication output at NIH, whereas no comparable associations are observed at NSF."
3571,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,9,"Notably, the productivity gains at NIH are concentrated in non-hit papers rather than the most highly cited work."
3572,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,10,"Together, these findings provide large-scale evidence that the rise of LLMs is reshaping how scientific ideas are positioned, selected, and translated into publicly funded research, with implications for portfolio governance, research diversity, and the long-run impact of science. 1 arXiv:2601.15485v1 [cs.DL] 21 Jan 2026 Introduction Federal research funding is the primary mechanism through which the United States converts public resources into scientific knowledge1,2."
3573,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,11,"Through competitive grant programs at agencies such as the National Science Foundation (NSF) and the National Institutes of Health (NIH), decisions about the allocation of taxpayer dollars influence which scientific ideas receive support, which fields advance, and which investigators are able to initiate and sustain research programs3–10."
3574,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,12,"Thus, the federal funding process plays a central role in shaping the direction, diversity, and long-run impact of the US scientific enterprise and—given America’s scientific leadership—the global research landscape as well 3–10."
3575,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,13,"Understanding forces that influence this process is therefore essential not only for science policy and the rate and direction of scientific progress, but also for the stewardship and accountability of public investment in research11–14."
3576,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,14,"Despite growing attention to the use of AI in science 15–26, little is known about how the rise of large language models (LLMs) is reshaping the public funding landscape."
3577,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,15,"This gap is consequential, as funding decisions operate upstream of publication, hiring, and recognition, shaping which scientific ideas are pursued long before other forms of evaluation occur."
3578,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,16,"Yet proposal texts, especially unfunded submissions, are typically confidential, making this stage of the funding pipeline difficult to study systematically at scale."
3579,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,17,"As a result, we lack systematic evidence on how LLM adoption enters the funding pipeline, how it relates to proposal evaluation, and how it shapes the research that ultimately receives public support."
3580,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,18,"At the same time, LLMs represent a potentially transformative development for scientific work 15–21."
3581,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,19,"Recent large-scale evidence shows that the diffusion of LLMs has already been accompanied by sharp increases in scientific production across major preprint platforms, underscoring their potential to substantially raise output at scale16."
3582,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,20,"By dramatically reducing the cost of drafting, synthesizing, and revising complex text, LLMs may help scientists articulate ideas more clearly, navigate the growing burden of knowledge, and explore unfamiliar domains more efficiently27,28."
3583,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,21,"In principle, such tools could accelerate the pace of discovery, lower barriers to entry, facilitate interdisciplinary recombination, and support more effective pivoting across research directions 22,28–31."
3584,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,22,"From this perspective, LLMs hold the promise of expanding scientific exploration and improving the efficiency with which ideas are generated, refined, and communicated32,33."
3585,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,23,Yet these same features also raise critical concerns 32.
3586,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,24,"Because LLMs are trained on large corpora of existing scientific text, including published papers and public records of funded projects, they may tend to produce high- probability, discipline-typical language."
3587,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,25,"When used in proposal preparation, such tools may enhance fluency and alignment with prevailing norms while reducing rhetorical and topical variance, making proposed projects more closely resemble those that have recently succeeded 23,26,34."
3588,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,26,"In this way, LLM use could shift the balance between exploration and exploitation in scientific funding, pulling proposals toward the center of existing funding patterns and potentially narrowing the diversity of ideas that are submitted for or receive public support, even as it may lower the barriers to producing competitive applications29,35."
3589,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,27,"Recent work highlights this tension more broadly, showing that AI can expand individual scientists’ productivity and impact while simultaneously contracting the collective focus of science, underscoring the possibility that gains at the individual level may coexist with reduced diversity at the system level26."
3590,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,28,"Beyond these concerns, a bottlenecks perspective further suggests caution in extrapolating writing-related productivity gains to downstream scientific outputs 36."
3591,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,29,"Discovery is constrained by multiple frictions, from data collection and experimental throughput to coordination, implementation, and more, many of which LLM involve- 2 ment does not directly resolve."
3592,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,30,"Because funding outputs depend on both communication and execution, there are reasons to believe that productivity gains observed in manuscript writing may not translate to the impact of funded projects."
3593,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,31,This distinction makes federal research funding a particularly important context in which to evaluate how LLM adoption reshapes scientific activity.
3594,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,32,"Reflecting the policy relevance of this uncertainty, federal agencies have begun to issue guidance on generative AI in proposal preparation."
3595,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,33,"In July 2025, NIH clarified that applications “substantially developed by AI” will not be considered applicants’ original work (see NOT-OD-25-132), while NSF has emphasized investigator responsibility for accuracy and originality and encouraged disclosure of generative AI use (see Notice to research community)."
3596,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,34,These actions underscore both the growing salience of LLMs in public funding and the need for empirical evidence on how they are being used and with what consequences.
3597,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,35,"Here, we examine LLM use at key stages in the federal funding pipeline by employing two complementary levels of analysis."
3598,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,36,"First, we collect novel datasets containing the complete set of NSF (D1) and NIH (D2) proposal submissions (hereafter private NSF and NIH data) from two large US R1 universities with request start dates from 2021 to 2025, including funded, unfunded, and pending proposals."
3599,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,37,These data offer us a unique opportunity to observe proposal language at the point of submission.
3600,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,38,"Second, we analyze the full population of publicly released NSF (D3) and NIH (D4) award abstracts (hereafter public NSF and NIH data) over the same period, together with publications supported by these awards."
3601,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,39,These data allow us to systematically analyze the funded awards (see Supplementary Note S1 for details on datasets).
3602,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,40,"Overall, these data enable us to characterize the evolution of LLM use in federal funding and to examine how it relates to the positioning of scientific ideas, their selection for funding, and their translation into publicly supported research output."
3603,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,41,"Rapid rise and bimodal distribution of LLM use in US federal research funding To estimate LLM use in federal grant proposals and awards, we analyze textual traces in their abstracts."
3604,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,42,"Specifically, we leverage an established detection method proposed by Lianget al. 15."
3605,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,43,"Using public grant abstracts with start dates in 2021, which preceded the widespread use of LLMs, we estimate the word distribution of human-written text."
3606,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,44,"We also estimate a corresponding word distribution of LLM-generated text by prompting OpenAI’s GPT-3.5- turbo-0125 model to rewrite the same abstracts, simulating LLM involvement in proposal language."
3607,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,45,Comparing these two distributions allows us to identify systematic differences between human and LLM-modified writing (see Supplementary Note S2.1 for details on model training).
3608,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,46,We then apply the detection method at both the corpus and individual grant levels.
3609,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,47,"At the corpus level, we pool grant abstracts for each focal month and its two adjacent months, and we estimate the fraction of LLM-modified sentences (𝛼) within this combined set in each dataset."
3610,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,48,"At the individual grant level, we estimate𝛼separately for each grant abstract in each dataset."
3611,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,49,"These two levels represent complementary estimates, as the corpus-level estimates leverage large volumes of text to capture aggregate LLM use over time, whereas grant-level estimates enable grant-level analyses that capture heterogeneity across grants, allowing us to examine how LLM use relates to semantic distinctiveness and other grant outputs."
3612,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,50,"Figures 1a-d trace the evolution of LLM involvement (𝛼) in NSF and NIH grants across two stages of the funding pipeline, proposal submission and award funding, drawing on confidential proposal submission abstracts (private data) and publicly released award abstracts (public data), respectively."
3613,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,51,"Across all four datasets,𝛼is relatively stable prior to late 2022, and then rises sharply beginning in 2023, coinciding with the widespread availability of ChatGPT. 3 This increase is visible both at the point of submission, when ideas first enter the system, and among funded awards that have passed peer review, indicating that LLM use is not confined to a single stage of the pipeline."
3614,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,52,"Over this period, NIH exhibits the same temporal pattern as NSF but with overall lower average levels of LLM involvement."
3615,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,53,"At the level of individual grants, Figs. 1e-h show that𝛼is not smoothly distributed."
3616,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,54,"Among grants starting in 2023-2025, it features a bimodal distribution, with one mode near zero and a second centered around roughly 10-15%."
3617,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,55,This pattern reveals a clear split: one group of grant abstracts that largely avoids LLM use and another that incorporates LLMs more substantively into proposal preparation.
3618,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,56,"These results indicate that LLM adoption has rapidly become a detectable feature of federal research proposals and awards, but it remains highly uneven across them."
3619,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,57,"This raises the question of whether the heterogeneity is systematically related to the kinds of ideas proposed and funded, or to downstream scientific outputs."
3620,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,58,"Private NSF Private NIH Public NSF Public NIH a b c d e f g h Fig. 1:Rapid rise and bimodal distribution of LLM use in US federal research funding.(a-d) Corpus-level estimates of LLM use (𝛼) for private and public NSF and NIH grants from 2021 to 2025, computed using rolling three-month windows (points)."
3621,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,59,Solid lines show locally weighted regressions.
3622,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,60,"The vertical dashed line marks November 30, 2022, corresponding to the public release of ChatGPT."
3623,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,61,"(e-h) Distributions of individual-grant𝛼for private and public NSF and NIH proposals and awards with start dates between 2023 and 2025, showing a bimodal pattern consistent with a split between minimal and substantive LLM use across grants."
3624,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,62,"LLM use and semantic distinctiveness in US federal research funding The rapid and uneven adoption of LLMs prompts another critical line of inquiry: Is greater LLM involvement associated with a shift in the kinds of ideas that enter, and ultimately shape, the federal research portfolio?"
3625,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,63,"To quantify the positioning of ideas, we measure the semantic distinctiveness of each proposal or award abstract (D1-D4) relative to the agency’s recent funding frontier, building on recent work using transformer-based embeddings26,37."
3626,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,64,"Specifically, for grants starting between 2023 and 2025, we compute each abstract’s average cosine distance (using SPECTER2 38 embeddings, an established embedding method for scientific texts) to all abstracts funded in the previous year within the same agency."
3627,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,65,"We then convert these distances into within-year percentiles, where higher 4 values indicate more distinctive ideas relative to other grants in that agency-year."
3628,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,66,"We relate distinctiveness to LLM involvement (𝛼), estimating regressions that include grant start year, field, and investigator (PI and co-PI) fixed effects, along with controls for requested or awarded funding amount (Supplemen- tary Note S2.2)."
3629,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,67,These fixed effects absorb time-invariant heterogeneity at the field and investigator levels while accounting for common shocks across grant start years.
3630,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,68,"Across all four datasets, including private submissions and public awards for both NSF and NIH, higher𝛼is consistently associated with lower distinctiveness percentiles (Fig. 2, Supplementary Note S2.2, Supplementary Tables S1-S4), indicating that proposals and awards with greater LLM involvement are positioned closer to the grants that the agency funded most recently."
3631,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,69,"For example, for NSF awards, moving from low LLM involvement (25th percentile) to high LLM involvement (75th percentile) corre- sponds to a ˜5-point decrease in the distinctiveness percentile; for NIH awards, the decrease is ˜4 points."
3632,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,70,"Importantly, the investigator fixed effects compare each investigator only to themselves across proposals and awards rather than comparing different investigators to one another."
3633,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,71,"We see that for the same investigator’s proposals and awards, when the LLM involvement is higher, their proposals and awards become systematically less distinctive."
3634,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,72,"These findings suggest that as LLM use rises, the proposal and award portfolio shifts toward the center of recently funded work, providing empirical evidence of idea homogenization in federal research funding that is already occurring across both agencies."
3635,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,73,"Private NSF Private NIH Public NSF Public NIH a b c d Fig. 2:LLM use and semantic distinctiveness in US federal research funding.(a-d) Regression estimates relating grant-level LLM use (𝛼) to semantic distance from abstracts funded in the prior year within the same agency, expressed as within-year percentiles."
3636,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,74,"Panels show results separately for private NSF (a), private NIH (b), public NSF (c), and public NIH (d) grants."
3637,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,75,"All regressions include grant start year, field, and investigator fixed effects, as well as controls for funding amount."
3638,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,76,"Points indicate coefficient estimates, and bars denote 95% confidence intervals."
3639,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,77,"Negative coefficients correspond to proposals and awards that are positioned closer, in semantic space, to recently funded work within the same agency. 5 LLM use and federal research proposal success We next ask whether LLM adoption is associated with a first-order consequence in the funding pipeline: which proposals actually receive funding."
3640,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,78,"Using confidential submissions that include both funded and unfunded proposals (D1-D2), we regress proposal success on proposal-level LLM involvement (𝛼) for request start years 2023-2025, estimating models with request start year, field, and investigator fixed effects and controlling for requested funding (Fig. 3, Supplementary Note S2.2, Supplementary Tables S5-S6)."
3641,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,79,"These fixed effects absorb time-invariant hetero- geneity across research areas and investigators, while accounting for common shocks across years."
3642,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,80,"For example, the investigator fixed effects hold constant time-invariant differences in investigators’ ability, style, and topic choice, asking whether an investigator’s proposals are more likely to be funded when their LLM involvement is higher."
3643,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,81,We find no statistically significant association between𝛼and proposal success for NSF proposals.
3644,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,82,"In contrast, for NIH submissions,𝛼is positively and significantly associated with proposal success."
3645,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,83,"Specifically, moving from low LLM involvement (25th percentile) to high LLM involvement (75th percentile) corresponds to a ˜4-percentage- point jump in NIH funding probability."
3646,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,84,"Overall, these results indicate that the consequences of LLM adoption for proposal selection are strongly agency-dependent: while LLM use does not systematically advantage proposals at NSF, it is associated with a higher likelihood of being funded at NIH, even for the same investigators."
3647,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,85,"This agency-dependent selection pattern raises the question of translation: conditional on being funded, is LLM adoption associated with downstream outputs from these funded projects? a b Private NSF Private NIH Fig. 3:LLM use and federal research proposal success.Based on private NSF and NIH proposal submissions from two large US R1 universities, this figure examines the relationship between LLM use at submission (𝛼) and proposal success."
3648,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,86,(a) Regression estimates for NSF submissions.
3649,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,87,(b) Corresponding estimates for NIH submissions.
3650,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,88,"All regressions include proposal request start year, field, and investigator fixed effects, as well as controls for requested funding amount."
3651,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,89,"Points indicate coefficient estimates, and bars denote 95% confidence intervals."
3652,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,90,"LLM use and federal research funding outputs Using the public NSF and NIH award data (D3-D4), we next relate grant-level LLM involvement (𝛼) to subsequent publication output for grants starting in 2023-2024, estimating regression models that control for funding amount and include grant start year, field, and investigator fixed effects (Fig. 4, Supplementary Note S2.2, Supplementary Tables S7-S12). 6 We again find no statistically significant relationship between𝛼and publication output for NSF awards (Fig. 4a)."
3653,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,91,"However, for NIH awards, higher𝛼is strongly associated with more resulting publications (Fig. 4b)."
3654,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,92,Moving from low LLM involvement (25th percentile) to high LLM involvement (75th percentile) predicts ˜5% more publications for NIH grants.
3655,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,93,"Moreover, this NIH productivity premium appears mostly concentrated in publication volume rather than high-impact outputs: when we restrict our analyses to highly-cited papers (e.g., top 5% papers in Figs. 4c-d; top 1% in Supplementary Fig."
3656,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,94,"S1), the relationship attenuates and is no longer statistically significant at conventional levels."
3657,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,95,"Taken together, these results suggest that the downstream consequences of LLM adoption are also agency-dependent."
3658,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,96,"At NIH, higher𝛼is associated with more follow-on publications, but the additional output is concentrated in non-hit papers rather than the most highly-cited work."
3659,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,97,These productivity patterns both align with and qualify recent evidence of large output gains following LLM diffusion in manuscript production 16.
3660,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,98,"While we observe a positive association between LLM involvement and publication output for NIH-funded grants, the magnitude of this association is smaller than the large increases documented in preprint production and is strongly agency-dependent, with no detectable relationship at NSF."
3661,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,99,"In the federal funding context, where projects are selected through peer review and outputs reflect execution constraints and portfolio objectives rather than writing speed alone, LLM adoption appears to translate into additional publications primarily at NIH, and predominantly among non-hit papers, while showing no detectable relationship with publication output at NSF. a b c d Public NSF # papers # hit papers (5%) Public NIH Fig. 4:LLM use and federal research funding outputs.(a-b) Regression estimates relating grant-level LLM use (𝛼) to the total number of resulting publications for NSF (a) and NIH (b) grants."
3662,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,100,"(c-d) Corresponding estimates for high-impact outputs, where a “hit” paper is defined as one whose citations fall within the top 5% of all papers published worldwide in the same year and field."
3663,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,101,"All regressions include grant start year, field, and investigator fixed effects, as well as controls for funding amount."
3664,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,102,"Points indicate coefficient estimates, and bars denote 95% confidence intervals. 7 Robustness and sensitivity checks We conduct a series of robustness and sensitivity checks across numerous dimensions."
3665,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,103,"First, to better characterize proposals and awards with higher LLM involvement, we follow prior work 16 and compute the Flesch Reading Ease score for each abstract as a measure of writing complexity (Supplementary Note S3.1)."
3666,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,104,"Consistent with prior work16, we find that higher LLM involvement is positively associated with greater writing complexity in both proposals and awards (Supplementary Fig."
3667,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,105,"Second, recent work has shown that the use of promotional language in grant proposals is positively associated with funding outputs and related proposal characteristics14."
3668,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,106,"To assess the extent to which our results may be driven by promotional words, we conduct a robustness analysis that explicitly removes promotional words at all stages of our text processing pipeline."
3669,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,107,"The resulting LLM-use measures remain highly similar to the original estimates across all datasets, indicating that our results are robust to the exclusion of promotional words (Supplementary Note S3.2, Supplementary Fig."
3670,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,108,"Third, in the main analysis of semantic distinctiveness, we define the comparison set using grants funded in the preceding year."
3671,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,109,"We redefine the comparison set using funded grants starting in the prior two years, finding the results are robust (Supplementary Note S3.3, Supplementary Fig."
3672,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,110,"Fourth, while our primary measure of semantic distinctiveness relies on cosine distances between embedding vectors, we also compute distances using L2 metrics and obtain consistent results (Supplementary Note S3.4, Supplementary Fig."
3673,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,111,"Fifth, in our primary specifications, we use ordinary least squares regressions."
3674,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,112,"We re-estimate proposal success using logistic regressions and publication outputs using negative binomial regressions and continue to observe the same associations between𝛼and outcomes (Supplementary Note S3.5, Supplementary Figs."
3675,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,113,"We further examine robustness by field using public award data where sample sizes are sufficiently large to support field-level analyses and find broadly consistent results (Supplementary Note S3.6, Supplementary Figs."
3676,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,114,"Lastly, we conduct analogous robustness checks by subagency using the public award data and again find broadly consistent patterns (Supplementary Note S3.7, Supplementary Figs."
3677,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,115,"Discussion Overall, our findings reveal that the rapid diffusion of LLMs is already reshaping key stages of the US federal research funding pipeline, from proposal submission to downstream scientific output."
3678,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,116,"By combining confidential proposal submissions with the full population of NSF and NIH awards, we provide systematic evidence that LLM adoption is associated with (i) how scientific ideas are positioned relative to recent funded work, (ii) whether proposals clear the funding threshold, and (iii) the publication output that funded projects go on to produce."
3679,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,117,"These results show that generative AI is not only changing how scientific text is produced, but also beginning to reshape the composition and consequences of public investment in research."
3680,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,118,"A central concern in science policy is maintaining a diverse and exploratory research portfolio, one that supports both cumulative progress and the pursuit of unconventional ideas."
3681,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,119,"Across both agencies and both stages (proposal submission and award funding), higher LLM involvement is consistently associated with lower semantic distinctiveness: proposals with greater LLM traces are positioned closer to recently funded work within the same agency."
3682,11,C011_P1_pdf.txt,120,This pattern echoes recent evidence that AI tools can expand individual scientists’ productivity and impact 8
3683,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,0,Can LLMs Generate Novel Research Ideas?
3684,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,1,"A Large-Scale Human Study with 100+ NLP Researchers Chenglei Si, Diyi Yang, Tatsunori Hashimoto Stanford University {clsi, diyiy, thashim}@stanford.edu Abstract Recent advancements in large language models (LLMs) have sparked optimism about their potential to accelerate scientific discovery, with a growing number of works proposing research agents that autonomously generate and validate new ideas."
3685,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,2,"Despite this, no evaluations have shown that LLM systems can take the very first step of producing novel, expert-level ideas, let alone perform the entire research process."
3686,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,3,We address this by establishing an experimental design that evaluates research idea generation while controlling for confounders and performs the first head-to-head comparison between expert NLP researchers and an LLM ideation agent.
3687,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,4,"By recruiting over 100 NLP researchers to write novel ideas and blind reviews of both LLM and human ideas, we obtain the first statistically significant conclusion on current LLM capabilities for research ideation: we find LLM-generated ideas are judged as more novel (p < 0.05) than human expert ideas while being judged slightly weaker on feasibility."
3688,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,5,"Studying our agent baselines closely, we identify open problems in building and evaluating research agents, including failures of LLM self-evaluation and their lack of diversity in generation."
3689,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,6,"Finally, we acknowledge that human judgements of novelty can be difficult, even by experts, and propose an end-to-end study design which recruits researchers to execute these ideas into full projects, enabling us to study whether these novelty and feasibility judgements result in meaningful differences in research outcome.1 1 Introduction The rapid improvement of LLMs, especially in capabilities like knowledge and reasoning, has enabled many new applications in scientific tasks, such as solving challenging mathematical problems (Trinh et al., 2024), assisting scientists in writing proofs (Collins et al., 2024), retrieving related works (Ajith et al., 2024, Press et al., 2024), generating code to solve analytical or computational tasks (Huang et al., 2024, Tian et al., 2024), and discovering patterns in large text corpora (Lam et al., 2024, Zhong et al., 2023)."
3690,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,7,"While these are useful applications that can potentially increase the productivity of researchers, it remains an open question whether LLMs can take on the more creative and challenging parts of the research process."
3691,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,8,We focus on this problem of measuring theresearch ideation capabilities of LLMs and ask: are current LLMs capable of generating novel ideas that are comparable to expert humans?
3692,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,9,"Although ideation is only one part of the research process, this is a key question to answer, as it is the very first step to the scientific research process and serves as a litmus test for the possibility of autonomous research agents that create their own ideas."
3693,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,10,Evaluating expert-level capabilities of LLM systems is challenging (Bakhtin 1Interested researchers can sign up for this end-to-end study at:https://tinyurl.com/execution-study.
3694,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,11,"We release our agent implementation and all human review scores at:https://github.com/NoviScl/AI-Researcher. ∗The last two authors advised this project equally. 1 arXiv:2409.04109v1 [cs.CL] 6 Sep 2024 7 N L P  T o p i c s B i a s C o d i n g S a f e t y M u l t i l i n g u a l F a c t u a l i t y M a t h U n c e r t a i n t y H u m a n  E x p e r t s A I  A g e n t C o n d i t i o n 1 : H u m a n I d e a s ( N = 4 9 ) C o n d i t i o n 2 : A I I d e a s ( N = 4 9 ) C o n d i t i o n 3 : A I I d e a s + H u m a n R e r a n k ( N = 4 9 ) B l i n d R e v i e w b y E x p e r t s ( N = 7 9 ) N o v e l t y S c o r e : 4 . 8 4  N o v e l t y S c o r e : 5 . 6 4 N o v e l t y S c o r e : 5 . 8 1 I d e a G e n e r a t i o n Figure 1: Overview of our study: we recruit 79 expert researchers to perform blind review of 49 ideas from each of the three conditions: expert-written ideas, AI-generated ideas, and AI-generated ideas reranked by a human expert."
3695,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,12,We standardize the format and style of ideas from all conditions before the blind review.
3696,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,13,We find AI ideas are judged as significantly more novel than human ideas (p <0.05).
3697,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,14,Human AI AI+Rerank3 4 5 6 7Score * * Novelty Human AI AI+Rerank3 4 5 6 7 * Excitement Human AI AI+Rerank3 4 5 6 7 Feasibility Human AI AI+Rerank3 4 5 6 7 Effectiveness Human AI AI+Rerank3 4 5 6 7 * Overall Figure 2: Comparison of the three experiment conditions across all review metrics.
3698,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,15,Red asterisks indicate that the condition is statistically better than theHuman baseline with two-tailed Welch’s t-tests and Bonferroni correction.
3699,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,16,All scores are on a 1 to 10 scale.
3700,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,17,"More detailed results are in Section 5. et al., 2022, Collins et al., 2024), and research ideation takes this to an extreme."
3701,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,18,"Qualified expert re- searchers are difficult to recruit at scale, evaluation criteria can be highly subjective, and it is difficult for even the best experts to judge the quality of an idea (Beygelzimer et al., 2021, Simsek et al., 2024)."
3702,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,19,"We address these challenges directly, recognizing that for important, high-stakes tasks like research ideation, there is no substitute for a large-scale expert evaluation."
3703,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,20,We design a carefully controlled comparison of human and LLM ideas that overcomes sample size and baseline problems present in earlier small-scale evaluation studies.
3704,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,21,Our study recruited a large pool of over 100 highly qualified NLP researchers to produce human baseline ideas and perform blind reviews of human and LLM ideas.
3705,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,22,"To reduce the possibility that confounding variables affect our outcome measures, we enforce strict controls that standardize the styles of human and LLM ideas and match their topic distribution."
3706,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,23,"We compare our human expert baseline with a simple and effective LLM agent that incorporates retrieval augmentation and adopts recent ideas in inference-time scaling, such as overgenerating and reranking LM outputs."
3707,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,24,"These measures allow us to make statistically rigorous comparisons between human experts and state-of-the-art LLMs (Figure 1). 2 Our evaluation-centric approach complements many recent methods-centric works that attempt to instantiate research agents (Baek et al., 2024, Li et al., 2024, Lu et al., 2024, Wang et al., 2024, Yang et al., 2024)."
3708,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,25,"The majority of these works rely on fast and lower-cost evaluation surrogates – either by decreas- ing the number of expert reviewers (Baek et al., 2024, Li et al., 2024, Wang et al., 2024, Yang et al., 2024), constraining the length and detailedness of the ideas (Wang et al., 2024, Yang et al., 2024), or relying on LLM-as-a-judge (Lu et al., 2024)."
3709,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,26,They do not perform the large-scale human comparison studies that are needed to answer the motivating question of our work.
3710,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,27,"Our work takes the opposite approach, performing a year-long and high-cost evaluation that provides human expert baselines and a stan- dardized evaluation protocol to serve as a foundation for future follow-up studies and methods work."
3711,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,28,"Through nearly 300 reviews across all our conditions, we find that AI-generated ideas are judged as more novel than human expert ideas (p <0.05), which holds robustly under multiple hypothesis correction and across different statistical tests."
3712,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,29,"We find some signs that these gains are correlated with excitement and overall score, and may come at the slight expense of feasibility, but our study size did not have sufficient power to conclusively identify these effects (Figure 2)."
3713,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,30,Qualitative analysis of free-text responses in our review corroborates these findings on novelty and feasibility.
3714,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,31,"Apart from evaluating the ideas, we also analyze the LLM agent, showing limitations and open problems – despite excitement about inference-time scaling of LLMs, we find that they lack idea diversity when we scale up idea generation, and they cannot currently serve as reliable evaluators. 2 Problem Setup The central experiment of our work is a comparison of human- and LLM-generated ideas."
3715,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,32,"While this goal is simple, there is no existing consensus on how to formulate the task of research ideation and evaluation, and we begin by defining the key aspects of our experiment design."
3716,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,33,"We think of research idea evaluation as consisting of three separate components: 1). the idea itself, generated in response to our instructions, 2). the writeup which communicates the idea, and 3). the evaluation of the writeup by experts."
3717,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,34,"We outline our experiment design in each of these three parts with particular focus on potential confounders, such as the area of research, the format of a research idea, and the evaluation process."
3718,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,35,Ideation Scope and Instructions Research ideas can take many different forms.
3719,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,36,"They can be simple tricks to improve model performance, or they may be large-scale research programs that form the basis of a Ph.D. thesis."
3720,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,37,Any experiment on ideation must carefully balance the realisticness and interestingness of a research idea with the practical realities of eliciting ideas from a large population.
3721,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,38,"In our case, these tradeoffs are even more pronounced, as we have designed our ideation experiments so that the resulting ideas can be executed by experts in a follow-up set of experiments."
3722,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,39,These constraints have led us to study prompting-based NLP research as a testbed for our study.
3723,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,40,"Prompting research has been popular in recent years of NLP and AI research (e.g., Chen et al., 2023, Diao et al., 2024, Madaan et al., 2023, Qin et al., 2024, Schulhoff et al., 2024, Si et al., 2023, Wang et al., 2023, Wei et al., 2022, Yao et al., 2023, Yasunaga et al., 2024, Zhou et al., 2023, inter alia)."
3724,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,41,This class of projects strikes a reasonable trade-off among our constraints.
3725,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,42,"The most impactful prompting projects like chain-of-thought have had a major influence on LLM performance (Wei et al., 2022), and prompting projects are executable with minimal computing hardware."
3726,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,43,We further structure our ideation process to avoid selection-bias-based confounders in ideation.
3727,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,44,"If we simply ask LLMs and humans to produce ideas on ‘prompting topics’, we may find that LLMs and humans differ in the types of research ideas they produce (for example, LLMs may naturally suggest more projects on safer topics, which might be judged as less exciting by humans)."
3728,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,45,"This would 3 lead us to simply measure misalignment in research topic preference between LLMs and humans, which is not the goal of our study."
3729,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,46,"To address this possibility, we define a set of seven specific research topics extracted from the Call For Papers page of recent NLP conferences such as COLM.2 Specifically, our topics include: Bias, Coding, Safety, Multilinguality, Factuality, Math, and Uncertainty (see Appendix A for a complete description of these topics)."
3730,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,47,"Each human and LLM participant of the ideation experiment receives the same set of natural language instructions including the same topic description, idea template, and demonstration example to ensure a fair comparison."
3731,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,48,"For human participants, we additionally allow them to select a preferred topic from the list, and for each selected topic, we generate a corresponding LLM idea."
3732,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,49,"This exactly matches the idea topic distribution between the LLM and human participants, while ensuring that human experts are able to select topics according to their expertise."
3733,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,50,"Idea Writeup An idea can only be evaluated if it is written up to be communicated, but this writing process introduces many additional potential confounders."
3734,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,51,"Human researchers may write in ways that subtly signal quality research, such as including more examples and implementation details."
3735,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,52,The format of the writeup functions as a way to scaffold what contents should be included and the level of detailedness.
3736,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,53,"Ideally, we want both human and LLM participants to provide all the necessary implementation details for their generated ideas."
3737,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,54,We take inspiration from guidelines used in grant submissions and introduce a template to specify the structure and detailedness of idea proposals.
3738,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,55,"Specifically, we construct a template that includes fields for the title, problem statement, motivation, proposed method, step-by-step experiment plan, test case examples, and the fallback plan."
3739,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,56,Both the LLM agent and the human idea writers are instructed to follow this template and our provided demonstration examples to produce a project proposal as the output (see Appendix B for the full template and Appendix C for the demo example).
3740,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,57,"Even with these templates, there may be subtle writing style cues that affect the outcome measure."
3741,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,58,"For example, humans may tend to write in a more engaging and informal tone."
3742,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,59,"To reduce this possibility further, we developed a style normalization module that uses an LLM to convert all ideas into the same writing and formatting style without changing the original content."
3743,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,60,Our small-scale human study shows that such a normalization approach leads to a 50% accuracy for expert human judges who are asked to distinguish AI ideas from human ideas.
3744,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,61,"Finally, the use of an LLM style anonymizer has the possibility of substantively changing the content of the ideas."
3745,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,62,"To rule this out, the first author of this paper manually verified each human idea proposal to ensure all contents of the original ideas were preserved."
3746,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,63,We present the full prompt used in Appendix D.
3747,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,64,"Review and Evaluation Reviewing research ideas is notoriously subjective, so we want to design a review form that defines all review criteria clearly to standardize and anchor the evaluations as much as possible."
3748,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,65,"At the same time, we want our review criteria and measured variables to capture all the desiderata of high-quality research ideas."
3749,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,66,"We follow best practices from AI conference reviewing (e.g., ICLR and ACL) when designing the review form, where we define four breakdown metrics including novelty, excitement, feasibility, and expected effectiveness, apart from the overall score."
3750,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,67,"For each metric, we ask for a numerical score on a 1-10 scale along with a free-text rationale."
3751,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,68,We provide clear definitions and grounding for each numerical scale to calibrate all reviewers’ standards (see Appendix E for the full review form).
3752,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,69,Our blind review evaluation will compare ideas from three different conditions: 1.
3753,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,70,Human Ideas : Idea proposals written by our recruited expert researchers. 2https://colmweb.org/cfp.html 4 2.
3754,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,71,AI Ideas : Idea proposals generated by our LLM agent.
3755,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,72,We directly take the top-ranked ideas from the agent’s output. 3.
3756,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,73,AI Ideas + Human Rerank : Idea proposals generated by our LLM agent.
3757,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,74,The first author of this paper manually selected the top-ranked ideas out of all the LLM agent’s generations rather than relying on the LLM ranker in order to better estimate the upper-bound quality of AI ideas.
3758,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,75,"In the next two sections, we instantiate how our LLM agent generates ideas and how our expert participants generate and review the ideas. 3 Idea Generation Agent We build a simple but effective LLM ideation agent to compare with the human expert baseline."
3759,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,76,"Rather than focusing on innovating the agent itself, we adhere to a minimalist design principle, aiming to understand the current capabilities of LLMs in idea generation."
3760,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,77,"Our research ideation agent has three essential components: paper retrieval, idea generation, and idea ranking, which we will describe in detail below. 3.1 Paper Retrieval for RAG To ground idea generation, the agent needs to retrieve papers related to the given research topic, so that it will be aware of related works when generating new ideas."
3761,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,78,"To do so, we lever- age retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), which has demonstrated effectiveness on many knowledge-intensive tasks (Lewis et al., 2020, Shi et al., 2024)."
3762,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,79,"Concretely, given a research topic (e.g., “novel prompting methods that can improve factuality and reduce hallucination of large language models""), we prompt an LLM to generate a sequence of function calls to the Semantic Scholar API."
3763,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,80,We use claude-3-5-sonnet-20240620 as the backbone model for our agent but the pipeline should generalize to other LLMs as well.
3764,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,81,"The paper retrieval action space includes: {KeywordQuery(keywords), PaperQuery(paperId), GetReferences(paperId) }."
3765,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,82,Each action generation is grounded on the previous actions and executed results.
3766,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,83,We keep the topk = 20 papers from each executed function call and stop the action generation when a max ofN = 120papers have been retrieved.
3767,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,84,We then use the LLM to score and rerank all retrieved papers based on three criteria: 1) the paper should be directly relevant to the specified topic; 2) the paper should be an empirical paper involving computational experiments;3 3) the paper is interesting and can inspire new projects.
3768,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,85,The LLM is prompted to score each retrieved paper on a scale of 1 to 10 based on these criteria and we use the top-ranked papers for the next step of idea generation. 3.2 Idea Generation Our key insight for idea generation is to generate as many candidate ideas as possible.
3769,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,86,"Our intuition is that only a small fraction of all generated ideas might be high-quality, and we should be willing to expend inference-time compute to generate more candidates so that we can later use a reranker to discover the ""diamond in the rough""."
3770,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,87,"This aligns with existing results showing that scaling inference compute with repeated sampling can boost LLM performance on various coding and reasoning tasks (Brown et al., 2024, Li et al., 2022)."
3771,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,88,"Specifically, we prompt the LLM to generate 4000 seed ideas on each research topic."
3772,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,89,The idea generation prompt includes the demonstration examples and the retrieved papers.
3773,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,90,"We craftk = 6 demonstration examples by manually summarizing exemplar 3Note that we exclude position papers, survey papers, and analysis papers throughout this study since their evaluation tends to be very subjective. 5 papers (Dhuliawala et al., 2023, Madaan et al., 2023, Weller et al., 2023, Weston and Sukhbaatar, 2023, Yasunaga et al., 2024, Zheng et al., 2024) into our desired idea format."
3774,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,91,"For retrieval augmentation, we randomly selectk = 10papers from the top-ranked retrieved papers and concatenate their titles and abstracts to prepend to the idea generation prompt."
3775,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,92,We also append the titles of all previously generated ideas to the prompt to explicitly ask the LLM to avoid repetitions.
3776,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,93,"To remove duplicated ideas from this large pool of candidate ideas, we first perform a round of dedu- plication by encoding all seed ideas withall-MiniLM-L6-v2 from Sentence-Transformers (Reimers and Gurevych, 2020) and then computing pairwise cosine similarities."
3777,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,94,We set a similarity threshold of 0.8 for the idea deduplication based on manual inspection.4 This leaves about 5% non-duplicated ideas out of all the generated seed ideas.
3778,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,95,We expand more on this duplication issue later in Section 7.1. 3.3 Idea Ranking The next step is for our ideation agent to rank all the remaining ideas so that we can find the best ones among them.
3779,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,96,"To build such an automatic idea ranker, we use public review data as a proxy."
3780,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,97,"Specifically, we scraped 1200 ICLR 2024 submissions related to LLMs (with keyword filtering) along with their review scores and acceptance decisions."
3781,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,98,"We explored multiple ways of predicting the scores and decisions of these submissions and found that LLMs are poorly calibrated when asked directly to predict the final scores or decisions, but can achieve non-trivial accuracy when asked to judge which paper is better in pairwise comparisons."
3782,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,99,"N Top-10 Bottom-10 Gap 1 6.28 5.72 0.56 2 6.14 5.24 0.90 3 5.83 4.86 0.97 4 5.94 4.99 0.95 5 6.42 4.69 1.73 6 6.11 4.81 1.30 Table 1: Average ICLR review scores of top- and bottom-10 papers ranked by our LLM ranker, with different rounds (N) of pairwise comparisons."
3783,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,100,We converted the ICLR submissions into our stan- dard project proposal format and randomly paired up accepted and rejected papers and asked LLMs to predict which one is accepted.
3784,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,101,"On this task, Claude-3.5-Sonnet achieves an accuracy of 71.4% with zero-shot prompting."
3785,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,102,"For comparison, GPT-4o achieves 61.1% and Claude-3-Opus achieves 63.5%, and we do not observe significant gains from addi- tional prompting techniques like few-shot or chain- of-thought prompting."
3786,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,103,We therefore choose the Claude-3.5-Sonnet zero-shot ranker.
3787,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,104,"In order to obtain reliable scores for all project proposals based on pairwise comparisons, we adopt a Swiss system tournament where all project proposals are paired with those whose accumulated scores are similar, and if the proposals are judged to be better, they gain an additional point."
3788,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,105,"We repeat this forN rounds so the total score of each project proposal will be within the [0, N] range."
3789,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,106,"As a sanity check, we use theClaude-3.5-Sonnet ranker to rank the 1.2K ICLR LLM-related submissions and compare the average review scores of the top 10 ranked papers and the bottom 10 ranked papers in Table 1."
3790,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,107,"We see a clear separation between the top and bottom ranked papers, indicating the effectiveness of the LLM ranker."
3791,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,108,We chooseN = 5for all our experiments since it gives the best ranking result on this validation set.
3792,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,109,The top-ranked project proposals from the agent will be directly used for theAI Ideas condition of the human study.
3793,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,110,"Since our AI ranker is still far from perfect, we also introduce another experiment condition where the first author of this paper manually reranked the generated project proposals instead of relying on the LLM ranker, and we call this the AI Ideas + Human Rerank condition."
3794,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,111,As we show in 4We provide randomly sampled idea pairs and their similarities in Appendix H.
3795,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,112,"We also provide additional implementa- tion details about the ideation agent in Appendix F. 6 Table 12, 17 out of the 49 ideas in theAI Ideas + Human Rerank condition overlap with the AI Ideas condition, while the other 32 are different, indicating the discrepancy between the LLM ranker and the human expert reranking. 4 Expert Idea Writing and Reviewing In this section, we shift focus to the human branch of idea generation comparison."
3796,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,113,"We present the details of our human study, including information about the recruited experts, the human idea generation task, and the subsequent review process. 4.1 Expert Recruitment We recruit our expert participants (including for idea writing and reviewing) by sending sign-up forms to several channels, including: 1) the OpenNLP Slack channel with 1426 NLP researchers from 71 institutions (with consent from the channel manager); 2) Twitter (X); 3) Slack channels of various NLP groups by direct communication with the group members; and 4) official chat app of the NAACL 2024 conference."
3797,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,114,We also conducted in-person recruitment by giving out name cards and wearing T-shirts 5 with sign-up links at the NAACL 2024 conference as well as various other local NLP social events.
3798,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,115,Our study has been approved by the Stanford IRB (ID 74246).
3799,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,116,We performed screening on all the US participants6 based on their provided Google Scholar profiles.
3800,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,117,We set a minimum requirement of having published at least one paper at a major AI venue.7 We reached out to all participants who satisfied this requirement with the consent form and followed up with the annotation documents for those who consented to participate.
3801,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,118,"In the end, we recruitedN = 49experts for writing ideas, andN = 79experts for reviewing ideas."
3802,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,119,"Note that 24 out of the 79 reviewers also participated in the idea writing, and we made sure no reviewer would review their own idea."
3803,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,120,This results in N = 104 total participants across the two tasks.
3804,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,121,"Each idea writer is asked to write one idea within 10 days and we compensate $300 for each, with a $1000 bonus for the top 5 ideas as scored by the expert reviewers."
3805,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,122,Each idea reviewer is assigned 2 to 7 ideas to review and we collectedN = 298 unique reviews in total.
3806,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,123,They are given one week to finish the reviews and we compensated $25 for each review written by the idea reviewers. 4.2 Expert Qualifications PhD 73% Master 18% Other 8% PhD 79% Master 6% Other 5% Postdoc 8% Figure 3: Positions of our idea writer (left) and reviewer (right) participants.
3807,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,124,Our pool of participants is highly qualified and diverse.
3808,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,125,The 49 idea writers come from 26 different institutions (Ta- ble 15) and the majority of them are current PhD students (Figure 3 left).
3809,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,126,The 79 reviewers come from 32 institutions (Table 16) and are mostly PhD students and Postdocs (Fig- ure 3 right).
3810,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,127,"We use their Google Scholar profiles to extract several proxy metrics, including the number of papers, citations, h-index, and i10-index at the time of their submis- sion."
3811,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,128,"Table 2 shows that our idea writers have an average of 12 papers and 477 citations, while every reviewer has published at least two papers and has an average citation of 635 and h-index of 7."
3812,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,129,"Moreover, based on their survey 5https://x.com/ChengleiSi/status/1804273510656749649 6We have to recruit participants located in the US due to logistical reasons. 7E.g., *ACL, NeurIPS, ICLR, ICML, AAAI. 7 Idea Writing Participants (N=49) Idea Reviewing Participants (N=79) Metric Mean Median Min Max SD Mean Median Min Max SD papers 12 10 2 52 9 15 13 2 52 10 citations 477 125 2 4553 861 635 327 0 7276 989 h-index 5 4 1 21 4 7 7 0 21 4 i10-index 5 4 0 32 6 7 5 0 32 6 Table 2: Research profile metrics of the idea writing and reviewing participants."
3813,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,130,Data are extracted from Google Scholar at the time of idea or review submission.
3814,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,131,"Metric Mean Median Min Max SD Human Ideas Familiarity (1-5) 3.7 4.0 1.0 5.0 1.0 Difficulty (1-5) 3.0 3.0 1.0 5.0 0.7 Time (Hours) 5.5 5.0 2.0 15.0 2.7 Length (Words) 901.7 876.0 444.0 1704.0 253.5 AI Ideas Length (Words) 1186.3 1158.0 706.0 1745.0 233.7 AI + Human Rerank Ideas Length (Words) 1174.0 1166.0 706.0 1708.0 211.0 Table 3: Statistics of the 49 ideas from each condition. responses, 72 out of the 79 reviewers have previously reviewed for major AI conferences or journals."
3815,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,132,These statistics indicate that our participants are highly qualified and have substantial research experience. 8 4.3 Idea Writing Topic Count Bias 4 Coding 9 Safety 5 Multilingual 10 Factuality 11 Math 4 Uncertainty 6 Total 49 Table 4: Idea topic distribution.
3816,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,133,We report statistics of our idea writers’ ideas to measure their quality.
3817,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,134,"As shown in Table 3, idea writers indicate a moderately high familiarity with their selected topic (3.7 on a 1 to 5 scale), and indicate the task as moderately difficult (3 on a 1 to 5 scale)."
3818,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,135,They spent an average of 5.5 hours on the task and their ideas are 902 words long on average.
3819,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,136,These indicate that participants are putting substantial effort into this task.9 We also show the distribution of their selected topics in Table 4. 4.4 Idea Reviewing Review Assignment We let all reviewer participants select their top two preferred topics as well as their preferred reviewing load (from 2 to 7).
3820,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,137,We then randomly assign them to ideas within their selected topics and all ideas are anonymized.
3821,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,138,"In the assignment, we balance the number of ideas from each condition for each reviewer and ensure that each reviewer gets at least one human idea and one AI idea."
3822,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,139,Every idea is reviewed by 2 to 4 different reviewers.
3823,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,140,We also avoid assigning ideas written by authors from the same institution to avoid any potential contamination.
3824,11,C011_S1_pdf.txt,141,"Table 5 shows that each reviewer wrote an average of 3.8 reviews from 2 or 3 conditions, across 1 to 3 topics. 8Detailed breakdown of participant positions is in Appendix K. 9See Appendix J for more details on the quality control of human ideas. 8"
3825,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,0,"The Rise of Large Language Models and the Direction and Impact of US Federal Research Funding Yifan Qian1,2,3,4, Zhe Wen1,2,3,4, Alexander C."
3826,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,1,"Furnas1,2,3,4, Yue Bai1,2,3,4, Erzhuo Shao1,2,3,5, and Dashun Wang1,2,3,4,5,* 1Center for Science of Science and Innovation, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL, USA 2Ryan Institute on Complexity, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL, USA 3Northwestern Innovation Institute, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL, USA 4Kellogg School of Management, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL, USA 5McCormick School of Engineering, Northwestern University, Evanston, IL, USA *Correspondence to: dashun.wang@kellogg.northwestern.edu Abstract Federal research funding shapes the direction, diversity, and impact of the US scientific enterprise."
3827,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,2,"Large language models (LLMs) are rapidly diffusing into scientific practice, holding substantial promise while raising widespread concerns."
3828,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,3,"Despite growing attention to AI use in scientific writing and evaluation, little is known about how the rise of LLMs is reshaping the public funding landscape."
3829,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,4,"Here, we examine LLM involvement at key stages of the federal funding pipeline by combining two complementary data sources: confidential National Science Foundation (NSF) and National Institutes of Health (NIH) proposal submissions from two large US R1 universities, including funded, unfunded, and pending proposals, and the full population of publicly released NSF and NIH awards."
3830,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,5,"We find that LLM use rises sharply beginning in 2023 and exhibits a bimodal distribution, indicating a clear split between minimal and substantive use."
3831,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,6,"Across both private submissions and public awards, higher LLM involvement is consistently associated with lower semantic distinctiveness, positioning projects closer to recently funded work within the same agency."
3832,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,7,The consequences of this shift are agency-dependent.
3833,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,8,"LLM use is positively associated with proposal success and higher subsequent publication output at NIH, whereas no comparable associations are observed at NSF."
3834,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,9,"Notably, the productivity gains at NIH are concentrated in non-hit papers rather than the most highly cited work."
3835,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,10,"Together, these findings provide large-scale evidence that the rise of LLMs is reshaping how scientific ideas are positioned, selected, and translated into publicly funded research, with implications for portfolio governance, research diversity, and the long-run impact of science. 1 arXiv:2601.15485v1 [cs.DL] 21 Jan 2026 Introduction Federal research funding is the primary mechanism through which the United States converts public resources into scientific knowledge1,2."
3836,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,11,"Through competitive grant programs at agencies such as the National Science Foundation (NSF) and the National Institutes of Health (NIH), decisions about the allocation of taxpayer dollars influence which scientific ideas receive support, which fields advance, and which investigators are able to initiate and sustain research programs3–10."
3837,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,12,"Thus, the federal funding process plays a central role in shaping the direction, diversity, and long-run impact of the US scientific enterprise and—given America’s scientific leadership—the global research landscape as well 3–10."
3838,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,13,"Understanding forces that influence this process is therefore essential not only for science policy and the rate and direction of scientific progress, but also for the stewardship and accountability of public investment in research11–14."
3839,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,14,"Despite growing attention to the use of AI in science 15–26, little is known about how the rise of large language models (LLMs) is reshaping the public funding landscape."
3840,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,15,"This gap is consequential, as funding decisions operate upstream of publication, hiring, and recognition, shaping which scientific ideas are pursued long before other forms of evaluation occur."
3841,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,16,"Yet proposal texts, especially unfunded submissions, are typically confidential, making this stage of the funding pipeline difficult to study systematically at scale."
3842,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,17,"As a result, we lack systematic evidence on how LLM adoption enters the funding pipeline, how it relates to proposal evaluation, and how it shapes the research that ultimately receives public support."
3843,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,18,"At the same time, LLMs represent a potentially transformative development for scientific work 15–21."
3844,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,19,"Recent large-scale evidence shows that the diffusion of LLMs has already been accompanied by sharp increases in scientific production across major preprint platforms, underscoring their potential to substantially raise output at scale16."
3845,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,20,"By dramatically reducing the cost of drafting, synthesizing, and revising complex text, LLMs may help scientists articulate ideas more clearly, navigate the growing burden of knowledge, and explore unfamiliar domains more efficiently27,28."
3846,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,21,"In principle, such tools could accelerate the pace of discovery, lower barriers to entry, facilitate interdisciplinary recombination, and support more effective pivoting across research directions 22,28–31."
3847,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,22,"From this perspective, LLMs hold the promise of expanding scientific exploration and improving the efficiency with which ideas are generated, refined, and communicated32,33."
3848,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,23,Yet these same features also raise critical concerns 32.
3849,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,24,"Because LLMs are trained on large corpora of existing scientific text, including published papers and public records of funded projects, they may tend to produce high- probability, discipline-typical language."
3850,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,25,"When used in proposal preparation, such tools may enhance fluency and alignment with prevailing norms while reducing rhetorical and topical variance, making proposed projects more closely resemble those that have recently succeeded 23,26,34."
3851,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,26,"In this way, LLM use could shift the balance between exploration and exploitation in scientific funding, pulling proposals toward the center of existing funding patterns and potentially narrowing the diversity of ideas that are submitted for or receive public support, even as it may lower the barriers to producing competitive applications29,35."
3852,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,27,"Recent work highlights this tension more broadly, showing that AI can expand individual scientists’ productivity and impact while simultaneously contracting the collective focus of science, underscoring the possibility that gains at the individual level may coexist with reduced diversity at the system level26."
3853,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,28,"Beyond these concerns, a bottlenecks perspective further suggests caution in extrapolating writing-related productivity gains to downstream scientific outputs 36."
3854,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,29,"Discovery is constrained by multiple frictions, from data collection and experimental throughput to coordination, implementation, and more, many of which LLM involve- 2 ment does not directly resolve."
3855,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,30,"Because funding outputs depend on both communication and execution, there are reasons to believe that productivity gains observed in manuscript writing may not translate to the impact of funded projects."
3856,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,31,This distinction makes federal research funding a particularly important context in which to evaluate how LLM adoption reshapes scientific activity.
3857,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,32,"Reflecting the policy relevance of this uncertainty, federal agencies have begun to issue guidance on generative AI in proposal preparation."
3858,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,33,"In July 2025, NIH clarified that applications “substantially developed by AI” will not be considered applicants’ original work (see NOT-OD-25-132), while NSF has emphasized investigator responsibility for accuracy and originality and encouraged disclosure of generative AI use (see Notice to research community)."
3859,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,34,These actions underscore both the growing salience of LLMs in public funding and the need for empirical evidence on how they are being used and with what consequences.
3860,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,35,"Here, we examine LLM use at key stages in the federal funding pipeline by employing two complementary levels of analysis."
3861,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,36,"First, we collect novel datasets containing the complete set of NSF (D1) and NIH (D2) proposal submissions (hereafter private NSF and NIH data) from two large US R1 universities with request start dates from 2021 to 2025, including funded, unfunded, and pending proposals."
3862,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,37,These data offer us a unique opportunity to observe proposal language at the point of submission.
3863,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,38,"Second, we analyze the full population of publicly released NSF (D3) and NIH (D4) award abstracts (hereafter public NSF and NIH data) over the same period, together with publications supported by these awards."
3864,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,39,These data allow us to systematically analyze the funded awards (see Supplementary Note S1 for details on datasets).
3865,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,40,"Overall, these data enable us to characterize the evolution of LLM use in federal funding and to examine how it relates to the positioning of scientific ideas, their selection for funding, and their translation into publicly supported research output."
3866,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,41,"Rapid rise and bimodal distribution of LLM use in US federal research funding To estimate LLM use in federal grant proposals and awards, we analyze textual traces in their abstracts."
3867,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,42,"Specifically, we leverage an established detection method proposed by Lianget al. 15."
3868,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,43,"Using public grant abstracts with start dates in 2021, which preceded the widespread use of LLMs, we estimate the word distribution of human-written text."
3869,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,44,"We also estimate a corresponding word distribution of LLM-generated text by prompting OpenAI’s GPT-3.5- turbo-0125 model to rewrite the same abstracts, simulating LLM involvement in proposal language."
3870,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,45,Comparing these two distributions allows us to identify systematic differences between human and LLM-modified writing (see Supplementary Note S2.1 for details on model training).
3871,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,46,We then apply the detection method at both the corpus and individual grant levels.
3872,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,47,"At the corpus level, we pool grant abstracts for each focal month and its two adjacent months, and we estimate the fraction of LLM-modified sentences (𝛼) within this combined set in each dataset."
3873,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,48,"At the individual grant level, we estimate𝛼separately for each grant abstract in each dataset."
3874,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,49,"These two levels represent complementary estimates, as the corpus-level estimates leverage large volumes of text to capture aggregate LLM use over time, whereas grant-level estimates enable grant-level analyses that capture heterogeneity across grants, allowing us to examine how LLM use relates to semantic distinctiveness and other grant outputs."
3875,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,50,"Figures 1a-d trace the evolution of LLM involvement (𝛼) in NSF and NIH grants across two stages of the funding pipeline, proposal submission and award funding, drawing on confidential proposal submission abstracts (private data) and publicly released award abstracts (public data), respectively."
3876,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,51,"Across all four datasets,𝛼is relatively stable prior to late 2022, and then rises sharply beginning in 2023, coinciding with the widespread availability of ChatGPT. 3 This increase is visible both at the point of submission, when ideas first enter the system, and among funded awards that have passed peer review, indicating that LLM use is not confined to a single stage of the pipeline."
3877,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,52,"Over this period, NIH exhibits the same temporal pattern as NSF but with overall lower average levels of LLM involvement."
3878,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,53,"At the level of individual grants, Figs. 1e-h show that𝛼is not smoothly distributed."
3879,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,54,"Among grants starting in 2023-2025, it features a bimodal distribution, with one mode near zero and a second centered around roughly 10-15%."
3880,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,55,This pattern reveals a clear split: one group of grant abstracts that largely avoids LLM use and another that incorporates LLMs more substantively into proposal preparation.
3881,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,56,"These results indicate that LLM adoption has rapidly become a detectable feature of federal research proposals and awards, but it remains highly uneven across them."
3882,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,57,"This raises the question of whether the heterogeneity is systematically related to the kinds of ideas proposed and funded, or to downstream scientific outputs."
3883,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,58,"Private NSF Private NIH Public NSF Public NIH a b c d e f g h Fig. 1:Rapid rise and bimodal distribution of LLM use in US federal research funding.(a-d) Corpus-level estimates of LLM use (𝛼) for private and public NSF and NIH grants from 2021 to 2025, computed using rolling three-month windows (points)."
3884,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,59,Solid lines show locally weighted regressions.
3885,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,60,"The vertical dashed line marks November 30, 2022, corresponding to the public release of ChatGPT."
3886,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,61,"(e-h) Distributions of individual-grant𝛼for private and public NSF and NIH proposals and awards with start dates between 2023 and 2025, showing a bimodal pattern consistent with a split between minimal and substantive LLM use across grants."
3887,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,62,"LLM use and semantic distinctiveness in US federal research funding The rapid and uneven adoption of LLMs prompts another critical line of inquiry: Is greater LLM involvement associated with a shift in the kinds of ideas that enter, and ultimately shape, the federal research portfolio?"
3888,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,63,"To quantify the positioning of ideas, we measure the semantic distinctiveness of each proposal or award abstract (D1-D4) relative to the agency’s recent funding frontier, building on recent work using transformer-based embeddings26,37."
3889,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,64,"Specifically, for grants starting between 2023 and 2025, we compute each abstract’s average cosine distance (using SPECTER2 38 embeddings, an established embedding method for scientific texts) to all abstracts funded in the previous year within the same agency."
3890,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,65,"We then convert these distances into within-year percentiles, where higher 4 values indicate more distinctive ideas relative to other grants in that agency-year."
3891,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,66,"We relate distinctiveness to LLM involvement (𝛼), estimating regressions that include grant start year, field, and investigator (PI and co-PI) fixed effects, along with controls for requested or awarded funding amount (Supplemen- tary Note S2.2)."
3892,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,67,These fixed effects absorb time-invariant heterogeneity at the field and investigator levels while accounting for common shocks across grant start years.
3893,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,68,"Across all four datasets, including private submissions and public awards for both NSF and NIH, higher𝛼is consistently associated with lower distinctiveness percentiles (Fig. 2, Supplementary Note S2.2, Supplementary Tables S1-S4), indicating that proposals and awards with greater LLM involvement are positioned closer to the grants that the agency funded most recently."
3894,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,69,"For example, for NSF awards, moving from low LLM involvement (25th percentile) to high LLM involvement (75th percentile) corre- sponds to a ˜5-point decrease in the distinctiveness percentile; for NIH awards, the decrease is ˜4 points."
3895,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,70,"Importantly, the investigator fixed effects compare each investigator only to themselves across proposals and awards rather than comparing different investigators to one another."
3896,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,71,"We see that for the same investigator’s proposals and awards, when the LLM involvement is higher, their proposals and awards become systematically less distinctive."
3897,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,72,"These findings suggest that as LLM use rises, the proposal and award portfolio shifts toward the center of recently funded work, providing empirical evidence of idea homogenization in federal research funding that is already occurring across both agencies."
3898,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,73,"Private NSF Private NIH Public NSF Public NIH a b c d Fig. 2:LLM use and semantic distinctiveness in US federal research funding.(a-d) Regression estimates relating grant-level LLM use (𝛼) to semantic distance from abstracts funded in the prior year within the same agency, expressed as within-year percentiles."
3899,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,74,"Panels show results separately for private NSF (a), private NIH (b), public NSF (c), and public NIH (d) grants."
3900,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,75,"All regressions include grant start year, field, and investigator fixed effects, as well as controls for funding amount."
3901,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,76,"Points indicate coefficient estimates, and bars denote 95% confidence intervals."
3902,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,77,"Negative coefficients correspond to proposals and awards that are positioned closer, in semantic space, to recently funded work within the same agency. 5 LLM use and federal research proposal success We next ask whether LLM adoption is associated with a first-order consequence in the funding pipeline: which proposals actually receive funding."
3903,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,78,"Using confidential submissions that include both funded and unfunded proposals (D1-D2), we regress proposal success on proposal-level LLM involvement (𝛼) for request start years 2023-2025, estimating models with request start year, field, and investigator fixed effects and controlling for requested funding (Fig. 3, Supplementary Note S2.2, Supplementary Tables S5-S6)."
3904,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,79,"These fixed effects absorb time-invariant hetero- geneity across research areas and investigators, while accounting for common shocks across years."
3905,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,80,"For example, the investigator fixed effects hold constant time-invariant differences in investigators’ ability, style, and topic choice, asking whether an investigator’s proposals are more likely to be funded when their LLM involvement is higher."
3906,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,81,We find no statistically significant association between𝛼and proposal success for NSF proposals.
3907,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,82,"In contrast, for NIH submissions,𝛼is positively and significantly associated with proposal success."
3908,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,83,"Specifically, moving from low LLM involvement (25th percentile) to high LLM involvement (75th percentile) corresponds to a ˜4-percentage- point jump in NIH funding probability."
3909,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,84,"Overall, these results indicate that the consequences of LLM adoption for proposal selection are strongly agency-dependent: while LLM use does not systematically advantage proposals at NSF, it is associated with a higher likelihood of being funded at NIH, even for the same investigators."
3910,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,85,"This agency-dependent selection pattern raises the question of translation: conditional on being funded, is LLM adoption associated with downstream outputs from these funded projects? a b Private NSF Private NIH Fig. 3:LLM use and federal research proposal success.Based on private NSF and NIH proposal submissions from two large US R1 universities, this figure examines the relationship between LLM use at submission (𝛼) and proposal success."
3911,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,86,(a) Regression estimates for NSF submissions.
3912,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,87,(b) Corresponding estimates for NIH submissions.
3913,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,88,"All regressions include proposal request start year, field, and investigator fixed effects, as well as controls for requested funding amount."
3914,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,89,"Points indicate coefficient estimates, and bars denote 95% confidence intervals."
3915,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,90,"LLM use and federal research funding outputs Using the public NSF and NIH award data (D3-D4), we next relate grant-level LLM involvement (𝛼) to subsequent publication output for grants starting in 2023-2024, estimating regression models that control for funding amount and include grant start year, field, and investigator fixed effects (Fig. 4, Supplementary Note S2.2, Supplementary Tables S7-S12). 6 We again find no statistically significant relationship between𝛼and publication output for NSF awards (Fig. 4a)."
3916,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,91,"However, for NIH awards, higher𝛼is strongly associated with more resulting publications (Fig. 4b)."
3917,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,92,Moving from low LLM involvement (25th percentile) to high LLM involvement (75th percentile) predicts ˜5% more publications for NIH grants.
3918,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,93,"Moreover, this NIH productivity premium appears mostly concentrated in publication volume rather than high-impact outputs: when we restrict our analyses to highly-cited papers (e.g., top 5% papers in Figs. 4c-d; top 1% in Supplementary Fig."
3919,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,94,"S1), the relationship attenuates and is no longer statistically significant at conventional levels."
3920,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,95,"Taken together, these results suggest that the downstream consequences of LLM adoption are also agency-dependent."
3921,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,96,"At NIH, higher𝛼is associated with more follow-on publications, but the additional output is concentrated in non-hit papers rather than the most highly-cited work."
3922,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,97,These productivity patterns both align with and qualify recent evidence of large output gains following LLM diffusion in manuscript production 16.
3923,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,98,"While we observe a positive association between LLM involvement and publication output for NIH-funded grants, the magnitude of this association is smaller than the large increases documented in preprint production and is strongly agency-dependent, with no detectable relationship at NSF."
3924,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,99,"In the federal funding context, where projects are selected through peer review and outputs reflect execution constraints and portfolio objectives rather than writing speed alone, LLM adoption appears to translate into additional publications primarily at NIH, and predominantly among non-hit papers, while showing no detectable relationship with publication output at NSF. a b c d Public NSF # papers # hit papers (5%) Public NIH Fig. 4:LLM use and federal research funding outputs.(a-b) Regression estimates relating grant-level LLM use (𝛼) to the total number of resulting publications for NSF (a) and NIH (b) grants."
3925,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,100,"(c-d) Corresponding estimates for high-impact outputs, where a “hit” paper is defined as one whose citations fall within the top 5% of all papers published worldwide in the same year and field."
3926,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,101,"All regressions include grant start year, field, and investigator fixed effects, as well as controls for funding amount."
3927,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,102,"Points indicate coefficient estimates, and bars denote 95% confidence intervals. 7 Robustness and sensitivity checks We conduct a series of robustness and sensitivity checks across numerous dimensions."
3928,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,103,"First, to better characterize proposals and awards with higher LLM involvement, we follow prior work 16 and compute the Flesch Reading Ease score for each abstract as a measure of writing complexity (Supplementary Note S3.1)."
3929,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,104,"Consistent with prior work16, we find that higher LLM involvement is positively associated with greater writing complexity in both proposals and awards (Supplementary Fig."
3930,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,105,"Second, recent work has shown that the use of promotional language in grant proposals is positively associated with funding outputs and related proposal characteristics14."
3931,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,106,"To assess the extent to which our results may be driven by promotional words, we conduct a robustness analysis that explicitly removes promotional words at all stages of our text processing pipeline."
3932,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,107,"The resulting LLM-use measures remain highly similar to the original estimates across all datasets, indicating that our results are robust to the exclusion of promotional words (Supplementary Note S3.2, Supplementary Fig."
3933,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,108,"Third, in the main analysis of semantic distinctiveness, we define the comparison set using grants funded in the preceding year."
3934,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,109,"We redefine the comparison set using funded grants starting in the prior two years, finding the results are robust (Supplementary Note S3.3, Supplementary Fig."
3935,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,110,"Fourth, while our primary measure of semantic distinctiveness relies on cosine distances between embedding vectors, we also compute distances using L2 metrics and obtain consistent results (Supplementary Note S3.4, Supplementary Fig."
3936,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,111,"Fifth, in our primary specifications, we use ordinary least squares regressions."
3937,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,112,"We re-estimate proposal success using logistic regressions and publication outputs using negative binomial regressions and continue to observe the same associations between𝛼and outcomes (Supplementary Note S3.5, Supplementary Figs."
3938,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,113,"We further examine robustness by field using public award data where sample sizes are sufficiently large to support field-level analyses and find broadly consistent results (Supplementary Note S3.6, Supplementary Figs."
3939,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,114,"Lastly, we conduct analogous robustness checks by subagency using the public award data and again find broadly consistent patterns (Supplementary Note S3.7, Supplementary Figs."
3940,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,115,"Discussion Overall, our findings reveal that the rapid diffusion of LLMs is already reshaping key stages of the US federal research funding pipeline, from proposal submission to downstream scientific output."
3941,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,116,"By combining confidential proposal submissions with the full population of NSF and NIH awards, we provide systematic evidence that LLM adoption is associated with (i) how scientific ideas are positioned relative to recent funded work, (ii) whether proposals clear the funding threshold, and (iii) the publication output that funded projects go on to produce."
3942,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,117,"These results show that generative AI is not only changing how scientific text is produced, but also beginning to reshape the composition and consequences of public investment in research."
3943,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,118,"A central concern in science policy is maintaining a diverse and exploratory research portfolio, one that supports both cumulative progress and the pursuit of unconventional ideas."
3944,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,119,"Across both agencies and both stages (proposal submission and award funding), higher LLM involvement is consistently associated with lower semantic distinctiveness: proposals with greater LLM traces are positioned closer to recently funded work within the same agency."
3945,12,C012_P1_pdf.txt,120,This pattern echoes recent evidence that AI tools can expand individual scientists’ productivity and impact 8
3946,13,C013_P1.txt,0,"[2409.14634] Human-LLM Compound System for Scientific Ideation through Facet Recombination and Novelty Evaluation       >   cs   > Help  |  Advanced Search Comments Journal reference Report number arXiv identifier DOI Full text Search Computer Science > Human-Computer Interaction  (cs)     Title: Human-LLM Compound System for Scientific Ideation through Facet Recombination and Novelty Evaluation Authors: Marissa Radensky ,  Simra Shahid ,  Raymond Fok ,  Pao Siangliulue ,  Tom Hope ,  Daniel S."
3947,13,C013_P1.txt,1,"Weld   View a PDF of the paper titled Human-LLM Compound System for Scientific Ideation through Facet Recombination and Novelty Evaluation, by Marissa Radensky and Simra Shahid and 3 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) Abstract: The scientific ideation process often involves blending salient aspects of existing papers to create new ideas - a framework known as facet-based ideation."
3948,13,C013_P1.txt,2,"We contribute Scideator, the first human-LLM system for facet-based scientific ideation."
3949,13,C013_P1.txt,3,"Starting from a user-provided set of scientific papers, Scideator extracts key facets -- purposes, mechanisms, and evaluations -- from these and related papers, allowing users to explore the idea space by interactively recombining facets to synthesize inventive ideas."
3950,13,C013_P1.txt,4,"Scideator is driven by three design choices: (1) human-in-the-loop facet recombination, in which users select facets from retrieved papers and the system generates ideas by finding analogies across them via the Faceted Idea Generator module; (2) distance-controlled retrieval via the Analogous Paper Facet Finder module, which surfaces papers from the same topic to entirely different subareas to provide a spectrum of creative directions; and (3) facet-based novelty verification via the Idea Novelty Checker module, a retrieve-then-rerank pipeline that evaluates idea originality using facets."
3951,13,C013_P1.txt,5,"In a user study with computer science researchers, Scideator provided significantly more creativity support than a baseline using the same backbone LLM without our facet-based modules, particularly in idea exploration and expressiveness."
3952,13,C013_P1.txt,6,"Participants' favorite ideas more often included facets selected by themselves rather than the LLM, and participants used fewer free-text instructions with Scideator, indicating a preference for facet-level steering over prompting."
3953,13,C013_P1.txt,7,"Finally, re-ranking papers by facet matching rather than general relevance improved novelty classification accuracy from 13.79% to 89.66%."
3954,13,C013_P1.txt,8,"Comments: Updated based on most recent submission Subjects: Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) ; Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI)   MSC  classes: H.5.2, I.2 Cite as:  [cs.HC]   (or   [cs.HC]  for this version) Focus to learn more  arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite Submission history  From: Marissa Radensky [ view email ]    [v1]  Mon, 23 Sep 2024 00:09:34 UTC (3,397 KB) [v2]  Mon, 18 Nov 2024 20:25:38 UTC (3,398 KB) [v3]  Mon, 13 Jan 2025 22:45:30 UTC (7,810 KB) [v4]  Tue, 29 Apr 2025 04:47:58 UTC (8,249 KB) [v5]  Sun, 26 Oct 2025 23:19:16 UTC (6,852 KB) [v6]  Mon, 2 Mar 2026 05:32:11 UTC (3,737 KB)   Full-text links: Access Paper: View a PDF of the paper titled Human-LLM Compound System for Scientific Ideation through Facet Recombination and Novelty Evaluation, by Marissa Radensky and Simra Shahid and 3 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) TeX Source   view license    Current browse context:  cs.HC < prev   |     next > new  |  recent  |  2024-09  Change to browse by:   cs cs.AI References & Citations NASA ADS Google Scholar Semantic Scholar export BibTeX citation Loading..."
