4448,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,183,"Peak occurs with 8 members and 5 turns, while larger teams or excessive turns hinder creativity. “Infer- ence Cost” is the product of team size and turns. ber of turns promotes deeper insights and more innovative research outputs."
4449,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,184,"While the initial turns facilitate idea generation, excessive turns can result in fatigue and reduced engagement, ultimately hin- dering creativity."
4450,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,185,Our findings suggest that peak ON is achieved at around 5 discussion turns.
4451,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,186,Effects of Team Freshness on Novelty.
4452,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,187,"As shown in Fig. 5, team freshness—the fraction of members who have not previously collaborated—affects the novelty of outputs."
4453,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,188,"Freshness has its strongest ef- fect at 50%, especially for larger teams (size 8), where HD peaks."
4454,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,189,This suggests that a balanced mix of new and returning members promotes inno- vation by diverging from past research.
4455,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,190,"As fresh- ness increases, CD decreases, indicating that teams with more fresh members align their ideas more closely with future research trends."
4456,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,191,"Both CI and ON reach their highest values around 50% fresh- ness, highlighting that a balanced team optimally combines novelty and future relevance, consistent with previous work (Guimera et al., 2005; Zeng et al., 2021)."
4457,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,192,Effects of Team Research Diversity on Novelty.
4458,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,193,Team research diversity is defined as the proportion of team members specializing in distinct research topics.
