4466,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,201,"This conclusion mirrors find- ings in Science of Science, where unexpected team combinations can enhance research impact (Uzzi et al., 2013; Shi and Evans, 2023). 5 Conclusion We introduce VIRSCI, an LLM-based multi-agent system that simulates the collaborative dynamics of scientific discovery."
4467,15,C015_P1_pdf.txt,202,"Our model focuses on the idea generation phase, demonstrating how special- ized agents collaborate to generate diverse insights,"
4468,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,0,Can LLMs Generate Novel Research Ideas?
4469,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,1,"A Large-Scale Human Study with 100+ NLP Researchers Chenglei Si, Diyi Yang, Tatsunori Hashimoto Stanford University {clsi, diyiy, thashim}@stanford.edu Abstract Recent advancements in large language models (LLMs) have sparked optimism about their potential to accelerate scientific discovery, with a growing number of works proposing research agents that autonomously generate and validate new ideas."
4470,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,2,"Despite this, no evaluations have shown that LLM systems can take the very first step of producing novel, expert-level ideas, let alone perform the entire research process."
4471,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,3,We address this by establishing an experimental design that evaluates research idea generation while controlling for confounders and performs the first head-to-head comparison between expert NLP researchers and an LLM ideation agent.
4472,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,4,"By recruiting over 100 NLP researchers to write novel ideas and blind reviews of both LLM and human ideas, we obtain the first statistically significant conclusion on current LLM capabilities for research ideation: we find LLM-generated ideas are judged as more novel (p < 0.05) than human expert ideas while being judged slightly weaker on feasibility."
4473,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,5,"Studying our agent baselines closely, we identify open problems in building and evaluating research agents, including failures of LLM self-evaluation and their lack of diversity in generation."
4474,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,6,"Finally, we acknowledge that human judgements of novelty can be difficult, even by experts, and propose an end-to-end study design which recruits researchers to execute these ideas into full projects, enabling us to study whether these novelty and feasibility judgements result in meaningful differences in research outcome.1 1 Introduction The rapid improvement of LLMs, especially in capabilities like knowledge and reasoning, has enabled many new applications in scientific tasks, such as solving challenging mathematical problems (Trinh et al., 2024), assisting scientists in writing proofs (Collins et al., 2024), retrieving related works (Ajith et al., 2024, Press et al., 2024), generating code to solve analytical or computational tasks (Huang et al., 2024, Tian et al., 2024), and discovering patterns in large text corpora (Lam et al., 2024, Zhong et al., 2023)."
4475,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,7,"While these are useful applications that can potentially increase the productivity of researchers, it remains an open question whether LLMs can take on the more creative and challenging parts of the research process."
4476,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,8,We focus on this problem of measuring theresearch ideation capabilities of LLMs and ask: are current LLMs capable of generating novel ideas that are comparable to expert humans?
4477,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,9,"Although ideation is only one part of the research process, this is a key question to answer, as it is the very first step to the scientific research process and serves as a litmus test for the possibility of autonomous research agents that create their own ideas."
4478,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,10,Evaluating expert-level capabilities of LLM systems is challenging (Bakhtin 1Interested researchers can sign up for this end-to-end study at:https://tinyurl.com/execution-study.
4479,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,11,"We release our agent implementation and all human review scores at:https://github.com/NoviScl/AI-Researcher. ∗The last two authors advised this project equally. 1 arXiv:2409.04109v1 [cs.CL] 6 Sep 2024 7 N L P  T o p i c s B i a s C o d i n g S a f e t y M u l t i l i n g u a l F a c t u a l i t y M a t h U n c e r t a i n t y H u m a n  E x p e r t s A I  A g e n t C o n d i t i o n 1 : H u m a n I d e a s ( N = 4 9 ) C o n d i t i o n 2 : A I I d e a s ( N = 4 9 ) C o n d i t i o n 3 : A I I d e a s + H u m a n R e r a n k ( N = 4 9 ) B l i n d R e v i e w b y E x p e r t s ( N = 7 9 ) N o v e l t y S c o r e : 4 . 8 4  N o v e l t y S c o r e : 5 . 6 4 N o v e l t y S c o r e : 5 . 8 1 I d e a G e n e r a t i o n Figure 1: Overview of our study: we recruit 79 expert researchers to perform blind review of 49 ideas from each of the three conditions: expert-written ideas, AI-generated ideas, and AI-generated ideas reranked by a human expert."
4480,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,12,We standardize the format and style of ideas from all conditions before the blind review.
4481,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,13,We find AI ideas are judged as significantly more novel than human ideas (p <0.05).
4482,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,14,Human AI AI+Rerank3 4 5 6 7Score * * Novelty Human AI AI+Rerank3 4 5 6 7 * Excitement Human AI AI+Rerank3 4 5 6 7 Feasibility Human AI AI+Rerank3 4 5 6 7 Effectiveness Human AI AI+Rerank3 4 5 6 7 * Overall Figure 2: Comparison of the three experiment conditions across all review metrics.
4483,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,15,Red asterisks indicate that the condition is statistically better than theHuman baseline with two-tailed Welch’s t-tests and Bonferroni correction.
4484,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,16,All scores are on a 1 to 10 scale.
4485,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,17,"More detailed results are in Section 5. et al., 2022, Collins et al., 2024), and research ideation takes this to an extreme."
4486,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,18,"Qualified expert re- searchers are difficult to recruit at scale, evaluation criteria can be highly subjective, and it is difficult for even the best experts to judge the quality of an idea (Beygelzimer et al., 2021, Simsek et al., 2024)."
4487,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,19,"We address these challenges directly, recognizing that for important, high-stakes tasks like research ideation, there is no substitute for a large-scale expert evaluation."
4488,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,20,We design a carefully controlled comparison of human and LLM ideas that overcomes sample size and baseline problems present in earlier small-scale evaluation studies.
4489,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,21,Our study recruited a large pool of over 100 highly qualified NLP researchers to produce human baseline ideas and perform blind reviews of human and LLM ideas.
4490,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,22,"To reduce the possibility that confounding variables affect our outcome measures, we enforce strict controls that standardize the styles of human and LLM ideas and match their topic distribution."
4491,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,23,"We compare our human expert baseline with a simple and effective LLM agent that incorporates retrieval augmentation and adopts recent ideas in inference-time scaling, such as overgenerating and reranking LM outputs."
4492,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,24,"These measures allow us to make statistically rigorous comparisons between human experts and state-of-the-art LLMs (Figure 1). 2 Our evaluation-centric approach complements many recent methods-centric works that attempt to instantiate research agents (Baek et al., 2024, Li et al., 2024, Lu et al., 2024, Wang et al., 2024, Yang et al., 2024)."
4493,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,25,"The majority of these works rely on fast and lower-cost evaluation surrogates – either by decreas- ing the number of expert reviewers (Baek et al., 2024, Li et al., 2024, Wang et al., 2024, Yang et al., 2024), constraining the length and detailedness of the ideas (Wang et al., 2024, Yang et al., 2024), or relying on LLM-as-a-judge (Lu et al., 2024)."
4494,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,26,They do not perform the large-scale human comparison studies that are needed to answer the motivating question of our work.
4495,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,27,"Our work takes the opposite approach, performing a year-long and high-cost evaluation that provides human expert baselines and a stan- dardized evaluation protocol to serve as a foundation for future follow-up studies and methods work."
4496,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,28,"Through nearly 300 reviews across all our conditions, we find that AI-generated ideas are judged as more novel than human expert ideas (p <0.05), which holds robustly under multiple hypothesis correction and across different statistical tests."
4497,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,29,"We find some signs that these gains are correlated with excitement and overall score, and may come at the slight expense of feasibility, but our study size did not have sufficient power to conclusively identify these effects (Figure 2)."
4498,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,30,Qualitative analysis of free-text responses in our review corroborates these findings on novelty and feasibility.
4499,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,31,"Apart from evaluating the ideas, we also analyze the LLM agent, showing limitations and open problems – despite excitement about inference-time scaling of LLMs, we find that they lack idea diversity when we scale up idea generation, and they cannot currently serve as reliable evaluators. 2 Problem Setup The central experiment of our work is a comparison of human- and LLM-generated ideas."
4500,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,32,"While this goal is simple, there is no existing consensus on how to formulate the task of research ideation and evaluation, and we begin by defining the key aspects of our experiment design."
4501,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,33,"We think of research idea evaluation as consisting of three separate components: 1). the idea itself, generated in response to our instructions, 2). the writeup which communicates the idea, and 3). the evaluation of the writeup by experts."
4502,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,34,"We outline our experiment design in each of these three parts with particular focus on potential confounders, such as the area of research, the format of a research idea, and the evaluation process."
4503,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,35,Ideation Scope and Instructions Research ideas can take many different forms.
4504,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,36,"They can be simple tricks to improve model performance, or they may be large-scale research programs that form the basis of a Ph.D. thesis."
4505,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,37,Any experiment on ideation must carefully balance the realisticness and interestingness of a research idea with the practical realities of eliciting ideas from a large population.
4506,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,38,"In our case, these tradeoffs are even more pronounced, as we have designed our ideation experiments so that the resulting ideas can be executed by experts in a follow-up set of experiments."
4507,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,39,These constraints have led us to study prompting-based NLP research as a testbed for our study.
4508,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,40,"Prompting research has been popular in recent years of NLP and AI research (e.g., Chen et al., 2023, Diao et al., 2024, Madaan et al., 2023, Qin et al., 2024, Schulhoff et al., 2024, Si et al., 2023, Wang et al., 2023, Wei et al., 2022, Yao et al., 2023, Yasunaga et al., 2024, Zhou et al., 2023, inter alia)."
4509,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,41,This class of projects strikes a reasonable trade-off among our constraints.
4510,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,42,"The most impactful prompting projects like chain-of-thought have had a major influence on LLM performance (Wei et al., 2022), and prompting projects are executable with minimal computing hardware."
4511,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,43,We further structure our ideation process to avoid selection-bias-based confounders in ideation.
4512,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,44,"If we simply ask LLMs and humans to produce ideas on ‘prompting topics’, we may find that LLMs and humans differ in the types of research ideas they produce (for example, LLMs may naturally suggest more projects on safer topics, which might be judged as less exciting by humans)."
4513,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,45,"This would 3 lead us to simply measure misalignment in research topic preference between LLMs and humans, which is not the goal of our study."
4514,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,46,"To address this possibility, we define a set of seven specific research topics extracted from the Call For Papers page of recent NLP conferences such as COLM.2 Specifically, our topics include: Bias, Coding, Safety, Multilinguality, Factuality, Math, and Uncertainty (see Appendix A for a complete description of these topics)."
4515,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,47,"Each human and LLM participant of the ideation experiment receives the same set of natural language instructions including the same topic description, idea template, and demonstration example to ensure a fair comparison."
4516,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,48,"For human participants, we additionally allow them to select a preferred topic from the list, and for each selected topic, we generate a corresponding LLM idea."
4517,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,49,"This exactly matches the idea topic distribution between the LLM and human participants, while ensuring that human experts are able to select topics according to their expertise."
4518,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,50,"Idea Writeup An idea can only be evaluated if it is written up to be communicated, but this writing process introduces many additional potential confounders."
4519,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,51,"Human researchers may write in ways that subtly signal quality research, such as including more examples and implementation details."
4520,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,52,The format of the writeup functions as a way to scaffold what contents should be included and the level of detailedness.
4521,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,53,"Ideally, we want both human and LLM participants to provide all the necessary implementation details for their generated ideas."
4522,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,54,We take inspiration from guidelines used in grant submissions and introduce a template to specify the structure and detailedness of idea proposals.
4523,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,55,"Specifically, we construct a template that includes fields for the title, problem statement, motivation, proposed method, step-by-step experiment plan, test case examples, and the fallback plan."
4524,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,56,Both the LLM agent and the human idea writers are instructed to follow this template and our provided demonstration examples to produce a project proposal as the output (see Appendix B for the full template and Appendix C for the demo example).
4525,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,57,"Even with these templates, there may be subtle writing style cues that affect the outcome measure."
4526,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,58,"For example, humans may tend to write in a more engaging and informal tone."
4527,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,59,"To reduce this possibility further, we developed a style normalization module that uses an LLM to convert all ideas into the same writing and formatting style without changing the original content."
4528,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,60,Our small-scale human study shows that such a normalization approach leads to a 50% accuracy for expert human judges who are asked to distinguish AI ideas from human ideas.
4529,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,61,"Finally, the use of an LLM style anonymizer has the possibility of substantively changing the content of the ideas."
4530,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,62,"To rule this out, the first author of this paper manually verified each human idea proposal to ensure all contents of the original ideas were preserved."
4531,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,63,We present the full prompt used in Appendix D.
4532,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,64,"Review and Evaluation Reviewing research ideas is notoriously subjective, so we want to design a review form that defines all review criteria clearly to standardize and anchor the evaluations as much as possible."
4533,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,65,"At the same time, we want our review criteria and measured variables to capture all the desiderata of high-quality research ideas."
4534,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,66,"We follow best practices from AI conference reviewing (e.g., ICLR and ACL) when designing the review form, where we define four breakdown metrics including novelty, excitement, feasibility, and expected effectiveness, apart from the overall score."
4535,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,67,"For each metric, we ask for a numerical score on a 1-10 scale along with a free-text rationale."
4536,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,68,We provide clear definitions and grounding for each numerical scale to calibrate all reviewers’ standards (see Appendix E for the full review form).
4537,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,69,Our blind review evaluation will compare ideas from three different conditions: 1.
4538,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,70,Human Ideas : Idea proposals written by our recruited expert researchers. 2https://colmweb.org/cfp.html 4 2.
4539,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,71,AI Ideas : Idea proposals generated by our LLM agent.
4540,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,72,We directly take the top-ranked ideas from the agent’s output. 3.
4541,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,73,AI Ideas + Human Rerank : Idea proposals generated by our LLM agent.
4542,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,74,The first author of this paper manually selected the top-ranked ideas out of all the LLM agent’s generations rather than relying on the LLM ranker in order to better estimate the upper-bound quality of AI ideas.
4543,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,75,"In the next two sections, we instantiate how our LLM agent generates ideas and how our expert participants generate and review the ideas. 3 Idea Generation Agent We build a simple but effective LLM ideation agent to compare with the human expert baseline."
4544,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,76,"Rather than focusing on innovating the agent itself, we adhere to a minimalist design principle, aiming to understand the current capabilities of LLMs in idea generation."
4545,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,77,"Our research ideation agent has three essential components: paper retrieval, idea generation, and idea ranking, which we will describe in detail below. 3.1 Paper Retrieval for RAG To ground idea generation, the agent needs to retrieve papers related to the given research topic, so that it will be aware of related works when generating new ideas."
4546,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,78,"To do so, we lever- age retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), which has demonstrated effectiveness on many knowledge-intensive tasks (Lewis et al., 2020, Shi et al., 2024)."
4547,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,79,"Concretely, given a research topic (e.g., “novel prompting methods that can improve factuality and reduce hallucination of large language models""), we prompt an LLM to generate a sequence of function calls to the Semantic Scholar API."
4548,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,80,We use claude-3-5-sonnet-20240620 as the backbone model for our agent but the pipeline should generalize to other LLMs as well.
4549,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,81,"The paper retrieval action space includes: {KeywordQuery(keywords), PaperQuery(paperId), GetReferences(paperId) }."
4550,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,82,Each action generation is grounded on the previous actions and executed results.
4551,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,83,We keep the topk = 20 papers from each executed function call and stop the action generation when a max ofN = 120papers have been retrieved.
4552,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,84,We then use the LLM to score and rerank all retrieved papers based on three criteria: 1) the paper should be directly relevant to the specified topic; 2) the paper should be an empirical paper involving computational experiments;3 3) the paper is interesting and can inspire new projects.
4553,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,85,The LLM is prompted to score each retrieved paper on a scale of 1 to 10 based on these criteria and we use the top-ranked papers for the next step of idea generation. 3.2 Idea Generation Our key insight for idea generation is to generate as many candidate ideas as possible.
4554,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,86,"Our intuition is that only a small fraction of all generated ideas might be high-quality, and we should be willing to expend inference-time compute to generate more candidates so that we can later use a reranker to discover the ""diamond in the rough""."
4555,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,87,"This aligns with existing results showing that scaling inference compute with repeated sampling can boost LLM performance on various coding and reasoning tasks (Brown et al., 2024, Li et al., 2022)."
4556,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,88,"Specifically, we prompt the LLM to generate 4000 seed ideas on each research topic."
4557,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,89,The idea generation prompt includes the demonstration examples and the retrieved papers.
4558,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,90,"We craftk = 6 demonstration examples by manually summarizing exemplar 3Note that we exclude position papers, survey papers, and analysis papers throughout this study since their evaluation tends to be very subjective. 5 papers (Dhuliawala et al., 2023, Madaan et al., 2023, Weller et al., 2023, Weston and Sukhbaatar, 2023, Yasunaga et al., 2024, Zheng et al., 2024) into our desired idea format."
4559,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,91,"For retrieval augmentation, we randomly selectk = 10papers from the top-ranked retrieved papers and concatenate their titles and abstracts to prepend to the idea generation prompt."
4560,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,92,We also append the titles of all previously generated ideas to the prompt to explicitly ask the LLM to avoid repetitions.
4561,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,93,"To remove duplicated ideas from this large pool of candidate ideas, we first perform a round of dedu- plication by encoding all seed ideas withall-MiniLM-L6-v2 from Sentence-Transformers (Reimers and Gurevych, 2020) and then computing pairwise cosine similarities."
4562,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,94,We set a similarity threshold of 0.8 for the idea deduplication based on manual inspection.4 This leaves about 5% non-duplicated ideas out of all the generated seed ideas.
4563,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,95,We expand more on this duplication issue later in Section 7.1. 3.3 Idea Ranking The next step is for our ideation agent to rank all the remaining ideas so that we can find the best ones among them.
4564,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,96,"To build such an automatic idea ranker, we use public review data as a proxy."
4565,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,97,"Specifically, we scraped 1200 ICLR 2024 submissions related to LLMs (with keyword filtering) along with their review scores and acceptance decisions."
4566,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,98,"We explored multiple ways of predicting the scores and decisions of these submissions and found that LLMs are poorly calibrated when asked directly to predict the final scores or decisions, but can achieve non-trivial accuracy when asked to judge which paper is better in pairwise comparisons."
4567,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,99,"N Top-10 Bottom-10 Gap 1 6.28 5.72 0.56 2 6.14 5.24 0.90 3 5.83 4.86 0.97 4 5.94 4.99 0.95 5 6.42 4.69 1.73 6 6.11 4.81 1.30 Table 1: Average ICLR review scores of top- and bottom-10 papers ranked by our LLM ranker, with different rounds (N) of pairwise comparisons."
4568,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,100,We converted the ICLR submissions into our stan- dard project proposal format and randomly paired up accepted and rejected papers and asked LLMs to predict which one is accepted.
4569,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,101,"On this task, Claude-3.5-Sonnet achieves an accuracy of 71.4% with zero-shot prompting."
4570,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,102,"For comparison, GPT-4o achieves 61.1% and Claude-3-Opus achieves 63.5%, and we do not observe significant gains from addi- tional prompting techniques like few-shot or chain- of-thought prompting."
4571,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,103,We therefore choose the Claude-3.5-Sonnet zero-shot ranker.
4572,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,104,"In order to obtain reliable scores for all project proposals based on pairwise comparisons, we adopt a Swiss system tournament where all project proposals are paired with those whose accumulated scores are similar, and if the proposals are judged to be better, they gain an additional point."
4573,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,105,"We repeat this forN rounds so the total score of each project proposal will be within the [0, N] range."
4574,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,106,"As a sanity check, we use theClaude-3.5-Sonnet ranker to rank the 1.2K ICLR LLM-related submissions and compare the average review scores of the top 10 ranked papers and the bottom 10 ranked papers in Table 1."
4575,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,107,"We see a clear separation between the top and bottom ranked papers, indicating the effectiveness of the LLM ranker."
4576,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,108,We chooseN = 5for all our experiments since it gives the best ranking result on this validation set.
4577,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,109,The top-ranked project proposals from the agent will be directly used for theAI Ideas condition of the human study.
4578,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,110,"Since our AI ranker is still far from perfect, we also introduce another experiment condition where the first author of this paper manually reranked the generated project proposals instead of relying on the LLM ranker, and we call this the AI Ideas + Human Rerank condition."
4579,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,111,As we show in 4We provide randomly sampled idea pairs and their similarities in Appendix H.
4580,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,112,"We also provide additional implementa- tion details about the ideation agent in Appendix F. 6 Table 12, 17 out of the 49 ideas in theAI Ideas + Human Rerank condition overlap with the AI Ideas condition, while the other 32 are different, indicating the discrepancy between the LLM ranker and the human expert reranking. 4 Expert Idea Writing and Reviewing In this section, we shift focus to the human branch of idea generation comparison."
4581,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,113,"We present the details of our human study, including information about the recruited experts, the human idea generation task, and the subsequent review process. 4.1 Expert Recruitment We recruit our expert participants (including for idea writing and reviewing) by sending sign-up forms to several channels, including: 1) the OpenNLP Slack channel with 1426 NLP researchers from 71 institutions (with consent from the channel manager); 2) Twitter (X); 3) Slack channels of various NLP groups by direct communication with the group members; and 4) official chat app of the NAACL 2024 conference."
4582,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,114,We also conducted in-person recruitment by giving out name cards and wearing T-shirts 5 with sign-up links at the NAACL 2024 conference as well as various other local NLP social events.
4583,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,115,Our study has been approved by the Stanford IRB (ID 74246).
4584,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,116,We performed screening on all the US participants6 based on their provided Google Scholar profiles.
4585,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,117,We set a minimum requirement of having published at least one paper at a major AI venue.7 We reached out to all participants who satisfied this requirement with the consent form and followed up with the annotation documents for those who consented to participate.
4586,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,118,"In the end, we recruitedN = 49experts for writing ideas, andN = 79experts for reviewing ideas."
4587,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,119,"Note that 24 out of the 79 reviewers also participated in the idea writing, and we made sure no reviewer would review their own idea."
4588,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,120,This results in N = 104 total participants across the two tasks.
4589,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,121,"Each idea writer is asked to write one idea within 10 days and we compensate $300 for each, with a $1000 bonus for the top 5 ideas as scored by the expert reviewers."
4590,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,122,Each idea reviewer is assigned 2 to 7 ideas to review and we collectedN = 298 unique reviews in total.
4591,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,123,They are given one week to finish the reviews and we compensated $25 for each review written by the idea reviewers. 4.2 Expert Qualifications PhD 73% Master 18% Other 8% PhD 79% Master 6% Other 5% Postdoc 8% Figure 3: Positions of our idea writer (left) and reviewer (right) participants.
4592,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,124,Our pool of participants is highly qualified and diverse.
4593,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,125,The 49 idea writers come from 26 different institutions (Ta- ble 15) and the majority of them are current PhD students (Figure 3 left).
4594,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,126,The 79 reviewers come from 32 institutions (Table 16) and are mostly PhD students and Postdocs (Fig- ure 3 right).
4595,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,127,"We use their Google Scholar profiles to extract several proxy metrics, including the number of papers, citations, h-index, and i10-index at the time of their submis- sion."
4596,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,128,"Table 2 shows that our idea writers have an average of 12 papers and 477 citations, while every reviewer has published at least two papers and has an average citation of 635 and h-index of 7."
4597,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,129,"Moreover, based on their survey 5https://x.com/ChengleiSi/status/1804273510656749649 6We have to recruit participants located in the US due to logistical reasons. 7E.g., *ACL, NeurIPS, ICLR, ICML, AAAI. 7 Idea Writing Participants (N=49) Idea Reviewing Participants (N=79) Metric Mean Median Min Max SD Mean Median Min Max SD papers 12 10 2 52 9 15 13 2 52 10 citations 477 125 2 4553 861 635 327 0 7276 989 h-index 5 4 1 21 4 7 7 0 21 4 i10-index 5 4 0 32 6 7 5 0 32 6 Table 2: Research profile metrics of the idea writing and reviewing participants."
4598,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,130,Data are extracted from Google Scholar at the time of idea or review submission.
4599,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,131,"Metric Mean Median Min Max SD Human Ideas Familiarity (1-5) 3.7 4.0 1.0 5.0 1.0 Difficulty (1-5) 3.0 3.0 1.0 5.0 0.7 Time (Hours) 5.5 5.0 2.0 15.0 2.7 Length (Words) 901.7 876.0 444.0 1704.0 253.5 AI Ideas Length (Words) 1186.3 1158.0 706.0 1745.0 233.7 AI + Human Rerank Ideas Length (Words) 1174.0 1166.0 706.0 1708.0 211.0 Table 3: Statistics of the 49 ideas from each condition. responses, 72 out of the 79 reviewers have previously reviewed for major AI conferences or journals."
4600,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,132,These statistics indicate that our participants are highly qualified and have substantial research experience. 8 4.3 Idea Writing Topic Count Bias 4 Coding 9 Safety 5 Multilingual 10 Factuality 11 Math 4 Uncertainty 6 Total 49 Table 4: Idea topic distribution.
4601,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,133,We report statistics of our idea writers’ ideas to measure their quality.
4602,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,134,"As shown in Table 3, idea writers indicate a moderately high familiarity with their selected topic (3.7 on a 1 to 5 scale), and indicate the task as moderately difficult (3 on a 1 to 5 scale)."
4603,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,135,They spent an average of 5.5 hours on the task and their ideas are 902 words long on average.
4604,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,136,These indicate that participants are putting substantial effort into this task.9 We also show the distribution of their selected topics in Table 4. 4.4 Idea Reviewing Review Assignment We let all reviewer participants select their top two preferred topics as well as their preferred reviewing load (from 2 to 7).
4605,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,137,We then randomly assign them to ideas within their selected topics and all ideas are anonymized.
4606,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,138,"In the assignment, we balance the number of ideas from each condition for each reviewer and ensure that each reviewer gets at least one human idea and one AI idea."
4607,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,139,Every idea is reviewed by 2 to 4 different reviewers.
4608,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,140,We also avoid assigning ideas written by authors from the same institution to avoid any potential contamination.
4609,15,C015_S1_pdf.txt,141,"Table 5 shows that each reviewer wrote an average of 3.8 reviews from 2 or 3 conditions, across 1 to 3 topics. 8Detailed breakdown of participant positions is in Appendix K. 9See Appendix J for more details on the quality control of human ideas. 8"
4610,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,0,"AI Conversational Interviewing: Transforming Surveys with LLMs as Adaptive Interviewers Alexander Wuttke1, Matthias Aßenmacher1,2, Christopher Klamm2, Max M."
4611,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,1,"Lang3, Quirin Würschinger1, Frauke Kreuter1,2 1LMU Munich, 2Munich Center for Machine Learning (MCML), 3University of Mannheim, 4University of Oxford Correspondence: a.wuttke@lmu.de Abstract Traditional methods for eliciting people’s opin- ions face a trade-off between depth and scale: structured surveys enable large-scale data col- lection but limit respondents’ ability to voice their opinions in their own words, while con- versational interviews provide deeper insights but are resource-intensive."
4612,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,2,This study explores the potential of replacing human interviewers with large language models (LLMs) to con- duct scalable conversational interviews.
4613,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,3,Our goal is to assess the performance of AI Con- versational Interviewing and to identify oppor- tunities for improvement in a controlled en- vironment.
4614,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,4,"We conducted a small-scale, in- depth study with university students who were randomly assigned to a conversational inter- view by either AI or human interviewers, both employing identical questionnaires on politi- cal topics."
4615,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,5,"Various quantitative and qualita- tive measures assessed interviewer adherence to guidelines, response quality, participant en- gagement, and overall interview efficacy."
4616,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,6,"The findings indicate the viability of AI Conversa- tional Interviewing in producing quality data comparable to traditional methods, with the added benefit of scalability."
4617,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,7,"We publish our data and materials for re-use and present spe- cific recommendations for effective implemen- tation. 1 Introduction Structured surveys are popular tools to assess pub- lic opinion (Groves, 2009; Kertzer and Renshon, 2022; Stantcheva, 2023)."
4618,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,8,"These surveys typically gather individual orientations through self-reports, asking respondents to select from predefined op- tions on fixed questions."
4619,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,9,"This method allows for efficient data collection across large populations, producing structured, tabular data that is straightfor- ward to analyze and comparable across respondents (Krosnick, 1999; Groves, 2009)."
4620,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,10,"Due to these ben- efits, structured surveys hold a prominent position in both academic and commercial research."
4621,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,11,"Despite their established utility, structured sur- veys with predefined response options have sig- nificant limitations (Schwarz and Hippler, 1987; Kash, 2013)."
4622,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,12,"Their static and impersonal nature often leads to respondent fatigue, which can di- minish engagement and, consequently, the quality of responses (Krosnick, 1999; Jeong et al., 2023)."
4623,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,13,"More critically, the rigid format of these surveys constrains respondents from fully expressing their thoughts, restricting them from offering responses that researchers may not have anticipated (Chang et al., 2021; Esses and Maio, 2002; Reja et al., 2003; Baburajan et al., 2022; Duck-Mayr and Mont- gomery, 2023)."
4624,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,14,This limitation hampers the discovery of new phenomena and prevents a comprehensive un- derstanding of the full spectrum of people’s at- titudes.
4625,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,15,"An alternative to structured surveys is conversational interviewing, sometimes called in- depth or semi-structured or qualitative interviewing (Adeoye-Olatunde and Olenik, 2021; Kallio et al., 2016; Adams, 2015)."
4626,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,16,"It involves interviewers en- gaging with respondents in a more open-ended for- mat, allowing them to freely express their thoughts on topics of interest."
4627,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,17,The dynamic nature of con- versational interviews helps alleviate respondent fatigue and permits the exploration of opinions be- yond predefined response options.
4628,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,18,"However, this approach requires skilled interviewers capable of conducting nuanced conversations, which limits its application to small sample sizes due to the associ- ated costs."
4629,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,19,"So, survey research faces a trade-off between depth and scale: researchers must choose between conducting in-depth explorations with small groups through or large-scale but rigid surveys."
4630,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,20,"However, recent advances in natural language processing (Dubey et al., 2024; Üstün et al., 2024; Workshop et al., 2023; Costello et al., 2024) present new pos- sibilities for addressing this dilemma."
4631,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,21,The conver- sational capabilities of instruction-finetuned large arXiv:2410.01824v2 [cs.HC] 12 Mar 2025 Figure 1: Illustration of the concurrent interview settings (human- vs.
4632,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,22,"AI-conducted) and the various metrics (/user, ὄ1, /file-altand ♂search) applied to assess interview quality. language models (Wei et al., 2022; Ouyang et al., 2022) have made them applicable across various academic and industrial domains."
4633,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,23,"Because LLMs can engage in human-like conversations (Cai et al., 2024; di San Pietro et al., 2023; Palmer and Spir- ling, 2023), they have the potential to assist or even replace human interviewers in conducting conver- sational interviews."
4634,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,24,"By eliminating the costly need for human interviewers, LLMs could enable scal- able in-depth conversations, potentially resolving the trade-off between depth and scale."
4635,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,25,Contributions We contribute to the emerging paradigm of AI Conversational Interviewing by conducting the first close-up investigation of its practical implementation and performance (cf.
4636,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,26,Fig- ure 1): • We provide a new comprehensive assessment pipeline of AI performance in conducting con- versational interviews • We document the practical challenges partici- pants face when interacting with an AI inter- viewer • We are the first to explore the performance of voice-assisted LLM-based interviewing • We are the first to perform a detailed compar- ative analysis of AI-conducted versus human- conducted conversational interviews • We pre-registered the study to ensure trans- parency in the research process • We publish code and data for reuse: conversational-interviewing-LaTeCH- CLfL2025 2 Related Work To implement and evaluate AI Conversational In- terviews this study combines insights from three distinct lines of work that have rarely been com- bined.
4637,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,27,"Advances in AI research have facilitated mul- tiple ongoing commercial and academic projects that use LLM-powered chatbots for in-depth, qual- itative, or semi-structured interviews, as they are interchangeably called (Chopra and Haaland, 2023; Weidmann et al., 2024)."
4638,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,28,"Although implementations vary, the studies collectively highlight the potential of LLMs for conducting conversational interviews."
4639,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,29,"Yet, critical questions regarding the implementa- tion remain unresolved and little is known about the relative performance compared with human-led interviews."
4640,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,30,"Qualitative studies have extensively explored best practices for conducting in-person interviews (Adams, 2015)."
4641,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,31,Our approach is to build on these insights when implementing AI Conversational In- terviewing.
4642,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,32,Studies in survey methodology have exten- sively examined how different interview implemen- tations influence responses.
4643,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,33,"One line of research has focused on interviewer and mode effects (Mit- tereder et al., 2018; Malhotra and Krosnick, 2007)."
4644,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,34,"The presence of an interviewer significantly im- pacts respondents, often leading to greater engage- ment but also increasing the likelihood of socially desirable responses (Atkeson et al., 2014; West and Blom, 2016)."
4645,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,35,"In this vein, studies on conversational interviewing has shown that a more active and flex- ible interviewer who engages with questions from respondents can improve data quality (Schober and Conrad, 1997; Davis et al., 2024; Mittereder et al., 2018).1 Another important factor is the input mode."
4646,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,36,Responses to open-ended questions vary depending on whether they are submitted via text or speech.
4647,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,37,"Text input typically requires more effort, which can result in shorter but more carefully considered re- sponses (Gavras et al., 2022; Höhne et al., 2024)."
4648,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,38,"So, the responses will not necessarily be better or worse depending on input mode, but they will differ predictably, as text- and speech-based interviews elicit distinct psychological reactions from partici- pants (Gavras et al., 2022). 3 Study Design and Implementation Our study pursues two goals: (a) Assess the perfor- mance of AI Conversational Interviewing (in com- parison to human-led interviewing) and (b) Identify problems and opportunities for improvement of AI Conversational Interviewing."
4649,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,39,We conducted a small-N study among univer- sity students in a controlled environment.
4650,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,40,"Ahead of data collection, we pre-registered our research questions, research design, and evaluation metrics (cf."
4651,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,41,"We conducted both AI-led and human-led inter- views as part of a class activity, where students were randomly assigned to serve as either inter- 1Our method is similar to traditional ""conversational in- terviewing"" in that it enhances flexibility during the inter- view."
4652,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,42,"However, AI Conversational Interviewing differs by highlighting the flexibility of the respondents rather than the interviewer. viewers or respondents in the respective conditions."
4653,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,43,Identical questionnaires were used in both inter- view settings.
4654,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,44,"After the interview, respondents filled out a structured questionnaire to evaluate their interview experience."
4655,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,45,"In the AI interview condition, students monitored the interviewees in real-time to identify any technical issues. 3.1 Procedure The study was embedded in a student seminar on survey methodology that was hosted via Zoom."
4656,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,46,Stu- dents were informed that they would participate in a pilot study of conversational interviewing.
4657,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,47,The seminar proceeded with a detailed script (cf.
4658,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,48,"Ap- pendix C.2), lasting about 120 minutes: 1."
4659,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,49,"Participants were informed about the upcom- ing procedure, the technical requirements were laid out, and they were asked for con- sent to participate and collect their data. 2."
4660,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,50,"As preparation for the upcoming tasks, an in- structor gave a 10-minute presentation about scientific approaches to interview respondents, and rules for good interviewer behavior. 3."
4661,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,51,"Students were paired up and randomly as- signed different roles: (a) Students participated in both a human- conducted and an AI-conducted inter- view, with the sequence randomly as- signed (b) In the human-conducted interviews, stu- dents took on roles as either respondents or interviewers (c) In the AI-conducted interviews, students served as either respondents or observers, monitoring for any technical issues dur- ing the interview 3.2 Model setup We implemented a voice-assisted AI Conversa- tional Interviewing pipeline with GPT-4 2 and a Chainlit-based user interface, using the following task-adapted prompts (cf."
4662,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,52,"The system instruction to act as an interviewer (You are a survey interviewer named ’Inter- viewGPT’, an AI interviewer, wanting to find out more about people’s views [...]) 2GPT-4 turbo, version: 04/2024 AI:Let’s talk about democracy."
4663,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,53,"What good things come to mind about democracy in Western countries like Germany? 10:30 AM ♂robot Respondent:A good thing is having a democracy that’s less corrupt than other countries, like the recent election in Russia. 10:31 AM /user AI:You appreciate the less corrupt system in Western democracies, contrasting with less transparent elections elsewhere."
4664,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,54,"What bad things come to mind about democracy in the West? 10:32 AM ♂robot Type a message... ♂paper-planeἺ4 Figure 2: Illustrative example of our used Chat Interface structure (with an interaction between an AI agent ♂robotand a user /user) of the AI in-depth interview, showcasing how the interviewer engages inactive listening by occasionally rehearsing the preceding answer, as instructed (cf."
4665,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,55,"The input field includes options for text input (♂paper-plane) and voice input (Ἲ4). 2. the user instructions with specific guidelines, derived from the qualitative literature on hu- man in-depth interviewing (Adams, 2015), specifying desirable and undesirable inter- viewer behavior ( [...] Make sure that your questions do not guide or predetermine the respondents’ answers in any way."
4666,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,56,"Do not pro- vide respondents with associations, sugges- tions, or ideas for how they could answer the question. [...]) 3. a task questionnaire on politics and democ- racy, developed by a democracy researcher among the authors (e.g."
4667,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,57,And what do you think “politics” is?
4668,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,58,"How would you define this term?) 3.3 User interface To enable voice-assisted interviewing, we devel- oped a user interface based on Chainlit3, with cus- tomization for audio input and output as shown in Figure 2)."
4669,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,59,Our voice-assisted implementation allowed respondents to choose between voice and text modes for both the model output (interviewer questions) and their input (responses).
4670,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,60,"When re- spondents selected audio input, their speech was transcribed into text, which they could then review and edit before submitting their responses."
4671,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,61,This approach sought to blend the spontaneity and ex- pressiveness of audio input with the precision and control offered by text-based refinements.
4672,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,62,"For au- dio output, interviewer questions were displayed 3https://chainlit.io/ as text and could be delivered as voice upon the user’s request."
4673,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,63,"We utilized OpenAI Whisper (Rad- ford et al., 2023) for text-to-speech transcriptions of model-generated text. 3.4 Interview Content Human and AI in-depth interviews were conducted with an identical questionnaire in English (cf."
4674,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,64,The questionnaire concerned questions on politics and democracy (e.g.
4675,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,65,"When you think about how democ- racy works right now in Western countries such as Germany, what are the good things that come to mind? or And what do you think “politics” is?"
4676,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,66,How would you define this term?).
4677,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,67,"Human-led in- terviews lasted 16 minutes, on average."
4678,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,68,"AI-led interviews lasted 22 minutes, on average. 3.5 Evaluation Metrics We computed a set of quantitative and qualitative measures, designed to evaluate the effectiveness, ef- ficiency, and quality of AI-conducted interviews in comparison to traditional human-conducted inter- views."
4679,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,69,"Besides quantitative text-based metrics (♂search), we evaluate indicators of participant engagement, response depth, and coherence (/user)."
4680,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,70,"Additionally, we gathered survey feedback (/file-alt) on the interview experience from participants in both interview set- tings. /userInterviewer behavior: Human coding."
4681,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,71,"We provided two research assistants with the inter- viewer guidelines, which outlined desirable and undesirable interviewer behaviors (cf."
4682,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,72,"The research assistants then manually double- coded each conversational turn of the interviewer (e.g., a question) to identify any potential viola- tions of these guidelines."
4683,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,73,"In essence, we assessed whether the human and AI interviewers adhered to the instructions. /userInterview responses: Human coding."
4684,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,74,Two research assistants were provided with a detailed coding manual to assess the quality of the par- ticipants’ responses (cf.
4685,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,75,"They as- sessed factors such as whether a response directly addressed the question, whether the participant ap- peared engaged, and the specificity and detail of the response."
4686,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,76,"In essence, we evaluated whether the interviews elicited insightful responses from participants. ♂searchInterview responses: Computational analysis."
4687,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,77,"We computed the Flesch Reading Ease scores on the transcribed interview data to evaluate response readability and length (Flesch, 1948)."
4688,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,78,"Additionally, we calculated the number of tokens per response to obtain a more granular measure of linguistic complexity and information density. /file-altStructured post-interview survey."
4689,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,79,"After each interview, the respondents were asked to fill out a survey on their experience (cf."
4690,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,80,Appendix K). ὄ1Real-time problem recording.
4691,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,81,"During the AI interview, one student from each pair was assigned to observe the other student’s interaction with the AI interviewer."
4692,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,82,The observer was given a form to document any technical difficulties or other issues the respondent encountered during the interview (cf.
4693,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,83,Appendix F). 4 Findings We collected data on six human-led and five AI- conducted interviews.
4694,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,84,Human-led interviews were audio-recorded and then transcribed.
4695,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,85,"Figure 2 presents an example snippet from an AI conversational interview, showcasing how the inter- viewer engages in active listening by occasionally repeating the preceding answer, as instructed."
4696,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,86,Qualitative inspection of the transcribed data shows that both the AI and human interview- ers faithfully followed the provided questionnaire.
4697,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,87,Manual coding of all interviewer behavior shows that neither humans nor AI always acted in full accordance with the interview guidelines (Figure 6).
4698,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,88,"Summarizing across all coded categories, we counted 72 violations per AI interview and 64 viola- tions (↓ -11.11%) per human interview, on average."
4699,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,89,"While error rates of human and AI interview- ers were at similar levels, the nature of the errors differed."
4700,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,90,"Contrary to instructions, human inter- viewers often failed to engage in active listening, which involves restating the respondent’s answer to ensure proper understanding."
4701,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,91,"Specifically, 94 percent of guideline violations related to active listening were committed by human interviewers, compared to only 6 percent by the AI interviewer (cf."
4702,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,92,"Conversely, and in contrast to internal pre-tests, the AI interviewer predominantly failed to follow the instruction to ’ask follow-up questions when a respondent gives a surprising, unexpected, or unclear answer,’ with 88 percent of violations of this rule attributed to the AI inter- viewer."
4703,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,93,These findings highlight the challenge of finding the right balance between asking too many and too few follow-up questions in any in-depth interviewing setting.
4704,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,94,"Moreover, the fact that the interviewer model had previously succeeded in ask- ing appropriate follow-up questions during internal tests serves as a reminder that even minor modi- fications to prompts can lead to unintended side effects."
4705,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,95,Another guideline was to avoid any behavior that could bias the respondents’ answers.
4706,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,96,"How- ever, despite the instruction to ’not take a position on whether their answers are right or wrong,’ the AI interviewer occasionally judged the respondent, typically in an encouraging manner (e.g., ’Your definition of politics is quite insightful’, 67 per- cent attributed to the AI interviewer)."
4707,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,97,"In contrast, human interviewers sometimes erred by guiding re- spondents through associations or suggestions for their answers, accounting for 75 percent of such violations."
4708,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,98,"Overall, while no interviewer setting perfectly adhered to the guidelines, these findings suggest that AI interviewers demonstrate a similar level of effectiveness to human student interviewers in following instructions for in-depth interviewing."
4709,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,99,"However, achieving optimal performance relies on fine-tuning and thoroughly testing model instruc- tions."
4710,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,100,"Turning from the interviewer’s behavior to the participants’ responses, we see that both inter- viewing settings succeeded in eliciting answers from respondents at substantial lengths."
4711,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,101,"In the AI interviewer setting, the average response length was 52.39 words."
4712,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,102,"In the human interview set- ting, the average response length was 32.81 words ↓ ↑ AI Interviewer Human Interviewer ∆ /userQualitative Assessments Clarity ↑ 4.3 3.9 +0.4 Empathy ↑ 2.6 2.9 -0.3 Engagement ↑ 2.6 3.2 -0.6 Grammatical correctness ↑ 4.3 3.8 +0.5 Relevance ↑ 4.6 4.3 +0.3 Response complexity ↓ 1.9 2.1 -0.2 Specificity ↑ 3.1 3.6 -0.5 Tone of answers ↑ 3.1 3.3 -0.2 ♂searchQuantitative Assessments Tokens per answers ↑ 52.39 32.81 +19.58 Readability ↑ 77.66 62.22 +15.44 /file-altSurvey Results Clarity ↑ 1.5 1.9 -0.4 Interestingness ↑ 2.5 3.9 -1.4 Repeatability ↑ 2.5 3.6 -1.1 Overall Satisfaction ↑ 3.8 3.8 +0.0 Understanding ↑ 4.0 4.3 +0.3 Table 1: Comparison of AI-conducted vs human-conducted interviews: Qualitative assessments /user, quantitative measurements ♂search, and participant survey /file-altresults where ∆ shows the difference between AI and human scores (+ AI performed better and − showing where humans performed better) and we use arrows (↓ ↑ ) to indicate the desired direction for each metric - whether a higher ↑ or lower score ↓ is better."
4713,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,103,"While participants‘ answers to the AI interviewer were substantial in length, were they also mean- ingful in substance?"
4714,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,104,The transcribed responses were given to human coders to rate response qual- ity.
4715,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,105,"While we observe minor differences across setting, overall, the ratings indicate a similar re- sponse quality."
4716,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,106,"Responses in human and AI in- terviews were rated as similarly clear (i.e., easy to understand), empathetic (i.e., sensitive towards the interviewer), engaged (i.e., high level of en- thusiasm or interest), complex (i.e., advanced vo- cabulary), grammatically correct (i.e., error-free), specific (i.e., detailed information), and adequate in tone (i.e., suitable for the context)."
4717,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,107,One particularly important outcome is the as- sessed relevance of the responses—whether they are useful and directly related to the question asked.
4718,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,108,"Once again, no substantial differences in relevance were observed between AI and human interviews."
4719,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,109,"While these estimates should be interpreted with caution due to the considerable imprecision associ- ated with the small sample size, the findings sug- gest that engaging with an AI interviewer does not lead to a significant decline in response qual- ity compared to a human interviewer."
4720,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,110,"We interpret this as a proof-of-concept, underscoring the general viability of AI Conversational Interviewing."
4721,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,111,Our setup allowed for a close-up investigation of how our AI interviews unfolded in practice.
4722,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,112,"Real-time problem recording during AI interviews showed that respondents interacted seamlessly with our user interface, which resembled familiar chat interfaces, indicating that no learning curve was necessary."
4723,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,113,"Yet, occasionally, the latency of the GPT responses was criticized (e.g. “Sometimes the time it takes to produce an answer is unexpectedly long."
4724,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,114,"But it is not really off putting.”, “run time is quite slow, it takes a couple (>5 seconds)”)."
4725,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,115,"While this latency may reflect similar reaction times in human-to-human chat interactions, participants ap- peared to prefer shorter waiting times when they were aware they were interacting with an AI inter- viewer."
4726,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,116,"Our implementation was voice-assisted, allow- ing respondents to choose between text and speech for both the interviewer’s output and their own input."
4727,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,117,"While no issues were reported with the voice output of the interview questions, the real- time problem recording noted several instances where respondents reported technical issues with audio recording and transcription (“Some problems Figure 3: Evaluation for AI ( green ) vs Human Interviewers ( orange ), showing the scores (y-axis) across different interview assessment criteria for participants’ evaluation of interview/file-alt(x-axis). with the microphone: Sometimes does not record, speech recognition sometimes recognises words in- correctly”, “small recurring problems with audio recording (not sure if it already runs, accidently stop in recording early”, “recording just stopped completely for a couple seconds and interviewee was kinda mad about it”)."
4728,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,118,Our post-interview survey confirmed these is- sues.
4729,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,119,"Although five AI interview participants re- ported trying the audio recording function, only one found it to work sufficiently well to rely on it primarily during the interview."
4730,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,120,The remaining respondents either partly or primarily preferred to provide written answers to the AI interviewer.
4731,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,121,"Although unintended, this presents an analytical opportunity to explore differences between written and audio-recorded responses in the AI interviewer setting."
4732,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,122,"As the survey-methodological literature suggests, the answers of respondents who relied on text input were significantly shorter (on average, 21 tokens per answer) than the answers by respon- dents who used audio-recorded throughout the AI interview (63 tokens per answer ( ↑ +67%)."
4733,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,123,"So, response length markedly varied with input mode."
4734,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,124,"However, the survey-methodological literature indicates that audio-recorded responses should not be considered inherently superior but rather quali- tatively different from written responses."
4735,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,125,"One stu- dent observing a respondent providing written in- put noted that "" the respondent does not have the opportunity to elaborate in a free way in the written answers."
4736,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,126,"She was very focused on writing good sentences which hindered her in her elaboration"", highlighting the distinct psychological processes associated with each input mode."
4737,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,127,"Further qualitative observation indeed suggests that text-based inputs encourage respondents to think before writing, whereas audio recording tends to prompt respondents to “think out loud”, allow- ing them to develop their thoughts while speaking (see Appendix F for an example)."
4738,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,128,The response styles associated with audio- and text-based input modes are also reflected in objective measures we extracted from the transcribed interview data.
4739,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,129,"Text- based AI interviews achieved a Flesch Reading Ease score of 77.66 while the fully audio-based AI interview scored at 48.32 (↑ +62,22%) (Flesch Reading Ease score for human interviews: 62; higher values indicate higher readability)."
4740,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,130,"Hence, compared to text input, audio input in AI interviews may be associated with longer but less elaborate answers."
4741,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,131,How did respondents experience the in- terviews?
4742,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,132,Participants felt that both the human and AI interviewers were clear in their questions and that each understood their responses (Figure 3).
4743,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,133,"Respondents in both settings left the interview satis- Figure 4: Evaluation for AI ( green ) vs Human Interviewers ( orange ), showing the scores (y-axis) across different interview assessment criteria for human-rated response quality /user(x-axis). fied."
4744,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,134,"However, participants found the AI interview less interesting and were less likely to repeat it, pos- sibly due to the technical problems with the audio recording."
4745,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,135,"While emphasizing that a satisfactory interview hinges on a flawless technical implemen- tation of the interview process, these findings sug- gest that the absence of a human interviewer does not necessarily need to go along with a deteriorated interview experience for the respondents. 5 Discussion and Recommendations Applying the questionnaire to a student sample with both human and AI interviewers demonstrates the general viability of AI Conversational Inter- viewing."
4746,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,136,"When properly implemented, AI Conver- sational Interviewing can collect high-quality data."
4747,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,137,"A comprehensive set of qualitative and quantitative metrics suggests that AI interviewing maintains quality comparable to that of human interviewing, but at significantly lower costs, thereby making in-depth interviews more scalable."
4748,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,138,"Although these findings highlight the potential of AI Conversational Interviewing, the success of the method depends on its precise implementation."
4749,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,139,"Based on our comprehensive analysis, we present five recommendations for the future development and employment of AI-driven in-depth interviews: Leverage existing knowledge."
4750,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,140,"When specifying desired interviewer behavior, it is crucial to draw on established principles from survey methodology."
4751,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,141,"These practices, developed through extensive re- search and practical experience, offer proven guide- lines for effective implementation."
4752,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,142,Context-specific definition of desired inter- viewer behavior.
4753,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,143,It is crucial to make deliberate judgment calls to tailor the desired interviewer be- havior to your specific research context.
4754,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,144,"This may involve decisions on aspects such as the importance or frequency of follow-up questions, the depth of probing on certain topics, or the level of formality in the interview tone (for example, Weidmann et al."
4755,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,145,(2024) demonstrated the effectiveness of empathy prompting).
4756,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,146,Each research project may require a unique approach to AI interviewer behavior to ensure the collection of appropriate data.
4757,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,147,The interface through which participants interact with the AI interviewer is crucial to the success of the interview.
4758,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,148,It is essential to rely on familiar and intuitive user interfaces that minimize cognitive load and technical barriers.
4759,16,C016_P1_pdf.txt,149,Well-designed interfaces enable participants to focus on providing thoughtful responses rather than being distracted by technical difficulties.
4760,17,C017_P1.txt,0,"Dynamic Surveys: Using LLMs to Blend Qualitative Depth, Quantitative Structure, and Collaborative Interaction KEHUA LEI, UC Santa Cruz, USA AIDAN LADENBURG, UC Santa Cruz, USA ZAHRA PETIWALA, UC Santa Cruz, USA ZILI WANG,UC Santa Cruz, USA DISHITA JHAWAR,UC Santa Cruz, USA IPSITA BISHT, UC Santa Cruz, USA ANSH KUMAR, UC Santa Cruz, USA DAVID T."
4761,17,C017_P1.txt,1,"LEE,UC Santa Cruz, USA Surveys are a powerful tool for collecting data and eliciting insights on social phenomena, and are critical in product design, marketing, scientific research, and other domains."
4762,17,C017_P1.txt,2,"However, traditional open-ended and closed-ended question formats limit researchers’ ability to capture data that combines both the richness of qualitative insights and the analytical rigor of quantitative data."
4763,17,C017_P1.txt,3,Closed-ended questions facilitate structured data collection that is amenable to statistical analysis but limit respondents’ answers.
4764,17,C017_P1.txt,4,"In contrast, open-ended questions allow for nuanced responses incorporating new perspectives but require significant effort to interpret due to their unstructured nature."
4765,17,C017_P1.txt,5,"Moreover, traditional survey tools lack mechanisms to prompt respondents for deeper reflections or to facilitate engagement with others’ perspectives, limiting the potential for richer insights."
4766,17,C017_P1.txt,6,"To address these problems, we propose Dynamic Surveys, a survey platform that uses Large Language Models (LLMs) to dynamically cluster qualitative responses in real time and to elicit quantitative ratings and rankings on those clusters and qualitative reflections on how their views compare to broader respondent trends, especially helpful in early-stage or exploratory research settings."
4767,17,C017_P1.txt,7,"This process generates a report showing survey creators and respondents the clustered responses as well as each cluster’s rank, rating distribution, and follow-up reflections."
4768,17,C017_P1.txt,8,"To evaluate Dynamic Surveys, we conducted two field studies with 93 participants over a 2-month period."
4769,17,C017_P1.txt,9,"In the first study, 52 students provided input for a career workshop, while in the second, 41 students gave feedback on gaps in their academic curriculum."
4770,17,C017_P1.txt,10,"Of these, 44 respondents filled out a survey on their experience using Dynamic Surveys."
4771,17,C017_P1.txt,11,"We also shared the generated report with 4 individuals who were interested in the insights for their work, and interviewed them to understand their perspectives on the results and any contextual risks they saw in the platform design."
4772,17,C017_P1.txt,12,"Our findings suggest that Dynamic Surveys not only provide richer and deeper insights into responses compared with traditional survey tools, but also increase engagement and foster a sense of community."
4773,17,C017_P1.txt,13,"We discuss broader implications for the design of survey platforms that blend qualitative depth with quantitative structure, facilitating richer insights and offering more collaborative interactions."
4774,17,C017_P1.txt,14,CCS Concepts: •Human-centered computing → Systems and tools for interaction design .
4775,17,C017_P1.txt,15,"Additional Key Words and Phrases: Surveys and Data Collection, LLM-Based Clustering, Participatory Decision- Making Platforms Authors’ Contact Information: Kehua Lei, klei4@ucsc.edu, UC Santa Cruz, USA; Aidan Ladenburg, aladenbu@ucsc.edu, UC Santa Cruz, USA; Zahra Petiwala, zpetiwal@ucsc.edu, UC Santa Cruz, USA; Zili Wang, zwang400@ucsc.edu, UC Santa Cruz, USA; Dishita Jhawar, djhawar@ucsc.edu, UC Santa Cruz, USA; Ipsita Bisht, ipsitabisht@gmail.com, UC Santa Cruz, USA; Ansh Kumar, ansh.khalasi@gmail.com, UC Santa Cruz, USA; David T."
