4782,17,C017_P1.txt,22,"Dynamic Surveys: Using LLMs to Blend Qualitative Depth, Quantitative Structure, and Collaborative Interaction."
4783,17,C017_P1.txt,23,"Interact. 9, 7, Article CSCW405 (November 2025), 26 pages. https: //doi.org/10.1145/3757586 1 INTRODUCTION Surveys are a widely used tool for collecting data in diverse domains, from product design and marketing to social research and academic feedback."
4784,17,C017_P1.txt,24,"Their ability to gather insights quickly and cost-effectively, across broad geographic areas, makes them a popular choice for both researchers and practitioners [11, 50, 55, 69]."
4785,17,C017_P1.txt,25,"However, traditional survey formats present significant challenges when it comes to capturing both the richness of qualitative data [23, 60] and the analytical rigor of quantitative data [9]."
4786,17,C017_P1.txt,26,"Quantitative questions, such as multiple-choice or Likert scales, provide structured data that is easily analyzed but limit respondents’ ability to fully express nuanced perspectives or to add new ones."
4787,17,C017_P1.txt,27,"Conversely, while open-ended qualitative questions encourage richer, more detailed insights, the resulting unstructured data is labor-intensive to process and hard to extrapolate to broader populations."
4788,17,C017_P1.txt,28,"Just as importantly, traditional survey platforms operate in a one-way fashion, where respondents answer questions in isolation without the opportunity to interact with the perspectives of others."
4789,17,C017_P1.txt,29,This lack of interaction limits the ability of researchers to foster community-driven insights and meaningful conversations among participants.
4790,17,C017_P1.txt,30,"Early innovations such as Wikisurveys [61] have explored new ways of blending the strengths of diverse research methods while also enhancing respondent engagement, e.g. by allowing participants to rank on responses of others through pairwise comparisons."
4791,17,C017_P1.txt,31,"Related efforts have been made in the context of systems for participatory democracy [43, 56]."
4792,17,C017_P1.txt,32,"However, these methods tend to focus on voting at scale and thus stop short of fully integrating the richness of qualitative input with a dynamic, collaborative process."
4793,17,C017_P1.txt,33,"Wikisurveys demonstrated the potential to deepen engagement by making respondents active participants in the evolving insights, but little work has since expanded on this concept to build a more robust and interactive form of qualitative-quantitative data collection."
4794,17,C017_P1.txt,34,"To address these limitations, we designed and implemented a survey platform, Dynamic Surveys, that builds on the community-driven potential of Wikisurveys while blending qualitative depth and quantitative structure in a more interactive and collaborative way."
4795,17,C017_P1.txt,35,"Dynamic Surveys is particularly useful for early-stage and exploratory research when deep interpretive immersion is not feasible and when the goal is not to build formal theory but to identify directional insights, surface common patterns, or provoke further inquiry, e.g. for systems-focused researchers and industry researchers looking to understand initial needs or experiences (see Section 3.7 for an in-depth comparison)."
4796,17,C017_P1.txt,36,"Dynamic Surveys uses large language models (LLMs) to elicit richer responses through generated follow-up questions, to dynamically cluster qualitative responses, and to ask respondents to reflect on, rate, rank, and engage with these clusters in real time."
4797,17,C017_P1.txt,37,"This interactive process transforms the survey from a solitary task into a community conversation, where participants actively shape the collective understanding, with the goal of fostering a greater sense of ownership over the results and of surfacing more nuanced community-driven insights that traditional survey tools might miss."
4798,17,C017_P1.txt,38,"Respondents can view the resulting survey report along with survey creators, which displays a ranked list of the clusters along with opinion distributions, summaries, detailed responses, and explanations of minority opinions."
4799,17,C017_P1.txt,39,We evaluated the effectiveness of Dynamic Surveys through two field studies.
4800,17,C017_P1.txt,40,"The first involved 52 students providing input on discussion topics for a career workshop, and the second gathered feedback from 41 students on perceived gaps in their academic curriculum."
4801,17,C017_P1.txt,41,"Of these 93 participants, Proc."
