4932,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,21,"Manuscript submitted to ACM Manuscript submitted to ACM 1 arXiv:2509.18297v2 [cs.HC] 8 Apr 2026 2 Anoushka Puranik, Ester Chen, Roshan L Peiris, and Ha-Kyung Kong data segments to create the foundational building blocks of analysis [10, 58]."
4933,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,22,"These codes are subsequently clustered and synthesized into themes, which are broader patterns and interpretive insights that capture significant meaning within the dataset [10, 58]."
4934,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,23,"While these qualitative data analysis (QDA) methods generate rich and nuanced findings, this process is often socially intensive, frequently involving teams of researchers engaging in discussion, negotiation, and interpretation to reach shared understanding of the data [ 28, 33, 38]."
4935,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,24,"As qualitative datasets grow larger and more complex, the collaborative labor involved in coding and interpreting becomes increasingly time-consuming and labor-intensive, and is susceptible to implicit bias due to the subjective nature of the process [59]."
4936,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,25,"Given the extensive nature of this work, qualitative researchers often rely on QDA tools to facilitate organization and streamline workflow [60, 63, 70]."
4937,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,26,"In addition, researchers have looked into ways to incorporate artificial intelligence (AI) to support QDA [21, 33, 53, 57]."
4938,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,27,"Recently, QDA tools including NVivo and MAXQDA started automating various tasks, such as coding and theme generation, reducing the manual effort involved in analysis."
4939,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,28,"AI-powered QDA tools offer the potential to streamline workflows, manage large datasets, and improve efficiency [73]."
4940,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,29,"Despite these advancements, the integration of AI into the collaborative practices of qualitative analysis was not immediately embraced by all qualitative researchers [31, 32, 34, 35, 49]."
4941,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,30,An earlier study showed that researchers enjoy the discoveries they make through manual coding due to the interpretive nature of qualitative research and resist the notion of AI fully automating this work [32].
4942,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,31,"More recent studies show a growing openness of qualitative researchers to collaborating with AI, and suggest ways in which AI can or should be used [21]."
4943,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,32,"Yet, while researchers have proposed AI as a novel form of collaborator [33], little is known about how people perceive this AI “collaborator"" compared to human collaborators, and how AI might affect or augment the collaborative nature of QDA."
4944,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,33,"Given the conflicting views on the integration of AI in QDA, this study explores how qualitative researchers perceive the role of AI in their collaborative analysis workflows, using Lubars and Tan’s framework on human perception of task delegation to AI [43]."
4945,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,34,"Their framework divides the degree of delegation into four categories: no AI assistance, the human leads and the AI assists, the AI leads and the human assists, and full AI automation."
4946,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,35,"We adjusted the degrees to describe different types of AI involvement in the QDA process: human-only, human-initiated, and AI-initiated coding. • Human-only codinginvolves human coders manually assigning codes based on their interpretation of the data, either by hand or using QDA software without any AI involvement. • Human-initiated codingrefers to a process where codes are created and applied by a human coder, grouped into themes, and the resulting codes and themes are later reviewed using AI tools. • AI-initiated coding, in contrast, uses machine learning algorithms to automatically identify codes and assign these codes to data segments, or cluster codes into broader themes, with human coders reviewing the results afterward."
4947,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,36,We omitted the full automation category given the strong resistance shown in prior work [ 32].
4948,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,37,"Based on this framework, we examined the desired role of AI in the QDA process through interviews with 16 qualitative researchers."
4949,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,38,We investigated the topic through the lens of how their preferences align with existing human collaboration in QDA and how AI might shift or support these collaborative practices.
4950,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,39,"We further explored the topic of bias in QDA and participants’ use of multimodal data (e.g., audio and video), as it represents an underexplored strategy for mitigating bias through capturing nuances like tone, pitch, and non-verbal cues [13]."
4951,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,40,"Through the study, we aimed to answer the following three research questions: Manuscript submitted to ACM Striking the Balance Between Efficiency and Ownership in Qualitative Data Analysis 3 • RQ 1."
4952,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,41,"How do qualitative researchers’ preferences for different degrees of AI involvement in QDA (human- only, human-initiated, and AI-initiated coding) vary across different contexts, and what factors shape these preferences? • RQ 2."
4953,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,42,What are qualitative researchers’ perspectives on bias in qualitative data analysis and the use of AI for mitigating bias? • RQ 3.
4954,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,43,"How do qualitative researchers perceive the value of multimodal data (e.g., audio, video), and how do they incorporate it into their analysis practices?"
4955,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,44,"Our study showed that human-only coding is still the most preferred method, as participants were reluctant to give interpretive authority to AI."
4956,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,45,"Yet, they were open to workflows where AI acts as an assistant, not collaborator or supervisor, either by generating code suggestions that humans can accept or reject, or by automating repetitive tasks."
4957,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,46,"Many expressed discomfort in human-initiated coding, where AIcheckshuman work, as it undermined their sense of ownership of the codes and professional identity as a qualitative researcher."
4958,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,47,The interviews surfaced a mistrust in the involvement of AI in the QDA workflow due to a lack of contextual understanding and concerns on data confidentiality.
4959,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,48,"Despite recognizing the potential of audio and video to enrich analysis, participants relied heavily on text due to time constraints and inadequate tools, highlighting an opportunity for future QDA systems to integrate multimodal analysis."
4960,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,49,"Through the study, we make the following three primary contributions: 1."
4961,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,50,"Qualitative comparison of AI delegation paradigms in QDA:We explored researchers’ preferences across three degrees of delegation for AI in the QDA workflow (human-only, human-initiated, and AI-initiated coding) and show how efficiency, ownership, and trust influence people’s preferred degree of delegation. 2."
4962,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,51,Design implications that position AI as an assistant rather than a collaborator:We propose concrete CSCW designs that use AI as a method of enhancing human collaboration in QDA by distinguishing authorship and establishing trust. 3.
4963,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,52,"Highlighting opportunities for mitigating bias, including multimodal integration:We address the underutilization of multimodal data in current QDA workflows and propose AI-driven approaches for incorporating non-verbal cues to support richer and more bias-aware analysis. 2 RELATED WORK 2.1 Tools for Qualitative Data Analysis Historically, manual qualitative data analysis (QDA) presented significant logistical hurdles."
4964,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,53,"The transcription process alone was exceptionally time-consuming; for instance, a mere 45-minute audio-recorded interview could demand approximately eight hours of a trained researcher’s time, resulting in 20 to 30 pages of written text for analysis [66]."
4965,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,54,This extensive manual effort in data preparation and handling was a major bottleneck in the research workflow.
4966,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,55,"When the QDA is performed collaboratively as a team, especially one that is geographically distributed or working on complex projects, a distinct set of challenges emerges [32, 34, 35, 49]."
4967,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,56,"These difficulties can be broadly categorized into three main areas.First, technical infrastructure issues pose significant barriers."
4968,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,57,"These include incompatibilities between different software tools, problems with secure data sharing, challenges related to legacy data, differing file standards, and complexities reminiscent of version control problems [5, 12, 18].Second, methodological coordination presents considerable challenges."
4969,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,58,"Teams often struggle with overcoming the absence of standardized analytical procedures, aligning coding schemes, and ensuring and managing inter-coder reliability [32, 34].Third, team communication and workflow management are often problematic, especially in remote settings."
4970,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,59,"Difficulties in decision-making, effective Manuscript submitted to ACM 4 Anoushka Puranik, Ester Chen, Roshan L Peiris, and Ha-Kyung Kong knowledge sharing, and coordinating efforts across different time zones are key challenges in such contexts [18, 30, 49, 56, 76]."
4971,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,60,"The advent of Computer-Assisted Qualitative Data Analysis Software (CAQDAS) marked a significant shift in the QDA landscape, addressing many of the initial manual challenges [20, 26]."
4972,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,61,Leading CAQDAS tools like NVivo [50] and ATLAS.ti [7] began to streamline the research process by offering features such as automated transcription and more efficient management of large datasets [20].
4973,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,62,These tools considerably reduced the time required for thematic analysis by allowing researchers to sort data by codes and summarize coded segments across multiple interviews.
4974,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,63,"While some CAQDAS packages offered assistance in theory development and advanced search functionalities, they fell short in areas such as recognizing synonyms, which could hinder the extraction of deeper insights [11, 70]."
4975,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,64,"Other tools focused on strengths like automated concept mapping, robust data storage, and flexible management capabilities [62, 63], illustrating the ongoing technological evolution within the field."
4976,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,65,"Despite the advancements brought by CAQDAS, limitations persisted, particularly in tasks requiring high-volume pattern recognition and time-intensive data sorting, which are uniquely suited for Artificial Intelligence (AI)."
4977,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,66,Marathe and Toyama [45] identified that many coding practices across various disciplines could potentially be automated.
4978,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,67,The application of computational methods in qualitative research promised enhanced efficiency and a potential reduction in bias and errors [3].
4979,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,68,"Consequently, the research community began to explore automation processes [9, 71], and some CAQDAS tools incorporated features like “Automated Insights” in NVivo, which leverage topic modeling [2]."
4980,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,69,"Further research into semi-automated systems such as Cody, which integrates user-defined rules with supervised machine learning, demonstrated improvements in coding efficiency and consistency [57]."
4981,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,70,(2024) [53] and van der Riet et al.
4982,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,71,(2021) [ 57] have further highlighted AI’s capacity to enhance coding quality and inter-rater reliability through AI-assisted coding.
4983,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,72,"While these earlier works focused on augmenting individual efficiency, recent HCI and CSCW research has shifted toward exploring how AI could be integrated to enhance thecollaborativeaspect across the full workflow of qualitative inquiry from dynamic data collection, collaborative coding, to interpretive partnership."
4984,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,73,"First, in thedata collection phase, researchers are reshaping how information is acquired by collaborating with AI."
4985,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,74,"Cuevas et al. [15] demonstrated that LLM-based interviewing chatbots can act as collaborative partners in gathering data, fostering new forms of dynamic engagement between researchers and participants that was previously difficult to scale."
4986,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,75,"Lei et al. [42] also explored AI-supported data collection, but through dynamic surveys where LLM is used to cluster responses in realtime and prompt survey respondents to reflect on the answer trends."
4987,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,76,Their work aimed at designing survey platforms that support both quantitative structure and collaborative interactions.
4988,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,77,"Second, in thecoding and consensus phase,Wang et al. [69] explored the feasibility of “LATA” (LLM-Aided Thematic Analysis), highlighting that while AI can mimic the coding process, it introduces challenges in reliability that require human oversight."
4989,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,78,"Consistent with these concerns, Gao et al. [ 24] investigated the dynamics of AI-mediated collaborative coding through CoAIcoder, and found that while AI suggestions improved efficiency and agreement, they also introduced a risk of “shallow agreement, ” where human researchers converged on the AI’s suggestions rather than engaging in deep, independent interpretation."
4990,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,79,"Third, regardinghigh-level interpretation,literature suggests a shift from automation to “augmentation” of serendipity."
4991,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,80,"Jiang et al. [32] framed the AI not as a tool for automation, but as a system that honors uncertainty and supports serendipity, arguing that the goal of collaboration is to expose researchers to unexpected patterns while maintaining human agency."
4992,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,81,"Feuston and Brubaker [21] expanded on this by using storyboard scenarios to map the “delegation” of tasks, identifying how researchers negotiate shifts in scale and abstraction when collaborating with AI."
4993,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,82,"Finally, moving into theme Manuscript submitted to ACM Striking the Balance Between Efficiency and Ownership in Qualitative Data Analysis 5 construction, Kang et al. [36] explored how interactive systems (ThemeViz) can mediate the “sense-making” process, allowing researchers to actively negotiate and refine AI-generated themes rather than simply accepting them."
4994,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,83,"Despite these collaborative advances, significant challenges remain regarding the depth of interpretation."
4995,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,84,"Qualitative research values subtle differences in meaning and the absence of utterances [19], nuance that current models often miss [37, 61]."
4996,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,85,This tension between efficiency and interpretive depth remains a central hurdle in Human-AI QDA.
4997,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,86,Our research extends this groundwork by focusing specifically on themechanisms of delegation.
4998,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,87,"Building on Lubars and Tan’s framework [43], we investigate whether researchers view the “AI partner” similarly to a human collaborator (requiring negotiation) or a research assistant (requiring supervision), and how these views shape the desired “collaborative contract” in QDA workflows. 2.2 Bias in Qualitative Data Analysis Qualitative analysis is inherently interpretive, relying on the researcher’s subjectivity as a lens to make sense of data."
4999,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,88,"However, a distinction must be drawn betweensubjectivity, which is a necessary feature of qualitative inquiry andbias, which threatens validity."
5000,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,89,"Drapeau explained that unexamined subjectivity may be introduced in qualitative research, particularly where there is a lack of consensus on definitions, leading researchers to code based on internalized prejudices or conflicts [17]."
5001,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,90,"In addition, researchers are often influenced by how the results may be used later on (e.g., in court, by the media) and could lead to an unconscious decision to derive conclusions based on the moral and legal implications rather than the data present [17]."
5002,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,91,"In HCI and CSCW,reflexivityis the standard method for mitigating these risks, requiring researchers to critically examine their own positionality [22, 29]."
5003,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,92,"Without this, unexamined subjectivity can harden into cognitive biases, such as confirmation bias, where researchers select data that fits pre-existing beliefs [51]."
5004,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,93,"This risk is particularly acute when researchers rely solely on text transcripts; the removal or underutilization of multimodal data (e.g., audio tone, hesitation) can strip away the nuance needed to challenge a researcher’s initial textual interpretation, thereby exacerbating confirmation bias."
5005,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,94,"While human researchers struggle with cognitive bias, AI introduces a different challenge."
5006,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,95,"Given that AI systems are trained on human-provided datasets, societal biases can be encoded into the model, resulting inalgorithmic bias."
5007,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,96,Panch et al. [54] discuss this form of bias and stress the importance of designing AI systems to actively mitigate it.
5008,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,97,Our study builds on these discussions by exploring qualitative researchers’ views on how these two distinct forms of bias — human cognitive bias and AI algorithmic bias interact and can be mediated.
5009,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,98,"Prior work by Ma et al. on trust calibration (i.e., comparing the user’s trust in AI with AI’s actual capability) showed that to establish an adequate level of trust, we not only have to assess AI’s correctness likelihood but also the user’s correctness likelihood [44]."
5010,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,99,"Similarly, rather than viewing AI as a neutral adjudicator, we investigate how QDA tools might allow researchers to leverage AI to identify their own blind spots, while simultaneously using their human contextual awareness to audit algorithmic limitations. 3 METHODOLOGY We define ""codes"" and ""themes"" in alignment with established qualitative research practices [ 10, 58].Codesare the specific, granular labels (word/short phrase) assigned directly to segments of qualitative data (e.g., text and audio transcripts) and serve as raw building blocks.Themesrepresent broader, more abstract patterns or insights that emerge from clustering, categorization, or analytic reflection of individual codes."
5011,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,100,"Our study investigates AI’s role in QDA, with the AI assistance primarily directed at supporting the coding phase by generating suggestions for these granular codes."
5012,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,101,The subsequent process of developing broader themes remains a researcher-led interpretive task.
5013,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,102,"Manuscript submitted to ACM 6 Anoushka Puranik, Ester Chen, Roshan L Peiris, and Ha-Kyung Kong 3.1 Participants We recruited individuals across various departments involving qualitative research (e.g., sociology, history, anthropology, and information science) through campus flyers, email outreach, and professional networking platforms such as LinkedIn."
5014,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,103,Inclusion criteria for eligible participants included a minimum of one year of experience in qualitative research and prior experience using a qualitative data analysis tool.
5015,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,104,"Interviews were conducted with 16 participants, aged 23 to 40 (mean = 29.1), with qualitative analysis experience ranging from 2 to 7 years (mean = 3.9)."
5016,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,105,"Participants reported their highest degree completed or currently being pursued: 9 were pursuing or had completed a PhD, and 7 a Master’s degree."
5017,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,106,"Eleven participants were in academia (8 PhD students and 3 MS students), and five participants were user experience researchers in industry."
5018,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,107,"The research expertise of participants ranged from accessibility, human-machine teaming, behavioral decision-making, paralinguistic elements in captions for the Deaf and Hard-of-Hearing, early childhood education, to HIV counseling."
5019,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,108,"More information is provided in Table 1. 3.2 ChromaScribe: AI-based QDA Prototype To ground the discussion and give participants an idea of what AI integration in QDA might look like, we developed ChromaScribe as shown in Figure 1, an AI-based QDA webtool prototype."
5020,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,109,The tool was introduced as an exploratory artifact rather than a fully realized QDA system.
5021,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,110,"It was not designed to adhere to a single AI-delegation type, and it was possible to use the tool for both the AI-initiated and human-initiated workflow."
5022,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,111,"This choice follows established prior work showing that early-stage prototypes are effective for exploration and reflection rather than evaluation, helping participants articulate needs, expectations, and values around emerging technologies [21, 24, 67]."
5023,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,112,"Thus, the prototype served as a concrete prompt to support discussion around AI-supported qualitative analysis, including perceived benefits, concerns, and feasibility."
5024,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,113,"However, its inclusion of AI-generated themes could have functioned as a framing device."
5025,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,114,"By exposing participants to these themes, the system may have anchored participants’ mental models of the role of AI in QDA."
5026,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,115,The study findings should be interpreted within this context.
5027,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,116,The webtool uses a locally hosted interface to ensure the data is not accessed by any third-party cloud servers.
5028,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,117,"Access to the prototype was restricted through a password-protected login, and credentials were shared only with study participants for the duration of the study."
5029,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,118,"To further ensure confidentiality, the access password was changed after each study session."
5030,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,119,"Upon logging in, participants encountered a pre-loaded dataset, which consisted of anonymized interview transcripts and corresponding audio recordings from a study on HIV molecular surveillance involving healthcare workers and individuals from affected communities."
5031,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,120,"The tool automatically identifies and color-codes themes based on transcripts and audio files, generating a set of preliminary themes using natural language processing, which are then presented to users for review."
5032,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,121,"We selected established, non-generative natural language processing (NLP) models over opaque Large Language Models (LLMs)."
5033,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,122,"Specifically, we utilized BERTopic [27] to derive initial latent topics and Word2Vec [47, 48] to identify related keywords."
5034,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,123,"This deterministic pipeline allowed us to explain the system’s logic clearly to participants, mitigating the “black box” effect often cited as a barrier to AI adoption [16]."
5035,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,124,"Users can either select the generated themes or manually add their own, as illustrated in Figure 2."
5036,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,125,"A visualization-based interface displays theme distributions over time, indicating where specific themes appear most frequently in the transcript, as shown in Figure 3."
5037,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,126,"Manuscript submitted to ACM Striking the Balance Between Efficiency and Ownership in Qualitative Data Analysis 7 Participants Age Gender Years of Experi- ence Highest Degree Research Area Tools used for QDA P1 26 F 4 PhD stu- dent Human-AI collaboration, com- puting education accessibility Google Docs, Google Sheets, Miro P2 27 F 2.5 PhD stu- dent Design, culture, and accessibil- ity Google Docs, Google Sheets, Miro P3 24 F 3 Masters Accessibility Google Docs, Google Sheets, Zoom, FigJam P4 33 F 7 PhD User studies on AI technology Zoom, Webex P5 27 F 5 Masters student Human-Computer Interaction (HCI) Word, Miro, Microsoft Teams, FigJam, ChatGPT, iOS voice recording app, Figma P6 26 F 4 Masters student Language learning, VR, ASR ex- periences Google Sheets, Zoom, Atlas.ti, Otter AI, Whiteboarding tools, AirTable, Descript P7 31 F 6 PhD stu- dent Chatbots, job support technolo- gies Excel, Miro, Microsoft Teams, Otter AI P8 40 M 2 PhD stu- dent Captioning for d/Deaf and HoH users Google Docs, Google Sheets, Miro P9 32 F 6 PhD stu- dent Human-Computer Interaction Google Docs, Zoom, Whisper, NVivo, Atlas.ti, Open source QDA on Github P10 26 M 3 Masters student AI in clinical decision-making, model analysis Google Docs, Google Sheets, Otter AI, Descript, Deedose P11 28 F 2 Masters Web and cognitive accessibility, digital tech use Google Docs, Excel, Microsoft Teams, Deedose P12 33 M 6 PhD stu- dent AI and media forensics, public sentiment Google Docs, ChatGPT, Gem- ini advanced, Claude P13 35 F 3 Masters Early childhood and home edu- cation Excel, Microsoft Teams, Dee- dose, Covidence P14 26 F 3 PhD stu- dent Deepfake detection tool design Google Docs, RefAI P15 23 F 3 PhD stu- dent Accessibility for older adults and neurodivergent users Google Docs, Excel, Miro, Zoom, Taguette P16 29 F 3 Masters HIV services and relationship dynamics NVivo Table 1."
5038,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,127,"Overview of participant demographics, academic background, research expertise, and prior experience with qualitative data analysis (QDA) tools."
5039,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,128,"The table includes information on age, gender, years of experience, highest degree attained, research domain, and QDA tools used by each participant."
5040,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,129,Gender is denoted as F (Female) and M (Male).
5041,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,130,"Manuscript submitted to ACM 8 Anoushka Puranik, Ester Chen, Roshan L Peiris, and Ha-Kyung Kong 3.3 Procedure We conducted a formative study involving a pre-study demographic survey, an exploration of ChromaScribe, a semi-structured interview, and a post-study survey."
5042,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,131,The study was reviewed and approved by the university’s Institutional Review Board (IRB).
5043,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,132,"The pre-study survey contained questions on demographic details, QDA experience, coding approaches, and the use of multimodal data."
5044,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,133,Participants were screened based on their research experience and inclusion criteria.
5045,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,134,"Each interview began with a consent process and included questions on participants’ current QDA workflow, QDA tool use and preferences, and current challenges related to the QDA process and tools."
5046,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,135,"In the next phase, participants were introduced to ChromaScribe."
5047,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,136,"After watching a demo video, participants were given time to explore the webtool independently and then asked to complete four structured tasks including (a) locating a participant who mentioned a selected theme at least three times and (b) playing the audio of a segment where the interviewer mentioned a selected theme."
5048,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,137,"These tasks were designed to prompt participants to explore how the tool supports theme discovery, navigation, transcript-audio alignment, search and to ensure that all participants engaged with the core functionalities of the prototype."
5049,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,138,Participants were informed that the prototype is preliminary and only meant to facilitate the discussion.
5050,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,139,"The main page of ChromaScribe, an AI-augmented QDA webtool prototype with a color-coded visualization panel (left) and transcription panel (right)."
5051,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,140,A mouse cursor highlights the user selecting a blue thematic block between 15:00 and 20:00 for participant P3.
5052,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,141,"Consequently, the transcription panel on the right displays the specific transcript segment corresponding to this selection.(Note, Transcript text is blurred to preserve the confidentiality of interview data)."
5053,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,142,"To address RQ1, participants were introduced to three distinct types (i.e. degrees of delegation) of AI involvement in qualitative coding: human-only coding, AI-initiated coding, and human-initiated coding, after the completion of four tasks on ChromaScribe."
5054,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,143,The three coding types were presented to participants in a written format to elicit preferences and perceptions during the interview.
5055,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,144,Each participant was given a brief textual description of the three types and allotted two minutes to read them carefully.
5056,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,145,They were then asked to rank the coding types from most to least preferred.
5057,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,146,We further prompted them to share the reason for their preference.
5058,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,147,"To minimize bias toward any particular AI delegation paradigm, the prototype was introduced prior to presenting participants with the three AI involvement modes and the participants were encouraged to explore different workflows as they desired."
5059,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,148,"To address RQ2, we then asked about their collaborative practices in QDA, their thoughts on subjectivity and bias in the process, and how QDA tools could address bias."
5060,18,C018_P1_pdf.txt,149,"Lastly, to address RQ3, participants were asked about their current reliance on transcripts, audio, and video during analysis and we asked about their use and thoughts on multimodal data in QDA."
5061,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,0,"From Assistance to Autonomy – A Researcher Study on the Potential of AI Support for Qualitative Data Analysis ELISABETH KIRSTEN,Ruhr University Bochum, Germany ANNALINA BUCKMANN,Ruhr University Bochum, Germany LEONA LASSAK,Ruhr University Bochum, Germany NELE BORGERT,University of Bern, Switzerland ABRAHAM MHAIDLI,Max Planck Institute for Security and Privacy, Germany STEFFEN BECKER∗,Ruhr University Bochum, Germany The advent of Artificial Intelligence (AI) tools, such as Large Language Models, has introduced new possibilities for Qualitative Data Analysis (QDA), offering both opportunities and challenges."
5062,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,1,"To help navigate the responsible integration ofAI into QDA, we conducted semi-structured interviews with 15 Human-Computer Interaction (HCI) researchers experienced in QDA."
5063,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,2,"While our participants were open to AI support in their QDA workflows, they expressed concerns about data privacy, autonomy, and the quality of AI outputs."
5064,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,3,"In response, we developed a framework that spans from minimal to high AI involvement, providing tangible scenarios for integrating AI into QDA practices while addressing researchers’ needs and concerns."
5065,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,4,"Aligned with real-lifeQDA workflows, we identify potential for AI tools in areas such as data pre-processing, researcher onboarding, or conflict mediation."
5066,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,5,Our framework aims to provoke further discussion on the development of AI-supported QDA and to help establish community standards for responsible Human-AI collaboration.
5067,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,6,"CCS Concepts:•Human-centered computing → Interactive systems and tools;Collaborative and social computing design and evaluation methods; Collaborative interaction;User studies; HCI theory, concepts and models;•Computing methodologies → Artificial intelligence."
5068,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,7,"Additional Key Words and Phrases: Qualitative Data Analysis, Large Language Models, Interview Study 1 Introduction Artificial Intelligence (AI) tools have grown increasingly popular, driven by the rapid rise of Large Language Models (LLMs)."
5069,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,8,"These powerful models can generate coherent, contextually relevant text across diverse topics and perform tasks such as classification and summarization [18, 105]."
5070,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,9,"LLMs have been widely adopted across domains, from programming assistance to educational tutoring, and are increasingly finding their way into research contexts."
5071,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,10,"One area where these models hold significant, yet debated potential is Qualitative Data Analysis (QDA)."
5072,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,11,"Human- Computer Interaction (HCI) and CSCW researchers are beginning to explore the usage ofLLMs throughout their research processes for tasks such as conducting QDA [28], generating synthetic data and substituting human participants [4, 49, 88], creative ideation [76, 89], literature reviews, and writing [58]."
5073,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,12,"Commercial tools have also started integrating AI features (e. g., ATLAS.ti,1 MAXQDA,2 and nVivo’s Lumivero AI Assistant3) [70]. ∗Also with Max Planck Institute for Security and Privacy. 1https://atlasti.com/ 2https://www.maxqda.com/products/ai-assist 3https://lumivero.com/product/nvivo-ai-assistant/ Authors’ Contact Information: Elisabeth Kirsten, Ruhr University Bochum, Bochum, Germany, elisabeth.kirsten@rub.de; Annalina Buckmann, Ruhr University Bochum, Bochum, Germany, annalina.buckmann@rub.de; Leona Lassak, Ruhr University Bochum, Bochum, Germany, leona.lassak@rub.de; Nele Borgert, University of Bern, Bern, Switzerland, nele.borgert@unibe.ch; Abraham Mhaidli, Max Planck Institute for Security and Privacy, Bochum, Germany, abraham.mhaidli@mpi-sp.org; Steffen Becker, Ruhr University Bochum, Bochum, Germany, steffen.becker@rub.de. 1 arXiv:2501.19275v3 [cs.CY] 27 Feb 2026 2 Kirsten et al."
5074,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,13,"The rapid adoption of AI tools begs the question:which steps of the QDA workflow are suitable for AI support, and how do we make these determinations?These questions are particularly pivotal for CSCW, where QDA plays a dual role: as a methodological tool, and as a site of collaboration, negotiation, and interpretive practice in interdisciplinary teams with different epistemic traditions [ 15, 40, 69]."
5075,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,14,"Although AI tools can be useful, they raise dilemmas about researcher autonomy [39] and the risks of imperfect AI outputs (e. g., LLMs hallucinating wrong information) [109]."
5076,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,15,"As a community, it is imperative to critically assess which tasks in the QDA workflow are appropriate or inappropriate for AI integration, and to ensure its responsible use."
5077,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,16,"To better understand how AI tools can, and should (not), be integrated into QDA, we conducted semi-structured interviews with HCI researchers about their QDA workflows and opinions on AI integration."
5078,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,17,"We found that while researchers’QDA workflows share structural similarities, they differ significantly based on project specifics, highlighting the need for AI tools that are highly customizable."
5079,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,18,"Researchers were generally open to AI assistance when it enhanced their workflow but stressed the importance of ethical considerations, trust in AI outputs, and maintaining control."
5080,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,19,Our contributions are as follows.
5081,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,20,"First, we provide an empirical account of researchers’QDA practices, pain points, and challenges."
5082,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,21,"Second, we present a framework for integrating AI into QDA workflows, grounded in researchers’ perspectives on the individual stages of QDA and prior work, extending beyond the task of coding itself."
5083,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,22,"Based on our findings we ideate tangible scenarios for the integration of AI, including AI as a productivity tool (e. g., taking on more technical tasks), as a mediator (e. g., facilitating consensus), or with human approval (e. g., suggesting codebook components with validation by a researcher)."
5084,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,23,"Finally, we discuss how this framework can guide the responsible deployment of AI tools that truly support researchers’ needs and preserve the social value of collaborative analysis practices. 2 Background In this section, we lay out the methodological backgrounds of Qualitative Data Analysis (QDA) and trace the evolution of AI-assisted QDA from basic computational methods to the growing role of Large Language Models ( LLMs)."
5085,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,24,"We conclude by synthesizing our research questions. 2.1 Qualitative Data Analysis in CSCW and HCI QDA is a fundamental process in qualitative and mixed-method research within CSCW and HCI, providing systematic techniques for interpreting non-numeric data such as interviews, field notes, videos, or documents [16, 69]."
5086,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,25,"Its primary goal is to juxtapose or integrate different sources to identify patterns, themes, and insights that deepen our understanding of the research subject."
5087,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,26,"At its core,QDA typically involves iterative cycles of data extraction, synthesis, and analysis [16]."
5088,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,27,"QDA is shaped by various methodological frameworks that may overlap in scientific practice (see reporting of QDA steps in Section 4.1) but are distinct in theoretical foundations, flexibility, and depth of analysis."
5089,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,28,"WhileThematic Analysis[ 17] is a theoretical framework that focuses on coding features relevant to the research question,Content Analysis[ 108] quantifies specific events or codes, enabling a blend with quantitative approaches.Grounded Theory[ 47] aims at theory generation through systematic coding directly from the data, andFramework Analysis[cf. 12] applies existing frameworks, refining them throughout analysis, useful in applied research contexts that aim to build upon and extend existing knowledge."
5090,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,29,"In contrast,Narrative Analysis[ 85] emphasizes the structure and meaning of data within its narrative context."
5091,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,30,"Coding strategies can bedeductive(codes follow predefined categories),inductive(patterns identified in the data), or hybrid, enabling researchers to choose an approach that aligns with their objectives."
5092,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,31,"The choice of A Researcher Study on the Potential of AI Support for Qualitative Data Analysis 3 coding strategy is not merely technical but reflects a researcher’s underlying goals and questions, guiding the research direction and ensuring the chosen method supports the intended outcomes."
5093,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,32,"Underlying these methods are different epistemologies, from more positivist ones aiming at recognition and discovery, to more interpretive ones, requiring in-depth analysis and centering researcher subjectivity and reflexivity [ 5, 6, 20, 48, 91]."
5094,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,33,"Within CSCW and HCI, projects commonly involve more than one researcher [ 57, 69], making QDA a fundamentally collaborative and social practice of negotiating, resolving disagreements, and making sense of ambiguity."
5095,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,34,"This collaboration is often asynchronous and distributed, and supported by digital tools and software [102], increasingly incorporating Natural Language Processing (NLP) and LLM methods into the QDA process – thus, QDA fundamentally becomescomputer-supported cooperative work."
5096,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,35,"At the same time, QDA in CSCW and HCI is shaped by interdisciplinary diversity [15]."
5097,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,36,"Researchers bring different epistemological traditions and backgrounds [15, 40, 69], which leads to ongoing debates about transparency, rigor, reliability, and measures thereof, such as Inter-Rater Reliability (IRR), [15, 40, 69, 91]."
5098,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,37,"Yet, despite QDA’s centrality to CSCW and HCI, there has been no systematic documentation of how CSCW andHCI researchers actually conduct QDA in practice, or how emerging technologies might reshape it."
5099,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,38,The closest analysis we could find is the work by McDonald et al.[69] documenting how interrater reliability is used in CSCW and CHI.
5100,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,39,They find that reporting IRR is rare and authors often use other methods to report on reliability.
5101,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,40,"A more comprehensive overview of the whole QDA process, though, is still lacking."
5102,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,41,"Our work addresses this gap by synthesizing and extending fragmented conversations into a coherent account of real-world QDA workflows. 2.2 From Computational Support to AI-Assisted Analysis While nowadays, CSCW and HCI researchers draw on a variety of tools for analysis [40], computer-assisted approaches have long supported QDA, from supporting basic coding tasks, to experiments with automation: Early tools applied basic NLP techniques such as word frequency analysis, keyword matching, and pattern-based rules [ 68, 92]."
5103,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,42,"While these methods introduced automation, they lacked the capacity to capture complex human interpretations."
5104,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,43,"Subsequent work introduced supervised machine learning for text classification, extending manual coding into larger datasets [86]."
5105,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,44,"Unsupervised approaches such as topic modeling uncovered latent themes without predefined categories [65], and some studies reported surprising alignment with qualitative methods like grounded theory [13, 72]."
5106,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,45,"Such combinations of QDA and machine learning can be especially useful for mixed-methods studies and for analyzing large-scale data, though they raise concerns about transparency and interpretability – values central to qualitative research."
5107,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,46,"Recent advances in generative AI, particularly LLMs like ChatGPT, offer new opportunities."
5108,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,47,"These models are trained on massive text corpora and can generate, summarize, and classify language with a high degree of contextual awareness [105]."
5109,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,48,"They encode vast amounts of diverse knowledge, making them potentially adaptable to various tasks within qualitative research."
5110,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,49,"Recent prototypes integrate LLMs at different points across the QDA workflow, from inductive coding to codebook development [10, 44, 70, 83, 96, 110]."
5111,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,50,"LLMs have shown remarkable performance on annotation tasks where little or no labeled data is provided [46, 98] and have been proposed ascollaboratorsin human annotation teams [ 113], indicating a shift from assistance to autonomy of computational methods supporting the cooperative work of QDA."
5112,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,51,"This evolution highlights not only the opportunities for scaling qualitative work, but also the risks it creates for preserving interpretive rigor and methodological integrity."
5113,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,52,"These concerns are shared by HCI and CSCW researchers [39, 57, 67], showing reservation and opposition to the integration of AI into QDA, or specifying specific use contexts that retain human agency."
5114,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,53,"While these studies were conducted prior to the advent of LLMs, recent work identified a ""generational gap"", with early career researchers being more open, and more experienced researchers more reserved towards the integration of AI into QDA, calling into question AI and QDA literacy as well as structural inequalities 4 Kirsten et al. that may facilitate attitudes [ 20]."
5115,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,54,This necessitates further engagement with shifting researcher attitudes towards AI-supported QDA. 2.3 Potentials and Risks of AI in the QDA Workflow Recent studies show how AI can assist at multiple points in the QDA process.
5116,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,55,Cuevas et al. [25] examine the usage of LLMs for conducting user studies and analyzing the collected data.
5117,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,56,"For labeling and annotating, LLM-based systems apply existing codes from a given codebook with notable consistency, though they often miss subtle contextual judgments [110]."
5118,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,57,"Lam et al . [64] develop a LLM-based text analysis tool that derives interpretable concepts from unstructured text, inspired by traditional topic models."
5119,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,58,"For data exploration and inductive coding, LLMs can surface novel patterns and assist in the initial exploration of themes and codes, potentially enabling a deeper understanding."
5120,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,59,"However, while LLMs can replicate many primary themes identified by humans, they often miss more subtle and complex interpretations [70, 97, 111]."
5121,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,60,"Hamilton et al . [50] observed complementary patterns between human and ChatGPT-generated codes, with each identifying themes that the other did not."
5122,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,61,"Barany et al. [11] investigated the use of ChatGPT for codebook creation, finding hybrid approaches to be more reliable."
5123,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,62,"They suggest LLMs can contribute to the improvement of codebooks, but stress that human involvement remains crucial."
5124,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,63,"While combining interpretive and positivist methods can cause epistemic tensions and discussions among researchers [13, 72, 81], studies highlight mutual compatibility [13, 20, 44, 64, 72]."
5125,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,64,"AI also holds potential for mediating discussions and facilitating collaboration by highlighting coding discrepancies, and suggesting resolutions [32, 41, 42]."
5126,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,65,"While these efforts illustrate potential, they also expose tensions."
5127,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,66,"Concerns persist around bias [3, 8, 10, 78, 99, 113], lack of reliability for non-English languages [ 54, 94], and the risk of treating AI as “culturally agnostic” despite its privileging of certain perspectives [81]."
5128,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,67,"Such issues are particularly important when engaging minority groups or Global South contexts, where AI risks reproducing inequalities in representation and missing interpretative nuance [56, 63, 74, 87, 101]."
5129,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,68,"This raises concerns regarding bias in interpretation, but also research ethics of fairness and inclusion [59]."
5130,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,69,"Moreover, perspectives from the Global Souths are largely absent from AI development, and little is known on how AI is used and deployed in the Global Souths [66, 74, 95]."
5131,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,70,"Another tension arises from the very foundations of AI itself: borne on statistical methods and probability, AI reflects a positivist paradigm that can impede the interpretative nature of qualitative inquiry [ 20, 57, 81]."
5132,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,71,"This is amplified by the problem of overreliance on AI, facilitated by the plausibility of AI generations: in QDA, AI-generated ""interpretations"" or suggestions may be simply accepted, instead of being critically interrogated [19, 59, 74], creating lopsided structures of collaboration between AI and human researchers in QDA."
5133,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,72,"This poses specific challenges for teams involving collaborators with varying degrees of literacy regarding AI as well as QDA, especially in interdisciplinary fields like CSCW and HCI."
5134,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,73,"Thus, while AI holds potential to bridge “big” and “small” data approaches and to enhance efficiency, it raises equally urgent questions about reliability, ethics, and researcher agency."
5135,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,74,"These risks and tensions require careful considerations for designing human-AI collaboration in QDA, preserving the depth and richness of QDA while leveraging the potentials of AI. 2.4 Designing for Human-AI Collaboration in QDA Integrating AI into QDA is not simply a matter of automation, but of collaboration as well: It requires careful design for human–AI and human-human collaboration in interpretive, context-sensitive work [57]."
5136,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,75,"Existing tools vary widely in how they support AI involvement, from minimal assistance to active roles in coding and analysis, with different levels of human involvement."
5137,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,76,"Moreover, designing for researchers differing in proficiency in QDA, tool usage, as well as AI A Researcher Study on the Potential of AI Support for Qualitative Data Analysis 5 capability [39, 67] poses specific challenges, especially in diverse fields such as CSCW and HCI."
5138,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,77,"For example, Gauthier and Wallace [44] developed a toolkit to facilitate computational thematic analysis, emphasizing the need to design it accessibly for a community with different proficiencies in tool usage as well as AI."
5139,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,78,"Thus, they call for ethical designs to involve friction to remind researchers of the imperfection of computational models and issues concerning ethics and transparency."
5140,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,79,These challenges are also identified by Kapania et al. [58] who found HCI researchers struggling to identify such issues in their projects and needing guidance.
5141,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,80,"Similarly, Lam et al. [64] suggest tools to be transparent to the researcher and acknowledging their limitations, e. g., by showcasing explicit inclusion criteria and scores."
5142,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,81,"At the same time, designs should avoid creating excessive “unanticipated labor” for researchers [39]."
5143,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,82,"While prior studies provide valuable insights into the potentials of AI in QDA [44, 64, 70, 83, 96], there is still limited understanding of how AI can beresponsiblyintegrated into researchers’ real-life QDA workflows, respecting their concerns and preferences [39, 67], facilitating collaboration between researchers as well as researchers and AI, while consolidating different research epistemologies."
5144,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,83,"We are thus in need for comprehensive frameworks addressing these issues [58, 78]."
5145,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,84,"Moreover, it remains crucial to critically reflect not only on AI capability, but also what itshoulddo in QDA, preserving researcher concerns and preferences [39, 67]."
5146,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,85,"We extend this to the era of LLMs, identifying new steps, tasks, and different levels of involvement of AI to support QDA while maintaining methodological integrity."
5147,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,86,"To address these gaps, we study HCI researchers’ QDA workflows and their perspectives on the involvement of AI in qualitative research."
5148,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,87,"Specifically, we investigate the following research questions: RQ1How does HCI researchers’ real-life QDA workflow look like?"
5149,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,88,RQ2 What are HCI researchers’ concerns and conditions for integrating AI-based support into theirQDA workflow?
5150,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,89,"Our overarching goal is toexplore how AI can be responsibly integrated into QDA, respecting the workflows, concerns, and conditions of HCI researchers.By systematically mapping QDA practices (RQ1) and surfacing researchers’ conditions for AI integration (RQ2), we contribute a framework for AI support that is aligned with the real-world QDA workflows of HCI researchers."
5151,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,90,This framework synthesizes fragmented CSCW debates around QDA and provides concrete guidance for developing AI tools that enhance – rather than disrupt – the collaborative and interpretive nature of qualitative research. 3 Research Method We conducted a two-step study to explore HCI researchers’ perspectives on integrating AI intoQDA.
5152,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,91,"The first step involved semi-structured interviews with 15 HCI researchers, representing a range of QDA experience levels."
5153,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,92,"These interviews were designed to uncover pain points, potentials, and conditions for AI support inQDA, focusing on real-life workflows, challenges, and concerns."
5154,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,93,"To promote transparency and rigor, we preregistered our study on the Open Science Framework (OSF) platform.4 In the second step, we used the findings of the interviews to conceptualize waysAI can be integrated into QDA."
5155,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,94,We developed a framework to illustrate concrete examples of how AI can be integrated into the QDA workflow and contextualize these examples with how they align (or do not align) with participants’ concerns. 3.1 Study Materials Our study included a pre-questionnaire and a semi-structured interview with a sketching task.
5156,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,95,The full interview guide is available in Appendix A.
5157,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,96,Both the complete pre-questionnaire and the interview guide are available in our anonymized OSF repository. 4see https://osf.io/yzkta/?view_only=c4bb80ff8635434db0e7c3166146fa53 6 Kirsten et al.
5158,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,97,"Pre-Questionnaire.The pre-questionnaire consisted of eight questions, capturing participants’ backgrounds and experience with QDA."
5159,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,98,"It covered their research background, current field of research, current position, tools used for QDA, years of experience working with qualitative data, the number of research projects involving QDA, and the data collection and analysis methods they have employed in the past."
5160,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,99,"Interview Guide.The interview guide was organized into three parts: (a) participants’ real-life QDA workflows, (b) pain points and gain points in QDA, and (c) perspectives on the potential for AI support."
5161,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,100,"First (a), we explored the participants’ overall research process, from data collection to analysis, with a particular focus on coding."
5162,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,101,"We asked them to reflect on their most recent research project, discussing the types of data used, the methods and tools employed, resources accessed, and, if applicable, collaboration with other researchers."
5163,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,102,"To facilitate this reflection, we asked them to sketch their coding process on a piece of paper (sketching task)."
5164,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,103,"This visual representation not only helped them articulate their workflow but also served as a reference in subsequent explanations, allowing them to highlight specific areas where pain points arose or where they saw potential for AI support."
5165,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,104,"Then (b), we delved more deeply into the QDA workflow, focusing on what participants found enjoyable or engaging, as well as what they found tedious or challenging."
5166,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,105,"We asked which steps were particularly time-consuming, the difficulties encountered, and the role of tool support, including both its benefits and limitations."
5167,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,106,"Lastly (c), we explored participants’ expectations around AI-assistedQDA."
5168,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,107,"We inquired about the conditions under which they would be willing to integrate AI into their workflows, which steps they believed could be automated, and which aspects should remain human-driven."
5169,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,108,"Finally, participants were given the opportunity to share any additional thoughts on the topic. 3.2 Recruitment & Participants We used purposive and snowball sampling methods [80] to recruit participants who had conducted at least one study involving QDA through our professional networks within the HCI and Usable Security and Privacy (USP) communities."
5170,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,109,"We approached researchers directly and invited them to refer interested colleagues, leveraging peer identification to build a diverse and qualified sample."
5171,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,110,Our recruitment strategy was designed to capture variation across research domains and methodological traditions relevant to CSCW and HCI.
5172,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,111,We categorized participants’ primary research field based on their self-description.
5173,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,112,"To capture a broad range of experiences and perspectives, we took care to recruit participants from diverse group affiliations, different study approaches, topic choices, and educational backgrounds."
5174,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,113,"Our goal was to achieve data saturation regarding participants’ workflows, pain points, and gain points."
5175,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,114,Sample Description.Table 1 summarizes the participant sample.
5176,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,115,"We interviewed 15 HCI researchers with backgrounds in computer science, cybersecurity, engineering, and social sciences, all firmly embedded in HCI research, with some specifying to focus on USP."
5177,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,116,"Twelve participants were early career researchers (mostly PhD candidates), and three were senior researchers."
5178,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,117,"Eight had worked on 1-3 QDA projects, four on 4-6, and three on more than 7 projects, with QDA experience ranging from 1 to 9 years."
5179,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,118,We recruited participants until data saturation was reached.
5180,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,119,We reached data saturation around interview 12 and conducted three additional interviews to confirm this.
5181,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,120,"Participants first completed the pre-questionnaire, which included an overview of the study procedure and a consent form."
5182,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,121,"Afterward, we scheduled interviews."
5183,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,122,"The interviews were semi-structured, conducted face-to-face, and lasted approximately 45 minutes."
5184,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,123,"Interviews were conducted in either English ( 𝑛= 9) or German (𝑛= 6), depending on participants’ native language and preference."
5185,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,124,"Two researchers were present: a lead interviewer who conducted the session and took notes, and a second researcher who created detailed protocols, including occasional verbatim quotes."
5186,18,C018_S1_pdf.txt,125,To A Researcher Study on the Potential of AI Support for Qualitative Data Analysis 7 Table 1.
