5245,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,14,"Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. 07 Apr 2026 at 15:09:38, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use. 2 Jing Xu and Jose Manuel Hernandez 1. “Kill that Strange Bird”: culture, cognition and meaning On September 1, 1959, in a village in the Taipei basin, a local research assistant, MC,1 Miss Chen, hired by the American anthropologist Arthur W olf to observe children’ s social interactions, documented the following episode in great detail."
5246,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,15,"In this observation, three boys and a seven-year-old girl (all in pseudonyms) played a game called “Kill that Strange Bird. ” Cheng Li-chu (6-year-old) & Cheng Mu-wen (6-year-old) were in front of House 104."
5247,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,16,Li-chu to Mu-wen: “Let’ s go kill that Strange Bird [reference from a recent movie]. ” Mu-wen: “I’m going to really kill it this time. ” They walked toward the back of the house.
5248,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,17,"As they crossed the ditch, Li-chu shot a stick through his hollow bamboo and said: “I’m going to really kill you this time, Strange Bird!” They walk over to Peng Ah-lien (7-year-old) who was playing house with some other children."
5249,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,18,Li-chu lifted his “gun” and said: “Bang!
5250,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,19,"They repeated this several time, but Ah-lien ignored them."
5251,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,20,"Li-chu finally said: “Come on, Strange Bird. ” Mu-wen repeated this."
5252,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,21,Li-chu: “This time we’re going to catch you wherever you go. ” Ah-lien turned her head to them and said: “I’m not afraid of you.
5253,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,22,I’m going to hide under the water. ” Li-chu: “I’m going to get an anti-aircraft gun.
5254,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,23,I’ll shoot you through the water and kill you. ” Ah-lien: “No.
5255,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,24,"Y ou can’t. ” Cheng Liang-wen [Cheng Mu-wen’ s brother, 8-year-old] came and said: “No, we’re going to use Nike missiles. ” Li-chu: “Y es."
5256,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,25,W e’ll use Nike missiles. ” Liang-wen: “W e’re going to shoot them into the water and the water will turn into fire and burn you!” Mu-wen & Li-chu: “Y eh!
5257,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,26,Then you can’t hide in the water anymore!” All three of them yelled threats at her [Ah-lien].
5258,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,27,Li-chu: “Let’ s say you are hiding in a volcano in your nest and there is a fire in there and I’m going to use my missile to fire right into your nest and the mountain will blow you up and you are going to be killed. ” Ah-lien argues with them about where she will hide.
5259,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,28,They stopped for a while to watch something else. 1MC was a teenage girl.
5260,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,29,"At that time, it was common for anthropologists to rely on local intermediaries for their fieldwork, including youths and young adults, especially when the research focused on studying children."
5261,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,30,"That was an era before the the IRB (Institutional Review Board) system was formally established in the United States, which regulates human subjects protection and research ethics."
5262,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,31,"This article is based on second-hand analysis of historical fieldnotes, with ethical approval from the Institutional Review Board of the University of W ashington."
5263,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,32,"Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. 07 Apr 2026 at 15:09:38, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use."
5264,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,33,"Cambridge Forum on AI: Culture and Society 3 The entire event unfolded spontaneously among four young children, without any top-down super- vision or instructions, which was a very ordinary part of their mundane life."
5265,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,34,"Y et such a simple text preserved incredibly rich information, not just about physical confrontations, or pretentious con- frontations, but with psychological, social, cultural and historical significance, all pointing to the mystery of children’ s play."
5266,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,35,"The dazzling “fight” in the opening vignette – the quotation marks are necessary because it is a pretend-play – presents a maze of meaning: It weaves together layers of symbolism, metaphors and sentiments embedded in the very specific setting of Cold-W ar Taiwan."
5267,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,36,Some layers of meaning and certain intersubjective dimensions of behavior are far from transparent in the text itself.
5268,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,37,"Children’ s play seems trivial but contains enormous educational power (Gray,2017)."
5269,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,38,"Play is meta-communication, “communication about communication” and inherently paradoxical: Conveying the very message “this is play” signals that the actions that children are about to engage in “do not denote what those actionsfor which they stand would denote” (Bateson,2000 [1972], 185)."
5270,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,39,"These playful dramas, spontaneously and creatively enactedby and for children, constitute an impor- tant platform for moral development, as children learn to cooperate, resolve conflict, read social minds and understand moral norms (Xu, 2024)."
5271,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,40,"Due to the imaginative nature of play, in which the actions are governed by rules in the players’ minds, these dramas can easily confuse an outside observer (Gray, 2017)."
5272,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,41,"T o decipher children’ s moral dramas, an anthropologist needs to grasp subtle cultural meanings and attune to meta-communicative cues."
5273,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,42,How would they “read” these scenes?
5274,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,43,"Situated at the intersection of anthropology, data science, digital humani- ties and developmental science, this article critically reflects on AI interdisciplinarity concerning the interpretation and translation of diverse lifeworlds and social experiences."
5275,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,44,"It tells the story of how children, anthropologists and AI make sense of such layered social interactions, and by doing so, interrogates the nature of learning morality."
5276,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,45,"The opening vignette invites us to explore how, in the process of learning morality, e.g., the good killing the evil, or my side beats your side, human cognition operates within and through cultural reality."
5277,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,46,"Human morality is “originated in our species’ natural history of cooperation and coordination and actualized in our holistic social history” (Xu, 2019: 657)."
5278,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,47,"In cognitive science, learning is often defined as the process by which an agent forms an internal model of the world (Dehaene, 2020:3)."
5279,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,48,"But learning is also a socially situated process where “agent, activity and the world mutually consti- tute each other” (Lave & W enger,1991: 33)."
5280,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,49,"In other words, children acquire their moral knowledge through active engagements in real-world contexts."
5281,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,50,"The episode contains complex cultural symbolism, fluid at the moment but also sedimented in history. “The Strange Bird” was not really a bird."
5282,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,51,"It referred to a military aircraft, and it was played by a child, the only female actor, Ah-lien, in this grandiose drama."
5283,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,52,"A bamboo stick was not really a stick, but a gun, which, in the children’ s later imagination, upgraded into an anti-aircraft gun; “Nike missiles, ” vivid in a six-year-old’ s fantasy, is a poignant reminder that quotidian details of everyday life in this small community reflect geopolitical trends at the height of the Cold W ar era."
5284,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,53,"In August 1958, just about a year before this observation took place, the Second Taiwan Strait Crisis broke out between the People’ s Republic of China, ruled by the Chinese Communist Party, and the Republic of China (ROC) under the KMT’s military dictatorship."
5285,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,54,"In October 1958, the United States Army sent out a Nike-Hercules Missile unit to Taipei County, Taiwan, at a site about 13 kilometers from the children’ s village, and a year later, the Nike-Hercules Missile was handed over to ROC forces (see Figure 1).2 It is equally important to attend to the cognitive aspects of this episode, from its production, chil- dren learning together, to its interpretation, anthropologists learning about children."
5286,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,55,"First of all, it was children’ s “shared intentionality” that made their coordination possible. “Shared intentionality” refers to the human capacity to engage with the psychological states of others and enact collaborative inter- actions, something that human children are exceptionally good at and arguably a part of what makes 2https://www.britishpathe.com/asset/162264/."
5287,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,56,"Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. 07 Apr 2026 at 15:09:38, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use. 4 Jing Xu and Jose Manuel Hernandez Figure 1."
5288,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,57,"The Nike-Hercules missile unit in Taipei County, Taiwan."
5289,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,58,"Source: Government of the Republic of China, public domain, via Wikimedia Commons. our species unique (T omasello & Carpenter,2007)."
5290,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,59,"No actor in the observation was confused about what “the Strange Bird” meant and everyone knew that to “kill” did not mean, literally and physically, to kill."
5291,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,60,"They all had some shared knowledge about the situation, about their own goals and about what they knew that the others knew."
5292,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,61,"Such shared knowledge also extends to the observer and local research assistant, MC, who was the only eyewitness to this event, and critically, a cultural insider and children’ s trusted playmate."
5293,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,62,"She inserted a short note, “reference from a recent movie, ” right after the boy announced, “Let’ s kill that Strange Bird. ” The intended reader of this message was MC’s supervi- sor, the American anthropologist Arthur W olf."
5294,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,63,"W olf was much less immersed in children’ s lives than MC and, therefore, might not immediately understand what the boy actually meant. 3 This is just one among many episodes of children’ s play that I 4 encountered while trying to re- analyze a rare and significant archive of fieldnotes left behind by Arthur W olf, which I call “the W olf 3MC did not specify which exact movie children were referring to in 1959, but I knew it was not the 1960 movie “T o Kill a Mockingbird. ” Decades later, a local informant told me that it was probably a movie about the Korean W ar, a popular movie during their childhood. 4This article is written in the first-person singular, from the perspective of the anthropologist Jing Xu’ s reflections."
5295,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,64,"Xu developed the ideas and concepts for this article, curated the data, obtained funding support, supervised research assistants, administered the project, and drafted and revised all sections of the manuscript."
5296,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,65,"In collaboration with Xu, Hernandez con- tributed to section 3.3. of the manuscript, “Semantic search via S-BERT , ” including developing and implementing the computer programs, writing and revising the draft."
5297,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,66,"For the specific workflow of this article, see Figure 2."
5298,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,67,"Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. 07 Apr 2026 at 15:09:38, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use."
5299,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,68,"Cambridge Forum on AI: Culture and Society 5 archive. ” These fieldnotes were collected over six decades ago (1958–60) as part of the first ethno- graphic research focused on ethnic Han children and childhood, but were buried in time until I was invited to bring them to light recently (Xu, 2024)."
5300,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,69,"T o re-interpret this unique and historically signif- icant set of fieldnotes, my team built a text-to-data pipeline to digitize and organize these materials."
5301,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,70,"W e used various “distant-reading” Natural language processing (NLP) methods, including the state- of-the-art large language models (LLMs), to complement ethnographic close reading and make sense of children’ s social life that we had never and could never have witnessed in person."
5302,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,71,"As I lacked first- person fieldwork experience, my ethnographic interpretation also benefited from reading testimonies from faithful observers like MC and other mediators."
5303,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,72,"I incorporated logical inferences and historical contextualization, ultimately resorting to commonsense – the practical intelligence in human agency that remains to be one of the hardest challenges for language AI (Choi, 2022; Hasselberger & Lott, 2023)."
5304,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,73,"I chose this hybrid approach both due to a top-down concern, my long-term interest in method- ological pluralism and interdisciplinary work (Xu, 2019), and a bottom-up reason, this archive’ s dual nature of both “big data” and “thick data” by anthropology’ s standard (W ang,2016)."
5305,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,74,"In this project, the methodological integration was not a simple addition in which each approach plays its own part without the influence from the other."
5306,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,75,"Instead, it always involved an interpretive loop, where ethno- graphic interpretation and machine reading mutually informed each other to answer a given question, generate a new question and/or inspire a new analytical direction."
5307,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,76,"For example, the core part of this archive, Child Observation (CO), contains over 1600 of episodes like the opening vignette."
5308,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,77,"I used topic-modeling analysis to discover clusters of high-frequency and co-occurring words in this cor- pus, as such textual patterns were hard to detect by the human eye."
5309,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,78,But the ethnographic method remained critical for evaluating the validity and interpreting the meaning of such latent topics.
5310,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,79,"One of such topics, or clusters of words, resembled children’ s fighting, a salient theme that emerged in my close reading."
5311,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,80,"T o systematically examine fighting in comparison to other themes related to my conceptual interests, I collaborated with a data scientist, the co-author of this paper, through learn- ing from each other, incorporating topic-modeling results and ethnographic insights into S-BERT semantic-similarity analysis."
5312,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,81,"While this informed LLM efficiently discerned conflict (fighting) as a dominant theme in the CO corpus, ethnographic reading discovered a problem, that is, the LLM took children’ s playful fights, such as the opening vignette, as real conflicts."
5313,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,82,"This discovery prompted me to identify and analyze a particular subset of playful fights, use a generative LLM, generative pre-trained transformer (GPT), to examine the sentiments and themes of these fieldnotes, and com- pare GPT outputs with my ethnographic knowledge (for a schematic representation of this workflow, see Figure 2)."
5314,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,83,"Fieldnotes about children’ s world are rare and intriguing; for example, children’ s moral dramas encapsulate the mystery of human communication, which blends layered cultural knowledge into shared intentionality."
5315,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,84,"Therefore, this human–machine hybrid approach became, simultaneously, a methodological experiment and an epistemological inquiry."
5316,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,85,"Take “kill that Strange Bird” as an example, exploring the interpretive loops between machine learning, children’ s social learning and anthropological meaning-making can shed valuable light on the nature of intelligence: How do chil- dren create such moral dramas and learn from them?"
5317,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,86,"How do algorithms make sense of words like “killing, ” “gun” and “bird, ” encrypted via layers of cultural symbolism, in the context of children’ s play in rural Taiwan during the Cold W ar?"
5318,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,87,"How do we, machine or human, understand concepts like conflict, aggression and violence, evaluate the valence of behavior and deal with the ambiguity of meaning? 2."
5319,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,88,"Sense-making from a human–AI hybrid approach My engagement with language AI started out as a methodological exploration, taking advantage of new technologies to make sense of historical texts, aligned with “the logic of innovation” in reflections Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. 07 Apr 2026 at 15:09:38, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use. 6 Jing Xu and Jose Manuel Hernandez Figure 2."
5320,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,89,A schematic representation of a workflow chart. on interdisciplinarity.
5321,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,90,"But due to the unique nature of these texts, systematic ethnographic fieldnotes of children’ s socio-moral life, this human–AI collaboration blurs the presumed boundaries between methodological and theoretical interdisciplinarity (Klein, 2010) and embodies a multi-layered inter- disciplinary pursuit: Creating a dialogue on learning between children, ethnographers and AI, it not just examines the methodological problem of how to interpret behavioral meaning via texts, i.e., ethnography versus AI."
5322,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,91,"Meanwhile, it examines the theoretical and epistemological question of how the socio-moral knowledge is acquired by human (or artificial) agents."
5323,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,92,"T o some extent, it also sheds light ontologically (Barry & Born, 2013), because how we (children/ethnographer/AI) know what we know in the socio-moral domain is intimately connected with the nature of the very entity itself: what is socio-moral intelligence, or what are the different types of such intelligence?"
5324,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,93,"All of these quests are entangled in my unexpected encounter with a rare archive, an encounter that bridges the archive’ s past life and afterlife, testifies disciplinary and interdisciplinary develop- ments, and signifies temporality and even serendipity."
5325,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,94,"I encountered this archive, ironically, thanks to my marginal positionality within my discipline: Mainstream cultural anthropologists are skeptical of quantitative methods (Horowitz et al.2019) and do not focus on children or how the human mind develops in childhood (Hirschfeld, 2002)."
5326,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,95,"But similar to my predecessor Arthur W olf six decades ago, I advocate methodological pluralism in anthropology, emphasize child development and have additional training in psychology (Xu, 2019)."
5327,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,96,"Arthur W olf loved and believed in numbers, but at the heyday of typewriters and 3 × 5 notecards, no efficient computational technologies were available for analyzing his archive, and no anthropologist anticipated the advent of language AI."
5328,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,97,"In a word, the story of my encounter defies a deterministic account of interdisciplinarity and prompts us to take seriously historical contours and contingencies (see also Barry & Born, 2013; Suchman, 2013). 2.1."
5329,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,98,"The wolf archive: when old fieldnotes meet new lenses Among the first Euro-American anthropologists to study postwar Taiwan, Arthur W olf conducted more than two years of dissertation fieldwork (1958–60), together with his then wife Margery W olf Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. 07 Apr 2026 at 15:09:38, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use."
5330,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,99,"Cambridge Forum on AI: Culture and Society 7 and a team of local research assistants, in a Hoklo Han village called Xia Xizhou."
5331,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,100,"In 1958, the village had about 600 residents, and on average, a household had more than three children."
5332,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,101,"On the eve of Taiwan’ s rapid industrialization and economic development, most households were still poor, making a living through farming and factory work."
5333,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,102,"In the context of the Martial Law era, most villagers were Taiwanese (benshengren), descendants of southern Fujian Chinese migrants who had settled in this area in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries during the Qing dynasty."
5334,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,103,"Once known under the pseudonym Peihotien in Margery W olf ’s classic ethnographies, this vil- lage, portrayed in the W olfs’ seminal works on marriage, kinship, women and gender, remains an iconic landmark in the study of Han societies."
5335,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,104,"Many did not know, however, that the original purpose of the W olfs’ trip to Taiwan was to study children, because the W olfs did not publish any system- atic analysis of their fieldnotes about children."
5336,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,105,"Their original research was an improved replication of the Six Cultures Study of Child Socialization (hereafter “SCS”), a landmark project in the mid- twentieth-century American anthropology and interdisciplinary research on childhood, based on mixed-methods ethnographic fieldwork across six societies, led by a team of anthropologists and psychologists (LeVine, 2010)."
5337,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,106,"The W olf archive contains several types of fieldnotes, including house- hold demographic survey, naturalistic observations of children’ s social life, standardized interviews with children and mothers and transcripts of projective tests that used culturally appropriate prompts to elicit children’ s spontaneous storytelling."
5338,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,107,"This archive, containing rich and systematic information about the everyday lives of over 200 children (ages 0–12 years) in rural Taiwan, was unprecedented at the time, because ethnographic materials on Chinese7 childhood before the W olfs’ research were rare and mostly anecdotal (Xu,2022)."
5339,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,108,"It also set up a benchmark difficult to match in anthropology today, due to its sheer volume, interdisciplinary methodology and comprehensive naturalistic observations."
5340,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,109,My re-analysis bears witness to historical developments in data processing.
5341,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,110,"Over six decades ago, before the era of personal computers, the demand for analyzing large amounts of fieldnotes was one reason why the publications of SCS data were delayed (LeVine,2010) and why Arthur W olf left these materials behind and turned to other projects. 5 Fortunately, these materials were well preserved in his private library in Northern California."
5342,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,111,"In 2018, when W olf ’s widow, anthropologist Hill Gates, granted me unique permission to use this archive, I decided to use NLP methods to analyze these precious data."
5343,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,112,"Moreover, AI-interdisciplinary in this project has a unique bottom-up dimension, where the nature of knowledge infrastructure and the form of our knowledge mutually transform each other (Bowker, 2018)."
5344,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,113,"While my predecessor lacked computational tools to process his data at that time, my predicament was how to write an ethnography without first-person fieldwork experience."
5345,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,114,"Fortunately, this archive has a rare duality, combining systematicity and richness, which affords me the oppor- tunity to apply computational analysis to complement close reading."
5346,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,115,My team built a text-as-data pipeline and incorporated computational methods to analyze these data.
5347,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,116,"Using OCR software, we transcribed all the raw fieldnotes into machine-readable text files, copyedited the texts manually to ensure data accuracy and then built a database through Python programming language to organize these texts."
5348,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,117,"The core part of this archive, CO, contains 1668 documents (about 250 words on average per document), with systematic information such as participants’ IDs, location, date and time."
5349,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,118,"Our database used an indexing system based on chronological order, according to the date and time each observation took place."
5350,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,119,"These observations provided quasi-randomized snapshots of children’ s spon- taneous interactions, not biased by pre-determined behavioral themes."
5351,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,120,New computational methods can extract textual patterns from CO that would have been obscured otherwise.
5352,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,121,"Meanwhile, each document contains microscopic and meticulous observation of social interactions and sometimes the observer’ s on-the-moment reflections too, which makes ethnographic interpretation possible. 7I use the term “Chinese” in the broad sense of cultural heritage. 5Margery W olf ’s work on women and childrearing only used a tiny portion of these data, presented sporadically (1972, 1978)."
5353,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,122,"Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. 07 Apr 2026 at 15:09:38, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use. 8 Jing Xu and Jose Manuel Hernandez NLP approaches have become increasingly important in many social sciences and humanities disciplines (Justin et al. 2022; T erras et al. 2016)."
5354,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,123,Cognitive scientists also advocate using LLMs to annotate cultural materials (Dubourg et al.2024).
5355,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,124,"In contrast, although texts, especially ethnographic fieldnotes, are essential in socio-cultural anthropology, applying NLP methods has not yet become popular in my discipline."
5356,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,125,"Mainstream anthropological critique tends to see ethnography, qualitative interpretations based on immersive, long-term engagements in often messy social situations, as a competitor epistemology to the “big data” approach (Douglas-Jones et al. 2021)."
5357,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,126,"At a fundamental level, however, ethnographers and language AI both face the challenge of interpreting the meaning of human experience through text."
5358,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,127,"Doubtlessly, language AI such as LLMs embodies a very different set of techniques from ethnography."
5359,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,128,"The very first step of any LLM is to tokenize texts and transform them into embeddings, numerical representations (vectors) in a high-dimensional space and mean- ing is inferred through patterns of statistical probabilities."
5360,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,129,"This ontology of language as geometry and statistics does not seem natural to the human mind, but some of the ways computational methods tackle the question of meaning-in-context potentially align with, rather than contradict, hermeneutic approaches (Fuller,2020; Widdows, 2004)."
5361,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,130,"T oward the shared goal of meaning-interpretation, ethno- graphic fieldnotes present a unique opportunity for applying language AI to understanding diverse human experience in cultural contexts."
5362,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,131,"My hybrid approach facilitates cross-fertilization between anthropology and data science, espe- cially in the era of AI."
5363,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,132,"At the beginning of this project, the affordance of this archive and the impact of NLP in social sciences prompted me to step out of my comfort zone to learn computational meth- ods, with the help of online tutorials, courses and consultants."
5364,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,133,"But at a later step, when I wanted to incorporate more advanced technologies like LLMs, I collaborated with a data scientist."
5365,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,134,"Rather than a mechanistic application of NLP to ethnographic fieldnotes, effective interdisciplinarity should embrace mutually constitutive collaboration of “grasping” (ethnography) and “measuring” meaning (LLMs)."
5366,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,135,"Our collaboration involves understanding each other’ s domain expertise, finding common ground related to this project – e.g., a specific goal in my project can be achieved through a particu- lar manipulation of an LLM – and acknowledging, not just at an abstract level but through concrete practice, the strengths and limits of each approach."
5367,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,136,"It includes revising our goals and plans to accom- modate differences, contingencies and setbacks."
5368,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,137,"It demands openness toward unexpected patterns in the data, updated technology, shifting conceptual interests and the entanglement of all these factors."
5369,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,138,"Moreover, from the original production of the W olf archive to my re-interpretation today, this jour- ney involves multiple actors and chains of translation."
5370,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,139,"My re-analysis reaffirms, rather than discounts, the inherently humanistic nature of fieldnotes: This is manifest “in the intersubjective experience that made the texts (fieldnotes) possible, in the human expertise essential for constructing and inter- preting ‘machine-reading’ patterns and numbers and in the layers of human biases in knowledge production (Xu, 2024: 24). ” 2.2."
5371,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,140,"Learning about and from children The ethnography–AI dialogue in this project also benefited from, and in some sense, was a novel extension of my interdisciplinary work in child development, which is an inherently open and hybrid field."
5372,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,141,"My re-analysis of the W olf archive focuses on patterns of cooperation and conflict in young children’ s social world, an important part of moral development, my long-term theoretical interest."
5373,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,142,"Trained in anthropology and psychology, I adopt a theoretical approach of cognitive anthropology that takes into consideration both psychological processes and cultural histories."
5374,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,143,"This basic theoret- ical premise is different from SCS’ and the W olfs’ behaviorist paradigm in the 1950s, which focused on behavior itself and treated the mind as a black box."
5375,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,144,"Their paradigm also bypassed the question of learning morality, as children’ s behavior was assumed simply as the response to external reward– punishment."
5376,19,C019_P1_pdf.txt,145,"Decades of new research have since revolutionized our understanding, revealing that young children have much more complex social cognition than what behaviorists once assumed Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. 07 Apr 2026 at 15:09:38, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use."
5377,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,0,"From Assistance to Autonomy – A Researcher Study on the Potential of AI Support for Qualitative Data Analysis ELISABETH KIRSTEN,Ruhr University Bochum, Germany ANNALINA BUCKMANN,Ruhr University Bochum, Germany LEONA LASSAK,Ruhr University Bochum, Germany NELE BORGERT,University of Bern, Switzerland ABRAHAM MHAIDLI,Max Planck Institute for Security and Privacy, Germany STEFFEN BECKER∗,Ruhr University Bochum, Germany The advent of Artificial Intelligence (AI) tools, such as Large Language Models, has introduced new possibilities for Qualitative Data Analysis (QDA), offering both opportunities and challenges."
5378,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,1,"To help navigate the responsible integration ofAI into QDA, we conducted semi-structured interviews with 15 Human-Computer Interaction (HCI) researchers experienced in QDA."
5379,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,2,"While our participants were open to AI support in their QDA workflows, they expressed concerns about data privacy, autonomy, and the quality of AI outputs."
5380,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,3,"In response, we developed a framework that spans from minimal to high AI involvement, providing tangible scenarios for integrating AI into QDA practices while addressing researchers’ needs and concerns."
5381,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,4,"Aligned with real-lifeQDA workflows, we identify potential for AI tools in areas such as data pre-processing, researcher onboarding, or conflict mediation."
5382,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,5,Our framework aims to provoke further discussion on the development of AI-supported QDA and to help establish community standards for responsible Human-AI collaboration.
5383,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,6,"CCS Concepts:•Human-centered computing → Interactive systems and tools;Collaborative and social computing design and evaluation methods; Collaborative interaction;User studies; HCI theory, concepts and models;•Computing methodologies → Artificial intelligence."
5384,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,7,"Additional Key Words and Phrases: Qualitative Data Analysis, Large Language Models, Interview Study 1 Introduction Artificial Intelligence (AI) tools have grown increasingly popular, driven by the rapid rise of Large Language Models (LLMs)."
5385,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,8,"These powerful models can generate coherent, contextually relevant text across diverse topics and perform tasks such as classification and summarization [18, 105]."
5386,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,9,"LLMs have been widely adopted across domains, from programming assistance to educational tutoring, and are increasingly finding their way into research contexts."
5387,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,10,"One area where these models hold significant, yet debated potential is Qualitative Data Analysis (QDA)."
5388,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,11,"Human- Computer Interaction (HCI) and CSCW researchers are beginning to explore the usage ofLLMs throughout their research processes for tasks such as conducting QDA [28], generating synthetic data and substituting human participants [4, 49, 88], creative ideation [76, 89], literature reviews, and writing [58]."
5389,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,12,"Commercial tools have also started integrating AI features (e. g., ATLAS.ti,1 MAXQDA,2 and nVivo’s Lumivero AI Assistant3) [70]. ∗Also with Max Planck Institute for Security and Privacy. 1https://atlasti.com/ 2https://www.maxqda.com/products/ai-assist 3https://lumivero.com/product/nvivo-ai-assistant/ Authors’ Contact Information: Elisabeth Kirsten, Ruhr University Bochum, Bochum, Germany, elisabeth.kirsten@rub.de; Annalina Buckmann, Ruhr University Bochum, Bochum, Germany, annalina.buckmann@rub.de; Leona Lassak, Ruhr University Bochum, Bochum, Germany, leona.lassak@rub.de; Nele Borgert, University of Bern, Bern, Switzerland, nele.borgert@unibe.ch; Abraham Mhaidli, Max Planck Institute for Security and Privacy, Bochum, Germany, abraham.mhaidli@mpi-sp.org; Steffen Becker, Ruhr University Bochum, Bochum, Germany, steffen.becker@rub.de. 1 arXiv:2501.19275v3 [cs.CY] 27 Feb 2026 2 Kirsten et al."
5390,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,13,"The rapid adoption of AI tools begs the question:which steps of the QDA workflow are suitable for AI support, and how do we make these determinations?These questions are particularly pivotal for CSCW, where QDA plays a dual role: as a methodological tool, and as a site of collaboration, negotiation, and interpretive practice in interdisciplinary teams with different epistemic traditions [ 15, 40, 69]."
5391,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,14,"Although AI tools can be useful, they raise dilemmas about researcher autonomy [39] and the risks of imperfect AI outputs (e. g., LLMs hallucinating wrong information) [109]."
5392,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,15,"As a community, it is imperative to critically assess which tasks in the QDA workflow are appropriate or inappropriate for AI integration, and to ensure its responsible use."
5393,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,16,"To better understand how AI tools can, and should (not), be integrated into QDA, we conducted semi-structured interviews with HCI researchers about their QDA workflows and opinions on AI integration."
5394,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,17,"We found that while researchers’QDA workflows share structural similarities, they differ significantly based on project specifics, highlighting the need for AI tools that are highly customizable."
5395,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,18,"Researchers were generally open to AI assistance when it enhanced their workflow but stressed the importance of ethical considerations, trust in AI outputs, and maintaining control."
5396,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,19,Our contributions are as follows.
5397,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,20,"First, we provide an empirical account of researchers’QDA practices, pain points, and challenges."
5398,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,21,"Second, we present a framework for integrating AI into QDA workflows, grounded in researchers’ perspectives on the individual stages of QDA and prior work, extending beyond the task of coding itself."
5399,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,22,"Based on our findings we ideate tangible scenarios for the integration of AI, including AI as a productivity tool (e. g., taking on more technical tasks), as a mediator (e. g., facilitating consensus), or with human approval (e. g., suggesting codebook components with validation by a researcher)."
5400,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,23,"Finally, we discuss how this framework can guide the responsible deployment of AI tools that truly support researchers’ needs and preserve the social value of collaborative analysis practices. 2 Background In this section, we lay out the methodological backgrounds of Qualitative Data Analysis (QDA) and trace the evolution of AI-assisted QDA from basic computational methods to the growing role of Large Language Models ( LLMs)."
5401,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,24,"We conclude by synthesizing our research questions. 2.1 Qualitative Data Analysis in CSCW and HCI QDA is a fundamental process in qualitative and mixed-method research within CSCW and HCI, providing systematic techniques for interpreting non-numeric data such as interviews, field notes, videos, or documents [16, 69]."
5402,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,25,"Its primary goal is to juxtapose or integrate different sources to identify patterns, themes, and insights that deepen our understanding of the research subject."
5403,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,26,"At its core,QDA typically involves iterative cycles of data extraction, synthesis, and analysis [16]."
5404,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,27,"QDA is shaped by various methodological frameworks that may overlap in scientific practice (see reporting of QDA steps in Section 4.1) but are distinct in theoretical foundations, flexibility, and depth of analysis."
5405,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,28,"WhileThematic Analysis[ 17] is a theoretical framework that focuses on coding features relevant to the research question,Content Analysis[ 108] quantifies specific events or codes, enabling a blend with quantitative approaches.Grounded Theory[ 47] aims at theory generation through systematic coding directly from the data, andFramework Analysis[cf. 12] applies existing frameworks, refining them throughout analysis, useful in applied research contexts that aim to build upon and extend existing knowledge."
5406,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,29,"In contrast,Narrative Analysis[ 85] emphasizes the structure and meaning of data within its narrative context."
5407,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,30,"Coding strategies can bedeductive(codes follow predefined categories),inductive(patterns identified in the data), or hybrid, enabling researchers to choose an approach that aligns with their objectives."
5408,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,31,"The choice of A Researcher Study on the Potential of AI Support for Qualitative Data Analysis 3 coding strategy is not merely technical but reflects a researcher’s underlying goals and questions, guiding the research direction and ensuring the chosen method supports the intended outcomes."
5409,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,32,"Underlying these methods are different epistemologies, from more positivist ones aiming at recognition and discovery, to more interpretive ones, requiring in-depth analysis and centering researcher subjectivity and reflexivity [ 5, 6, 20, 48, 91]."
5410,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,33,"Within CSCW and HCI, projects commonly involve more than one researcher [ 57, 69], making QDA a fundamentally collaborative and social practice of negotiating, resolving disagreements, and making sense of ambiguity."
5411,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,34,"This collaboration is often asynchronous and distributed, and supported by digital tools and software [102], increasingly incorporating Natural Language Processing (NLP) and LLM methods into the QDA process – thus, QDA fundamentally becomescomputer-supported cooperative work."
5412,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,35,"At the same time, QDA in CSCW and HCI is shaped by interdisciplinary diversity [15]."
5413,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,36,"Researchers bring different epistemological traditions and backgrounds [15, 40, 69], which leads to ongoing debates about transparency, rigor, reliability, and measures thereof, such as Inter-Rater Reliability (IRR), [15, 40, 69, 91]."
5414,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,37,"Yet, despite QDA’s centrality to CSCW and HCI, there has been no systematic documentation of how CSCW andHCI researchers actually conduct QDA in practice, or how emerging technologies might reshape it."
5415,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,38,The closest analysis we could find is the work by McDonald et al.[69] documenting how interrater reliability is used in CSCW and CHI.
5416,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,39,They find that reporting IRR is rare and authors often use other methods to report on reliability.
5417,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,40,"A more comprehensive overview of the whole QDA process, though, is still lacking."
5418,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,41,"Our work addresses this gap by synthesizing and extending fragmented conversations into a coherent account of real-world QDA workflows. 2.2 From Computational Support to AI-Assisted Analysis While nowadays, CSCW and HCI researchers draw on a variety of tools for analysis [40], computer-assisted approaches have long supported QDA, from supporting basic coding tasks, to experiments with automation: Early tools applied basic NLP techniques such as word frequency analysis, keyword matching, and pattern-based rules [ 68, 92]."
5419,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,42,"While these methods introduced automation, they lacked the capacity to capture complex human interpretations."
5420,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,43,"Subsequent work introduced supervised machine learning for text classification, extending manual coding into larger datasets [86]."
5421,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,44,"Unsupervised approaches such as topic modeling uncovered latent themes without predefined categories [65], and some studies reported surprising alignment with qualitative methods like grounded theory [13, 72]."
5422,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,45,"Such combinations of QDA and machine learning can be especially useful for mixed-methods studies and for analyzing large-scale data, though they raise concerns about transparency and interpretability – values central to qualitative research."
5423,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,46,"Recent advances in generative AI, particularly LLMs like ChatGPT, offer new opportunities."
5424,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,47,"These models are trained on massive text corpora and can generate, summarize, and classify language with a high degree of contextual awareness [105]."
5425,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,48,"They encode vast amounts of diverse knowledge, making them potentially adaptable to various tasks within qualitative research."
5426,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,49,"Recent prototypes integrate LLMs at different points across the QDA workflow, from inductive coding to codebook development [10, 44, 70, 83, 96, 110]."
5427,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,50,"LLMs have shown remarkable performance on annotation tasks where little or no labeled data is provided [46, 98] and have been proposed ascollaboratorsin human annotation teams [ 113], indicating a shift from assistance to autonomy of computational methods supporting the cooperative work of QDA."
5428,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,51,"This evolution highlights not only the opportunities for scaling qualitative work, but also the risks it creates for preserving interpretive rigor and methodological integrity."
5429,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,52,"These concerns are shared by HCI and CSCW researchers [39, 57, 67], showing reservation and opposition to the integration of AI into QDA, or specifying specific use contexts that retain human agency."
5430,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,53,"While these studies were conducted prior to the advent of LLMs, recent work identified a ""generational gap"", with early career researchers being more open, and more experienced researchers more reserved towards the integration of AI into QDA, calling into question AI and QDA literacy as well as structural inequalities 4 Kirsten et al. that may facilitate attitudes [ 20]."
5431,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,54,This necessitates further engagement with shifting researcher attitudes towards AI-supported QDA. 2.3 Potentials and Risks of AI in the QDA Workflow Recent studies show how AI can assist at multiple points in the QDA process.
5432,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,55,Cuevas et al. [25] examine the usage of LLMs for conducting user studies and analyzing the collected data.
5433,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,56,"For labeling and annotating, LLM-based systems apply existing codes from a given codebook with notable consistency, though they often miss subtle contextual judgments [110]."
5434,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,57,"Lam et al . [64] develop a LLM-based text analysis tool that derives interpretable concepts from unstructured text, inspired by traditional topic models."
5435,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,58,"For data exploration and inductive coding, LLMs can surface novel patterns and assist in the initial exploration of themes and codes, potentially enabling a deeper understanding."
5436,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,59,"However, while LLMs can replicate many primary themes identified by humans, they often miss more subtle and complex interpretations [70, 97, 111]."
5437,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,60,"Hamilton et al . [50] observed complementary patterns between human and ChatGPT-generated codes, with each identifying themes that the other did not."
5438,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,61,"Barany et al. [11] investigated the use of ChatGPT for codebook creation, finding hybrid approaches to be more reliable."
5439,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,62,"They suggest LLMs can contribute to the improvement of codebooks, but stress that human involvement remains crucial."
5440,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,63,"While combining interpretive and positivist methods can cause epistemic tensions and discussions among researchers [13, 72, 81], studies highlight mutual compatibility [13, 20, 44, 64, 72]."
5441,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,64,"AI also holds potential for mediating discussions and facilitating collaboration by highlighting coding discrepancies, and suggesting resolutions [32, 41, 42]."
5442,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,65,"While these efforts illustrate potential, they also expose tensions."
5443,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,66,"Concerns persist around bias [3, 8, 10, 78, 99, 113], lack of reliability for non-English languages [ 54, 94], and the risk of treating AI as “culturally agnostic” despite its privileging of certain perspectives [81]."
5444,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,67,"Such issues are particularly important when engaging minority groups or Global South contexts, where AI risks reproducing inequalities in representation and missing interpretative nuance [56, 63, 74, 87, 101]."
5445,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,68,"This raises concerns regarding bias in interpretation, but also research ethics of fairness and inclusion [59]."
5446,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,69,"Moreover, perspectives from the Global Souths are largely absent from AI development, and little is known on how AI is used and deployed in the Global Souths [66, 74, 95]."
5447,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,70,"Another tension arises from the very foundations of AI itself: borne on statistical methods and probability, AI reflects a positivist paradigm that can impede the interpretative nature of qualitative inquiry [ 20, 57, 81]."
5448,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,71,"This is amplified by the problem of overreliance on AI, facilitated by the plausibility of AI generations: in QDA, AI-generated ""interpretations"" or suggestions may be simply accepted, instead of being critically interrogated [19, 59, 74], creating lopsided structures of collaboration between AI and human researchers in QDA."
5449,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,72,"This poses specific challenges for teams involving collaborators with varying degrees of literacy regarding AI as well as QDA, especially in interdisciplinary fields like CSCW and HCI."
5450,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,73,"Thus, while AI holds potential to bridge “big” and “small” data approaches and to enhance efficiency, it raises equally urgent questions about reliability, ethics, and researcher agency."
5451,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,74,"These risks and tensions require careful considerations for designing human-AI collaboration in QDA, preserving the depth and richness of QDA while leveraging the potentials of AI. 2.4 Designing for Human-AI Collaboration in QDA Integrating AI into QDA is not simply a matter of automation, but of collaboration as well: It requires careful design for human–AI and human-human collaboration in interpretive, context-sensitive work [57]."
5452,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,75,"Existing tools vary widely in how they support AI involvement, from minimal assistance to active roles in coding and analysis, with different levels of human involvement."
5453,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,76,"Moreover, designing for researchers differing in proficiency in QDA, tool usage, as well as AI A Researcher Study on the Potential of AI Support for Qualitative Data Analysis 5 capability [39, 67] poses specific challenges, especially in diverse fields such as CSCW and HCI."
5454,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,77,"For example, Gauthier and Wallace [44] developed a toolkit to facilitate computational thematic analysis, emphasizing the need to design it accessibly for a community with different proficiencies in tool usage as well as AI."
5455,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,78,"Thus, they call for ethical designs to involve friction to remind researchers of the imperfection of computational models and issues concerning ethics and transparency."
5456,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,79,These challenges are also identified by Kapania et al. [58] who found HCI researchers struggling to identify such issues in their projects and needing guidance.
5457,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,80,"Similarly, Lam et al. [64] suggest tools to be transparent to the researcher and acknowledging their limitations, e. g., by showcasing explicit inclusion criteria and scores."
5458,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,81,"At the same time, designs should avoid creating excessive “unanticipated labor” for researchers [39]."
5459,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,82,"While prior studies provide valuable insights into the potentials of AI in QDA [44, 64, 70, 83, 96], there is still limited understanding of how AI can beresponsiblyintegrated into researchers’ real-life QDA workflows, respecting their concerns and preferences [39, 67], facilitating collaboration between researchers as well as researchers and AI, while consolidating different research epistemologies."
5460,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,83,"We are thus in need for comprehensive frameworks addressing these issues [58, 78]."
5461,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,84,"Moreover, it remains crucial to critically reflect not only on AI capability, but also what itshoulddo in QDA, preserving researcher concerns and preferences [39, 67]."
5462,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,85,"We extend this to the era of LLMs, identifying new steps, tasks, and different levels of involvement of AI to support QDA while maintaining methodological integrity."
5463,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,86,"To address these gaps, we study HCI researchers’ QDA workflows and their perspectives on the involvement of AI in qualitative research."
5464,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,87,"Specifically, we investigate the following research questions: RQ1How does HCI researchers’ real-life QDA workflow look like?"
5465,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,88,RQ2 What are HCI researchers’ concerns and conditions for integrating AI-based support into theirQDA workflow?
5466,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,89,"Our overarching goal is toexplore how AI can be responsibly integrated into QDA, respecting the workflows, concerns, and conditions of HCI researchers.By systematically mapping QDA practices (RQ1) and surfacing researchers’ conditions for AI integration (RQ2), we contribute a framework for AI support that is aligned with the real-world QDA workflows of HCI researchers."
5467,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,90,This framework synthesizes fragmented CSCW debates around QDA and provides concrete guidance for developing AI tools that enhance – rather than disrupt – the collaborative and interpretive nature of qualitative research. 3 Research Method We conducted a two-step study to explore HCI researchers’ perspectives on integrating AI intoQDA.
5468,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,91,"The first step involved semi-structured interviews with 15 HCI researchers, representing a range of QDA experience levels."
5469,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,92,"These interviews were designed to uncover pain points, potentials, and conditions for AI support inQDA, focusing on real-life workflows, challenges, and concerns."
5470,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,93,"To promote transparency and rigor, we preregistered our study on the Open Science Framework (OSF) platform.4 In the second step, we used the findings of the interviews to conceptualize waysAI can be integrated into QDA."
5471,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,94,We developed a framework to illustrate concrete examples of how AI can be integrated into the QDA workflow and contextualize these examples with how they align (or do not align) with participants’ concerns. 3.1 Study Materials Our study included a pre-questionnaire and a semi-structured interview with a sketching task.
5472,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,95,The full interview guide is available in Appendix A.
5473,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,96,Both the complete pre-questionnaire and the interview guide are available in our anonymized OSF repository. 4see https://osf.io/yzkta/?view_only=c4bb80ff8635434db0e7c3166146fa53 6 Kirsten et al.
5474,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,97,"Pre-Questionnaire.The pre-questionnaire consisted of eight questions, capturing participants’ backgrounds and experience with QDA."
5475,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,98,"It covered their research background, current field of research, current position, tools used for QDA, years of experience working with qualitative data, the number of research projects involving QDA, and the data collection and analysis methods they have employed in the past."
5476,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,99,"Interview Guide.The interview guide was organized into three parts: (a) participants’ real-life QDA workflows, (b) pain points and gain points in QDA, and (c) perspectives on the potential for AI support."
5477,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,100,"First (a), we explored the participants’ overall research process, from data collection to analysis, with a particular focus on coding."
5478,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,101,"We asked them to reflect on their most recent research project, discussing the types of data used, the methods and tools employed, resources accessed, and, if applicable, collaboration with other researchers."
5479,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,102,"To facilitate this reflection, we asked them to sketch their coding process on a piece of paper (sketching task)."
5480,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,103,"This visual representation not only helped them articulate their workflow but also served as a reference in subsequent explanations, allowing them to highlight specific areas where pain points arose or where they saw potential for AI support."
5481,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,104,"Then (b), we delved more deeply into the QDA workflow, focusing on what participants found enjoyable or engaging, as well as what they found tedious or challenging."
5482,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,105,"We asked which steps were particularly time-consuming, the difficulties encountered, and the role of tool support, including both its benefits and limitations."
5483,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,106,"Lastly (c), we explored participants’ expectations around AI-assistedQDA."
5484,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,107,"We inquired about the conditions under which they would be willing to integrate AI into their workflows, which steps they believed could be automated, and which aspects should remain human-driven."
5485,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,108,"Finally, participants were given the opportunity to share any additional thoughts on the topic. 3.2 Recruitment & Participants We used purposive and snowball sampling methods [80] to recruit participants who had conducted at least one study involving QDA through our professional networks within the HCI and Usable Security and Privacy (USP) communities."
5486,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,109,"We approached researchers directly and invited them to refer interested colleagues, leveraging peer identification to build a diverse and qualified sample."
5487,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,110,Our recruitment strategy was designed to capture variation across research domains and methodological traditions relevant to CSCW and HCI.
5488,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,111,We categorized participants’ primary research field based on their self-description.
5489,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,112,"To capture a broad range of experiences and perspectives, we took care to recruit participants from diverse group affiliations, different study approaches, topic choices, and educational backgrounds."
5490,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,113,"Our goal was to achieve data saturation regarding participants’ workflows, pain points, and gain points."
5491,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,114,Sample Description.Table 1 summarizes the participant sample.
5492,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,115,"We interviewed 15 HCI researchers with backgrounds in computer science, cybersecurity, engineering, and social sciences, all firmly embedded in HCI research, with some specifying to focus on USP."
5493,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,116,"Twelve participants were early career researchers (mostly PhD candidates), and three were senior researchers."
5494,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,117,"Eight had worked on 1-3 QDA projects, four on 4-6, and three on more than 7 projects, with QDA experience ranging from 1 to 9 years."
5495,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,118,We recruited participants until data saturation was reached.
5496,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,119,We reached data saturation around interview 12 and conducted three additional interviews to confirm this.
5497,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,120,"Participants first completed the pre-questionnaire, which included an overview of the study procedure and a consent form."
5498,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,121,"Afterward, we scheduled interviews."
5499,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,122,"The interviews were semi-structured, conducted face-to-face, and lasted approximately 45 minutes."
5500,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,123,"Interviews were conducted in either English ( 𝑛= 9) or German (𝑛= 6), depending on participants’ native language and preference."
5501,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,124,"Two researchers were present: a lead interviewer who conducted the session and took notes, and a second researcher who created detailed protocols, including occasional verbatim quotes."
