5519,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,142,"The lead interviewer, fluent in both German and English, conducted all interviews for consistency."
5520,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,143,The second researcher varied among four researchers and was either fluent in English or fluent in both languages as needed.
5521,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,144,"To ensure objectivity, they noted down points that stood out without performing any immediate analysis or interpretation."
5522,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,145,"The researchers then compared, merged, and verified the completeness of their notes, ensuring no conflicts arose."
5523,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,146,"Finally, when necessary, the researchers manually translated their synthesized interview protocols into English for subsequent data analysis."
5524,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,147,We piloted our study with three participants to evaluate the procedure and interview flow.
5525,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,148,"As no changes were made, these pilot sessions were included in the final dataset, resulting in 15 participants. 8 Kirsten et al. 3.3 Ethical Considerations & Data Protection The study was conducted in accordance with the Menlo Report’s ethical principles [60] and approved by our institution’s ethics committee."
5526,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,149,All participants gave informed consent via the pre-questionnaire and again at the start of the interview.
5527,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,150,"Before the interviews began, the interviewer walked the participants through the consent form again and gave them the opportunity to ask questions and asked for their consent again."
5528,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,151,"To protect the privacy of the participants, they were given pseudonyms after completing the questionnaire and all data was pseudonymized."
5529,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,152,"We stored and managed all data according to national data protection regulations and in accordance with our institution’s policies on confidentiality and data protection. 3.4 Data Analysis Three authors developed an initial set of deductive codes for tools and resources, data types, and participants’ overall willingness to use AI, based on the pre-questionnaire answer options and interview guide."
5530,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,153,"They each coded three protocols for the coding process, pain points, fun points, and concerns and conditions for using AI withinQDA to derive common themes."
5531,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,154,This process involved closely examining the protocols to identify and conceptualize subcategories.
5532,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,155,All three coders then created the final codebooks by discussing the identified themes and resolving conflicts in a collaborative session.
5533,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,156,"Two authors then coded the entire dataset, resolving disagreements through discussion until full agreement was reached."
5534,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,157,"To help us later illustrate our findings, the coders included example quotations from the protocols in our codebooks, both paraphrased and verbatim."
5535,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,158,"Additionally, we analyzed the drawings from the sketching task to derive commonalities and differences in the coding process and extracted participants’ suggestions for concrete AI applications as in vivo codes."
5536,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,159,Two coders reviewed sketches together with protocols to create a combined metaview of current QDA practices.
5537,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,160,Each participant’s workflow was redrawn and sequentially mapped into a shared metaview.
5538,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,161,"New elements were added as the emerged, recurring ones were skipped."
5539,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,162,Closely related processes were later merged to reduce complexity.
5540,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,163,We differentiated elements taking into account the SeeMe-method developed by Herrmann [53].
5541,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,164,"SeeMe is a semi-structured socio-technical modeling technique used for task analysis that involves three visualization elements: (1) roles assigned to individuals or teams, (2) activities that are of a more dynamic characteristic and represent change functions, and (3) entities, defined as objects from the physical world."
5542,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,165,"For entities, we excluded tools and software support from the metaview as they were heavily dependent on the participant’s individual preference, but generally involved in each process element. 4 Results Here, we present HCI researchers’QDA workflows, including their pain points (Section 4.1) and report participants’ willingness to use AI support along with concerns and conditions (Section 4.2)."
5543,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,166,"In Appendix B, we provide the complete codebooks from our interviews, including descriptions, examples, and quantities for each code."
5544,19,C019_S1_pdf.txt,167,"Appendix C shows example workflow sketches. 4.1 RQ1: HCI Researchers Real-Life QDA Workflow 4.1.1 Contexts of Studied QDA Workflows.In the pre-questionnaire, participants reported having analyzed open-ended survey responses (𝑛= 12), interview transcripts (𝑛= 11), written documents (𝑛= 8), and social media posts (𝑛= 5) as the most common data types."
