6263,21,C021_S2.txt,3,"Corresponding author. †Abby and Jon Wikelried Professor, Vanderbilt University josh.clinton@vanderbilt.edu ‡Assistant Professor of Political Science, Vanderbilt University cassy.dorff@vanderbilt.edu §Assistant Professor of Political Science, Vanderbilt University brenton.kenkel@vanderbilt.edu ¶Associate Professor of Political Science, Vanderbilt University jennifer.larson@vanderbilt.edu 1 10 Regression Analysis Extensions 68 10.1 Conditional Relationships . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 68 10.2 Additional Regression Results . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 68 11 New and Improved Models? 74 11.1 Detailed Analysis of GPT 4 . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 74 12 Other outcomes 81 13 Generalizability 86 14 Replication with Open Source LLM 88 14.1 Full Inference Procedure . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 93 14.2 ANES in the Training Data . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 95 2 1 Prompt Engineering Creating the final prompt used for the main results was an iterative process."
6264,21,C021_S2.txt,4,We initially tried simply asking the LLM to imagine that they were a certain persona and to answer questions.
6265,21,C021_S2.txt,5,This produced results that were both difficult to process (open-ended text results) as well as often resulting in the LLM’s refusal to provide the answers requested.
6266,21,C021_S2.txt,6,We found that using the instruction “Provide responses from this person’s perspective.
6267,21,C021_S2.txt,7,"Use only knowledge about politics that they would have.” helped avoid refusals by the AI, although the resulting output remained open-ended and hard to process."
6268,21,C021_S2.txt,8,"We then provided more detailed instructions about the format of the output requested, describing the the desired .csv format where each row corresponded to a given target group, and the columns included the name of the group and the synthetic thermometer score."
6269,21,C021_S2.txt,9,"The code that produced the resulting prompt for our initial synthetic data was used in early April of 2023, and is reproduced below."
6270,21,C021_S2.txt,10,"We relied on the openai package for R and described the persona along the dimensions of age, race, gender, income ( inc), education ( educ), and party ID (pid)."
6271,21,C021_S2.txt,11,All persona were defined as registered voters who lived in the United States in 2019.
6272,21,C021_S2.txt,12,"The following approach was inspired by Marquez [2023]. 1 library ( ti dy ve rs e ) 2 library ( openai ) 3 4 Sys . setenv ( O P E N A I _ A P I _ K E Y = ' Y O U R _ K E Y _ H E R E') 5 6 # Function to create prompt out of inputs 7 c r e a t e _ p r o m p t <- function ( a u d i t _ d a t a ) { 8 res <- list () 9 for ( i in 1: nrow ( a u d i t _ d a t a ) ) { 10 age = a u d i t _ d a t a $ age [ i ] 11 race = a u d i t _ d a t a $ race [ i ] 12 gender = a u d i t _ d a t a $ gender [ i ] 13 inc = a u d i t _ d a t a $ inc [ i ] 14 educ = a u d i t _ d a t a $ educ [ i ] 15 pid = a u d i t _ d a t a $ pid [ i ] 16 res [ [ i ] ] <- list ( 17 list ( 18 "" role "" = "" system "" , 19 "" content "" = stringr :: str_c ( 20 "" You are a "" , age , "" year old "" , race , "" "" , gender , 21 "" with a "" , educ , "" , earning $ "" , inc , "" per year . "" , 22 "" You are a r e g i s t e r e d "" , pid , "" living in the USA in 2019. "" ) 23 ) , 24 list ( 25 "" role "" = "" user "" , 26 "" content "" = stringr :: str_c ( 27 "" Provide re sp on se s from this person 's p e r s p e c t i v e .\ n 28 Use only kn ow le dg e about politics that they would have .\ n 29 Format the output as a csv table with the fo ll ow in g format :\ n 30 group , t h e r m o m e t e r \ n 31 The fo ll ow in g qu es ti on s ask about i n d i v i d u a l s ' feelings 32 toward di ff er en t groups .\ n 33 R es po ns es should be given on a scale from 0 ( meaning cold 34 feelings ) to 100 ( meaning warm feelings ) .\ n 35 Ratings between 50 degrees and 100 degrees mean that \ n 36 you feel fa vo ra bl e and warm toward the group ."
6273,21,C021_S2.txt,13,Ratings 3 37 between 0\ n 38 degrees and 50 degrees mean that you don 't feel 39 f av or ab le toward \ n 40 the group and that you don 't care too much for that 41 group .
6274,21,C021_S2.txt,14,"You \ n 42 would rate the group at the 50 degree mark if you don 't feel \ n 43 p a r t i c u l a r l y warm or cold toward the group .\ n 44 How do you feel toward the fo ll ow in g groups ?\ n "" , 45 ' The D e m o c r a t i c Party ?\ n ' , 46 ' The R e p u b l i c a n Party ?\ n ' , 47 ' D em oc ra ts ?\ n' , 48 ' R e p u b l i c a n s ?\ n' , 49 ' Black Am er ic an s ?\ n ' , 50 ' White Am er ic an s ?\ n ' , 51 ' Hispanic A me ri ca ns ?\ n ' , 52 ' Asian Am er ic an s ?\ n ' , 53 ' Muslims ?\ n ' , 54 ' C h r i s t i a n s ?\ n' , 55 ' I m m i g r a n t s ?\ n' , 56 ' Gays and Lesbians ?\ n ' , 57 ' Jews ?\ n ' , 58 ' Liberals ?\ n ' , 59 ' C o n s e r v a t i v e s ?\ n' , 60 ' Women ?\ n ') 61 ) 62 ) 63 } 64 65 return ( res ) 66 } 67 68 # Define profiles to iterate over 69 a u d i t _ d a t a <- expand . grid ( age = c (20 ,35 ,50 ,65) , 70 race = c ( 'non - Hispanic white ' , 71 'non - Hispanic black ' , 72 ' Hispanic ') , 73 gender = c ( ' male ' , ' female ') , 74 inc = c ( ' 30 ,000 ' , ' 50 ,000 ' , ' 80 ,000 ' , 75 ' 100 ,000 ' , ' more than $150 ,000 ') , 76 educ = c ( ' high school diploma ' , 77 "" some college , but no degree "" , 78 "" bachelor 's degree "" , 79 "" p o s t g r a d u a t e degree "" ) , 80 pid = c ( ' R e p u b l i c a n' , ' Democrat ' , ' I n d e p e n d e n t') , 81 s t r i n g s A s F a c t o r s = F ) % >% 82 a s_ ti bb le () 83 84 # Function to submit the query 85 s u b m i t _ o p e n a i <- function ( prompt , t e m p e r a t u r e = 0.2 , n = 1) { 86 res <- openai :: c r e a t e _ c h a t _ c o m p l e t i o n ( model = "" gpt -3.5 - turbo "" , 87 messages = prompt , 88 t e m p e r a t u r e = temperature , 89 n = n ) 90 Sys . sleep (1) 4 91 res 92 } 93 94 # Create an empty csv file to append to . 95 # df <- data . frame ( a u d i t _ d a t a [0 ,] , 96 # group = as . c ha ra ct er () , 97 # t h e r m o m e t e r = as . numeric () , 98 # draw = as . numeric () , 99 # index = as . numeric () , 100 # s t r i n g s A s F a c t o r s = F ) 101 # 102 # write . table ( df , file = './ results / t h e r m _ A N E S . csv', 103 # append = F , row . names = F , col . names = T , sep = ' , ') 104 105 # Load the already c om pl et ed data 106 df <- read_csv ( ' ./ results / t h e r m _ A N E S . csv') % >% 107 mutate ( index = as . numeric ( gsub ( ' , NA ' , ' ', index ) ) ) 108 109 # Pick up where the previous run left off 110 if ( nrow ( df ) == 0) { 111 start = 1 112 } else { 113 start = max ( df $ index , na . rm = T ) + 1 114 } 115 116 toSave <- NULL 117 TPM <- RPM <- NULL 118 zz <- zzz <- Sys . time () 119 for ( i in start : nrow ( a u d i t _ d a t a ) ) { 120 prompts <- c r e a t e _ p r o m p t ( a u d i t _ d a t a [i , ] ) 121 122 # Iterate over d if fe re nt t e m p e r a t u r e settings 123 for ( t in seq (.1 ,1 , by = .3) ) { 124 o p e n a i _ c o m p l e t i o n s <- try ( prompts | > 125 purrr :: map ( submit_openai , t e m p e r a t u r e = t , n = 20) ) 126 127 while ( class ( o p e n a i _ c o m p l e t i o n s ) == 'try - error ') { 128 Sys . sleep (60) 129 cat ( ' issue on \ n ' , 130 ' temp = ' ,t , '\ n' , 131 paste ( a u d i t _ d a t a [i , ] , collapse = ' / ') ,'\ n') 132 o p e n a i _ c o m p l e t i o n s <- try ( prompts | > 133 purrr :: map ( submit_openai , t e m p e r a t u r e = t , n = 20) ) 134 135 } 136 137 tmp <- NULL 138 for ( j in 1: length ( o p e n a i _ c o m p l e t i o n s [ [1 ] ]$ choices $ message . content ) ) { 139 tmp <- bi nd _r ow s ( tmp , 140 read . csv ( text = gsub ( ' \\\\ ' , ' ', 141 o p e n a i _ c o m p l e t i o n s [ [1 ] ]$ choices $ message . content [ j ] ) , 5 142 col . names = c ( ' group ' , ' t h e r m o m e t e r') ) % >% 143 mutate ( draw = j , 144 temp = t , 145 t h e r m o m e t e r = as . numeric ( t h e r m o m e t e r ) ) ) 146 } 147 148 toSave <- toSave % >% 149 a s_ ti bb le () % >% 150 b in d_ ro ws ( data . frame ( a u d i t _ d a t a [i , ] ) % >% 151 cbind ( tmp % >% 152 mutate ( index = i ) ) ) 153 154 TPM <- sum ( TPM , o p e n a i _ c o m p l e t i o n s [ [1 ] ]$ usage $ t o t a l _ t o k e n s ) 155 RPM <- sum ( RPM ,1) 156 } 157 158 # Code to prevent e xc ee di ng API limits 159 if ( difftime ( Sys . time () , zzz , units = ' mins ') < 1) { 160 if ( RPM > 3000 | TPM > 85000) { 161 cat ( ' RPM = ' , RPM , '\ nTPM = ' , TPM , '\ n') 162 Sys . sleep ( max (0 , as . numeric (60 - difftime ( Sys . time () , zzz , units = ' secs ') ) ) ) 163 RPM <- TPM <- NULL 164 zzz <- Sys . time () 165 cat ( ' A p p r o a c h i n g rate limit \ n ') 166 } 167 } else { 168 RPM <- TPM <- NULL 169 zzz <- Sys . time () 170 } 171 172 # Append results to csv file every hundred profiles 173 if ( i %% 100 == 0) { 174 write . table ( toSave , file = ' ./ results / t h e r m _ A N E S . csv' , 175 append = T , row . names = F , col . names = F , sep = ' , ') 176 toSave <- NULL 177 178 cat (i , ' in ' , round ( difftime ( Sys . time () ,zz , units = ' mins ') ,2) , ' minutes \ n ' ) 179 zz <- Sys . time () 180 } 181 } We ran the preceding prompt three times in the spring and summer of 2023: first in mid-April, second in mid-June, and again in early July."
6275,21,C021_S2.txt,15,"In each case, there were rare instances in which either the code or the API experienced an issue that prevented us from gathering the data for a given target group-by-persona."
6276,21,C021_S2.txt,16,"In most cases, these were random with respect to our quantities of interest."
6277,21,C021_S2.txt,17,"In one case though, there were systematically more issues with our synthetic responses for the Democratic Party."
6278,21,C021_S2.txt,18,"This was due to the fact that we asked about this group first in the list of target groups, meaning it would occupy the first row in the resulting csv/tsv file. 1 In some cases, 1We initially requested the results in .csv format, but found that this would create issues with the detailed version of the prompt that asked for explanations, since these would often include commas."
6279,21,C021_S2.txt,19,"As such, we switched to the tsv 6 this first row would not include a header, meaning that we treated the response for the Democratic Party target group as the header and lost it."
6280,21,C021_S2.txt,20,These issues were rare enough in the initial April run of the script that we did not notice the issue until later.
6281,21,C021_S2.txt,21,"However, the June iteration of the same prompt yielded many errors of this type, but – perplexingly – only for the prompts for Democrat and Independent personas."
6282,21,C021_S2.txt,22,The Republican persona was far more likely to include the header row and avoid the issue.
6283,21,C021_S2.txt,23,"We fixed the issue in subsequent runs of the API, and drop the Democratic Party results from all analyses of the June vintage of our data."
6284,21,C021_S2.txt,24,"We plot the API errors below in Figure 1 by party, target group, and vintage, highlighting that, with the exception of the aforementioned issue with the Democratic Party target group, there is little evidence to make us concerned that errors in data collection are non-randomly associated with the target groups or persona profiles."
6285,21,C021_S2.txt,25,"Even in cases where we observe larger proportions missing, these never exceed 1.15% of the intended synthetic sample size."
6286,21,C021_S2.txt,26,"In most cases, missingness amounts to a single synthetic sample out of the 20 intended to be gathered for a given persona for a given target group. 0.01% 0.02% 0.06% 0.02% 0.05% 0.02% 0.01% 0.02% 0.03% 0.02% 0.03% 0.02% 99% 0.01% 0.02% 99% 0.01% 29.1% 0.01% 0.02% 0.01% 0.02% 0.01% 0.02% 0.01% 0.02% 0.01% 0.03% 0.05% 0.03% 0.05% 0.03% 0.05% 0.04% 0.03% 0.05% 0.04% 0.05% 0.07% 0.04% 0.05% 0.08% 0.04% 0.05% 2.4% 0.05% 0.02% 0.21% 0.02% 0.03% 0.02% 0.01% 0.02% 0.12% 0.01% 0.02% 0.01% 0.02% Simple (April) Simple (June) Simple (July) First−Person (June) Democrat IndependentRepublican Democrat IndependentRepublican Black Americans Republicans Women Asian Americans Christians Democrats Hispanic Americans Immigrants White Americans Muslims Conservatives Jews Liberals Gays and Lesbians Republican Party Democratic Party Party ID (persona) Target Group % of all synthetic samples expected Missing Synthetic Data Figure 1: Proportion of missing synthetic responses by target group (y-axes), synthetic party ID (x-axes) and vintage of data collection / prompt type (columns)."
6287,21,C021_S2.txt,27,"In June, we also re-ran the preceding prompt replacing second-person pronouns with first- person pronouns at the suggestion of a reviewer who pointed out that human respondents believe out-groups hold more extreme views than they actually do [Levendusky and Malhotra, 2016]."
6288,21,C021_S2.txt,28,"It is possible therefore that ChatGPT inherits this second-person bias, exaggerating extremism not via any particular limitation of the technology, but rather by accurately reflecting how humans perceive polarization."
6289,21,C021_S2.txt,29,"The revised first-person prompt is copied below (note that the only difference between the original prompt and the first person is found in the system parameter, and we save space by only copying the adjusted language). 1 list ( 2 list ( 3 "" role "" = "" system "" , format in June. 7 4 "" content "" = stringr :: str_c ( 5 "" I am a "" , age , "" year old "" , race , "" "" , gender , 6 "" with a "" , educ , "" , earning $ "" , inc , "" per year . "" , 7 "" I am a r e g i s t e r e d "" , pid , "" living in the USA in 2019. "" ) 8 ) , 9 list ( 10 "" role "" = "" user "" , 11 "" content "" = stringr :: str_c ( 12 "" Provide re sp on se s to the f ol lo wi ng q ue st io ns .\ n 13 Format the output as a csv table with the fo ll ow in g format :\ n 14 group , t h e r m o m e t e r \ n 15 The fo ll ow in g qu es ti on s ask about i n d i v i d u a l s ' feelings toward di ff er en t groups .\ n 16 R es po ns es should be given on a scale from 0 ( meaning cold feelings ) to 100 ( meaning warm feelings ) .\ n 17 Ratings between 50 degrees and 100 degrees mean that \ n 18 you feel fa vo ra bl e and warm toward the group ."
6290,21,C021_S2.txt,30,Ratings between 0\ n 19 degrees and 50 degrees mean that you don 't feel f av or ab le toward \ n 20 the group and that you don 't care too much for that group .
6291,21,C021_S2.txt,31,"You \ n 21 would rate the group at the 50 degree mark if you don 't feel \ n 22 p a r t i c u l a r l y warm or cold toward the group .\ n 23 How do you feel toward the fo ll ow in g groups ?\ n "" , 24 ' The D e m o c r a t i c Party ?\ n ' , 25 ' The R e p u b l i c a n Party ?\ n ' , 26 ' D em oc ra ts ?\ n' , 27 ' R e p u b l i c a n s ?\ n' , 28 ' Black Am er ic an s ?\ n ' , 29 ' White Am er ic an s ?\ n ' , 30 ' Hispanic A me ri ca ns ?\ n ' , 31 ' Asian Am er ic an s ?\ n ' , 32 ' Muslims ?\ n ' , 33 ' C h r i s t i a n s ?\ n' , 34 ' I m m i g r a n t s ?\ n' , 35 ' Gays and Lesbians ?\ n ' , 36 ' Jews ?\ n ' , 37 ' Liberals ?\ n ' , 38 ' C o n s e r v a t i v e s ?\ n' , 39 ' Women ?\ n ') 40 ) We also created a new prompt that allowed us to more carefully test which aspects of the persona matter most to accuracy of the synthetic data."
6292,21,C021_S2.txt,32,"This prompt operated slightly differently from the preceding, although the core components remained."
6293,21,C021_S2.txt,33,"Specifically, we used this prompt to collect 30 synthetic respondents per human, not per persona."
6294,21,C021_S2.txt,34,"In addition, we also asked the AI to provide both an explanation for its response, as well as a numeric measure of its confidence in its response."
6295,21,C021_S2.txt,35,"The inclusion of an explanation, although significantly more expensive, was based on an anony- mous reviewer’s observation that restricting the LLM to provide only numbers may hurt its perfor- mance, since numbers live in a similar part of the embedding space."
6296,21,C021_S2.txt,36,"The inclusion of a confidence measure was also based on reviewer feedback, who wondered whether we could actually measure the posterior probability of the thermometer score chosen."
6297,21,C021_S2.txt,37,We analyze both of these additional 8
6298,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,0,"Finetuning LLMs for Human Behavior Prediction in Social Science Experiments Akaash Kolluri1*, Shengguang Wu1*, Joon Sung Park1, Michael S."
6299,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,1,"Bernstein1 1Stanford University {akaash,shgwu}@stanford.edu Abstract Large language models (LLMs) offer a power- ful opportunity to simulate the results of so- cial science experiments."
6300,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,2,"In this work, we demonstrate that finetuning LLMs directly on individual-level responses from past experi- ments meaningfully improves the accuracy of such simulations across diverse social science domains."
6301,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,3,"We construct SOCSCI210 via an automatic pipeline, a dataset comprising 2.9 million responses from 400,491 participants in 210 open-source social science experiments."
6302,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,4,"Through finetuning, we achieve multiple levels of generalization."
6303,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,5,"In completely unseen studies, our strongest model, SOCRATES-QWEN-14B, produces predictions that are 26% more aligned with distributions of human responses to di- verse outcome questions under varying condi- tions relative to its base model (Qwen2.5-14B), outperforming GPT-4o by 13%."
6304,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,6,"By finetuning on a subset of conditions in a study, general- ization to new unseen conditions is particularly robust, improving by 71%."
6305,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,7,"Since SOCSCI210 contains rich demographic information, we re- duce demographic parity difference, a measure of bias, by 10.6% through finetuning."
6306,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,8,"Because social sciences routinely generate rich, topic- specific datasets, our findings indicate that fine- tuning on such data could enable more accurate simulations for experimental hypothesis screen- ing."
6307,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,9,"We release our data, models and finetuning code atstanfordhci.github.io/socrates. 1 Introduction Large language models have shown impressive po- tential to simulate human behavior (Park et al., 2024; Hewitt et al., 2024; Kim and Lee, 2023)."
6308,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,10,"For social science experiments, simulations enable researchers to screen and iterate on hypotheses be- fore committing to costly studies (Rothschild et al., 2024; Hewitt et al., 2024; Wang et al., 2025b)."
6309,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,11,"Ac- cordingly, LLM-based simulation methods have * Denotes equal contribution."
6310,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,12,"SocSci210 Dataset {Age: 20, Race: Black, Gender: Male, Response: 6} {Age: 31, Race: White, Gender: Female, Response: 4} {Age: 42, Race: Asian, Gender: Male, Response: 1} … Condition 1 Receives  treatment A Condition 2 Receives  treatment B Outcome: On a scale from 1 to 7, how willing would you be to have a  partner of the opposite political party? {Age: 19, Race: White, Gender: Female, Response: 2} {Age: 67, Race: Black, Gender: Female, Response: 3} {Age: 41, Race: Hispanic, Gender: Male, Response:1} … 2.9 million responses, 210 studies,  1194 conditions, 1197 outcomes sociology, psychology,  economics, political  science, communication  Socrates Models Figure 1: We release SOCSCI210, a large-scale dataset built from open-source social science experi- ments."
6311,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,13,"Through finetuning, we create behavioral predic- tion models SOCRATES-LLAMA-8B and SOCRATES- QWEN-14B, which predict responses that are 12.1% and 13.2% respectively more aligned with human re- sponse distributions to outcomes under diverse experi- mental conditions, relative toGPT-4o. been explored across various social science disci- plines (Argyle et al., 2023; Horton, 2023; Brand et al., 2023)."
6312,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,14,"Previous work simulating human responses has used direct prompting such as with demographic personas (Hewitt et al., 2024), human conversa- tions (Cho et al., 2024), and detailed life narratives (Park et al., 2024; Moon et al., 2024)."
6313,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,15,"Still, LLMs routinely distort opinion distributions (Bisbee et al., 2024; Gao et al., 2024), overestimate effect sizes in experimental manipulations by2 to 10times (Park et al., 2024; Hewitt et al., 2024), and incorrectly predict significant effect directions10 - 32% of arXiv:2509.05830v2 [cs.LG] 5 Nov 2025 the time(Hewitt et al., 2024; Bisbee et al., 2024)."
6314,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,16,"LLMs further introduce biases that flatten variation across demographic groups (Wang et al., 2025a)."
6315,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,17,These error cases currently limit the viability of effective LLM-simulations for social science exper- iments.
6316,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,18,"Recent work has begun exploring the viability of finetuning language models for improved human response prediction (Suh et al., 2025; Chu et al., 2023; Lu et al., 2025; Binz et al., 2024) and has demonstrated generalization on their specific tasks (e.g., cognitive science, public opinion)."
6317,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,19,"In this work, we broaden the domain and scope of prior fine-tuning work in pursuit of a general purpose, domain-agnostic human behavior predic- tion model."
6318,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,20,"To enable this, we first construct SOC- SCI210, a standardized, large-scale dataset com- prising2.9 millionindividual responses from over 400,000participants across210social science stud- ies."
6319,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,21,"All studies were drawn from NSF’s Time- sharing Experiments for the Social Sciences—peer- reviewed, high-powered experiments spanning mul- tiple disciplines (e.g., economics, political science, behavioral psychology) and conducted on nation- ally representative samples with rich demographic reporting (""TESS"", 2025)."
6320,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,22,"We design an LLM agent to convert each study’s data into a consis- tent text-based representation describing respon- dent demographic profiles, the experimental ques- tions, and the recorded responses."
6321,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,23,"Using this dataset, we provide a comprehen- sive comparison of finetuning methods (super- vised fine-tuning, augmenting with reasoning traces, contrastive preference optimization) against various prompting baselines (reasoning and in- context learning) on both proprietary GPT-4o and open-source LLaMa3-8B (Grattafiori et al., 2024), Qwen2.5-14B (Yang et al., 2024a) LLMs."
6322,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,24,"Through our evaluations, we highlight that supervised fine- tuning greatly improves distributional alignment between predicted responses and human responses, while contrastive preference optimization leads to the best prediction accuracy for individual re- sponses."
6323,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,25,"Notably, relative to their base models, fine-tuning improves alignment with human re- sponse distributions in unseen studies by 30% for LLaMa3-8B and 26% for Qwen2.5-14B."
6324,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,26,"We further demonstrate robust generalization to unseen par- ticipants, conditions and outcomes."
6325,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,27,"Finally, we highlight finetuning improve demographic bias in predictions by 10+%."
6326,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,28,Our main contributions are: 1.
6327,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,29,"We release SOCSCI210, a standardized, large-scale dataset comprising 2.9 million individ- ual responses from over 400,000 participants (5× the number participants of prior work’s datasets) with rich demographic reporting across 210 social- science studies spanning multiple disciplines. 2."
6328,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,30,"We present SOCRATES-LLAMA-8B and SOCRATES-QWEN-14B finetuned on SOCSCI210, which, relative to GPT-4o, generate predictions that align 12.1% and 13.2% better to human response distributions, reflecting 26+% performances gains relative to their base models. 3."
6329,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,31,"Motivated by practical use cases of social sci- entists with in-domain data, we demonstrate robust generalization at various levels."
6330,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,32,"Finetuning on as little as 10% of an experiment’s data reduces pre- diction error by 13% on unseen participants, and training on subsets of experimental conditions or outcomes boosts generalization to unseen condi- tions by 71% and unseen outcomes by 49%. 2 Related Work Datasets for Human Response Finetuning.Re- cent works have assembled large-scale public- opinion datasets and used them to finetune LLMs."
6331,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,33,"For instance, Santurkar et al."
6332,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,34,(2023) train on opin- ion distributions from 60 U.S. demographic groups over 500 contentious questions.
6333,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,35,"(2025) compile 3,362 survey questions with the re- sponses distributions from 70,000 demographics, demonstrating a great breadth of topic diversity."
6334,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,36,Other works have focused on datasets of in- dividual decision-making across different behav- ioral contexts.
6335,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,37,"(2024), for example, introduce Psych-101, which contains over 10 mil- lion choices from 60,000 participants across 160 cognitive-science experiments."
6336,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,38,"(2025) collect and finetune on 60,000 individuals reactions to different texts to explore how sociode- mographic factors shape perception, and Lu et al."
6337,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,39,"(2025) finetune on 230,965 logged decisions from 3,526 users to predict web-action generation."
6338,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,40,"(2025) explores reinforcement fine-tuning for reasoning trace generation from a dataset of 13,000 risky human choices produced by Peterson et al."
6339,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,41,"(2025) combines multi- ple types of datasets for fine-tuning, aggregating data from 17,667 individual surveys and economic games played by 68,790 individuals."
6340,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,42,"(they also include titles and abstracts from 2,703 behavioral science publications)."
6341,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,43,Although rich in behavioral Dataset Size Feats.
