6343,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,45,"Under “Feats (features)” column, “D” indicates if the dataset includes participant demographics, and “I” refers to if training samples are done at the individual level (as opposed to the aggregate distribution level)."
6344,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,46,"When training occurs at the aggregate level, we omit the total number of individuals used to construct the dataset as they do not maintain individual granularity."
6345,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,47,"Figure 2: t-SNE projected embedding space of ques- tions in SOCSCI210, compared to SubPop (Suh et al., 2025) and Psych101 (Binz et al., 2024)."
6346,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,48,"SOCSCI210 shows much broader topic diversity across social sci- ence disciplines. detail, these datasets do not yet capture the full di- versity of social science disciplines that simulations could enable at a granular, individual level."
6347,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,49,"Our work attempts to bridge these gaps by con- structing a dataset that expands upon the cover- age of human behavioral sciences covered in prior datasets while enabling granular, individual-level responses in behavioral contexts."
6348,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,50,Increased scien- tific topic breadth is a key enabler of engineering a shared agent model that can enable any simulation across any social science context.
6349,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,51,"LLM Finetuning Methods.Finetuning adapts pretrained LLMs for specific tasks, such as follow- ing user instructions (Ouyang et al., 2022; Wang et al., 2022; Zhang et al., 2023) or learning so- cial skills (Liu et al., 2023; Yang et al., 2024b; Wu et al., 2024)."
6350,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,52,"Apart from supervised fine- tuning (SFT), reinforcement learning from hu- man feedback (RLHF) (Christiano et al., 2017; Ziegler et al., 2019), as well as the simplified DPO (Rafailov et al., 2024) and SimPO (Meng et al., 2024), all use paired data of {preferred response, dispreferred response} for fine- tuning, which aligns model outputs to annotated human preferences."
6351,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,53,"More recently, reasoning mod- els (DeepSeek-AI, 2025; Abdin et al., 2025; Team, 2025b) trained with RL show strong performance in improving LLM capability by exploring chain- of-thought (Wei et al., 2022a), especially for solv- ing complex tasks."
6352,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,54,"The reasoning abilities of larger teacher models can also be distilled into smaller models via finetuning on the teacher-generated rea- soning traces (Zhao et al., 2025; Team, 2025a)."
6353,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,55,"In this work, we provide a comparative evalua- tion of SFT and DPO—contrasting the scenarios in which each is most effective (see §4)."
6354,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,56,"Prior finetun- ing studies in this domain have explored direct SFT (Suh et al., 2025; Binz et al., 2024), SFT augmented with reasoning (Lu et al., 2025), and reinforcement fine-tuning with GRPO (Zhu et al., 2025). 3 Task Formulation 3.1 Task Description We finetune an LLM to predict the responses of an individual (of some demographic) to a stimulus in an experiment with multiple treatments."
6355,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,57,"Fig. 3 SocSci210 Dataset Examples Finetuning Methods EvaluationAccuracy - Age: 42,  - Race: Black - Gender: Female Pretend to be a persona giving by the  following attributes:  You read: You read: “Most Americans Face an  Insecure Economic Future: Less than 37%  of 18 – 20 year olds have any savings.” On a scale from 1 (not at all) to 7  (very), how worried are you about the  stability of the US economy?"
6356,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,58,"Outcome Condition Persona Given the participants high  income bracket, the headline  will incite minimal worries. 2 PersonaConditionOutcomeReasoning Response Prediction Outcome Condition Persona Reasoning Outcome 1 Condition 1 Persona 1 Prediction 1 Outcome 2 Condition 2 Persona 2 Prediction 2 SFTSFT + reasoningDPO 4 3 Distribution vs. rejected preferred - Ideology: Conservative - Area: Metropolitan - Income: 150 – 175K Prediction preferred Figure 3: Overview of our task formulation, methods, and evaluation."
6357,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,59,"Our dataset contains information on personas, conditions, outcomes, and predictions."
6358,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,60,"We compare SFT, SFT on reasoning traces, and DPO."
6359,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,61,Our evaluation measures performance gains on both predicting individual accuracy and aggregate distributions under conditions. shows an example prediction.
6360,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,62,"We consider ques- tions that are ordinal (e.g., “On a scale from 1 to 7, how satisfied are you with your life?”) or binary (e.g., “Would you buy this?"
6361,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,63,"In the dataset of experiments we draw from, outcomes were primarily ordinal or binary; restricting to only these response types standardized our model evalu- ations, with minimal data size reduction."
6362,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,64,"Formally, in our dataset D, a person is repre- sented as P , a set of unique attributes."
6363,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,65,"In our dataset, these attributes are demographic charac- teristics."
6364,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,66,"Each experiment is set up as E= ([c1, ..., cj],[o 1, ..oi]) with j different conditions and i outcome questions."
6365,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,67,The goal of the exper- iment is to see how different conditions impact participant responses to a given outcome.
6366,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,68,"Stud- ies may have a between-subject design (i.e., par- ticipants are randomized into a single condition and answer multiple outcome questions (between- subject studies) or they may have an within-subject design (participants are randomized into multiple conditions and answer the same outcome)."
6367,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,69,"In either setup, each participant gives k responses, r, each corresponding to a question representing a (c, o) pair, which we refer to as the stimuli."
6368,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,70,"Note, the randomization process occurred when the study of the original dataset was conducted, so we do not randomize the participants into the conditions, we simply tag the participants’ responses with the con- dition they were in in the original study."
6369,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,71,"For every individual participant in a study, we have k tuples of (P, c, o, r)."
6370,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,72,"We finetune an LLM, F ′, to learn F(P, c, o) =⇒r. 3.2 Evaluation We evaluate the performance of our finetuned modelF ′ at two levels."
6371,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,73,"Individual Response Accuracy.Given the ordinal property of all predictions (§3.1), we compute a normalized accuracy between predicted and actual responses as Acc.= 1− 1 N X (P,c,o) F ′(P, c, o)−r  rmax −r min where rmax, rmin represent the maximum and min- imum value of r under a specific condition and outcome in the ground truth responses (i.e., the bounds of the response scale)."
6372,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,74,"This value is com- puted for each study, and then averaged across all studies to get a final individual response accuracy score."
6373,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,75,Distribution Alignment Under Conditions.
6374,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,76,"While predicting individual responses is impor- tant, accuracy is upper-bounded by the non- deterministic nature of F(P, c, o) (i.e., the same demographic may have different responses to the same stimuli, so F(P, c, o) is a distribution)."
6375,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,77,The primary goal of social-science experiments is to compute an end statistic that represents how re- sponses to outcome questions vary across stimulus conditions.
6376,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,78,"The exact statistical analyses in these contexts (e.g., t-tests, ANOV A, regressions) depend on the type of experiment being conducted (Mar- avelakis, 2019), but all statistics depend on the un- derlying distribution of the responses to outcome questions under each condition."
6377,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,79,"Because of this, distributional alignment for this context is more im- portant than measuring just accuracy (we provide further examples and justification of this in §B)."
6378,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,80,"Thus, we also measure whether the distribution of responses to each outcome under each experi- mental condition aligns with corresponding human responses."
6379,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,81,"Specifically, for each (condition, outcome) pair (c, o)∈E , we compare the distribution of pre- dicted responses across all participants assigned to c against the empirical distribution of actual re- sponses."
6380,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,82,"(2025), we compute distributional alignment using the Wasserstein dis- tance, which estimates both the shape and mean of distributions."
6381,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,83,"For consistency, we first standardize all distributions to be between [0,1] by subtracting rmin and dividing by rmax −r min."
6382,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,84,We average the Wasserstein distance across all condition outcomes pairs in a study to get an aggregate score for the study.
6383,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,85,We then average each study’s score across all studies to get the final score.
6384,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,86,"A lower Wasser- stein distance indicates better alignment between predicted and empirical response distributions. 3.3 Dataset Construction Data Source.We collect studies from NSF’s Time-sharing Experiments for the Social Science (TESS) project (""TESS"", 2025), a repository of peer-reviewed experiments across various social disciplines (e.g., psychology, political science, and economics)."
6385,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,87,TESS studies are nationally represen- tative and high powered (studies in SOCSCI210 have mean 1907 and median 1954.5 participants).
6386,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,88,"Reconstruction.We employ a data-construction agent – powered by OpenAI’so4-mini-high – to automatically parse the source data into {persona, stimuli, response} formats from each study, where the stimuli is tagged by its respective con- dition and outcome question."
6387,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,89,We detail the re- construction workflow in §A.
6388,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,90,"In total, our agent successfully reconstructs 210 studies."
6389,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,91,"Final Dataset Statistics.SOCSCI210 comprises 2.9 million individual responses spanning 1197 outcomes and 1194 conditions (yielding collec- tively 5,998 unique stimuli) from 400,491 partic- ipants."
6390,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,92,Our SOCSCI210 includes responses from five times as many individuals as prior finetun- ing work.
6391,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,93,Tab. 1 offers an explicit comparison with prior datasets used for human behavior finetuning.
6392,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,94,"Apart from being large in scale, SOCSCI210 is also diverse across disciplines."
6393,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,95,"Fig. 2 shows the embedding space of our stimuli with other large- scale fine-tuning datasets (Binz et al., 2024; Suh et al., 2025), illustrating this broad topic diversity. 4 Finetuning Methods To finetune LLMs for simulating responses, we ex- periment with supervised finetuning (SFT), SFT on oracle reasoning traces, and contrastive preference tuning via DPO (Rafailov et al., 2024)."
6394,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,96,"Supervised Finetuning (SFT).Given our dataset D, an individual persona P , experiment condition c, and outcome question o, we form a prompt q that asks the model to predict the individual’s re- sponse (see §D for the template)."
6395,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,97,Let F ′ denote the model being finetuned.
6396,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,98,"The SFT objective min- imizes the negative log-likelihood (cross-entropy) of the ground-truth responser: LSFT ␀ F ′ =−E (q,r)∼D  logF ′(r|q)  (1) Augmentation with Oracle Reasoning Traces."
6397,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,99,"Prior work has used explanatory reasoning for pre- dicting human behavior (Park et al., 2024) and im- proving fine-tuning performance (Lu et al., 2025), so we also augment SFT with oracle reasoning."
6398,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,100,"Specifically, given the LLM prompt and the corre- sponding human response, we query GPT-4o-mini to generate reasoning traces explaining the human decision from a social scientist’s perspective (see §D)."
6399,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,101,"These oracle-generated reasoning traces are incorporated into the target output, enriching the responserwith explicit rationales 1."
6400,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,102,"Contrastive Finetuning via Preference Opti- mization.To enhance the model’s ability to differ- entiate responses based on variations in conditions c, demographics P , or outcome questions o, we construct paired data by varying these components and contrasting the corresponding responses."
6401,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,103,"For demographic contrastive pairs (see §5.5), we take a focal persona ppos and randomly sample a contrasting persona pneg from the dataset D un- der the same condition c and outcome question o, while ensuring their responses differ (rneg)."
6402,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,104,"Each pair specifies that (ppos, c, o, rpos) is preferred over (ppos, c, o, rneg)."
6403,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,105,"(2024), the DPO objective is 1While we use GPT-4o for our main evaluation, we opted to generate the oracle reasoning traces with GPT-4o-mini due to practical cost constraints."
6404,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,106,"Since these traces are produced oracle-style, we believe any difference in reasoning quality between the models is minimal."
6405,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,107,"LDPO ␀ F ′;F  = −E (q,rpos,rneg)∼D h logσ  βlog F ′(rpos |q) F(r pos |q) −βlog F ′(rneg |q) F(r neg |q) i ,(2) where q concatenates ppos, c, and o into a single prompt (see §D); F ′ is the finetuned model, F the fixed reference model, σ is the sigmoid function, andβscales the preference impact. 5 Experiments 5.1 Training Configurations We train LLaMA3-8B-Instruct (Grattafiori et al., 2024) and Qwen2.5-14B-Instruct (Yang et al., 2024a) as representative base LLMs of different sizes. §C has complete training details. 5.2 Baselines Bounds on Metrics.When computing the Wasser- stein distance, we treat the responses in our dataset as the ground-truth distribution of human responses."
6406,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,108,"Because individual responses naturally vary, this empirical sample may not perfectly capture the true distribution of outcomes under each condition."
6407,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,109,"Our source experiments were highly powered to esti- mate a treatment effect of a certain size, not to ro- bustly estimate the full distribution."
6408,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,110,"To estimate an empirical upper bound on performance given this variance, we perform bootstrapping: we generate 100 resampled datasets (with replacement) from the original responses."
6409,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,111,"For each bootstrapped dataset, we compute the Wasserstein distance between that resample and the full original sample, then aver- age these distances across all 100 iterations."
6410,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,112,"If our models Wasserstein distance meets or exceeds this, our error is no larger than the variability inherent in our data."
6411,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,113,We label this the “Empirical Best”.
6412,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,114,"To establish a lower bound, we compare the stan- dardized distribution of our predicted responses to a uniform distribution across [0,1] ."
6413,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,115,We use this uniform baseline “Uniform Guess” to calculate a corresponding lower bound on both Wasserstein distance and accuracy.
6414,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,116,"Comparing Metrics.Because the Wasserstein dis- tance has a narrow range (e.g., 0.2 for a uniform guess, 0.1 for the empirical best), we report re- sults asrelative changeversus a baseline (either the base model with one-shot prompting or GPT-4o with one-shot prompting)."
6415,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,117,"For each method, we compute |amethod−abase| |abase| ×100%, assigning the sign so that positive values indicate improvement and negative values indicate regression."
6416,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,118,"Here,a method is the metric (e.g., Wasserstein distance) for the method under evaluation, and abase is the metric for the baseline."
6417,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,119,"Prompting Baselines.In our task formulation, we already incorporate all available demographic information from participants, which has proven an effective prompting mechanism in prior work (Hewitt et al., 2024)."
6418,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,120,"Prior work has also shown that reasoning over intermediate decisions (Wei et al., 2022b) or using in-context-prompting (Dong et al., 2022) improves LLM prediction accuracy."
6419,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,121,"Accordingly, we evaluate three baselines: (1) di- rect prediction prompting; (2) prompting to gen- erate explicit reasoning traces before prediction; and (3) in-context prompting with few-shot exam- ples."
6420,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,122,"We select few-shot examples by finding the closest prompt stimuli neighbor via cosine sim- ilarity of embeddings, then choosing examples from five random participants."
6421,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,123,We use OpenAI’s text-embedding-3-large model to embed stim- uli.
6422,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,124,"Prompt templates are provided in §D and §E. 5.3 Generalization Across Unseen Studies First, we consider the case when there isno in- domain studies data are availableto finetune on."
6423,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,125,"Specifically, we assess the study-wise generaliza- tion of our finetuning methods by evaluating on studies that are completely out of domain (i.e.,, not seen during training)."
6424,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,126,"Setup.From the 210 studies in SOCSCI210, we split 170 studies as our train-studies and 40 studies as test-studies."
6425,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,127,"We train over 100% of the training studies data, and evaluate on the 40 test studies."
6426,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,128,"We compare the performance of our three finetuning objectives (SFT, SFT+Reasoning, and Contrastive DPO (§4)) across two open-source models, to three prompting baselines onGPT-4o."
6427,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,129,Results.Tab. 2 details the results on our evaluation metrics (§3.2).
6428,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,130,We find that finetuning meaning- fully generalizes to unseen studies and improves the distributional alignment metric.
6429,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,131,"Relative to the GPT-4o baseline, after SFT, LLaMA3-8B out- performs GPT-4o by12.1%, and Qwen2.5-14B outperforms GPT4o by13.2%, reflecting relative gains of 30.1% and 26.3% from fine-tuning."
6430,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,132,"In open-source models, prompting through reasoning achieves significant gains, though our fine-tuned Model Variant Accuracy↑Distribution↓ Score%∆ vs Base vsGPT-4oScore%∆ vs Base vsGPT-4o Proprietary Models GPT-4o Base 72.9 – – 0.174 – – + Few-shot (5) 73.2 0.4% 0.4% 0.161 7.5% 7.5% + Reasoning 73.1 0.3% 0.3% 0.169 2.9% 2.9% Open-Source Models LLaMA3-8B Base 70.3 – -3.6% 0.219 – -25.9% + Few-shot (5) 68.9 -2.0% -5.5% 0.212 3.2% -21.8% + Reasoning 69.8 -0.7% -4.3% 0.174 20.6% – + SFT 69.1 -1.7% -5.2%0.15330.1% 12.1% + SFT w/ Reasoning 67.5 -4.0% -7.4% 0.165 24.7% 5.2% + DPO72.63.3% -0.4% 0.185 15.5% -6.3% Qwen2.5-14B Base 72.9 – – 0.205 – -17.8% + Few-shot (5) 71.9 -1.4% -1.4% 0.196 4.4% -12.6% + Reasoning 72.7 -0.3% -0.3% 0.166 19.0% 4.6% + SFT 69.5 -4.7% -4.7%0.15126.3% 13.2% + SFT w/ Reasoning 67.6 -7.3% -7.3% 0.164 20.0% 5.7% + DPO74.01.4% 1.4% 0.181 11.7% -4.0% Bounds Uniform Guess 61.2 – -16.1% 0.203 – -16.7% Empirical Best – – – 0.125 – 28.2% Table 2: Comparison of model variants on accuracy and distribution distance metrics across unseen studies (§5.3)."
6431,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,133,"In each scenario,best scores are in boldface, second-best underlined ."
6432,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,134,Percent changes are relative. model still outperforms this baseline on distribution alignment.
6433,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,135,"The best distributional alignment score (0.151) is achieved by fine-tuning Qwen2.5-14B; given an empirical best bound of 0.125 on this met- ric, our modelclosely approximate actual human response distributions."
6434,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,136,"Interestingly, although distributional alignment improves for unseen studies, response-level accu- racy does not necessarily increase."
6435,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,137,"This suggests that individual predictions may become less precise as we better approximate the distribution of how re- sponses should look (for example, if user responses under condition follow a distribution N(0,1) , then a model that more accurately captures that distri- bution can incur higher error than one that always predicts the mean)."
6436,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,138,We include an in-depth discus- sion analyzing this in §B.
6437,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,139,"For predicting individual accuracy metric, con- trastive DPO outperforms all other methods achiev- ing 73.9% accuracy."
6438,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,140,"This is potentially due to our demographic-focused contrastive pair construction (§4) that enables models to learn detailed distinc- tion in simulating individual decisions, leading to more precise predictions of each individual. 5.4 Generalization to Unseen Conditions and Outcomes Researchers often have topic-specific dataset they can leverage for finetuning."
6439,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,141,"For example, a politi- cal polarization researcher may have existing data on how an intervention shifts feelings toward the opposing party and want to run studies to predict either (a) how this intervention influences a dif- ferent outcome, such as respondents’ confidence in government or (b) how a new intervention will affect that same outcome."
6440,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,142,"Thus, in this section, we examine:How does finetuning help generaliza- tion to unseen conditions/outcomes within the same study?"
6441,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,143,Setup.We subset SOCSCI210 to all studies that contain at least 4 conditions / outcomes.
6442,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,144,"We split the dataset into two splits: one for testing condi- tion generalization, and one for testing outcome generalization."
6443,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,145,"For the condition split, we ran- domly selected 75% of the conditions across stud- ies, and take all questions under those conditions for train, and hold out the other 25% for test."
6444,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,146,"For outcome splits, we repeat the same process but sam- pling on outcomes."
6445,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,147,"For each, we finetune on the train set, then run our evaluation on the test set."
6446,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,148,LLaMA3-8B-Instruct is used as an example base model.
6447,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,149,"Results.As shown in Tab. 3, when predicting held- outconditions, our finetuned model with reasoning improves by71%in estimating response distri- butions relative to the base model."
