6451,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,153,SFT also increases the accuracy on individual predictions from 71.0% to 74.2%.
6452,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,154,"Acrossoutcomes, finetuning with reasoning also improves distribution distance, leading to 49% rel- ative improvement compared to LLaMA3-8B base."
6453,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,155,Generalization across unseen conditions tends to be greater than across unseen outcomes.
6454,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,156,"This may be because LLMs grasp the underlying effects of how condition manipulations influence responses, but are more prone to misestimate the initial dis- tribution of outcome questions."
6455,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,157,"Thus, by holding the outcome constant and varying only the stimuli, the model can more effectively learn the resulting effects."
6456,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,158,"This has especially practical value since studies often test many different condition stimuli on the same outcome (e.g., Strand et al."
6457,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,159,(2024) tests 25 interventions to reduce partisan animosity). 5.5 Generalization to Unseen Participants Researchers often run pilot experiments on a small set of participants before committing to fully pow- ered studies.
6458,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,160,"Specific to such use case, we consider finetuning directly on a subset of participants and testing generalization to unseen participants in the same study."
6459,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,161,We examine how little data from a pi- lot study is needed to accurately predict outcomes for the remaining high-powered sample.
6460,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,162,Setup.We reuse the same study-level train-test split from §5.3: 170 studies for training and 40 for testing.
6461,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,163,"For the 170 training studies, we randomly divide the participantsonceinto:participant-train (50% of all individuals for training);participant- eval(the remaining 50% for evaluation of unseen participantsbutseen studies)."
6462,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,164,"From theparticipant- trainpool we draw progressively largerpilotsub- sets corresponding to 1,5,10,20,30,40,50% of allparticipants (i.e., the 50% splitallofparticipant- train)."
6463,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,165,For each split size we finetune the model and report performance on (i) the participant-eval splits of the 170 training studies (unseen individ- ualsbutseen studies) and (ii) the 40 completely held-out studies (unseen individualsandunseen studies).
6464,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,166,This design reveals how much participant data a pilot must collect to obtain reliable generalization across both new participants and new studies.
6465,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,167,Results.Fig. 4 shows the results on both the par- ticipants remained in the observed studies and all the participants in the observed studies.
6466,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,168,"In seen studies (the 50% held-out evaluation set), contrastive DPO tuning outperforms simple SFT for learning individual responses: with just 10% of the data, accuracy rises from 71% to 75% (a 13% relative error reduction)."
6467,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,169,"However, SFT estimates the distribution more effectively."
6468,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,170,"When augmented by reasoning traces, SFT+Reasoning brings even further alignment on the distribution."
6469,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,171,"Across all studies, the learning curves in Fig. 4 indicate that saturation of learning is consistently achieved at around10%of participant data."
6470,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,172,"In unseen studies (the completely held-out 40 studies), a similar pattern holds."
6471,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,173,"Contrastive DPO tuning also shows superior performance on the indi- vidual response accuracy, surpassing GPT4o with only 10% of data."
6472,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,174,"SFT yields better distribution alignment, whereas reasoning trace augmentation provides little benefit in this setting. 5.6 Demographic Bias and Parity A principal strength of our dataset is that it cap- tures rich demographic attributes of all participants and how they may affect responses."
6473,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,175,"In this section, we analyze the response distributions for the full- data SFT of LLaMA3-8B, described in §5.3."
6474,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,176,"We fur- ther break down our distributional alignment metric (i.e., the Wasserstein distance between model re- sponses under each unique condition and outcome) by demographic category: we subset the responses to each demographic subgroup and compute the average Wasserstein distance."
6475,22,C022_P1_pdf.txt,177,"Using this, we also compute demographic parity difference, a measure"
6476,23,C023_P1.txt,0,"[2504.01167] Predicting Field Experiments with Large Language Models       >   cs   > Help  |  Advanced Search Comments Journal reference Report number arXiv identifier DOI Full text Search Computer Science > Computers and Society  (cs)     Title: Predicting Field Experiments with Large Language Models Authors: Yaoyu Chen ,  Yuheng Hu ,  Yingda Lu   View a PDF of the paper titled Predicting Field Experiments with Large Language Models, by Yaoyu Chen and 2 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) Abstract: Large language models (LLMs) have demonstrated unprecedented emergent capabilities, including content generation, translation, and simulation of human behavior."
6477,23,C023_P1.txt,1,"Field experiments, on the other hand, are widely employed in social studies to examine real-world human behavior through carefully designed manipulations and treatments."
6478,23,C023_P1.txt,2,"However, field experiments are known to be expensive and time consuming."
6479,23,C023_P1.txt,3,"Therefore, an interesting question is whether and how LLMs can be utilized for field experiments."
6480,23,C023_P1.txt,4,"In this paper, we propose and evaluate an automated LLM-based framework to predict the outcomes of a field experiment."
6481,23,C023_P1.txt,5,Applying this framework to 276 experiments about a wide range of human behaviors drawn from renowned economics literature yields a prediction accuracy of 78%.
6482,23,C023_P1.txt,6,"Moreover, we find that the distributions of the results are either bimodal or highly skewed."
6483,23,C023_P1.txt,7,"By investigating this abnormality further, we identify that field experiments related to complex social issues such as ethnicity, social norms, and ethical dilemmas can pose significant challenges to the prediction performance."
6484,23,C023_P1.txt,8,"Subjects: Computers and Society (cs.CY) Cite as:  [cs.CY]   (or   [cs.CY]  for this version) Focus to learn more  arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite Submission history  From: Yaoyu Chen [ view email ]    [v1]  Tue, 1 Apr 2025 20:14:35 UTC (3,614 KB) [v2]  Tue, 20 May 2025 17:10:12 UTC (5,410 KB) [v3]  Wed, 21 May 2025 02:06:29 UTC (5,410 KB)   Full-text links: Access Paper: View a PDF of the paper titled Predicting Field Experiments with Large Language Models, by Yaoyu Chen and 2 other authors View PDF HTML (experimental) TeX Source   view license    Current browse context:  cs.CY < prev   |     next > new  |  recent  |  2025-04  Change to browse by:   cs References & Citations NASA ADS Google Scholar Semantic Scholar export BibTeX citation Loading..."
