6490,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,0,"Nonstandard Errors in AI Agents Ruijiang Gao Steven Chong Xiao Naveen Jindal School of Management, University of Texas at Dallas ruijiang.gao@utdallas.edu steven.xiao@utdallas.edu Abstract We study whether state-of-the-art AI coding agents, given the same data and re- search question, produce the same empirical results."
6491,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,1,"Deploying 150 autonomous Claude Code agents to independently test six hypotheses about market quality trends in NYSE TAQ data for SPY (2015–2024), we find that AI agents exhibit sizablenonstandard errors(NSEs), that is, uncertainty from agent-to-agent variation in analytical choices, analogous to those documented among human researchers."
6492,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,2,"AI agents diverge sub- stantially on measure choice (e.g., autocorrelation vs. variance ratio, dollar vs. share volume)."
6493,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,3,Different model families (Sonnet 4.6 vs.
6494,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,4,"Opus 4.6) exhibit stable “empirical styles,” reflecting systematic differences in methodological preferences."
6495,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,5,"In a three-stage feedback protocol, AI peer review (written critiques) has minimal effect on disper- sion, whereas exposure to top-rated exemplar papers reduces the interquartile range of estimates by 80–99% withinconvergingmeasure families."
6496,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,6,"Convergence occurs both through within-family estimation tightening and through agents switching measure families entirely, but convergence reflects imitation rather than understanding."
6497,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,7,These findings have implications for the growing use of AI in automated policy evaluation and empirical research.
6498,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,8,"Keywords:Nonstandard errors, AI agents 1 arXiv:2603.16744v2 [cs.AI] 19 Mar 2026 1 Introduction The deployment of artificial intelligence in empirical research is accelerating rapidly."
6499,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,9,"AI agents now automate tasks ranging from data collection and coding to statistical estimation and report writing (Lu et al., 2024)."
6500,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,10,"Projects such as Autonomous Policy Evaluation (APE; Social Catalyst Lab, 2026) deploy AI to produce end-to-end economics research papers, raising a fundamental question: if we ask different AI agents to analyze the same data and test the same hypothesis, will they produce the same result?"
6501,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,11,The concern is well motivated.
6502,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,12,"A large literature documents that “researcher degrees of freedom” (Simmons et al., 2011) introduce substantial variation into empirical findings."
6503,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,13,(2018) show that 29 teams analyzing the same soccer data reach divergent conclusions about whether dark-skinned players receive more red cards.
6504,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,14,(2020) find that 70 neuroimaging teams testing nine hypotheses on the same fMRI data produce highly variable results.
6505,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,15,"(2024) document that 164 research teams, given the same data and hypotheses about market microstructure, produce estimates with an interquartile range (IQR) comparable in magnitude to the standard error of any individual estimate."
6506,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,16,They use the termnonstandard errors(NSE) to describe this addi- tional uncertainty arising from researcher-to-researcher variation in analytical choices in the “evidence-generating process” (EGP).
6507,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,17,"A natural question is whether AI agents, which lack the idiosyncratic training and in- stitutional pressures that shape human researchers’ choices, would exhibit similar variation."
6508,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,18,"On one hand, AI agents drawing on the same foundation model might converge to a single “best” approach, eliminating NSE."
6509,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,19,"On the other hand, the stochasticity inherent in language model sampling, combined with the underspecification of most empirical tasks (Steegen et al., 2016), could produce meaningful variation even among identically initialized agents."
6510,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,20,We address this question by replicating the Menkveld et al.
6511,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,21,(2024) experimental design with AI agents.
6512,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,22,"We deploy 150 autonomous Claude Code agents (100 Sonnet 4.6, 50 Opus 4.6) to independently test six hypotheses about market quality trends in SPY using NYSE 2 Stage 1 Independent Agent 1 Sonnet Agent 2 Sonnet Agent 150 Opus ..."
6513,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,23,"NYSE TAQ 66 GB, 7B rows Measurechoice AC:−0.3%/yr VR:−0.1%/yr abs vssigned |AC|: +1.6 signed:−0.6 abs vssigned |VR−1|:−0.02 signed: +5.5 Stage 2 Peer Review AI Evaluators (Sonnet + Opus) →written feedbackundirected 150 reports Stage 3 T op Papers 5 highest-rated exemplar papers correlated 150 revised Key Finding S1→S2: IQR unchanged (undirected movement) S2→S3: IQR−80% to−99% (correlated imitation) AI NSE = discrete measure-choice forks Within any fork: Small IQR Effect size distribution (%/yr) S1 IQR = 2.43 S3 Small IQR Same data Garden of forking paths (H1 example) Figure 1: Experimental design overview. 150 AI agents independently analyze the same NYSE TAQ data (Stage 1), receive AI peer review (Stage 2), and see the five highest-rated exemplar papers (Stage 3)."
6514,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,24,"At each stage, agents face a “garden of forking paths” (Steegen et al., 2016): measure choice, functional form, and other decision forks."
6515,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,25,Peer review causes undirected movement (IQR unchanged); exemplar exposure causes correlated imitation (IQR collapses within measure families).
6516,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,26,TAQ millisecond data (2015–2024).
6517,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,27,"Each agent operates as a fully autonomous researcher: it reads instructions, explores the data, constructs measures, estimates trends, writes a 2,000– 4,000-word research report, and produces code, figures, and structured results."
6518,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,28,"The entire pipeline, from data to deliverables, runs fully autonomously without human intervention."
6519,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,29,"We conduct a three-stage feedback protocol that mimics a fully automated AI research society: Stage 1 (independent analysis), Stage 2 (AI peer review with written feedback), and Stage 3 (exposure to the five highest-rated exemplar papers)."
6520,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,30,We analyze the dynamics of AI NSE in these stages.
6521,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,31,The complete workflow is shown in Figure 1.
6522,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,32,"First, we find that AI agents exhibit sizable nonstandard errors."
6523,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,33,"The effect can range from negative to positive, insignificant to significant, and small to large."
6524,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,34,"For example, for the market efficiency hypothesis (H1), the IQR of effect size estimates across agents is 2.43%/yr, with estimates ranging from−0.74%/yr to +1.7%/yr."
6525,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,35,"For the hypothesis on trading volume 3 (H4), the IQR of effect size estimates across agents is 10.69%/yr, driven entirely by agents choosing different volume measures (dollar volume at approximately +6%/yr vs. share vol- ume at approximately−5%/yr)."
6526,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,36,"For price impact (H6), the IQR is 10.34%/yr, reflecting a split between trade-level price impact and Amihud illiquidity ratio measures (Amihud, 2002)."
6527,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,37,"Second, the structure of AI NSE is distinctive."
6528,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,38,"All 150 agents independently choose regression with a linear time trend as the estimation paradigm, split between level specifica- tions (56%) and log specifications (44%)."
6529,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,39,"No agent uses relative changes (period-over-period ratios), first differences, that are common in human choices."
6530,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,40,AI NSE is therefore concen- trated almost entirely in measure-choice forks (which measure to compute) rather than in estimation-paradigm forks (how to estimate a given measure).
6531,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,41,"Notably, the relative-change specification, which Menkveld et al."
6532,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,42,"(2024) identify as a major source of dispersion through Jensen’s inequality bias, is entirely absent from the AI agents’ repertoire."
6533,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,43,"Third, different model families exhibit stable “empirical styles.” Sonnet 4.6 agents over- whelmingly prefer autocorrelation measures for market efficiency (87%), level OLS, and daily frequency."
6534,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,44,"Opus 4.6 agents universally choose variance ratio measures (100%), prefer log OLS, and use monthly frequency 28% of the time."
6535,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,45,"These preferences are systematic rather than random, consistent with recent evidence that LLMs embed stable biases in code generation (Zhang et al., 2025)."
6536,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,46,"Fourth, we implement a three-stage feedback protocol consisting of independent analysis (S1), AI peer review (S2), and exposure to the five highest-rated papers (S3), analogous to stages S1–S3 in Menkveld et al."
6537,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,47,We find that AI peer review has no effect on reducing dispersion: the IQR is essentially unchanged from S1 to S2.
6538,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,48,"In contrast, exposure to top papers triggers dramatic convergence."
6539,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,49,"For converging measure families, the IQR collapses by 80–99% from S1 to S3."
6540,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,50,"However, for two hypotheses (H1 and H5), dispersion increases as exemplar papers introduce new methodological options that agents adopt inconsistently."
6541,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,51,A striking additional mechanism ismeasure-family migration: 62 of 87 autocorrelation agents 4 switch to variance ratio after seeing top papers that use variance ratio measures.
6542,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,52,Our paper contributes to several literatures.
6543,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,53,"We add to the growing body of work on replication and the credibility of empirical research (Simmons et al., 2011; Harvey et al., 2016; Brodeur et al., 2020)."
6544,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,54,We extend the NSE framework of Menkveld et al.
6545,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,55,"(2024) from human researchers to AI agents, showing that the problem of analytical variation persists even when human judgment is removed from the pipeline."
6546,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,56,"We contribute to the literature on multiverse analysis (Steegen et al., 2016) by providing a large-scale demonstration that AI-generated multiverses may be structurally narrower than human-generated ones."
6547,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,57,"Finally, we inform the nascent policy discussion around automated research by documenting the NSE in AI agents in empirical analysis."
6548,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,58,The remainder of this paper is organized as follows.
6549,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,59,Section 2 reviews related work.
6550,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,60,Section 3 describes the experimental design.
6551,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,61,Section 4 documents the existence and structure of AI NSE.
6552,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,62,Section 5 analyzes the effects of peer feedback and exemplar exposure.
6553,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,63,Section 6 presents the multiverse analysis of decision forks.
6554,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,64,Section 7 discusses implications.
6555,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,65,Section 8 concludes. 2 Related Work 2.1 Automated Research with AI Agents AI systems are increasingly deployed not merely as tools for researchers but as autonomous researchers themselves.
6556,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,66,"(2024) introduce the AI Scientist, a system that au- tonomously generates hypotheses, designs experiments, runs code, and writes full scientific papers at a cost of less than$15 per paper."
6557,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,67,"Project APE (Social Catalyst Lab, 2026) deploys AI agents for end-to-end economics policy evaluation."
6558,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,68,"These systems raise a fundamental question that existing work has not addressed:how reliable are the empirical estimates they produce?A single demonstration that an AI agent can write a paper tells us nothing about whether a different run, or a different model, would reach the same conclusion. 5 In concurrent and independent work, Huang et al."
6559,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,69,(2026) run 158 instances of GPT-5.2 on the #fincap dataset from Menkveld et al.
6560,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,70,(2024) and find that AI agents concentrate on a narrow set of analysis paths.
6561,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,71,Our study differs in three important ways.
6562,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,72,"First, our agents are fully autonomous tool-using systems (Claude Code) that interactively explore data, write and debug code, and produce complete research reports, whereas their agents are customized themselves and generate code in a single shot against dataset metadata without seeing the data."
6563,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,73,This distinction matters because interactive data exploration may lead to different methodological choices than blind code generation.
6564,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,74,"Second, we implement a three-stage feedback protocol (independent analysis, AI peer review, exemplar exposure) that allows us to study how AI agents respond to social scientific feedback mechanisms."
6565,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,75,"Third, we deploy two model families (Sonnet and Opus) within the same architecture, enabling us to decompose AI NSE into within-model stochasticity and between-model “empirical style” components. 2.2 Nonstandard Errors in Social Science A growing literature documents that researcher-to-researcher variation in analytical choices, termed “researcher degrees of freedom” by Simmons et al."
6566,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,76,"(2011), introduces substantial uncertainty into empirical findings."
6567,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,77,This literature has progressed through increasingly large- scale crowdsourced experiments.
6568,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,78,(2018) recruit 29 teams to analyze the same soccer data and find conclusions ranging from a significant positive to a significant negative effect.
6569,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,79,(2020) scale to 70 neuroimaging teams testing nine hypotheses on the same fMRI data.
6570,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,80,"(2022) study 73 teams analyzing identical cross-country survey data on immigration attitudes, finding that observable team characteristics explain only 4% of the variability in results, with the remaining 96% attributable to undocumented analytical choices."
6571,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,81,"(2024) formalize this phenomenon as “nonstandard errors” (NSE) and conduct the largest such study to date, with 164 research teams and 34 peer evaluators 6 testing six hypotheses on EURO STOXX 50 futures data."
6572,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,82,"They introduce a multiverse- based diagnostic that identifies sampling frequency and model choice as the dominant sources of dispersion, and show that peer feedback reduces NSE by 47% across four stages."
6573,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,83,The multiverse analysis framework of Steegen et al.
6574,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,84,"(2016) provides a complementary single- researcher approach, while Brodeur et al."
6575,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,85,(2020) document the downstream consequences of analytical flexibility at scale.
6576,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,86,"A critical gap in this literature is that all existing many-analyst studies usehumanre- searchers, leaving open whether the observed variation reflects irreducible task ambiguity or idiosyncratic human factors (training, incentives, fatigue)."
6577,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,87,"Our study addresses this gap by replacing human researchers with AI agents, which share training data and architecture, thereby isolating the variation attributable to task underspecification from that attributable to researcher heterogeneity."
6578,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,88,"If AI agents, which lack idiosyncratic human biases, still exhibit substantial NSE, the variation must arise from the research question itself rather than from the researchers. 2.3 LLM Behavioral Research A parallel literature investigates the behavioral properties of LLMs as computational models of human decision-making."
6579,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,89,(2023) propose treating LLMs as “Homo silicus”: simulated economic agents that can be endowed with preferences and information and whose behavior can be explored via simulation.
6580,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,90,"(2023) demonstrate “algorithmic fi- delity,” showing that GPT-3, when conditioned on sociodemographic backstories, generates response distributions that closely match real survey data from diverse human subpopula- tions."
6581,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,91,"This work establishes that LLMs encode rich models of human behavior, but it also reveals systematic biases."
6582,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,92,"(2024) documentsycophancy: the tendency of LLMs to conform to a user’s stated opinion even when incorrect, a bias arising from reinforcement learning from human feedback."
6583,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,93,"Sycophancy has been studied 7 primarily in conversational settings, but our findings suggest it has a direct analog in research methodology: when AI agents see exemplar papers in Stage 3, they engage in wholesale imitation rather than independent evaluation, switching measures to match the exemplar regardless of whether the switch is analytically justified (Section 5)."
6584,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,94,Our work bridges and extends these three literatures.
6585,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,95,"Unlike the automated research literature, we do not ask whether AI candoresearch but whether AI research outputs are reliableacross runs."
6586,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,96,"Unlike the NSE literature, we use AI agents as a controlled probe to separate task-inherent ambiguity from researcher-specific variation."
6587,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,97,"Unlike the LLM be- havioral literature, we study LLM behavior not through surveys or games but through the complete pipeline of empirical research, from data exploration to report writing."
6588,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,98,"The result is a new lens on the credibility of AI-generated empirical evidence, with implications for both the deployment of automated research systems and the interpretation of the human NSE literature. 3 Experimental Design 3.1 The #AIcap Project We design the #AIcap project as an AI analog of the #fincap crowdsourced research project in Menkveld et al."
6589,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,99,"Where #fincap recruited 164 human research teams, we deploy 150 AI coding agents."
6590,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,100,"Each agent receives identical instructions and access to the same dataset, and independently produces a research report with quantitative estimates."
6591,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,101,"AI agents.Each agent is an instance of Claude Code (Anthropic), a command-line AI cod- ing agent that can read files, write code, execute programs, inspect outputs, and iteratively refine its analysis."
6592,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,102,We use two model variants: 100 agents run Sonnet 4.6 (claude-sonnet-4-6) and 50 agents run Opus 4.6 (claude-opus-4-6).
6593,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,103,Both models use default sampling parame- ters (temperature = 1.0).
6594,24,C024_P1_pdf.txt,104,The agents operate with the--dangerously-skip-permissions 8
6595,24,C024_S1.txt,0,Project APE: Can policy evaluation be automated?
6596,24,C024_S1.txt,1,Or is hallucinated slop unavoidable?
6597,24,C024_S1.txt,2,Mar 5 update:   Feedback   is now open.
6598,24,C024_S1.txt,3,"Tell us what APE is doing wrong, suggest research directions, or critique a paper. ✕ Social Catalyst Lab · University of Zurich PROJECT APE Autonomous Policy Evaluation About Methodology Countries EU GitHub Can we  automate policy evaluation?"
6599,24,C024_S1.txt,4,AI may soon be capable of producing rigorous economic research.
6600,24,C024_S1.txt,5,"If that happens, policy evaluation could scale dramatically: highlighting what works, what fails, and what harms, far faster than human researchers alone."
6601,24,C024_S1.txt,6,"We want to find out whether an autonomous system can generate, replicate, and revise empirical policy research, with everything made public."
6602,24,C024_S1.txt,7,This is an experiment in building reliable AI research systems.
6603,24,C024_S1.txt,8,"For a global overview,   click here . 2,464 Ideas + 342  this week 943 Papers + 181  this week 17 k+ Matches 4 % Win Rate Last updated:  April 7, 2026 Top APE papers Loading top APE papers..."
6604,24,C024_S1.txt,9,Most policies — probably millions of them globally — are never rigorously evaluated.
6605,24,C024_S1.txt,10,Data is plenty but there aren't enough researchers.
6606,24,C024_S1.txt,11,So we're running an experiment.
6607,24,C024_S1.txt,12,"An AI system attempts to produce economics research at scale,  end to end , using publicly available data."
6608,24,C024_S1.txt,13,"Ideally, we'd want PhDs or editors of top journals to evaluate all of them."
6609,24,C024_S1.txt,14,We run an automated tournament evaluating the papers against human benchmarks from top journals.
6610,24,C024_S1.txt,15,"Get to a ""you know it when you see it"" moment, faster."
6611,24,C024_S1.txt,16,"Most importantly, everything is  public : papers, code, data, failures."
6612,24,C024_S1.txt,17,"The more people look, the faster mistakes get caught."
6613,24,C024_S1.txt,18,"In fact, the core thesis is that recursive self-improvement is possible and can be enhanced by human feedback."
6614,24,C024_S1.txt,19,"The next milestone: generate a 1000 papers, evaluate, and share lessons in a report."
6615,24,C024_S1.txt,20,Can policy evaluation be automated?
6616,24,C024_S1.txt,21,Or is hallucinated slop unavoidable?
6617,24,C024_S1.txt,22,"Let's find out! ⚠️  Warning:  We are  learning  how to build a reliable, autonomous research system."
6618,24,C024_S1.txt,23,"Expect bugs, errors, hallucinations, and trashable papers."
6619,24,C024_S1.txt,24,None of the generated papers have been peer-reviewed and should not be used for evidence-based policy making.
6620,24,C024_S1.txt,25,"What does ""autonomous"" even mean?"
6621,24,C024_S1.txt,26,We need funding for scaling AI compute!
6622,24,C024_S1.txt,27,How the Tournament Works ▼ What is this?
6623,24,C024_S1.txt,28,"We built an AI system (APE) that writes economics research papers from scratch — finding data, running statistical analysis, and producing full academic papers."
6624,24,C024_S1.txt,29,"At its core, this is currently powered by  Claude Code  (currently Claude Opus 4.6), orchestrating an ensemble of currently (March 2025) 11 external models from 7 providers, sometimes in collaboration with Codex."
6625,24,C024_S1.txt,30,See  Methodology  for details on model evolution.
6626,24,C024_S1.txt,31,"This leaderboard tracks whether those AI-written papers can ""compete"" with human-written papers from top economics journals, through an automated process."
6627,24,C024_S1.txt,32,The Tournament Papers compete in head-to-head matches.
6628,24,C024_S1.txt,33,"Each day at 9:00 AM UTC, we run a round of matches."
6629,24,C024_S1.txt,34,An LLM judge reads both papers and picks one as preferred (or declares a tie).
6630,24,C024_S1.txt,35,The preferred paper gains rating points; the other loses points.
6631,24,C024_S1.txt,36,"Over time, papers consistently favored by the LLM judge rise in the rankings — though this is a noisy and potentially biased signal, not ground truth."
6632,24,C024_S1.txt,37,"How Matches Work For each match, we send both paper PDFs directly to  Gemini 3.1 Flash Lite  (Google's LLM)."
6633,24,C024_S1.txt,38,"The model sees the full papers — text, figures, tables, formatting — exactly as a human reviewer would."
6634,24,C024_S1.txt,39,"The judge is prompted to act as a  ""senior editor at a top economics journal""  and evaluate papers on:  identification strategy  (is the causal inference credible?),  novelty ,  policy relevance ,  execution quality , and  appropriate scope ."
6635,24,C024_S1.txt,40,"To control for position bias (LLMs sometimes prefer whichever paper they see first), we run each comparison twice with the papers swapped."
6636,24,C024_S1.txt,41,A paper must win both rounds to win the match; otherwise it's a tie.
6637,24,C024_S1.txt,42,"Rating System Rankings use  TrueSkill , a Bayesian rating system developed by Microsoft."
6638,24,C024_S1.txt,43,Each paper has two numbers: μ (mu)  — estimated skill level.
6639,24,C024_S1.txt,44,Higher = paper wins more often. σ (sigma)  — uncertainty.
6640,24,C024_S1.txt,45,Decreases as the paper plays more matches.
6641,24,C024_S1.txt,46,"Papers are ranked by their  conservative rating  (μ − 3σ), which represents the lower bound of estimated skill."
6642,24,C024_S1.txt,47,This means papers need consistent wins across multiple matches — a single lucky win won't send a paper to the top.
6643,24,C024_S1.txt,48,Head-to-Head Statistics Win counts  exclude  895  tie s  where the judge couldn't determine a clear winner.
6644,24,C024_S1.txt,49,"Prob(Human Win)  answers: if we randomly pick one human paper and one APE paper, what's the probability the human paper wins according to the LLM judge?"
6645,24,C024_S1.txt,50,"Computed from TrueSkill ratings, accounting for uncertainty — papers with fewer matches contribute less certainty."
6646,24,C024_S1.txt,51,The main metric compares recent cohorts (last 25 of each); all-time ( 89.4 %) includes all  908  AI and  43  human papers with 5+ matches.
6647,24,C024_S1.txt,52,Matchup Selection Each day we run  50 matches  (100 LLM calls with position swapping) in 10 batches of 5.
6648,24,C024_S1.txt,53,"Within each batch, no paper plays twice."
6649,24,C024_S1.txt,54,We combine random matching with structured matching.
6650,24,C024_S1.txt,55,Important Caveats ⚠️ The ⚠️ warning icon in the leaderboard indicates AI-generated papers that have not been peer reviewed.
6651,24,C024_S1.txt,56,The LLM judge is  not a substitute for human peer review .
6652,24,C024_S1.txt,57,"AI-generated papers may contain errors, hallucinations, or fabricated results."
6653,24,C024_S1.txt,58,"In fact, we have found that these are  very common  and sometimes take a lot of effort to spot."
6654,24,C024_S1.txt,59,"If a paper looks too good to be true, it probably is."
6655,24,C024_S1.txt,60,"The judge evaluates the PDF only, not the underlying code or data."
6656,24,C024_S1.txt,61,Rankings should not be taken at face value.
6657,24,C024_S1.txt,62,"That's why everything is  open source  — code, data, and papers are all public so anyone can spot errors, report issues, and contribute improvements."
6658,24,C024_S1.txt,63,Ranking Metrics ▼ Rank Position based on conservative rating (lower bound of estimated skill) 48h Change in rank over the past 48 hours μ Estimated skill level — higher means the paper wins more often σ Uncertainty — decreases as the paper plays more matches Cons.
