6831,26,C026_S1.txt,0,Project APE: Can policy evaluation be automated?
6832,26,C026_S1.txt,1,Or is hallucinated slop unavoidable?
6833,26,C026_S1.txt,2,Mar 5 update:   Feedback   is now open.
6834,26,C026_S1.txt,3,"Tell us what APE is doing wrong, suggest research directions, or critique a paper. ✕ Social Catalyst Lab · University of Zurich PROJECT APE Autonomous Policy Evaluation About Methodology Countries EU GitHub Can we  automate policy evaluation?"
6835,26,C026_S1.txt,4,AI may soon be capable of producing rigorous economic research.
6836,26,C026_S1.txt,5,"If that happens, policy evaluation could scale dramatically: highlighting what works, what fails, and what harms, far faster than human researchers alone."
6837,26,C026_S1.txt,6,"We want to find out whether an autonomous system can generate, replicate, and revise empirical policy research, with everything made public."
6838,26,C026_S1.txt,7,This is an experiment in building reliable AI research systems.
6839,26,C026_S1.txt,8,"For a global overview,   click here . 2,464 Ideas + 342  this week 943 Papers + 181  this week 17 k+ Matches 4 % Win Rate Last updated:  April 7, 2026 Top APE papers Loading top APE papers..."
6840,26,C026_S1.txt,9,Most policies — probably millions of them globally — are never rigorously evaluated.
6841,26,C026_S1.txt,10,Data is plenty but there aren't enough researchers.
6842,26,C026_S1.txt,11,So we're running an experiment.
6843,26,C026_S1.txt,12,"An AI system attempts to produce economics research at scale,  end to end , using publicly available data."
6844,26,C026_S1.txt,13,"Ideally, we'd want PhDs or editors of top journals to evaluate all of them."
6845,26,C026_S1.txt,14,We run an automated tournament evaluating the papers against human benchmarks from top journals.
6846,26,C026_S1.txt,15,"Get to a ""you know it when you see it"" moment, faster."
6847,26,C026_S1.txt,16,"Most importantly, everything is  public : papers, code, data, failures."
6848,26,C026_S1.txt,17,"The more people look, the faster mistakes get caught."
6849,26,C026_S1.txt,18,"In fact, the core thesis is that recursive self-improvement is possible and can be enhanced by human feedback."
6850,26,C026_S1.txt,19,"The next milestone: generate a 1000 papers, evaluate, and share lessons in a report."
6851,26,C026_S1.txt,20,Can policy evaluation be automated?
6852,26,C026_S1.txt,21,Or is hallucinated slop unavoidable?
6853,26,C026_S1.txt,22,"Let's find out! ⚠️  Warning:  We are  learning  how to build a reliable, autonomous research system."
6854,26,C026_S1.txt,23,"Expect bugs, errors, hallucinations, and trashable papers."
6855,26,C026_S1.txt,24,None of the generated papers have been peer-reviewed and should not be used for evidence-based policy making.
6856,26,C026_S1.txt,25,"What does ""autonomous"" even mean?"
6857,26,C026_S1.txt,26,We need funding for scaling AI compute!
6858,26,C026_S1.txt,27,How the Tournament Works ▼ What is this?
6859,26,C026_S1.txt,28,"We built an AI system (APE) that writes economics research papers from scratch — finding data, running statistical analysis, and producing full academic papers."
6860,26,C026_S1.txt,29,"At its core, this is currently powered by  Claude Code  (currently Claude Opus 4.6), orchestrating an ensemble of currently (March 2025) 11 external models from 7 providers, sometimes in collaboration with Codex."
6861,26,C026_S1.txt,30,See  Methodology  for details on model evolution.
6862,26,C026_S1.txt,31,"This leaderboard tracks whether those AI-written papers can ""compete"" with human-written papers from top economics journals, through an automated process."
6863,26,C026_S1.txt,32,The Tournament Papers compete in head-to-head matches.
6864,26,C026_S1.txt,33,"Each day at 9:00 AM UTC, we run a round of matches."
6865,26,C026_S1.txt,34,An LLM judge reads both papers and picks one as preferred (or declares a tie).
6866,26,C026_S1.txt,35,The preferred paper gains rating points; the other loses points.
6867,26,C026_S1.txt,36,"Over time, papers consistently favored by the LLM judge rise in the rankings — though this is a noisy and potentially biased signal, not ground truth."
6868,26,C026_S1.txt,37,"How Matches Work For each match, we send both paper PDFs directly to  Gemini 3.1 Flash Lite  (Google's LLM)."
6869,26,C026_S1.txt,38,"The model sees the full papers — text, figures, tables, formatting — exactly as a human reviewer would."
6870,26,C026_S1.txt,39,"The judge is prompted to act as a  ""senior editor at a top economics journal""  and evaluate papers on:  identification strategy  (is the causal inference credible?),  novelty ,  policy relevance ,  execution quality , and  appropriate scope ."
6871,26,C026_S1.txt,40,"To control for position bias (LLMs sometimes prefer whichever paper they see first), we run each comparison twice with the papers swapped."
6872,26,C026_S1.txt,41,A paper must win both rounds to win the match; otherwise it's a tie.
6873,26,C026_S1.txt,42,"Rating System Rankings use  TrueSkill , a Bayesian rating system developed by Microsoft."
6874,26,C026_S1.txt,43,Each paper has two numbers: μ (mu)  — estimated skill level.
6875,26,C026_S1.txt,44,Higher = paper wins more often. σ (sigma)  — uncertainty.
6876,26,C026_S1.txt,45,Decreases as the paper plays more matches.
6877,26,C026_S1.txt,46,"Papers are ranked by their  conservative rating  (μ − 3σ), which represents the lower bound of estimated skill."
6878,26,C026_S1.txt,47,This means papers need consistent wins across multiple matches — a single lucky win won't send a paper to the top.
6879,26,C026_S1.txt,48,Head-to-Head Statistics Win counts  exclude  895  tie s  where the judge couldn't determine a clear winner.
6880,26,C026_S1.txt,49,"Prob(Human Win)  answers: if we randomly pick one human paper and one APE paper, what's the probability the human paper wins according to the LLM judge?"
6881,26,C026_S1.txt,50,"Computed from TrueSkill ratings, accounting for uncertainty — papers with fewer matches contribute less certainty."
6882,26,C026_S1.txt,51,The main metric compares recent cohorts (last 25 of each); all-time ( 89.4 %) includes all  908  AI and  43  human papers with 5+ matches.
6883,26,C026_S1.txt,52,Matchup Selection Each day we run  50 matches  (100 LLM calls with position swapping) in 10 batches of 5.
6884,26,C026_S1.txt,53,"Within each batch, no paper plays twice."
6885,26,C026_S1.txt,54,We combine random matching with structured matching.
6886,26,C026_S1.txt,55,Important Caveats ⚠️ The ⚠️ warning icon in the leaderboard indicates AI-generated papers that have not been peer reviewed.
6887,26,C026_S1.txt,56,The LLM judge is  not a substitute for human peer review .
6888,26,C026_S1.txt,57,"AI-generated papers may contain errors, hallucinations, or fabricated results."
6889,26,C026_S1.txt,58,"In fact, we have found that these are  very common  and sometimes take a lot of effort to spot."
6890,26,C026_S1.txt,59,"If a paper looks too good to be true, it probably is."
6891,26,C026_S1.txt,60,"The judge evaluates the PDF only, not the underlying code or data."
6892,26,C026_S1.txt,61,Rankings should not be taken at face value.
6893,26,C026_S1.txt,62,"That's why everything is  open source  — code, data, and papers are all public so anyone can spot errors, report issues, and contribute improvements."
6894,26,C026_S1.txt,63,Ranking Metrics ▼ Rank Position based on conservative rating (lower bound of estimated skill) 48h Change in rank over the past 48 hours μ Estimated skill level — higher means the paper wins more often σ Uncertainty — decreases as the paper plays more matches Cons.
