7084,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,168,This indicates that LLMs are capable of leveraging data loaders to effectively integrate knowledge from data of diverse formats. 5.2 Qualitative Analysis We analyze agent traces on REPRO-B ENCH to demonstrate agents’ ability to reason critically and autonomously perform complex assessments.
7085,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,169,"Phase 1: General Information Retrieval $ list_folder(""."") $ read_file(""paper.pdf"") $ read_file(""reproduction_package/readme.txt"") $ cd reproduction_package Phase 2: Code Inspections $ read_file(""main.R"") Phase 3: Script Edition & Execution Phase 4: Result Comparison $ Rscript main.R $ <PATH & Package fixes> $ list_folder(""output"") $ read_file(""output/main.tex"") $ query_vision_language_model(prompt=""Are the reproduced results consistent?"",   images=[<Original PNG>, <Reproduced PNG>]) Figure 4: Agent workflow for REPRO-B ENCH tasks, exemplified by the traces of CORE-Agent for Task 4."
7086,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,170,"By analyzing the traces of all successful cases, we outline a general work- flow of the agents in Figure 4."
7087,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,171,"Specifically, the agents start by developing a broad understanding of the task and the environment in Phase 1, where they (1) list all files and directories in the workspace to identify available materials, (2) read the paper, and (3) read the README file."
7088,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,172,"In Phase 2, they inspect the provided code for potential inconsistencies."
7089,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,173,"In Phase 3, they edit and execute scripts, and in Phase 4, they compare the execution results with the orig- inal results."
7090,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,174,"This workflow closely aligns with real-world scenarios (Brodeur et al., 2024), demon- strating the effectiveness of REPRO-B ENCH tasks."
7091,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,175,Why do AI agents fail to reproduce and analyze results?
7092,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,176,"By analyzing all the traces that misclas- sify score 4 tasks as score 1 across the 3 agents, we summarize the general workflow of executing scripts and comparing results (i.e., Phases 3 and 4 in Figure 4), categorize the sources of failure to reproduce results in social science papers into 4 types, and illustrate their distributions in Figure 5."
7093,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,177,Type 1 failures occur when result comparison is incorrect.
7094,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,178,"For example, CORE-Agent wrote an erroneous Python script for comparison in Task 50, falsely classifying consistent results as un- matched."
7095,27,C027_P1_pdf.txt,179,"Type 2 failures occur when agents see no terminal output for Stata scripts because er- ror messages are stored in log files rather than printed in the terminal, leading them to conclude 23623"
