7113,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,0,"Automating Computational Reproducibility in Social Science: Comparing Prompt-Based and Agent-Based Approaches Syed Mehtab Hussain Shah GESIS - Leibniz-Institut für Sozialwissenschaften Cologne, Germany mehtab.shah@gesis.org Frank Hopfgartner University of Koblenz Koblenz, Germany hopfgartner@uni-koblenz.de Arnim Bleier GESIS - Leibniz-Institut für Sozialwissenschaften Cologne, Germany arnim.bleier@gesis.org Abstract Reproducing computational research is often treated as a straight- forward matter of re-running shared code on shared data."
7114,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,1,"In prac- tice, published analyses frequently fail even when materials are available, due to missing dependencies, brittle paths, version mis- matches, and—more challenging—gaps in analytical logic."
7115,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,2,"We in- vestigate whether large language models (LLMs) and agentic AI systems can automate the routine but labor-intensive work of re- pairing such failures, thereby lowering the practical barrier to com- putational verification."
7116,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,3,We evaluate two automated repair paradigms in a controlled setting derived from five fully reproducible R-based social science studies.
7117,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,4,"Starting from ground-truth executions, we inject realistic failure modes spanning execution-level issues, contextual code fixes, and structural logic omissions, and package them into 130 synthetic test cases."
7118,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,5,"We then run (i) a prompt-based workflow that iteratively queries LLMs with structured prompts at increasing levels of contextual richness, and (ii) an agent-based workflow in which coding agents inspect project files, apply targeted edits, and re-run analyses until completion or a time limit."
7119,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,6,"Repairs are only counted as successful if the resulting outputs match the ground- truth outputs, not merely if the code executes."
7120,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,7,"Across prompt-based runs, reproduction success varies substan- tially (31–79%), shaped by both failure complexity and the amount of context provided; richer context yields the largest gains on struc- turally complex cases."
7121,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,8,"Agent-based workflows consistently achieve higher success (69–96%) across all error categories, suggesting that environment-aware, iterative tool use provides a decisive advan- tage over API-only prompting."
7122,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,9,"By isolating post-publication repair under controlled, systematic failure modes, our benchmark enables direct comparisons between prompt-based and agentic workflows and provides evidence that agentic repair systems can meaningfully reduce manual labour while improving the reliability of computa- tional reproducibility in realistic research pipelines."
7123,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,10,CCS Concepts •Computing methodologies → Artificial intelligence;Natu- ral language processing;Intelligent agents;•Applied com- puting→Sociology.
7124,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,11,"Keywords Computational Reproducibility, Large Language Models, AI Agents, Social Science, Synthetic Benchmark, Meta-Science, Open Science 1 Introduction Reproducing computational research still feels harder than it should be."
7125,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,12,"Ideally, every published analysis would provide all code and data necessary to regenerate its results seamlessly and without requiring any difficult debugging or modifications [2, 6]."
7126,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,13,"However, in practice this is often not the case."
7127,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,14,"Empirical reviews suggest that only a small fraction of papers provide fully executable analysis code [5, 18]."
7128,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,15,Prior work has shown how common these problems are.
7129,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,16,"For example, Hardwicke et al. [10] manually examined 250 psychology articles and found that only a tiny minority made analysis scripts available."
7130,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,17,"Similarly, Trisovic et al . [22] found that about 74% of shared R scripts in replication datasets failed to run successfully in a clean environment."
7131,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,18,Survey evidence also suggests that more than 70% of researchers report struggling to reproduce published findings and over half cannot reproduce their own work later on [1].
7132,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,19,Large- scale audits confirm the issue across disciplines.
7133,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,20,"Similar results have appeared in ecology and evolutionary biology, where only 15% of meta-analyses shared usable data and code and most results still could not be reproduced [13]."
7134,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,21,These patterns suggest a wider reproducibility problem that affects both verification and the long- term usefulness of scientific work.
7135,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,22,"At the same time, AI is transforming how researchers write and execute computational analyses."
7136,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,23,"Modern large language mod- els (LLMs) can read scripts, suggest revisions, and explain errors."
7137,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,24,"Some studies argue that they may help reduce the burden of debug- ging and might even handle some reproducibility tasks indepen- dently [15, 26]."
7138,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,25,"The idea is that instead of requiring human experts to manually go through every analysis step and debug problems, we could prompt LLMs to carry out these steps automatically or at least to assist humans more effectively."
7139,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,26,"However, it is not yet clear how far these tools can go."
7140,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,27,"LLMs often make plausible but incorrect suggestions, miss analytical logic, or ignore domain-specific as- sumptions that human experts would typically notice [12, 23]."
7141,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,28,Very little systematic evidence exists on whether LLMs and AI agents can reliably reproduce published results or under what conditions they succeed or fail.
7142,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,29,We address this gap by introducing a benchmark dataset and conducting two separate reproducibility experiments.
7143,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,30,One experi- mental workflow uses a prompt-based approach with varying levels of context.
7144,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,31,The other employs an agent-based approach that oper- ates directly on the published code.
7145,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,32,Both workflows are evaluated in isolated environments and use the same dataset with identical test cases.
7146,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,33,The goal is to measure how well each approach repairs non-executable research code and if these tools can recover the original published results.
7147,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,34,"The aim is to gain empirically grounded arXiv:2602.08561v2 [cs.SE] 16 Mar 2026 WWW Companion ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Dubai, United Arab Emirates Syed Mehtab Hussain Shah, Frank Hopfgartner, and Arnim Bleier Figure 1:Overview of the experimental framework.First, we construct a synthetic benchmark dataset by injecting systematic failures into reproducible R studies to create a controlled testbed."
7148,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,35,"Then, we evaluate two repair strategies: an iterative, prompt-based workflow and an autonomous agent-based workflow, both operating in isolated Docker environments."
7149,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,36,"Finally, results were aggregated by error category and workflow to enable comparative statistical analyses. insights into where AI tools fit within computational reproducibil- ity studies and what their current limitations are."
7150,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,37,"Building on this motivation, we structure this report around the following research questions: RQ1:To what extent can LLM–based workflows automatically re- pair published computational social science analyses?"
7151,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,38,RQ2:How does the performance of prompt-based LLM repair work- flows compare to agent-based workflows?
7152,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,39,RQ3:How does the complexity of reproducibility failures affect the success of automated repair approaches?
7153,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,40,RQ4:How does the amount and type of contextual information influence the ability to repair non-executable analyses?
7154,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,41,We report on several contributions.
7155,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,42,"First, we present a synthetic benchmark dataset for assessing computational reproducibility in R-based analyses typically used in computational social science."
7156,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,43,"The benchmark consists of fully reproducible studies paired with systematically injected, realistic failure modes that reflect common barriers encountered when reproducing published research."
7157,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,44,"Second, we propose a prompt-based reproducibility repair workflow that uses different prompts to interact with LLMs to diagnose and repair non-executable analysis scripts under varying levels of contextual information."
7158,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,45,"Third, we introduce an agent-based reproducibility repair workflow in which standard software coding agents inspect files, modify code, iteratively rerun analyses, and reason about errors in a more interactive manner."
7159,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,46,"Finally, we report on a em- pirical evaluation of both workflows on the synthetic benchmark, comparing their effectiveness in restoring computational repro- ducibility across different classes of errors and validating whether successful repairs preserve the original analytical results."
7160,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,47,"This work establishes a controlled benchmark and evaluation framework for studying AI-assisted reproducibility repair, enabling systematic comparison between prompt-based and agent-based approaches. 2 Related Work Computational reproducibility is widely regarded as a necessary requirement for credible and cumulative science [ 14]; however, empirical evidence consistently shows that it remains difficult to achieve in practice."
7161,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,48,"Large-scale surveys and audits demonstrate that shared code and data are frequently missing, incomplete, or non-executable, even in fields with strong computational tradi- tions [1, 5, 10, 18]."
7162,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,49,"Similar findings appear outside social science: attempts to computationally reproduce published meta-analytic results often fail despite nominal artifact availability, underscoring that transparency alone is insufficient [13]."
7163,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,50,"Collectively, this work highlights a significant gap between stated reproducibility norms and empirical reality."
7164,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,51,"To address these challenges, research has focused on stabiliz- ing computational environments and preserving execution context."
7165,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,52,"Containerization and environment encapsulation have become stan- dard approaches for mitigating dependency and configuration drift, particularly in R-based workflows [3]."
7166,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,53,"Complementary tools empha- size provenance capture and packaging, bundling scripts, data, and dependencies into self-contained artifacts that can be re-executed elsewhere [4]."
7167,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,54,"Recently, LLMs have emerged as potential tools for reproducing non-executable computational workflows after publication."
7168,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,55,Bench- marks in code generation and program understanding show that modern LLMs can synthesize functional code from natural language specifications [8].
7169,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,56,"Dedicated studies of debugging and code repair demonstrate that LLMs can fix non-trivial defects, although perfor- mance remains imperfect and sensitive to task structure [16, 21]."
7170,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,57,"Automating Computational Reproducibility in Social Science WWW Companion ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Dubai, United Arab Emirates Agent-based approaches further improve repair capability by struc- turing interaction around execution feedback and iterative reason- ing [24]."
7171,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,58,Several recent benchmarks evaluate LLMs and agents directly on scientific reproducibility and replication tasks.
7172,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,59,"CORE-Bench frames computational reproduction as an interactive agent task requiring execution, inspection, and output validation across difficulty levels [19]."
7173,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,60,"PaperBench evaluates end-to-end reproduction of machine learning research from paper descriptions, revealing sharp perfor- mance drops as executable structure is removed [20]."
7174,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,61,"In the social sciences, REPRO-Bench frames reproducibility assessment itself as a challenging agentic task [11]."
7175,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,62,"Taken together, prior work motivates a focused comparison between prompt-based and agent-based approaches for repairing non-executable but partially available computational social science artifacts."
7176,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,63,"Existing benchmarks either emphasize full replication from minimal structure or rely on idealized artifacts, leaving open questions about realistic post-publication repair. 3 Methodology We conduct controlled experiments to evaluate whether LLMs, specifically prompt-based and agent-based approaches, can restore non-executable research code and aid in achieving computational reproducibility."
7177,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,64,"To this end, we constructed a controlled replication study."
7178,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,65,"Our methodology operationalizes the research questions posed in Section 1 through a new synthetic benchmark, as well as by systematically varying the models and harnesses used, er- ror complexity, and contextual information to assess the ability of LLMs to repair non-executable research code under controlled con- ditions."
7179,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,66,"We begin by describing the synthetic benchmark; next, we introduce the prompt-based and agent-based workflows, followed by a description of the validation steps taken to ensure that the AI- driven repair attempts were indeed successful."
7180,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,67,Figure 1 illustrates our methodological design. 3.1 Synthetic Benchmark Creation We created our synthetic benchmark dataset in a structured process.
7181,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,68,"First, we curated a set of fully computational reproducible publi- cations as a ground truth dataset."
7182,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,69,"Then, we generated synthetic errors and compiled them into bundles of synthetic test cases as non-reproducible variants to our ground truth publications."
7183,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,70,"To curate the set of fully computational reproducible publica- tions, we defined the following three selection criteria for candidate papers: 1) a paper must be openly accessible, 2) all necessary code and data must be equally accessible, 3) and executing the code to- gether with the provided data must reproduce the original results reported in the corresponding publication."
7184,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,71,"To verify reproducibility, we followed the workflow described by Saju et al. [17]."
7185,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,72,The compu- tational aspects of reproducibility testing was done in Rocker[3] (rocker/r-ver:4.4.1) Docker environments.
7186,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,73,Each container was allo- cated 8 GB of RAM and 8 CPU cores.
7187,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,74,"With these criteria in place, we evaluated the StatCodeSearch subset of the GenCodeSearchNet dataset [8] and identified five papers that satisfied all criteria."
7188,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,75,"To generate the synthetic test cases, we started by creating and injecting individual errors into copies of the code appendices of our ground truth dataset."
7189,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,76,"To best mimic real-world conditions, we have generated our synthetic errors based on what large-scale studies have shown to be the most common reasons why computational reproducibility fails [ 7, 17, 22]."
7190,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,77,"They include problems such as missing packages, incorrect file paths, missing objects or functions, shared library loading issues, package installation failures, and file read error related issues."
7191,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,78,"To structure this we organized the injected errors into three categories that capture two main factors: first, the diversity of potential issues encountered during a reproduction attempt; and second, the difficulty of achieving a successful re-run of the computations."
7192,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,79,The three error categories are as follows: • Category A:Errors that affect execution without altering the analytical structure of the code.
7193,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,80,"Examples include wrong file paths, missing packages or simple typos in the code."
7194,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,81,"This category encompasses errors that are potentially easy to fix but require some knowledge of the required packages as well as insight into the file system of the execution environment. • Category B:Errors that require more nuanced, code-level fixes and reasoning about the analysis."
7195,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,82,"Examples include in- correct or outdated packages, several syntax errors, missing variables or small missing parts of the code."
7196,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,83,"This category of errors also include one or more Category A errors in ad- dition to new issues, creating more complex problems that are more difficult to resolve than isolated Category A errors. • Category C:Errors that are structural and involve incom- plete or missing analytical logic."
7197,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,84,"Examples include missing functions, incomplete code blocks, or combinations of errors - such as path issues together with missing variables or syn- tax errors that affect multiple files simultaneously."
7198,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,85,"Category C also includes multiple Category A and B errors, captur- ing the diversity and complexity of issues that require deep understanding of the intended computations to reproduce successfully."
7199,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,86,Figure 2a provides a graphic overview of the synthetic error cate- gories .
7200,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,87,"In real-world settings, researchers are typically faced with a com- bination of errors preventing computational reproducibility [5, 18]."
7201,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,88,"To mimic these combinatorial characteristics in our benchmark, we merged multiple errors — including combinations across cat- egories — into bundles of realistic synthetic test cases."
7202,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,89,Each test case contains a single or set of multiple synthetic injected errors.
7203,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,90,"Across all five papers, this resulted in a total of 130 synthetic test cases in our benchmark."
7204,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,91,"Figure 2b illustrates the structure of an individual synthetic test case consisting of the non-executable code with multiple synthetic errors, utility functions, data, as well as a Markdown representation of the publication the code belongs to."
7205,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,92,"The different injected error types in the synthetic test cases of the reproducibility benchmark, enable a controlled analysis of how different categories of errors affect automated repair success (RQ3). 3.2 Prompt-based Repair Workflow In the first experiment, we evaluated a prompt-based repair pipeline in which large language models were used with structured prompts of varying contextual detail to iteratively detect and correct errors in test cases of our benchmark."
7206,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,93,Docker containers were used to execute code and record the logs for the experiments.
7207,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,94,"We used the Docker environment and system configuration described in WWW Companion ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Dubai, United Arab Emirates Syed Mehtab Hussain Shah, Frank Hopfgartner, and Arnim Bleier Diversity Difficulty Category A (Execution Errors) Category B (Contextual Fixes) Category C (Structural Errors) (a) Categories of errors P paper.md (Context) D data.csv (Input) </> script.R (Injected Errors) { } utils.R (Supporting Scripts) (b) Sample Structure Figure 2:Overview of the synthetic reproducibility benchmark."
7208,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,95,"(a) Classification of error types plotted against error diversity and repair dif- ficulty, ranging from simple execution errors (Category A) to complex structural logic gaps (Category C).(b)The structural organization of a single synthetic test case, containing the original publication as context, input data, support scripts, and the analysis script with multiple injected errors."
7209,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,96,Section 3.1 ensuring consistency and comparability across exper- iments.
7210,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,97,"When execution failed, the failing script and associated error logs were collected and used to construct a prompt for the selected model."
7211,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,98,"For each execution–repair loop - one cycle in which model proposes updates to the script, which is then executed to check for errors — a fresh container was instantiated to ensure a consistent runtime environment."
7212,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,99,All runs were executed in isolated containers with fixed environments; stochasticity arises only from model inference and is reflected in aggregate success rates.
7213,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,100,"Every run produced a standardized set of artifacts, including raw con- sole logs, structured metadata summarizing the run, and the final state of the repaired working directory."
7214,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,101,This uniform setup allowed results from different workflows to be compared directly.
7215,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,102,"We evaluated three models, GPT-4o (release 2024-06-08), Gem- ini 2.5 Pro (release preview-06-05), and Qwen3-Coder-480B-A35B using the same repair loop to ensure comparability."
7216,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,103,"Furthermore, prompts were generated at three levels of contextual richness."
7217,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,104,"Based on early trials on a small set of tasks, we gradually adjusted the prompt templates to ensure that the repair process worked reliably from start to finish and that the models clearly understood what they were asked to do."
7218,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,105,"This resulted in three well-defined prompt versions that shared the same core instructions but differed in how much supporting information they included. • Minimal prompt:Included the script, the log-file from the previous run, and a request to fix any existing issues. • Medium prompt:Included the minimal prompt plus the text of the publication in Markdown giving the model access to the analysis as described in the respective papers. • Full prompt:Included the medium prompt plus all support- ing scripts for the respective paper, and detailed instructions on how to perform the repair task."
7219,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,106,"For each attempt, the model was requested to return an updated version of the script, which was then re-executed in the same con- tainer."
7220,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,107,"If execution failed again, the new error output was appended to the prompt and the process repeated, up to a maximum of five iterations."
7221,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,108,A run was considered successful only if the script com- pleted without errors and reproduced the original ground truth outputs.
7222,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,109,A detailed discussion of this validation is done in Sec- tion 3.4.
7223,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,110,"Across all 130 samples described in Section 3.1, all three models and three prompt types were evaluated, resulting in 1,170 unique repair runs."
7224,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,111,"By varying prompt context while holding ex- ecution conditions constant, this workflow allows us to examine both the overall effectiveness of prompt-based repair (RQ1) and the role of contextual information in addressing analytically complex errors (RQ4)."
7225,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,112,"The templates for the prompts Minimal, Medium, and Full are provided in Appendix B. 3.3 Agent-based Repair Workflow The second experiment evaluated an agentic repair approach in which AI agents operated directly inside the containerized envi- ronment."
7226,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,113,"This workflow reused the same set of non-executable study samples, however, instead of our custom prompts, we em- ployed off-the-shelf coding agents that have access to the execu- tion environment."
7227,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,114,"These agents could inspect files, modify code, and iteratively re-run analyses."
7228,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,115,"To evaluate the agent-based re- pair workflow, we focused on a single model, Qwen3-Coder."
7229,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,116,"We selected Qwen3-Coder-480B-A35B due to its strong performance on real-world coding benchmarks, particularly SWE-bench1, which evaluates a model’s ability to resolve practical coding tasks."
7230,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,117,We embedded the command-line interfaces for the OpenCode2 and Claude Code 3 agents directly into the Docker image.
7231,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,118,Both agents were configured to use Qwen3-Coder-480B-A35B as their underlying language model via OpenRouter4.
7232,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,119,"By fixing the under- lying language model, this setup ensures that observed differences in performance — both between prompt-based and agent-based ap- proaches — can be attributed to differences in workflow and control strategy, such as how they manage iterations and tool use, instead of model choice."
7233,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,120,"For each test case, we launched a fresh container with the sample mounted as the working directory and executed the selected agent in non-interactive mode using the prompt shown in Appendix C."
7234,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,121,The ground-truth outputs were mounted separately in the container to enable a final reproducibility check.
7235,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,122,"During execution, we manually monitored the agents’ live logs to verify their behavior; in all runs, the agents did not access ground-truth outputs before completing the repair process."
7236,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,123,"The agent was free to explore the workspace, understand the paper, edit files, and re-run the R scripts."
7237,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,124,This process repeated until the script succeeded or a maximum time limit of 20 minutes was reached.
7238,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,125,All agent runs used again the Docker environment and system configuration de- scribed in Section 3.1.
7239,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,126,"This agent-based workflow is designed to evaluate whether direct interaction with the execution environment provides practical advantages over prompt-based LLM workflows when repairing complex reproducibility failures (RQ2). 1https://www.swebench.com/ 2https://opencode.ai 3https://code.claude.com 4https://openrouter.ai/ Automating Computational Reproducibility in Social Science WWW Companion ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Dubai, United Arab Emirates 3.4 Validation After each repair attempt, whether conducted via the prompt-based or an agent-based workflow, the output of the repaired script was automatically compared against the ground truth dataset of the orig- inal study’s successful computational outputs and the markdown of the publication."
7240,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,127,"Based on the comparison results, a classifica- tion label Reproduced, or Not Reproduced was assigned to that run."
7241,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,128,"Here,Reproducedmeans the script ran to completion and produced outputs that matched the stored ground truth."
7242,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,129,Whereas Not Reproducedmeans the script either failed to run or outputs differed from the ground truth.
7243,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,130,"This validation is important because, as noted by Wysocka et al . [23], a model may appear to solve a problem and write code that runs without errors, yet still produce analytically incorrect outputs. 3.5 Analysis Both workflows produced structured metadata for every repair attempt, including the sample identifier, error name, error category, model or agent used, number of attempts, execution time, and final reproduction outcome. 4 Results We evaluated performance using the same metrics across workflows, focusing on reproduction success rates broken down by error cate- gory, prompt type, model or agent used, and reproducibility status as determined by output validation."
7244,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,131,"Results were then aggregated by workflow, model or agent, error category, and reproducibility status to assess whether successful repairs preserved the original analytical intent."
7245,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,132,"The results are reported with reference to the research questions outlined in Section 1, focusing on differences be- tween workflows (RQ1–RQ2), sensitivity to error complexity (RQ3), and the influence of contextual information (RQ4)."
7246,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,133,"We begin by examining how the prompt-based repair workflow performs across the three models and varying error categories, by considering both the type of error and the richness of the prompt context. 4.1 Results from Prompt-based Workflow By examining success rates across error categories and prompt types (Figure 3), we can see that each model handles reproducibility challenges in a distinct way, with some models performing better on certain types of errors or prompt conditions than others."
7247,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,134,Gemini 2.5 Pro.Gemini 2.5 Pro consistently leads across nearly all conditions.
7248,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,135,"For minimal prompt, it already achieves solid per- formance on Category A (71.9%) and (78.7%) on Category B errors, and maintains relatively strong outcomes on Category C errors (59.2%)."
7249,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,136,"Interestingly, performance is not strictly monotonic with prompt context: while medium prompt improves some scores in Category C problems, other error types see a slight drop, consistent with recent evidence that additional not required context alone can degrade LLM performance even when the provided context is accurate [9, 25]."
7250,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,137,"Full prompt generally restores and enhances performance best, particularly for errors where restoring analytical logic is required, with success rates reaching 73.5% for Category C errors."
7251,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,138,Figure 3:Prompt-based LLM Repair Workflow.
7252,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,139,"Success rates (%) of GPT- 4o, Gemini 2.5 Pro, and Qwen3-Coder across error categories (y-axis) and prompt types (x-axis)."
7253,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,140,"Each prompt level shows a grouped bar chart of model performance for that error–prompt combination, illustrating how error complexity and contextual information affect automated reproducibility."
7254,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,141,GPT-4o.The results for GPT-4o show that success was highly de- pendent on prompt richness.
7255,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,142,"Under minimal prompt, the model struggles with Category C errors, achieving only 42.9% success."
7256,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,143,"As context increases, however, performance improves significantly."
7257,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,144,"Medium prompt boosts success rates across all complexities and full prompt pushes Category C errors up to 71.4%, nearly matching Gemini 2.5 Pro."
7258,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,145,This pattern illustrates that GPT-4o is a strong model but one that requires sufficient context to reach its potential.
7259,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,146,"Without that context, it tends to underperform, especially on tasks that demand analytical problem solving and logic building."
7260,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,147,Qwen3-Coder.Qwen3-Coder presents a more conservative profile.
7261,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,148,"Category A errors are handled reliably 52.9%, even with minimal prompt, suggesting a solid baseline for straightforward fixes."
7262,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,149,"How- ever, performance drops sharply as complexity rises: Category B errors only reach around 46.8%–55.3%, and Category C errors suc- cess rate resulted at 32.7%–54.2%."
7263,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,150,Qwen3-Coder also seemed to improve with more context and information especially in Category C tasks.
7264,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,151,"These patterns highlight that GPT-4o has strong code repair ca- pabilities when provided in with sufficient context, while Gemini 2.5 Pro has robust capabilities even with sparse prompts."
7265,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,152,Qwen3- Coder offers some utility on simpler errors but has clear limits on complex cases.
7266,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,153,"The findings also reveal that LLMs are capable of meaningfully repairing erroneous research code and restoring functionality in a substantial portion of real-world cases, but their effectiveness depends heavily on the nature of the error, the struc- ture and clarity of the original research workflow and the amount and type of context that is provided to the model [ 20]."
7267,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,154,"Overall, these findings provide initial answers to RQ1 and RQ4, showing that while prompt-based workflows can restore reproducibility in a substantial share of cases, their effectiveness depends strongly on both error complexity and the availability of relevant contextual information."
7268,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,155,"WWW Companion ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Dubai, United Arab Emirates Syed Mehtab Hussain Shah, Frank Hopfgartner, and Arnim Bleier Figure 4:Qwen3-Coder Performance in Agent-based and Prompt- based Workflow.Percentage of successfully reproduced cases using Qwen3-Coder across error categories."
7269,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,156,"Bars show agent-based workflow per- formance with OpenCode and Claude Code, while dashed horizontal lines indicate for comparison the success rates of the prompt-based workflow using Qwen3-Coder with the full-context prompt. 4.2 Results from the Agent-based Workflow The following section presents the outcomes of the agent-based re- pair workflow."
7270,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,157,We evaluate how each agent performed in restoring non-executable scripts and reproducing the original study results across the different error categories.
7271,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,158,OpenCode: Figure 4 shows the results for Qwen3-Coder combined with the OpenCode agent.
7272,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,159,"It illustrates the success rates across error categories (Category A, Category B, Category C)."
7273,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,160,OpenCode agent was able to successfully repair a majority of scripts across all categories.
7274,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,161,"For Category A errors, 81.5% of the scripts were fully repaired and produced results identical to the original study."
7275,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,162,"Category B errors, which included missing libraries or small sec- tions of code, were successfully repaired in 76.9% of cases."
7276,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,163,"Even the complex errors (Category C), which involved reconstructing missing logic or complex interactions across multiple parts of the code, were correctly fixed in 69.2% of the scripts."
7277,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,164,OpenCode agent demonstrated strong capabilities in systematically identifying and resolving errors while restoring the original analytical outcomes and making the studies reproducible.
7278,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,165,Claude Code: As shown in figure 4 the Claude Code agent ex- hibited even higher repair performance compared to OpenCode.
7279,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,166,"Category A errors were fully resolved in 96.3% of scripts, restoring the intended results almost universally."
7280,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,167,"For Category B errors, 91.7% of scripts were repaired successfully, while even the most complex errors (Category C) were correctly fixed in 82.1% of cases."
7281,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,168,"These re- sults show that Claude Code was highly effective in handling more complex and logic-intensive errors, systematically identifying the causes of failure and generating corrected scripts that matched the ground truth outputs."
7282,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,169,"These results directly address RQ2, indicating that agent-based workflows consistently outperform prompt-based approaches, particularly for errors requiring multi-step reasoning and interaction with the execution environment."
7283,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,170,Figure 5:Improvement of Agent-based Workflows over Prompt-based.
7284,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,171,Absolute improvement in reproducibility success rates achieved by agent- based workflows relative to the prompt-based results using Qwen3-Coder.
7285,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,172,"Bars show the difference in percentage points, meaning the absolute increase in success rates for each agent (OpenCode and Claude Code) compared to the prompt-based workflow. 4.3 Prompt-based vs Agent-based Workflows To better understand how the prompt-based workflow performs in comparison to the agent-based workflow, we compared success rates using the same model i.e., Qwen3-Coder with OpenCode and Claude agents."
7286,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,173,Figure 3 shows the success rate on Qwen3-Coder for different error categories in the prompt-based workflow.
7287,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,174,"It can be observed that Qwen3-Coder performed consistently best with full prompt type, therefore, we focus on comparing the full-prompt results with the agent-based workflow."
7288,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,175,"Prompt-based workflow: In the prompt-based workflow, Qwen3- Coder showed moderate performance across errors."
7289,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,176,"For Category A errors, success rates were consistent at 52.9%."
7290,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,177,"Category B errors achieved 55.3% with the full context prompt, and Category C errors which were the most challenging, peaked at 54.2% under the full context prompt type, where the model had access to all scripts, the original paper and detailed instructions (see Figure 4)."
7291,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,178,"Agent-based workflow: When we used the same Qwen3-Coder model within agent-based workflows, success improved notably."
7292,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,179,"Using the OpenCode agent, Category A errors were reproduced 81.5% of the time, Category B errors 76.9% and Category C errors 69.2% (fig 4)."
7293,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,180,"Similarly, with the Claude agent, performance was even higher, with 96.3% of success in Category A errors, Category B errors at 91.7% and Category C errors reaching 82.1% (see Figure 4)."
7294,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,181,"To highlight the specific contribution of the agent-based work- flow, we calculated the net performance gain of each agent relative to the standalone prompt-based workflow using the same model (Qwen3-coder) with full-context prompts, as illustrated in Figure 5."
7295,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,182,"For the simplest errors (Category A), the OpenCode agent improved success rates by 28.6 percentage points, while the Claude Code agent delivered an even larger boost of 43.4 points."
7296,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,183,"For intermedi- ate errors (Category B), gains were 21.6 points with OpenCode and 36.4 points with Claude."
7297,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,184,"Even on the most complex structural errors (Category C), agent-based workflows continued to outperform the prompt-based workflow, with 15.0 points gained using OpenCode and 27.9 points with Claude."
7298,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,185,"Automating Computational Reproducibility in Social Science WWW Companion ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Dubai, United Arab Emirates These results demonstrate that the agent-based workflow consis- tently outperforms the isolated prompt-based API approach."
7299,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,186,"Agent- based workflow allows models to handle more complex cases ef- fectively, likely due to the agents’ ability to actively explore the workspace, analyze error logs, iteratively modify scripts, and re-run analyses until a correct solution is found."
7300,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,187,"In contrast, prompt-based workflows are limited and cannot interact with or adapt to the workspace, which constrains their ability to resolve more complex situations that involve multiple errors at the same time."
7301,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,188,"The com- parison highlights that the observed performance gap between workflows is not solely model-dependent but is equally driven by differences in interaction and control afforded by agent-based execution, reinforcing the comparative claims posed in RQ2. 5 Conclusion and Future Work In this paper we reported on work in progress exploring the poten- tial of large language models and agent-based approaches to support computational reproducibility in the social sciences."
7302,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,189,"Using a con- trolled synthetic benchmark of R-based studies with systematically injected failures, we evaluated two automated repair workflows, a prompt-based approach and an agent-based approach, under iden- tical execution and validation conditions."
7303,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,190,Our findings offer clear answers to the research questions posed at the outset of this study.
7304,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,191,"Regarding RQ1 (extent of automated repair) and RQ3 (impact of error complexity), our initial results suggest that prompt-based workflows can successfully repair and reproduce a non-trivial share of broken analyses, particularly for execution-level and moderately complex errors."
7305,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,192,"However, their effectiveness is strongly conditioned on the availability and structure of contextual information, and per- formance degrades substantially when errors require reconstruct- ing missing analytical logic (Category C)."
7306,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,193,"Concerning RQ4 (influ- ence of contextual information), we found that the effectiveness of prompt-based repair is strongly conditioned on the availability and structure of context."
7307,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,194,"Providing the full text of the publication and supplementary scripts significantly improved success rates for complex failures, whereas minimal context was often insufficient for logic-heavy repairs."
7308,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,195,"This confirms that while LLMs can reduce manual debugging effort, they remain highly sensitive to prompt design and context selection."
7309,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,196,"Finally, addressing RQ2 (comparison of workflows), our analysis shows that agent-based workflows con- sistently outperform prompt-based LLM approaches across all error categories, with particularly strong gains for complex, multi-step failures."
7310,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,197,"By allowing models to interact directly with the execution environment—inspecting files, iteratively modifying code, and re- running analyses—agentic systems appear better suited to handling the practical realities of computational reproducibility."
7311,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,198,"This sug- gests that the added autonomy and environmental access provided by agents is a key factor in achieving higher reproduction success rates, rather than model capability alone."
7312,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,199,"As ongoing work, this report comes naturally with countless limi- tations, and several next steps to address them are planned."
7313,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,200,"First, we consider expanding the synthetic benchmark to include additional studies, a broader range of failure modes, and more diverse analyti- cal patterns common in computational social science."
7314,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,201,"Second, we plan to evaluate additional models and agent architectures to better understand how general these findings are across different AI sys- tems."
7315,28,C028_P1_pdf.txt,202,"Third, in future work will focus on systematically analyzing failure cases, particularly instances where automated workflows produce executable but incorrect results, to better characterize the limits of our approach. 6 Data Availability All data and code used in this study will be made publicly available."
