7734,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,0,Reactive Writers: How Co-Writing with AI Changes How We Engage with Ideas Advait Bhat Paul G.
7735,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,1,"Allen School of Computer Science, University of Washington Seattle, Washington, United States advaitmb@cs.washington.edu Marianne Aubin Le Quéré Center for Information Technology Policy, Princeton University Princeton, New Jersey, United States Mor Naaman Cornell Tech New York, New York, United States Maurice Jakesch Bauhaus University Weimar, Germany Abstract Emerging experimental evidence shows that writing with AI assis- tance can change both the views people express in writing and the opinions they hold afterwards."
7736,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,2,"Yet, we lack substantive understand- ing of procedural and behavioral changes in co-writing with AI that underlie the observed opinion-shaping power of AI writing tools."
7737,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,3,"We conducted a mixed-methods study, combining retrospective in- terviews with 19 participants about their AI co-writing experience with a quantitative analysis tracing engagement with ideas and opinions in 1,291 AI co-writing sessions."
7738,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,4,"Our analysis shows that engaging with the AI’s suggestions—reading them and deciding whether to accept them—becomes a central activity in the writing process, taking away from more traditional processes of ideation and language generation."
7739,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,5,"As writers often do not complete their own ideation before engaging with suggestions, the suggested ideas and opinions seeded directions that writers then elaborated on."
7740,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,6,"At the same time, writers did not notice the AI’s influence and felt in full control of their writing, as they—in principle—could always edit the final text."
7741,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,7,"We term this shiftReactive Writing: an evaluation- first, suggestion-led writing practice that departs substantially from conventional composing in the presence of AI assistance and is highly vulnerable to AI-induced biases and opinion shifts."
7742,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,8,"CCS Concepts •Human-centered computing → Empirical studies in col- laborative and social computing;Interaction design theory, concepts and paradigms;•Computing methodologies → Ar- tificial intelligence."
7743,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,9,"Keywords Co-writing, opinion change, risks of large language models, reactive writing ACM Reference Format: Advait Bhat, Marianne Aubin Le Quéré, Mor Naaman, and Maurice Jakesch. 2026."
7744,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,10,Reactive Writers: How Co-Writing with AI Changes How We Engage This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License.
7745,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,11,"CHI ’26, Barcelona, Spain ©2026 Copyright held by the owner/author(s)."
7746,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,12,ACM ISBN 979-8-4007-2278-3/2026/04 with Ideas.
7747,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,13,"InProceedings of the 2026 CHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems (CHI ’26), April 13–17, 2026, Barcelona, Spain.ACM, New York, NY, USA, 21 pages. https://doi.org/10.1145/3772318.3791529 1 Introduction AI writing assistants have rapidly become ubiquitous tools in ev- eryday communication, from email composition to creative writ- ing [58, 63, 121]."
7748,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,14,"Systems like GPT-based autocomplete, Gram- marly [58], and integrated assistants in Google Docs and Microsoft Word [56, 121, 132] promise to augment human writing by increas- ing speed, improving surface-level quality, and democratizing ac- cess to polished prose [23, 95]."
7749,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,15,"These tools generate contextually relevant suggestions that can help writers overcome blank-page paralysis, correct grammatical errors, and produce professional- sounding text [118, 133]."
7750,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,16,"As these systems become increasingly sophisticated and deeply embedded in our writing ecosystem, they are reshaping how millions of people express themselves in text."
7751,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,17,"However, emerging evidence reveals tradeoffs in this human-AI collaboration."
7752,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,18,"Recent studies demonstrate that writers using AI assistance may experience cognitive offloading that hinders idea generation [79, 123], produce more predictable language [ 5, 25], and report reduced satisfaction with the writing process despite improved productivity [42]."
7753,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,19,"More troublingly, AI writing assistants have been shown to systematically influence not just how people write, but what they express—biased language models can shift both the opinions writers convey in their text and their subsequent personal attitudes [69, 130], affect sentiment through positive bias in suggestion models [4, 66], and nudge participants to write about themselves using different lenses [104]."
7754,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,20,"These effects often occur without writers’ awareness [69], suggesting a form of influence that operates below conscious recognition."
7755,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,21,"While these outcome-level effects are concerning, understanding outcomes alone is insufficient: we need a descriptive account of how AI suggestions reshape the process and experience dimensions of writing."
7756,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,22,We lack detailed process-level accounts of how writers actually interact with opinionated suggestions during composition.
7757,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,23,"How do writers encounter, evaluate, and integrate AI suggestions moment-by-moment?"
7758,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,24,"When suggestions appear inline during com- position, how does this reshape the fundamental cognitive pro- cesses of ideation, memory retrieval, and expression [50, 78]?"
7759,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,25,"With- out understanding these interactions and their cumulative effects on the writing process, we cannot fully grasp how AI assistance arXiv:2603.10374v1 [cs.HC] 11 Mar 2026 CHI ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Barcelona, Spain Bhat et al. transforms human expression, or design systems that preserve writer agency."
7760,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,26,The impact of such systems extends far beyond individual writ- ing sessions.
7761,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,27,"If AI suggestions systematically influence which ideas writers express, they may subtly direct public discourse toward particular topics while marginalizing others."
7762,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,28,"As AI-assisted text proliferates across the web—from social media posts to profes- sional documents—the biases and priorities embedded in language models become entrenched in our collective information ecosys- tem [1, 12, 73]."
7763,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,29,"Understanding how AI shapes the writing process is therefore critical not just for individual writers, but also for ad- dressing broader concerns about human expression and democratic discourse."
7764,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,30,"To address this gap, we investigate two interrelated re- search questions: RQ1: How does an inline opinionated AI writing assistant reshape writers’ processes of ideation and composition?"
7765,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,31,RQ2: How does co-writing with AI affect the ideas that writers ultimately express?
7766,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,32,We employ a mixed-methods approach.
7767,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,33,We conducted 19 cued retrospective verbal protocol interviews in which participants re- flected on their writing process while viewing replays of their AI-assisted writing sessions.
7768,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,34,"We complement these with a quan- titative analysis of interaction logs from 1,291 writing sessions to examine systematic patterns in how AI suggestions propagate into final texts."
7769,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,35,"We examine these questions in the context of an opinionated, in- line AI writing assistant."
7770,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,36,"We focus on inline suggestions that appear directly at the cursor in tools like email clients and word processors, since this interface is the most common way that AI suggestions are incorporated into writing today [56, 121, 132]."
7771,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,37,"Within this in- terface, we deploy an inline assistant powered by an opinionated language model that surfaces biased text completions, in this case taking a definite stance on whether social media is good or bad for society."
7772,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,38,We deploy an opinionated model for three reasons.
7773,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,39,"First, while most deployed autocomplete systems claim to avoid overt political content, even ostensibly neutral models encode systematic political and moral biases, and any assistant must still choose which framings, examples, or arguments to present [48]."
7774,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,40,"The mechanisms by which writers encounter, evaluate, and integrate AI suggestions operate regardless of whether bias is explicit or implicit."
7775,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,41,"Second, we treat an explicitly opinionated assistant as an analytic extreme, which allows us to more clearly observe these mechanisms."
7776,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,42,This approach has been deployed successfully for studying confident versus uncertain AI [74] and culturally aligned versus misaligned AI [1].
7777,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,43,"Third, prior work suggests cognitive and persuasive im- pacts of using biased AI writing assistants [69, 130], and we seek to understand the processes underlying these effects."
7778,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,44,Our findings reveal a reorientation of the writing process that we termreactive writing: a mode of writing where writers shift from generating ideas through memory retrieval to evaluating and elaborating on AI-presented content.
7779,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,45,"Through detailed process accounts, we document how rapid inline suggestions interrupt ideation, redirecting writers’ attention toward agreement-based evaluation rather than independent idea generation."
7780,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,46,Writers main- tain a strong sense of agency and control even as they accept sug- gestions that introduce new topics and framings into their text.
7781,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,47,"Our quantitative analysis confirms that exposure to AI suggestions on specific topics strongly predicts their presence in final essays, with effects persisting even when controlling for directly accepted text."
7782,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,48,"Together, these findings illuminate how AI writing assistants can function as subtle but powerful algorithmic agenda-setting technologies [92, 122], shaping not just how we write, but funda- mentally what we think and write about. 2 Related Work We situate our work within research on technologies that support writing and emerging work on the persuasive effects of AI and algorithms. 2.1 Writing with Technological Assistance Classical theories of writing posit that writing begins with human ideation, where“the generating process derives its first memory probe from information about the topic and the intended audience. ”[50, 78]."
7783,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,49,"These models, such as Flower and Hayes [50]’s Cognitive Process Model of Writing, identify key internal writing processes includ- ing the proposer (generating ideas), translator (converting ideas to language), transcriber (producing written text), and evaluator (assessing outputs) as the building blocks of the writing process."
7784,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,50,"With the evolution of writing technologies, researchers have tried to augment the writing process using tools for improving writing quality or productivity."
7785,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,51,"HCI research on text entry has traditionally focused on efficiency [ 80], with systems providing word- or sentence-level suggestions based on likelihood distribu- tions [6, 15, 25, 125]."
7786,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,52,"These systems typically suggested one to three subsequent words [45, 51, 57, 105], with more recent systems providing multiple short reply suggestions [ 76] or single longer phrases [27]."
7787,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,53,"Extensive suggestions were generally avoided because they required time to read and select, and studies showed that fea- tures such as autocorrection and word prediction could negatively impact writing performance [10, 24, 40, 100]."
7788,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,54,"However, as computational capabilities have advanced, partic- ularly with large language models [18, 124, 131], there has been a shift toward viewing writing assistants as active partners rather than tools for writing faster [39, 84, 133]."
7789,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,55,"Such systems have been integrated and studied as tools supporting idea generation [14, 84, 118, 133], story writing [118, 133], text revision [38, 134], and cre- ative writing [32, 53]."
7790,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,56,"Recent work has mapped design spaces for intelligent writing assistants, identifying five pertinent aspects: the user, task, interaction, technology, and ecosystem [83]."
7791,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,57,"Reza et al. [109] distinguish different writing assistants based on their design approach, including tools that provide structured guidance, critical feedback, exploration, and active co-writing."
7792,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,58,"AI autocomplete tools, such as the one used in this study, fall under the category of active co-writing assistants."
7793,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,59,Research has also examined how users actually engage with AI writing assistance and how it may affect the process of writ- ing.
7794,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,60,"Bhat et al. [14] discuss how writers evaluate suggestions and integrate them into cognitive writing processes such as idea gen- eration, language generation, and transcription."
7795,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,61,Singh et al. [118] observe writers making “integrative leaps” when incorporating AI suggestions during creative story writing with multimodal systems.
7796,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,62,"Buschek et al. [25] identify nine behavioral patterns of interaction Reactive Writers: How Co-Writing with AI Changes How We Engage with Ideas CHI ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Barcelona, Spain with suggestions, ranging from complete avoidance to chaining multiple suggestions together."
7797,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,63,"This engagement can take differ- ent forms: writers can leverage AI assistants in ways that foster ideation and creativity, and potentially engender constructive learn- ing, or in ways that focus on rote and mindless tasks [123]."
7798,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,64,"Writers’ perceptions of such tools vary, with different writers being comfort- able delegating or maintaining ownership over different writing processes such as planning and ideation [109]."
7799,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,65,"Beyond affecting the writing process, AI assistance has also been shown to impact the products of writing."
7800,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,66,"AI suggestions have been shown to produce more predictable language and shorter sentences [5], increase the use of standard phrases [ 14, 25], and affect sentiment, with positive sentiment bias in suggestion models leading to more positive writing [4, 66]."
7801,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,67,"Additionally, AI assistants can nudge participants to write about themselves using different lenses [104]."
7802,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,68,Empirical work has revealed important trade-offs in AI-assisted writing.
7803,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,69,"Increased scaffolding with active co-writing tools such as autocomplete AI suggestions can indeed improve writing quality and productivity; however, this may come at the cost of writers’ satisfaction with the process [42]."
7804,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,70,"Recent work has suggested that making AI suggestions reflect participants’ own voice can improve feelings of control and agency [74]. 2.2 Influence, Algorithms, and AI Persuasion Social influence alters individuals’ thoughts, feelings, and actions through interactions with others [107]."
7805,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,71,"The impacts of such influ- ence range from collaboration to unethical behavior at the individ- ual level [8, 94], and from effects on markets, voting, and health behaviors at the societal level [28, 29, 82, 114]."
7806,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,72,"Sources of influence vary widely, including friends and family, experts, and internet celebrities [55, 91]."
7807,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,73,"In digital environments, influence increasingly comes from al- gorithmic systems."
7808,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,74,"Online, influence can come from brand pages and bots [49], as well as technical artifacts such as recommender systems and chatbots that steer user decisions [13, 35, 62, 85]."
7809,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,75,"Al- gorithmic influence depends on user perceptions and trust [62, 87], and people may rely more on algorithms in uncertain environ- ments [17]."
7810,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,76,"Growing public awareness of AI has led many to view algorithms as authoritative, which can foster over-reliance even when algorithms are wrong [3, 77, 87, 101, 102, 129]."
7811,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,77,"In the context of writing assistance, emerging work examines how algorithmic systems may influence writers through suggested content."
7812,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,78,"Text suggestions based on language models can inherit biases and dominant views from training corpora [11, 67, 81, 113], and the degree of alignment between writers’ perspectives and model biases may affect interaction patterns."
7813,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,79,"These writing assis- tants represent a specific instance of algorithmic influence, where the act of providing suggestions can shape writing content and di- rection [4]."
7814,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,80,"More broadly, the political implications of social media and recommender systems have received extensive scrutiny [135]."
7815,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,81,Technologies that shape public opinion are vulnerable to power- ful political and commercial interests [19].
7816,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,82,"As algorithms become constitutive features of public life, they can shift the political land- scape [2, 54] and contribute to polarization, even without being explicitly designed to change opinions [9, 22, 30]."
7817,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,83,"Today, with the advent of large language models such as GPT- style systems [ 21, 106], emerging work has found that humans may be particularly susceptible to AI persuasion."
7818,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,84,"These models can produce human-like text [71], giving rise to concerns over broad ethical and social risks [ 126, 127]."
7819,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,85,"New studies have found that chatbot-based interactions can perform remarkably well at human persuasion tasks, including through personalized arguments on socially contentious issues [36, 112]."
7820,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,86,"In the context of AI writing assistants, previous work has also documented that opinionated models can consistently change people’s minds across a range of social issues [69, 130]."
7821,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,87,"Prior work has shown that writing produced with biased AI suggestions reflects the AI’s positive or negative opinions [69] and framing [104], but we lack a granular understand- ing of how this process unfolds through the introduction of new ideas."
7822,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,88,The products of human-AI co-writing have significant down- stream impacts on our information ecosystem.
7823,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,89,"LLMs frequently mirror values in their training data, often aligning more with domi- nant U.S. values than those of other cultures [1, 73]."
7824,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,90,"Since future AI models are likely to be trained on these human-AI co-written texts, biases may become entrenched over time, causing value lock-in or even model collapse [12, 115]."
7825,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,91,Researchers have raised concerns that entrenching biases into predictive text models may produce effects where people feel differentially included [74].
7826,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,92,The convergence of writing assistance technologies with algo- rithmic influence and persuasion creates new concerns about how AI shapes both the cognitive processes of writing and the ideas writers ultimately express.
7827,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,93,Recent research reveals that interactions with AI writing assistants can lead writers to adopt cognitive short- cuts that undermine the learning benefits traditionally associated with writing.
7828,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,94,Umarova et al. [123] demonstrate that problematic writer-AI interactions can hinder idea generation.
7829,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,95,"Similarly, Kos- myna et al. [79] provide neurological evidence that LLM assistance creates “cognitive debt, ” with participants showing weaker neural connectivity patterns and reduced cognitive engagement compared to those writing without AI support."
7830,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,96,"These findings take on additional significance in light of Jakesch et al. [69]’s demonstration that opinionated language models can shift both what users write and their subsequent attitudes, often without users’ awareness of the model’s influence."
7831,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,97,"Together, these studies suggest that as writers increasingly rely on AI assistance, they may simultaneously become more cognitively passive and more susceptible to the biases embedded in AI suggestions."
7832,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,98,"How- ever, existing research has largely examined these phenomena sep- arately—studying either the cognitive impacts of AI assistance or its persuasive effects, but not how these processes interact during the act of writing itself. 3 Methods The current study investigates two interrelated questions: how an inline opinionated AI writing assistant reshapes the writer’spro- cessof ideation and composition (RQ1), and how the AI shifts the contentthat writers ultimately produce (RQ2)."
7833,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,99,"Since the first ques- tion concerns people’s lived experiences, while the second relates to data in the text output of a large-scale experiment, we chose a CHI ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Barcelona, Spain Bhat et al. mixed-methods design to answer these questions [37]."
7834,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,100,"In this meth- ods section, we first review the experimental platform (Section 3.1), then introduce our qualitative (Section 3.2) and quantitative methodologies (Section 3.3). 3.1 Experimental Platform To observe participants in the process of co-writing with AI, we needed an experimental platform that provided both fine-grained control over the writing interface and detailed logs of the inter- actions."
7835,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,101,We chose to work with the open-source AI-Cowriting Research Platform (AI-CRP) by Jakesch et al . [70].
7836,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,102,The platform combines a mock-up of a social media discussion page with a rich- text editor and an embedded inline opinionated AI writing assistant.
7837,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,103,"To provide a realistic social media context, the platform replicates the design of a Reddit discussion page."
7838,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,104,"After providing informed consent, participants were asked to compose an opinion statement on the platform expressing their perspective on the impact of social media on society."
7839,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,105,"The discussion topic of social media was chosen because it is an accessible topic of personal and societal relevance, and would allow us to compare our results to data collected in previous studies [69]."
7840,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,106,"We connected the experimental platform to a GPT-3-based language model in the backend [21], generating contextual suggestions that appeared after natural pauses in participants’ typing (typically 2 seconds)."
7841,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,107,"To make the influence of the AI model on people’s writing more salient so that the changes in participants’ writing and ideation processes could be discerned more clearly, we prompted the model to produce opinionated suggestions."
7842,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,108,"The platform captures comprehensive interaction logs including keystroke timing, cursor movements, suggestion appearances, and participant responses (accept, edit, or ignore). 3.2 Qualitative Interviews For the qualitative component, participants were recruited to use the AI-CRP tool [70] and then complete a follow-up interview about their experience."
7843,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,109,"We conducted cue-based retrospective interviews to understand writers’ cognitive decision-making processes during composition with an opinionated AI writing assistant [47, 52]."
7844,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,110,"We adopted a replay-based retrospective protocol inspired by Progres- sion Analysis [ 59, 103] where we aligned verbal protocols with time-stamped traces of the session so that interpretations could be anchored in observable events rather than unaided recall. 3.2.1 Participant Recruitment.We recruited US- and UK-based par- ticipants aged 18 and above from Prolific [99]."
7845,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,111,Participants booked a single session via Calendly that included the writing task im- mediately followed by the interview; the interview occurred right after task completion within the same scheduled slot.
7846,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,112,"We continued recruitment and data collection until we reached thematic satura- tion after 19 interviews—the point at which additional interviews yielded little to no new codes or themes relevant to our research questions [61, 64]."
7847,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,113,"Participants were compensated at$30per hour for their time, cov- ering both the writing task and interview components."
7848,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,114,"Following each interview, participants received a full debriefing that disclosed the AI assistant’s opinionated stance and the study’s research ob- jectives."
7849,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,115,All participants provided informed consent for both the writing task and interview recording before participation began.
7850,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,116,"The study protocols were approved by the university’s Institutional Review Board. 3.2.2 Interview Protocol and Qualitative Analysis.During their scheduled timeslot, participants were randomly assigned to write using an AI assistant with either a critical or positive stance towards social media, mirroring the treatment used in Jakesch et al. [70] (see Figure 1)."
7851,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,117,Participants received a link to the writing platform and completed the writing task in their assigned condition.
7852,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,118,"Immediately following task completion, participants joined a Zoom call for a 30–45 minute retrospective interview."
7853,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,119,"This immediate transition allowed us to conduct the interview while the writing experience remained vivid in participants’ memory, before any substantial memory decay could occur."
7854,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,120,We developed a custom replay tool to use during the interview that reconstructed the participants’ entire writing session from the interaction logs.
7855,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,121,"The tool visualized the evolving user text, cursor position, and AI suggestions as they appeared in the text editor, with accepted suggestions clearly highlighted."
7856,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,122,"The inter- viewer could play, pause, scrub through the timeline, and jump to specific moments in the session."
7857,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,123,"Using this replay as a visual cue provided a concrete anchor for participants’ retrospective accounts, helping them ground recollections in specific, observable moments rather than relying solely on unaided memory [ 26, 52, 88]."
7858,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,124,The semi-structured interview protocol was built around this replay of each participant’s writing experience with the AI tool.
7859,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,125,"We elicited retrospective verbal protocols using a semi-structured interview guide [44, 75] (Interview guide in appendix)."
7860,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,126,"We identified salient actions during the writing task (e.g., beginning to write, suggestions appearing, accepting/rejecting/editing suggestions)."
7861,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,127,"As the replay progressed, we paused at these actions and invited participants to narrate what they were thinking or doing in those specific moments."
7862,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,128,"For example, when a suggestion appeared, we asked: “What did this suggestion make you think?” and “What were you planning to write here?” Interviews were transcribed using OtterAI and transcripts were manually refined for accuracy [98]."
7863,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,129,"We coded the resulting verbal protocols against the interview video with the process replay to pre- serve the context of participants’ actions [47, 52]."
7864,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,130,We used thematic analysis inspired by grounded theory as a methodological starting point [20].
7865,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,131,"We began with an initial open-coding approach [34, 111] for the first 10 participants’ protocols to develop a preliminary codebook."
7866,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,132,The open coding was conducted by one researcher.
7867,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,133,"We iteratively collated codes into candidate themes, reviewed them against the full corpus and the video recordings, and wrote analytic memos throughout to document emerging patterns and formulate preliminary theories [20]."
7868,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,134,"After analyzing the initial 10 protocols, we conducted subsequent data collection and analysis simultane- ously, allowing findings from earlier interviews to inform later data collection. 3.3 Quantitative Topic Analysis The quantitative analysis examines the downstream effects of AI au- tocomplete suggestions on written content at scale."
7869,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,135,"Prior work has established that opinionated writing assistants affect the opinions people write about and hold after writing [69, 130], but it is unclear Reactive Writers: How Co-Writing with AI Changes How We Engage with Ideas CHI ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Barcelona, Spain Figure 1: Screenshot of the experimental writing platform showing AI suggestions. how this influence unfolds."
7870,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,136,"In the quantitative part of the study, we examine how the AI assistant influenced participants’ engagement with ideas and concepts through a topic-based analysis. 3.3.1 Dataset and Sample.The analysis complements the data collected in interviews with an extensive dataset of interaction logs of 1,506 co-writing sessions publicly shared by Jakesch et al. [69]."
7871,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,137,"Collected from a comparable online experiment, the interaction logs capture every user interaction with the text editor, including suggestions appearing, accepted suggestions, and text edits over time."
7872,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,138,"The dataset includes these detailed interaction logs, a unique participant identifier, and a label for the experimental condition."
7873,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,139,"We removed malformed data, incomplete process captures, and outliers with unusually high or low writing session times and pause times."
7874,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,140,"After this process, 1,291 participants remained in our sample, with 462 in the no-AI control group, 423 in the pro-social media treatment group, and 406 in the anti-social media treatment group."
7875,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,141,"For an in-depth analysis of participants’ interactions with the AI assistant, we needed an appropriately scoped unit of analysis."
7876,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,142,"To capture how AI suggestions influenced what participants wrote about, we needed to define our units of analysis carefully."
7877,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,143,"For treatment groups, we labeled ’writing bursts’—text that a user had written between two pauses—along with the AI suggestions that appeared after each pause with topics."
7878,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,144,"For the control group, we labeled sentences split from the essay column."
7879,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,145,"These became our units of analysis—text segments that we could then analyze at the participant × topic level, aggregating across the full session for outcome and exposure measures. 3.3.2 Topic Discovery.We treat topics as proxies for ideas: broad thematic areas or conceptual domains that represent new direc- tions of thought introduced into the writing."
7880,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,146,"To analyze how AI suggestions influenced the ideas expressed in participants’ writing, we developed a multi-step topic analysis pipeline."
7881,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,147,"This pipeline consists of two stages: first, topic discovery, where we identify a set of candidate topics that are neither too granular nor too coarse to label ideas, followed by topic assignment, where these topics are assigned to participant text."
7882,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,148,"The first step in this pipeline was topic discovery, where we needed to systematically identify relevant topics from participants’ text and AI suggestions."
7883,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,149,"In particular, we needed to be able to assign topics at a granular sub-sentence level, to reflect how participants adapted to new ideas throughout the writing process."
7884,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,150,"Prior work shows that short snippets are too sparse to sup- port coherent topics, and benefits from expanding them into richer pseudo-documents before modeling [16, 86]."
7885,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,151,"To do so, we employed an LLM-based method to expand out from the sentence-level."
7886,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,152,"For the topic discovery phase, we used 30% of the text data from partic- ipant writing and AI suggestions, and split them at the sentence- level."
7887,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,153,"For each sentence, we used gpt-3.5-turbo [97] to generate between 0 and 3 relevant topic titles and descriptions."
7888,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,154,We also gavegpt-3.5-turbothe previous sentence as context to help the model understand the surrounding text and assign the appropriate topic [21].
7889,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,155,"Through this process, we obtained several thousand total topics and descriptions, which we then clustered to derive our final topics."
7890,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,156,"To cluster the topic descriptions together, we employed hierar- chical agglomerative clustering into 40 initial clusters based on a BERTopicpipeline for topic clustering [ 60]."
7891,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,157,"The forty resulting au- tomatic clusters were then manually evaluated using a dendrogram visualization, and merged and split to ensure meaningful groupings that were internally consistent and distinct."
7892,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,158,"This process was con- ducted by two researchers, who grouped clusters separately and then discussed them until agreement was reached."
7893,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,159,"For example, we merged the two clusters “anxiety” and “depression” together into a single topic called “mental health, ” since they are closely related."
7894,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,160,"We manually reviewed a subset of the descriptions within each of the CHI ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Barcelona, Spain Bhat et al."
7895,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,161,Figure 2: Simplified overview of the topic classification pipeline.
7896,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,162,"Step 1 (topic discovery) shows how initial topics were identified from user-written and accepted text using gpt-3.5-turbo, with each topic receiving a description to en- able clustering."
7897,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,163,"Step 2 (topic assignment) shows how text was split into sub-sentences based on topic separation, with each sub-sentence assigned by gpt-3.5-turbo to one of the final topics derived from hierarchical clustering. resulting 20 topics to ensure they were accurate and contextually appropriate."
7898,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,164,We include the hierarchical agglomerative clustering visualization and the twenty final topics in the Appendix. 3.3.3 Topic assignment.The second step in our pipeline is the la- beling of “writing bursts” with the 20 topics for further analysis.
7899,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,165,We used gpt-4o [96] to (1) split the writing bursts into topic-based segments (including uncategorized segments) and (2) assign topics to each topic-based segment (including uncategorized segments).
7900,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,166,"We again used few-shot prompting to help the model understand the task, along with a set of examples of how we wanted the model to label the sentences and negative examples of how we did not want the model to label the segments."
7901,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,167,"We asked the model to split each writing burst into a set of sub-sentences, since one sentence could contain from zero (e.g., generic statements like “social media is good for society”) to multiple topics (e.g., “social media can lead to loneliness in teenagers and they could also face cyberbullying”)."
7902,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,168,"To reduce noise, we removed generic terms like “social media” and “benefits” that appeared frequently but carried little semantic speci- ficity from the essays."
7903,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,169,"As a validation to check the contents of the uncategorized segments, we manually labeled a subset of the uncategorized segments (𝑛= 166) as (1) unclear/incomplete text, (2) general evaluative statements without a specific topic, and (3) specific topics not covered in the 20 identified topics."
7904,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,170,"We found that, based on this manual labeling, any uncategorized content with meaningful topics that were not covered in the 20 identified topics is only 4.7% of the entire dataset."
7905,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,171,We decided to remove all uncate- gorized segments from the dataset.
7906,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,172,"During prompt refinement, we iteratively manually reviewed subsets of generated labels to ensure they were plausible and contextually appropriate. 3.3.4 Statistical Analysis.To complement the qualitative findings, we conducted statistical analyses to examine how AI assistance affected participants’ writing behavior and content."
7907,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,173,"First, we analyzed the time participants spent on their essay based on whether they saw AI suggestions."
7908,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,174,"For statistical analysis, we fitted a linear regression model (formula: time spent∼ treatment group) to evaluate the extent to which the AI treatment predicted participants’ time spent on the essay."
7909,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,175,"We also report descriptive statistics of the mean and median time spent on the essay, the percentage of text accepted, and the time suggestions were visible on screen."
7910,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,176,"Second, we fitted a linear model (formula: topic frequency in text∼topic frequency in suggestions) to predict relative topic fre- quency in participants’ final text based on the frequency of a topic in the AI’s suggestions to examine the correlation between topics in the predictions and in participants’ writing."
7911,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,177,"We also fitted a complementary model (formula: topic words in text ∼ number of suggestions related to topic) based on the number of words partici- pants wrote on a topic compared to how many related suggestions they saw, as well as a linear model (formula: self-written words on topic ∼ number of topic suggestions) predicting the amount of self-written text (as opposed to text accepted from the AI) based on the number of suggestions seen."
7912,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,178,"Finally, we fitted a logistic model (formula: any text written on topic ∼ any suggestion seen on topic) to estimate how receiving any suggestions about a topic affected the odds of writing on it. 4 Qualitative Results: The Reactive Writing Model In this section, we summarize the results from our qualitative in- terviews."
7913,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,179,"We followed a cue-based retrospective protocol, where participants were asked to reflect on their thoughts at the time of the experiment while they watched the behaviors they adopted."
7914,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,180,"Through our thematic analysis, we identified three stages that cap- ture the reshaping of the writing process with AI autocomplete suggestions:attention capture,agreement-governed inclusion, and post-hoc personalization."
7915,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,181,These three steps become the foundation for what we termreactive writing.
7916,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,182,"In thereactive writingmodel, the author is continually redirected to the AI suggestion, pushed to consider whether to accept or reject a suggestion, and finally completes a reconciliation process to adapt the AI text to their own views and experiences."
7917,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,183,"Notably, the AI suggestions influence the writing process regardless of whether the author accepts or agrees with the suggestion."
7918,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,184,"In this section, we describe our qualitative investigations of each of these steps in depth."
7919,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,185,"Reactive Writers: How Co-Writing with AI Changes How We Engage with Ideas CHI ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Barcelona, Spain 4.1 Attention Capture Kintsch [78] suggest that writing starts with an ideation phase that probes writers’ long-term memory."
7920,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,186,"In these models, the writing prompt serves as an initial catalyst to recall pertinent past experi- ences and knowledge [50]."
7921,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,187,"This ideation-first process starts with memory retrieval and idea generation, followed by composition, and thus assumes writers begin with internal resources and work outward toward expression."
7922,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,188,"In this section, we describe how partic- ipants reported that AI suggestions displace this ideation process and trigger an immediate shift to evaluation. 4.1.1 Inline automatic suggestions interrupted the ideation process."
7923,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,189,"As expected from classical writing models [50, 78], our participants appeared to go through a process of ideation at the very beginning of the writing exercise—they drew on personal anecdotes (P10 de- scribed making new friends during the pandemic), observations of close others (P6 recalled how their wife lost friends due to political fights on social media), and broader knowledge from media (P17 referenced reading about the psychological effects of social media)."
7924,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,190,Inline suggestions systematically interrupted participants’ inter- nal ideation process.
7925,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,191,"As AI suggestions began to appear on the text editor, participants shared that their attention immediately became focused on the content of the suggestions."
7926,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,192,"P7 described their initial ideation process, and the experience of watching inline suggestions appear: I was going to say something along the lines of social media being very helpful with people with particular interests."
7927,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,193,"You know, the way I use social media is to connect with people that have similar interests to me, and we can advance our knowledge about those topics."
7928,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,194,"So [. . . ] very specific things, broad philosophical debates, trying to get information about certain hobbies that we might have. [. . . ] And as I started typing, the AI started feeding a full set of this [text] that was along the lines of what I was thinking."
7929,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,195,"In this quote, P7 described how their complex, internal ideation process was redirected to the AI suggestions."
7930,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,196,"P6 felt these suggestions interrupted their train of thought, say- ing“Well, now I’m not thinking about what I’m writing."
7931,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,197,"I’m reading the sentence. ”Suggestions appeared after 1–2 seconds of pause in typing, and participants felt this interrupted their ideation process."
7932,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,198,"For example, P1 shared,“I was just trying to frame a sentence in my mind when I saw the suggestion. ”This speed often outpaced participants’ own ideation and sentence planning."
7933,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,199,"P4 explained, “[the AI] gave me the suggestion in one second, whereas it would have taken me time to think of something. ” 4.1.2 When AI suggestions appeared, participants immediately be- gan to evaluate them, which they attributed to the inline interface design and cognitive tradeoffs.Once a suggestion appeared, par- ticipants instinctively began to evaluate if they agreed with the suggestion."
7934,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,200,"P10 explained,“I was reading the suggestions that the AI provided and I was just thinking—does this agree with how I feel. ”Sim- ilarly, P8 noted,“I was just double-checking with myself if I agreed with it."
7935,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,201,"And it made sense. ” Since the suggestions were shown inline, participants found them hard to ignore."
7936,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,202,"For example, P8 got the impression that“I was just getting started, thinking about [the prompt]."
7937,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,203,"And then the suggestions just throw themselves at me. ”P4 and P6 felt that the inline nature of the text was disruptive to their usual writing process: “[The suggestions] made it more difficult for me; I like to write, but I don’t like to be hurried, rushed or have words thrown out there that I have to read and they distract me from my thought process."
7938,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,204,"I’m reading. ” – P4 “I would type, and when I’m typing, I stopped to think and compose my next thought."
7939,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,205,"And thenbingo, here comes a sentence."
7940,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,206,"Well, now I’m not thinking about what I’m writing."
7941,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,207,"I’m reading the sentence. ” – P6 P6 went so far as to“type so fast that [the AI assistant wouldn’t] throw ideas at me. ”Overall, participants felt that the inline for- mat encouraged and sometimes forced them to focus on the AI suggestions rather than their own writing."
7942,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,208,Participants also explained that evaluating AI suggestions re- quired less effort—recalling experiences and crafting arguments was more demanding than vetting pre-constructed sentences.
7943,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,209,"P4 stated,“It takes more effort for me to come up with it myself than to read it, decide if I agree with it, ”and P8 echoed,“the whole sentence was already laid out for me."
7944,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,210,"And I didn’t really have any issue with it. ”Participants explained that the speed of suggestions, and the difficulty of crafting their own sentences, compelled them to think more about evaluating the AI suggestions than producing their own writing."
7945,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,211,"In these ways, AI suggestions appear ideally suited to interrupt and skew our participants’ ideation process towards evaluating the AI suggestions. 4.2 Agreement-governed inclusion When participants evaluated an AI suggestion, they needed to de- cide whether to accept the text, or reject the text by requesting a new suggestion or typing something else instead."
7946,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,212,Our qualitative anal- ysis identified key reasons why writers choose to accept or reject AI-generated suggestions.
7947,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,213,"Accepting suggestions appeared to be driven by four primary factors: content agreement (alignment with existing beliefs and written text), form appreciation (admiration for polish and eloquence), effort economics (the ease of evaluation versus generation), and default positioning (treating suggestions as starting points to be modified)."
7948,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,214,"Participants appeared readily will- ing to accept suggestions they tangentially agreed with—potentially suggesting a default effect, where AI suggestions are seen as the most frictionless choice [43]."
7949,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,215,"Rejecting suggestions, conversely, was motivated by content disagreement, voice preservation concerns, originality preferences, or perceived disruption. 4.2.1 Main drivers for accepting and rejecting AI suggestions.Many participants thought about suggestions as template text that could be modified as needed, which appeared to lower their threshold for acceptance."
7950,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,216,"P10 expressed:“For me, suggestions are more like a default. ”Because these suggestions were automatically shown in the editor, some participants did not perceive an explicit choice to include or ignore suggestions, but rather thought of these sug- gestions as the default path forward in writing."
7951,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,217,"P14, who agreed with a suggestion, explained:“My thought process was if I agreed with it, I would leave it in. ”Conversely, P5, who disagreed, said:“I think I want to get rid of these suggested texts and to put my own CHI ’26, April 13–17, 2026, Barcelona, Spain Bhat et al. in [...] it is different to my opinion. ”In this way, the interface de- sign made accepting suggestions the path of least resistance, with opinion alignment often serving as sufficient justification to retain pre-populated AI suggestions."
7952,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,218,"In this vein, most participants recalled that their primary reason for accepting suggestions was broad agreement with the content of the suggestion."
7953,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,219,"P4 explained this common way of thinking:“I would read the suggestion, decide if I agreed with it, and if I did, I would accept it. ”Some participants simply accepted suggestions as long as they did not contradict their existing arguments or planned con- tent."
7954,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,220,P7 explained:“I don’t think they hurt any argument that I was making.
7955,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,221,"They just kind of didn’t contradict what I was going to say. ” Overall, participants tended to accept suggestions that matched their overall stance—or did not directly contradict their beliefs."
7956,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,222,"Participants also often accepted suggestions due to the credible, well-formed prose."
7957,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,223,"For example, P1 emphatically noted“the sen- tences were perfectly constructed!”P2 highlighted the AI’s efficient communication:“[The AI] was pretty efficient in what it was saying."
7958,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,224,"It was short, it was succinct, it got to the point. ”Participants praised the AI’s sentence construction regardless of the content or opinion in the suggestions."
7959,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,225,"P14 echoed this perspective, saying,“the writing is so superior with the assistant, whether it’s negative or positive, it’s very superior writing. ”This admiration for prose led some to ascribe expertise to the AI."
7960,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,226,"P1 explained:“From the vocabulary and how the sentences are framed it sounds like how someone who is learned or knowledgeable in the topic would write; somebody who has researched on it and someone who knows the effects of social media, that’s why I kinda started believing in it. ”Participants treated the AI’s profi- ciency in language not just as good writing, but as a signifier of authority and expertise (P6:“I think it came across fairly intelligent. ”) For many, the sophisticated language of suggestions appeared to be an important factor in accepting suggestions."
7961,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,227,"Participants seemed comfortable accepting suggestions they agreed (or did not disagree) with, often regardless of whether they reflected their precise thoughts, ideas, or voice."
7962,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,228,"As P7 noted:“they weren’t things that I would have written myself specifically, ”or P14: “there were things that came up that I do agree with, but I hadn’t actually thought of at the time that I was writing. ”P4 candidly ex- pressed:“I may not have framed it in the same way [...] but I like the way it’s written, so I accepted that suggestion. ”In these ways, complete alignment between the writer and the AI suggestions was not always necessary to accept suggestions."
7963,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,229,"Conversely, participants rejected suggestions when they did not cross the minimum threshold of reflecting their voice or experiences."
7964,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,230,"For instance, P7 rejected a suggestion,“this suggestion is fine, but I’d rather articulate in my own way what I want to say. ”Multiple other participants also rejected suggestions that did not reflect what they knew or felt, for example, P13 recalled“I don’t have any personal experience of that, so I don’t think it’s a fair comment for me to make. ”, while P9 simply stated“that was not the thing I experienced. ” P17, on the other hand, explained that the AI suggestion was not original enough:“when expressing opinions, I think of how it relates to my life, that’s what makes it original. ”They contrasted their own perspective with the AI suggestions,“[the AI] was giving a very piece-meal average view of social media. ” Some participants also rejected suggestions they felt were too opinionated or biased."
7965,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,231,"P13, for example, felt“the suggestion [...] was more negative than I wanted to be. ”P5 was particularly dubious of the suggestions: at various points they noted“I’m noticing how positive these suggestions seem to be [...] I know not to use those”, and “it made me feel that the writing suggestion prompt was sort of skewed in its agenda. ”Thus, some participants did try to maintain their own ideas or way of writing, despite the AI’s encroachment. 4.2.2 Participants maintained a sense of control and agency over their writing, even when accepting opinionated AI suggestions.Through- out the study, participants expressed strong confidence in their agency over the writing."
7966,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,232,"Participants felt in control as they were confident that they could reject, accept, or later modify suggestions at any time."
7967,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,233,"Some emphasized their power to reject: P14 stated,“If there was something that I didn’t agree with, I wouldn’t accept it. ” Others felt empowered by their ability to revise, as P2 expressed: “I didn’t have any pressure, I have my free will, I hope."
7968,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,234,I didn’t feel any pressure as I can always change it.
7969,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,235,"I wasn’t hindered by any of the responses and I did not feel I was forced to take any of them. [. . . ] I can see that I have deviated from my original neutral stance, but I was fine with it."
7970,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,236,"I always thought that if I disagreed with it, I could take it back. ” This sense of retained agency appeared crucial in participants’ comfort with accepting AI suggestions."
7971,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,237,"Participants perceived the suggestions as easy to change, in part due to the inline and editable interface."
7972,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,238,"Even P5, who disagreed with the AI’s positive stance, chose to accept a few AI suggestions, explaining“I was exploring how the suggested prompt worked, and thinking about how I would delete it. ”This retained sense of control may explain why partici- pants felt comfortable accepting suggestions from an opinionated AI assistant."
7973,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,239,"Despite this sense of control, multiple participants did acknowl- edge that accepting AI suggestions could lead to unintended shifts in content direction."
7974,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,240,"P4 was aligned with the AI’s negative stance, and said“I probably would’ve given a different reason why its harm- ful. ”For example, P15, who initially planned to write“more on the positives”about social media, ended up accepting critical sug- gestions because they“weren’t wrong”:“Ultimately, no matter how negative the suggestions were, they weren’t wrong!”After reviewing their process, P15 acknowledged:“The suggestions were geared to- wards fake news, mental health, harassment, all of which we know are real issues!”."
7975,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,241,These were topics that P15 had not initially planned to address.
7976,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,242,"Similarly, P1 reflected how“the suggestion kinda convinced me that the cons are more and my thoughts went in that direction, and I started thinking less about the pros. ”Thus, participants did write about substantially different content with the AI’s help — and some even noted they had changed their stance."
7977,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,243,These shifts in content occurred in spite of (or perhaps because of) participants’ sense of control over the suggestions.
7978,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,244,"When asked explicitly whether the AI had influenced their writing, P7 empha- sized“I don’t think [I was influenced]."
7979,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,245,"Because in the end I chose not to use some of its suggestions. ”Yet P2’s reflection captures a contra- diction: although they recognize their writing deviated from their original stance, they are comfortable with this change since they retained editorial control to accept or reject suggestions."
7980,29,C029_S1_pdf.txt,246,This broad sense of control may have concealed the AI’s true influence on par- ticipant writing: the biased selection of ideas.
7981,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,0,"AI Disclosure with DAISY Yoana Ahmetoglu UCL Interaction Centre London, United Kingdom yoana.ahmetoglu@ucl.ac.uk Marios Constantinides∗ CYENS Centre of Excellence Nicosia, Cyprus marios.constantinides@cyens.org.cy Anna L."
7982,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,1,"Cox UCL Interaction Centre London, United Kingdom anna.cox@ucl.ac.uk Figure 1: Overview of the design and user study of DAISY, a form-based tool for AI disclosure in academic writing, showing literature- and co-design–informed development (Phase A), a survey-based user study with authors (Phase B), and key findings."
7983,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,2,"Abstract The use of AI tools in research is becoming routine, alongside growing consensus that such use should be transparently disclosed."
7984,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,3,"However, AI disclosure statements remain rare and inconsistent, with policies offering limited guidance and authors facing social, cognitive, and emotional barriers when reporting AI use."
7985,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,4,"To ex- plore how structured disclosure shapes what authors report and how they experience disclosure, we present DAISY (Disclosure of AI-uSe in Your Research), a form-based tool for generating AI dis- closure statements."
7986,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,5,"DAISY was developed from literature-derived requirements and co-design (N=11), and deployed in a user study with authors (N=31)."
7987,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,6,"DAISY-supported disclosures met more com- pleteness criteria, offering clearer breakdowns of AI use across research and writing than unsupported disclosures."
7988,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,7,"Surprisingly, despite concerns about how transparently disclosed AI use might be perceived, the use of DAISY did not reduce authors’ comfort ∗Also affiliated with University of Cyprus, Cyprus and University College London, UK."
