7997,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,16,We discuss design implications and a research agenda for AI disclosure as a sociotechnical practice.
7998,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,17,CCS Concepts •Human-centered computing → Empirical studies in HCI; HCI design and evaluation methods.
7999,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,18,"Keywords Artificial Intelligence, AI disclosure, co-design, reporting tool ACM Reference Format: Yoana Ahmetoglu, Marios Constantinides, and Anna L."
8000,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,19,"InProceedings of CHIWORK ’26: Proceedings of the 5th Annual Symposium on Human-Computer Interaction for Work (CHIWORK ’26).ACM, New York, NY, USA, 23 pages. https://doi.org/just_accepted 1 Introduction A broad consensus has emerged in the scientific community that, when AI tools are incorporated into research, their use warrants disclosure [18, 31, 32]."
8001,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,20,"For example, authors are expected to report when AI tools have been used to generate research ideas, draft or revise text, analyze data, or support methodological decisions."
8002,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,21,"Such uses span a growing range of AI tools that are increasingly embedded in everyday research practice (e.g., large language models such as ChatGPT, code assistants like GitHub Copilot, and many others; for a review, see [49])."
8003,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,22,"Disclosure of use of these kinds of AI tools is typically provided via a dedicated disclosure statement placed in the acknowledgements section, or an equivalent venue- mandated location [ 5]."
8004,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,23,"Existing policies frame AI disclosure as arXiv:2604.02760v1 [cs.HC] 3 Apr 2026 CHIWORK ’26, June 22–25, 2026, Linz, Austria Ahmetoglu et al. supporting scientific norms of accountability and transparency by allowing others to assess how AI tools may have influenced the research and its reported claims [45]."
8005,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,24,"Despite broad agreement on the importance and purpose of AI disclosure in the ethics literature, AI disclosure statements remain largely absent in published research."
8006,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,25,"A recent bibliometric study of medical education journals found that only around 2.5% of articles included an AI-use disclosure statement [5], even though survey evidence suggests that over 80% of researchers use AI tools in at least some parts of their research and writing [36]."
8007,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,26,There may be several reasons for this gap.
8008,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,27,One possible reason is that disclosure can be challenging in practice.
8009,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,28,"Existing policies require authors to disclose AI use beyond language-only edits but offer limited guidance on how such disclosures should be formulated (e.g., see the ACM policy on authorship and generative AI use [6])."
8010,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,29,"Another reason is that disclosure often involves social and reputational con- siderations; recent evidence suggests that declaring AI assistance can negatively influence how authors’ competence and credibility are perceived [10, 44]."
8011,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,30,A third possible reason is that disclosure relies on authors’ ability to retrospectively (re)construct how AI tools were used throughout the research and writing process.
8012,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,31,"Prior work shows that such (re)construction is often unreliable in mixed human-AI tasks, with individuals misattributing ideas or underre- porting AI contributions [60]."
8013,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,32,"A structured disclosure format can reduce the effort involved in reporting AI use and make expectations clearer, which may help reduce underreporting."
8014,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,33,"By offering a shared set of categories for common forms of AI assistance, such formats reduce the need for authors to invent wording or guess how their disclosures will be interpreted [56]."
8015,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,34,"They may also help authors to reflect on where AI was used, helping to recall uses that might otherwise be omitted."
8016,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,35,"Prior work in adjacent domains, such as model cards for machine learning systems [39] and structured risk or impact reporting for AI technologies [9], suggests that structured and standardized formats can effectively support disclosure."
8017,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,36,"However, it remains unclear how these insights translate into the context of academic AI-use disclosure."
8018,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,37,"While proposals for AI disclosure frameworks [56] and online AI label generators (e.g., [1]) have begun to emerge, these efforts have largely focused on proposing what could be disclosed rather than on empirically examining how structured supports shape reporting practices or how authors experience the task of producing structured AI-use disclosures in practice."
8019,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,38,"To investigate the questions ofhow structuring the AI disclo- sure process shapes what authors report, andhow they experience the task of disclosure for academic manuscripts, we present DAISY (Disclosure of AI-uSe in Your Research), a digital AI disclosure form that guides authors through questions about their use of AI tools, and generates an AI disclosure statement for academic manuscripts (Figure 1)."
8020,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,39,"The tool was developed through elicitation of literature- based design requirements, and a co-design study with different academic stakeholders (N= 11) and deployed in a mixed-methods user study with authors (N= 31)."
8021,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,40,"DAISY produced longer and more complete disclosure statements, and participants preferred DAISY-generated statements (with the option to manually edit them) over statements written without DAISY."
8022,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,41,We also observed a disciplinary contrast.
8023,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,42,"Non-HCI academics expected easy-to-use disclosure support that helps them navigate policies, while HCI academics imagined more complex logging and reflective systems focused on transparency and fairness that exceeded the current needs of most other academics."
8024,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,43,"In so doing, we made three main contributions: (1) DAISY, a structured AI disclosure form that operationalises disclosure as an author-facing interaction (§3); (2) empirical evidence of how structured AI disclosure reshapes both reported content and author experience, and how aca- demics are currently using AI in their research practice (§4); (3) design implications and a research agenda for an ecology of AI disclosure tools that can serve diverse needs and disci- plinary expectations (§5). 2 Related Work We surveyed various lines of research that our work draws upon, and grouped them into three main areas:i)research on AI disclosure spanning ethics and policy scholarship (§2.1);ii)challenges on AI disclosure (§2.2); andiii)design of documentation and reporting artefacts (§2.3). 2.1 Policy and Ethics on Disclosing AI use in Academia We reviewed ethical analyses and publisher policies on AI-use disclosure in academia, which collectively define the goals and expectations of disclosure."
8025,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,44,We use this literature to surface a gap between normative guidance and the practical challenges authors face when constructing disclosure statements.
8026,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,45,A recent 2024 survey with 816 researchers found that 81% have started to use AI assistance with research activities in some ca- pacity [36].
8027,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,46,AI-assisted writing is also already appearing in pub- lishing processes.
8028,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,47,Liang et al. [35] found widespread evidence of LLM-modified text in peer reviews at major AI conferences.
8029,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,48,"Given such widespread adoption, it is increasingly accepted that AI-use in research must be transparent and responsibly reported."
8030,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,49,"Ethical analyses draw attention to the importance of AI-use disclosure for fairness, accountability, and scientific integrity."
8031,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,50,"For example, Resnik and Hosseini [45] argue that failing to disclose AI-use can distort the scientific record by masking who actually performed specific parts of the work."
8032,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,51,"Similarly, Cohen and Moher [15] note that inconsistencies in how authors report AI assistance make it difficult for editors, reviewers, and readers to assess the credibility of findings."
8033,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,52,"Related concerns around attribution and responsibility in academic work have also been examined within HCI, for example in studies of how credit is assigned in multi-author publications [20]."
8034,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,53,"At the same time, studies of academic writing and authorship practices suggest that norms of attribution and credit vary across disciplines and research communities [15, 20], implying that expec- tations around AI disclosure may likewise differ across contexts."
8035,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,54,"Similar concerns about transparency, attribution, and ownership of AI-generated contributions have also been raised more broadly across creative and knowledge work domains [23]."
8036,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,55,"One example is in journalism, where researchers have begun to examine practition- ers’ expectations and needs around communicating AI involvement in news production [55]."
8037,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,56,"This growing recognition is also visible AI Disclosure with DAISY CHIWORK ’26, June 22–25, 2026, Linz, Austria within the HCI community, where recent discussions have indi- cated worrying uncertainty about when AI involvement should be disclosed and what form such disclosures should take [19]."
8038,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,57,"In response to these concerns, publishers have begun to formalise expectations around AI disclosure."
8039,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,58,"The ACM authorship policy, for example, permits the use of AI tools to assist with research activities but requires authors to fully disclose such use in their manuscripts, recommending explicit statements in the acknowl- edgments section [ 6]."
8040,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,59,"Comparable policies are being developed across publishers which focus on calls for transparency [ 22, 50]."
8041,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,60,"However, existing policies leave substantial room for interpreta- tion and limited direction on how authors should construct such statements, what level of detail is appropriate, or how responsi- bility should be expressed."
8042,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,61,They tend to frame AI disclosure as a reporting requirement rather than a practically challenging and cognitively demanding task.
8043,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,62,"This overlooks the lived experience of constructing disclosure statements, including authors’ concerns about how their AI use is framed."
8044,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,63,"Prior work on responsible AI has cautioned against reducing complex ethical practices to checklist- based compliance [8, 34]."
8045,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,64,"For example, Constantinides et al. [16] argue that RAI guidelines should function as interpretive and re- flective instruments rather than signals of conformity."
8046,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,65,"Applying this lens to AI disclosure suggests that disclosure statements should not be treated as a tick-box requirement, a concern also reflected in critiques of the “transparency ideal” as insufficient when divorced from practice [4]. 2.2 Challenges of AI Disclosure Creating AI disclosure statements in manuscripts is itself a complex reporting task."
8047,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,66,"We discuss three types of AI disclosure challenges (i.e.,social,cognitive, andemotional) identified in prior HCI and re- lated interdisciplinary work."
8048,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,67,"While the salience of these challenges may vary depending on the purpose, level, and context of AI use, prior research consistently shows that uncertainty about how AI contributions should be interpreted, remembered, and evaluated can make disclosure difficult for authors [10, 12, 60]. 2.2.1 Social Challenges.A substantial body of work shows that declaring AI assistance can alter how one’s work and competence are judged by others."
8049,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,68,"Reif et al. [44] find that employees who use AI help are viewed as less competent, motivated, and hireable than those who rely on human assistance."
8050,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,69,"In academic settings, Brown et al. [10] report widespread concern that peers, supervisors, or insti- tutions may interpret AI use unfavourably, and that this anxiety is often amplified by inconsistent or ambiguous guidance."
8051,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,70,"Reviewers likewise express suspicion toward AI-assisted manuscripts, raising concerns about fraud and diminished expertise [26]."
8052,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,71,"More broadly, AI use has become entangled with moral stigma and perceptions of unfair advantage in knowledge work, with accusations of AI assis- tance functioning as a status-laden judgement about competence and legitimacy [47]."
8053,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,72,Such dynamics may lead individuals to fear being seen as less capable or less deserving of credit.
8054,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,73,"This concern aligns with attribution research showing that when a salient ex- ternal aid is present, observers tend to attribute outcomes to that aid rather than to the individual, systematically discounting the person’s effort and ability [33]. 2.2.2 Cognitive Challenges.Recent studies demonstrate that there are significant memory recall challenges when remembering and assessing AI contributions."
8055,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,74,"While some of the studies were con- ducted in general writing or creative tasks rather than academic contexts, they provide relevant insights into how people remem- ber and attribute AI contributions during human–AI collabora- tion."
8056,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,75,"For example, Zindulka et al. [60] conducted an experiment in which participants completed creative writing and idea-generation tasks either alone, with AI assistance, or with mixed human-AI tasks."
8057,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,76,"When tested one week later, participants showed substantial source-memory errors, often misattributing whether specific ideas or sentences had been written by themselves or by the AI, with the mixed human-AI condition producing the highest misattribution rates."
8058,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,77,"Jakesch, Hancock, and Naaman [29] show that people cannot reliably distinguish AI-generated self-presentations from human- written ones, and may be relying on intuitive but flawed heuristics that mislead their judgments."
8059,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,78,This difficulty extends to evaluating others’ use of AI.
8060,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,79,"Nelson et al. [40] show that students overesti- mate teachers’ ability to detect AI-generated work, misjudging both detectability and the associated integrity risks."
8061,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,80,"Skulmowski [ 48] suggested a theoretical account of why people misjudge their own contribution when assisted by AI, identifying two reasons: theAI placebo effect, where assistance makes tasks feel easier and leads users to overestimate their own ability, and theghostwriter effect, where AI contributions are psychologically backgrounded, leading users to downplay or underreport the role of AI in the final output. 2.2.3 Emotional Challenges.Disclosing AI use can itself be emo- tionally challenging."
8062,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,81,The emerging construct ofAI guiltcaptures the moral discomfort some users feel when relying on AI tools for tasks traditionally seen as requiring human effort [12].
8063,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,82,The guilt is compounded when disclosure is incentivised by policy but social norms or audience perceptions remain uncertain.
8064,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,83,"Indeed, authors who honestly disclose their AI use report shame or unease, reflect- ing a sense that honesty may be punished rather than rewarded [7]."
8065,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,84,"Among students, higher levels of AI guilt are associated with reduced willingness to both use AI for creative tasks and openly report that use [12]."
8066,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,85,"In classroom contexts, ambiguous norms inten- sify anxiety and embarrassment when deciding whether to declare AI assistance [2], and similar moral discomfort appears in other sensitive AI use settings [37]. 2.3 Design Interventions and Artefacts for Improving Disclosure Practices These challenges raise the question of how authors might be sup- ported when reporting their AI-use in academic manuscripts."
8067,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,86,"While relatively little design research has directly examined AI disclosure as an author-facing task, several adjacent strands of work have explored how structured disclosure artefacts can support accurate and compliant reporting while allowing authors discretion over how their work is represented."
8068,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,87,"Prior work on structured documentation for responsible AI intro- ducedDatasheets for Datasets, which propose a standardised format for documenting the motivation, composition, and intended use of datasets [24]."
8069,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,88,"Other work in machine learning documentation introducedmodel cards, structured documentation artefacts that CHIWORK ’26, June 22–25, 2026, Linz, Austria Ahmetoglu et al. summarise a model’s intended use, evaluation procedures, perfor- mance characteristics, and limitations [39]."
8070,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,89,Subsequent large-scale examinations show that many existing cards remain incomplete or omit critical sections [42].
8071,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,90,"Related approaches such as RiskRAG build on these templates by automatically pre-populating context- appropriate risk fields, aiming to increase reporting completeness [43]."
8072,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,91,This work aligns with prior HCI research showing that prede- fined disclosure templates can shape what information is revealed while reducing user effort in reporting [25].
8073,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,92,"A separate line of research treats disclosure as a problem of in- formation presentation, examining how AI-related information is structured and formatted to support comprehension by different stakeholders."
8074,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,93,"Bogucka et al. [9] introduceImpact Assessment Cards as a card-based format for communicating system-level informa- tion about AI systems, including their purpose, intended context of use, potential risks and benefits, and regulatory classification under the EU AI Act."
8075,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,94,This research argues for shifting disclosure away from long narrative reports toward a more compact format that supports quicker interpretation and comparison.
8076,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,95,Evaluations indi- cate that card-based designs support faster information extraction and higher-quality task performance than narrative documentation.
8077,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,96,"These findings connect to earlier evidence that disclosure formats influence both the quantity and character of disclosure, for example, computer-administered forms tend to elicit greater self-report than face-to-face or paper formats due to reduced evaluation anxiety [53]."
8078,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,97,"To date, there is little peer-reviewed research that examines AI-use disclosure as an author-facing practice."
8079,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,98,"One relevant contri- bution is the Artificial Intelligence Disclosure framework, which adapts contributorship taxonomies to the writing process by out- lining stages such as conceptualisation, analysis, and drafting [56]."
8080,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,99,"However, this work presents a conceptual structure rather than an evaluated disclosure tool."
8081,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,100,"Alongside this, a small number of initiatives have proposed label-style disclosure formats inspired by nutrition labels, aiming to provide simple, standardised ways of listing common forms of AI assistance, though these efforts are not peer-reviewed and lack empirical evaluation ( e.g. [1])."
8082,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,101,"Evidence from published research suggests that such proposals have so far had limited impact on practice: large-scale analyses show that AI- use disclosures remain rare and, when present, are typically brief and vague."
8083,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,102,"For example, a review of over 2,000 medical education articles found that only 2.5% included any AI-use disclosure, usually limited to naming the tool and asserting author responsibility, with little detail on how AI was used [5]."
8084,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,103,"Research Gap.Prior work has established the importance of trans- parency around AI use in academic publishing and identified a range of cognitive, social, and emotional factors that shape disclo- sure decisions [10, 44, 48, 60]."
8085,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,104,"In parallel, research on AI governance and machine-learning documentation shows that structured report- ing formats can influence what information is recorded and how it is interpreted [9, 39, 43]."
8086,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,105,"However, this work has largely overlooked the moment when researchers are actually required to write AI disclosure statements for their own manuscripts."
8087,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,106,"There is limited understanding of how authors interpret AI disclosure requirements, decide what to report, and experience the task of producing these statements in practice."
8088,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,107,"Existing AI-use disclosures in published research remain rare and inconsistent [5, 21], and little empirical work has examined whether and how interactive tools can support authors in producing more complete and less burdensome disclo- sures [1, 19, 56]."
8089,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,108,"These gaps point to the need for research that empirically examines author-facing disclosure support tools and their effects on disclosure content and experience. 3 DAISY To examine how interactive tools might support the task of writ- ing AI disclosure statements, we designed DAISY, a structured disclosure form intended to guide authors through reporting their AI-use (Figure 1)."
8090,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,109,"We followed a two-phase process to identify de- sign requirements for the tool, adapting the approach of Bogucka et al. [9]."
8091,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,110,"First, we derived design requirements by synthesising literature-based sources: publisher policies, analysis of disclosure statements from recent publications, and empirical research on how researchers use and disclose AI."
8092,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,111,"Second, we used the initial design requirements as co-design materials to further develop them using a participatory approach."
8093,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,112,The aim of the co-design sessions was to contextualize the literature-based requirements by answering the questions of:i)How do academics understand and reason about AI disclosure? andii)What forms of support for authors do academics envision for producing AI disclosures? 3.1 Identify Design Requirements from Literature-based Sources and Co-Design Activities 3.1.1 Publisher Policies.We reviewed publisher policies on AI- use in research.
8094,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,113,"To scope the set of publishers included, we drew on a curated overview of publisher AI policies maintained by the UC Merced Library [ 54]."
8095,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,114,"At the time of writing, this overview provided one of the most widely used and consolidated summaries of publisher AI policies."
8096,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,115,"Based on this overview, we included all 11 major publishers listed whose guidance academic authors are most likely to encounter, including ACM, IEEE, Springer Nature, Elsevier and Wiley, which together publish a substantial proportion of high-impact research across domains [14]."
8097,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,116,"For each publisher, we consulted and analysed the official policy documents available on the publisher’s website (see the policies in theGlossarysection of the study materials here: [38])."
8098,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,117,The review of the AI policies indicated that all publishers prohibit listing AI systems as authors.
8099,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,118,"Minor assistive uses of AI for grammar, style, or basic editing typically do not require disclosure, whereas more substantive uses such as generating text, code, tables, figures, images, or conceptual content do."
8100,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,119,"When disclosure is required, policies commonly ask authors to name the tool and version where relevant, indicate which parts of the manuscript or research process involved AI assistance, and describe the nature and purpose of that assistance."
8101,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,120,Publishers differ in the specificity of the guidance provided.
8102,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,121,"Some specify where disclosures should appear, such as in a dedicated declaration, the Methods section when AI is used in the research process, or the Acknowledgements, while others leave placement to author judgement."
8103,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,122,"Policies also differ in how explicitly they define disclosure content, from general guidance to more specific requirements with example wording."
8104,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,123,"A small number AI Disclosure with DAISY CHIWORK ’26, June 22–25, 2026, Linz, Austria include explicit restrictions, such as limits on AI-generated or AI- manipulated images, figures or research data. 3.1.2 Recent Publications.To examine how AI-use disclosure is currently reported in practice, we conducted a targeted literature review of recently published research articles across a subset of major academic publishers [41]."
8105,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,124,"Using the set of publishers iden- tified in (§3.1.1), we selected journals with reported acceptance rates below 30% because acceptance rates below 30% are commonly used in prior work to indicate selective publication venues (e.g. [13])."
8106,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,125,"For each journal or venue, we sampled between 2 and 5 of the most recently published research articles (to achieve diversity within the publishers), resulting in a total sample of 100 papers."
8107,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,126,"For each paper, we examined the acknowledgements, methods, and end matter for included AI disclosure statements."
8108,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,127,"In addition, we conducted keyword searches within the PDFs using terms such as AI,artificial intelligence,ChatGPTandGemini."
8109,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,128,"These tools were included because prior surveys indicate that ChatGPT and Gemini are among the most commonly used AI tools in academic research [10, 36]."
8110,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,129,"We found that only two papers in the sample contained explicit AI disclosure statements, which reported stylistic use of ChatGPT for language correction [11] or no use of AI tools at all."
8111,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,130,"A list of all reviewed papers can be found in Appendix A. 3.1.3 Empirical Studies.Empirical studies cited in the Related Work section of this paper (§2) were reviewed to understand how AI disclosure shapes authors’ social, emotional, and cognitive ex- periences, informing the design requirements presented in the fol- lowing section, following the approach used by Bogucka et al. [9]."
8112,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,131,"Similar to their work, we did not conduct a systematic literature review at this stage but used relevant prior studies as a starting point for identifying key challenges related to AI disclosure."
8113,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,132,These insights were subsequently contextualised through the co-design sessions and triangulated with publisher policy requirements and the analysis of existing disclosure statements.
8114,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,133,"Prior work on social and reputational effects of AI disclosure informed requirements related to how disclosure is framed and experienced by authors, including concerns about judgement and stigma [ 10, 44], while studies on AI guilt and emotional discomfort informed require- ments aimed at reducing emotional burden during disclosure [7, 12]."
8115,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,134,"Research on cognitive challenges in mixed human–AI contexts, in- cluding source-memory errors and misattribution of contributions, informed requirements aimed at supporting recall across the re- search and writing process [48, 60]."
8116,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,135,"In this context, the Artificial Intelligence Disclosure framework provided an activity-level break- down of research and writing tasks (e.g. ideation, analysis, drafting), informing which types of activities should be considered during disclosure [56]."
8117,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,136,"Finally, work on structured disclosure and report- ing artefacts informed requirements related to possible disclosure formats and interaction elements (e.g. forms, cards, labels), which were used as design ingredients in the co-design sessions (§3.2) [9, 25, 53]. 3.1.4 Synthesis of initial design requirements from literature-based sources.We organised insights the literature-based sources into three groups ofinitialdesign requirements that served as a starting point for the co-design sessions and, in some cases, directly in- formed the design of the disclosure artefact presented in this paper (as described in §3.3)."
8118,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,137,"Content requirements (R1) specifiedwhatinformation a disclo- sure statement should include: disclosure of any meaningful use of generative AI beyond basic proofreading; naming the AI tool used and, where relevant, its version; indicating which parts of the research or manuscript involved AI assistance; describing the nature and extent of that assistance across research and writing activities, such as conceptualisation, methodology, information col- lection, data analysis, visualisation, writing, and administrative work; and affirming that authors retain full responsibility for the final content."
8119,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,138,Presentation requirements (R2) specifiedhowdisclo- sure should be supported: providing guidance to support recall of AI involvement; using neutral phrasing to reduce shame or fear; generating ready-to-use disclosure statement.
8120,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,139,"Context-of-use re- quirements (R3) specifiedwhenandwheredisclosure support should fit: enabling reuse across submissions and support for collabora- tive authorship; aligning with disclosure expectations across major publishers. 3.2 Conduct Co-Design Activities We conducted co-design activities to explore how academic stake- holders understand AI disclosure and what forms of support they en- vision to ground the literature-based requirements outlined above in people’s lived experiences. 3.2.1 Participants.We conducted 4 co-design sessions with a total of 11 academic authors, reviewers, academic journal editors and conference committee members (1-4 participants per session)."
8121,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,140,"This sample size is consistent with prior HCI co-design studies in related domains, which typically involve 10–15 participants in small groups (for example, [9])."
8122,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,141,"We recruited participants through departmental mailing lists and personal networks, aiming for variation in career stage (doctoral researchers, postdoctoral researchers, faculty), dis- ciplinary background, and familiarity with AI tools."
8123,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,142,Prior use of AI tools was not an explicit recruitment criterion for the co-design sessions.
8124,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,143,"However, all participants reported having used AI tools in their research."
8125,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,144,Table 1 provides demographic details.
8126,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,145,The study was approved by the UCL ethics committee. 3.2.2 Procedure.Each session lasted 60 minutes and was con- ducted online with the help of a Miro board (which can be accessed here [38]).
8127,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,146,"Sessions were split in three parts: conversation, ideating and creating."
8128,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,147,"In the conversation part, participants were introduced to a summary of publishers AI policies and to a brief overview of AI disclosure statements."
8129,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,148,"They discussed if any of the information was surprising to them, and they shared their prior experience with AI disclosure policies and statements from their experience as authors, reviewers, conference chairs and editors where rele- vant."
8130,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,149,"In the ideating part, participants were asked to imagine a tool that supports authors in creating an AI disclosure statement."
8131,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,150,"They were invited to suggest requirements related to the content the tool should capture (R1), how this information should be presented (R2), and the context-of-use in which the tool would fit (R3), recording their ideas as sticky notes on separate boards for each participant which they later discussed with the group."
8132,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,151,"The researcher noted CHIWORK ’26, June 22–25, 2026, Linz, Austria Ahmetoglu et al."
8133,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,152,Table 1: Participant demographics and academic experience in the co-design study. # Gender Position Field Experience Country 1 Female PhD student HCI Author UK 2 Male Associate Prof.
8134,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,153,Psychology Author; Reviewer UK 3 Female PhD student HCI Author; Reviewer UK 4 Male Lecturer Psychology Author; Reviewer UK 5 Male Postdoctoral Res.
8135,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,154,Mathematics Author; Reviewer UK 6 Male Associate Prof.
8136,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,155,Political Science Author; Reviewer; Editor UK 7 Female PhD student Education Author; Reviewer UK 8 Female Professor Sports & Health Author; Reviewer; Editor UK 9 Male Professor HCI; Psych.; ML Author; Reviewer; Chair; Editor Austria 10 Female Assistant Prof.
8137,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,156,HCI & CS Author; Reviewer; Chair Germany 11 Male Lecturer Machine Learning Author; Reviewer UK collective requirements that were common in participants ideas.
8138,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,157,"Next, participants were shown a new board presenting require- ments derived from the literature and were invited to note which aspects they agreed or disagreed with."
8139,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,158,"In the creating part, partic- ipants were asked to sketch how an AI disclosure artefact might look, using pen and paper to draw a tool over a 15-minute period, drawing on example elements (such as forms, cards, or agents), which they could get inspiration from."
8140,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,159,"The design elements were based on prior work on card-based design elements to communi- cate AI risks [9], form-based elements described in [58], and one chatbot-inspired design element based on a pilot study (P1), which was included in the main corpus."
8141,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,160,"Participants took photos of their sketches and sent to the researchers via email. 3.2.3 Analysis.All co-design sessions were recorded, transcribed, and analysed using inductive thematic analysis [52]."
8142,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,161,"The first au- thor coded the transcripts and regularly presented the evolving codebook and emerging themes during research team discussions, where codes and theme definitions were iteratively refined using a shared Miro board."
8143,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,162,"The sticky notes created during the second part of the co-design sessions were clustered based on the require- ments they referred to, providing additional context for the analysis."
8144,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,163,"Each sketch was supplemented by participants’ explanations and any relevant comments made during the co-design sessions (see Figure 2 for sketches, and Appendix B for post-its and Appendix C for a mind-map of initial thematic analysis used during the re- search group discussions)."
8145,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,164,"Data analysis meetings amounted to approximately four hours in total. 3.2.4 Results.The thematic analysis resulted in two main themes, each broadly corresponding to one of the research questions guid- ing the co-design activities about authors’ understandings of AI disclosure and their expectations of support for producing such disclosures."
8146,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,165,Theme 1: Initial Sense-making and Questioning of AI Disclosure.
8147,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,166,"Most co-design participants reported low prior level of engagement with AI disclosure policies, and the majority (8 out of 11) had never written an AI disclosure statement before."
8148,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,167,Awareness of disclosure requirements was often limited even among experienced reviewers and editors although with some exceptions (P9 and P10).
8149,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,168,"In most cases, the discussions focused less on how AI disclosure should be implemented and more on why AI disclosure exists, whose interests it is intended to protect, and how it should function in the absence of clear norms or verification mechanisms."
8150,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,169,A wareness.Participants expressed uncertainty about what types of AI use should be disclosed.
8151,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,170,"For example, language-correcting uses were often described as not something participants would think of declaring."
8152,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,171,P8 said: “Because I’m not asking it to create anything. . .
8153,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,172,I’m asking it to improve the language. . . it would never cross my mind to declare that”.
8154,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,173,"However, during the discussion, this conclusion was reconsidered: the same participant later reflected on using AI to generate new pieces of text such as abstracts or paper titles, noting that “I have to admit I’ve done it for titles before. . . because I’m not very catchy or creative."
8155,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,174,"Sometimes you want that punchier title, so you get it to come up with that” thereby recognising a form of contribution that went beyond language correction."
8156,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,175,Trust.Participants often saw AI disclosure as operating as a trust-based “honour” system because there were no verification mechanisms.
8157,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,176,"Editors and reviewers noted that they largely rely on authors’ self-reporting and have limited ability to assess whether disclosure statements fully capture how AI was used: “It’s purely the authors’ willingness to adhere to that disclosure, because there is no proof in any sense” (P11)."
8158,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,177,"While some participants saw this reliance on trust as consistent with broader academic norms, others (e.g."
8159,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,178,"P9) expressed discomfort with how easily AI contributions could be minimised or selectively framed, particularly when minimal disclosures such as “used to improve grammar” could plausibly ""mask"" more substantive involvement."
8160,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,179,"Purpose.Several questioned the purpose of disclosure, for exam- ple, whether disclosure was intended to protect authors, inform reviewers or safeguard venues."
8161,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,180,P5 said: “I don’t understand what is the purpose of this. . .
8162,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,181,"If someone doesn’t state it and uses AI, how do you catch them?"
8163,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,182,Do you want to catch them?” Disclosure was often perceived as risky and encouraging strategic behaviour such as minimising detail or tailoring statements to venue-specific expectations.
8164,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,183,"Other participants suggested that disclosure could also serve more constructive roles, such as supporting transparency or helping authors reflect on their own AI use."
8165,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,184,"For example, P10 described encountering highly competent and creative uses of AI that they found “more admirable than judgable”, noting that such AI Disclosure with DAISY CHIWORK ’26, June 22–25, 2026, Linz, Austria Figure 2: Speculative AI disclosure artefacts created by 11 participants (P1-11) during four co-design sessions, sorted by participant background and layout. practices require “creativity” and “knowledge” but are not yet val- ued within academia: “the disclosure is always there looking like as if I’m policing someone. . . not the other way”."
8166,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,185,"P10 suggested that disclosure mechanisms could instead make room for authors to describe how they work with AI, including innovative methods."
8167,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,186,Theme 2: Tensions in Disclosure as a Protective Task or an Oppor- tunity for Transparency.Participants’ sketches pointed to a tension between viewing AI disclosure as a protective and compliance- oriented task and as a potential opportunity for transparency about research practices.
8168,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,187,"This tension was most strongly shaped by dis- ciplinary background, particularly whether participants had expe- rience in HCI, rather than by formal academic roles and editorial experience."
8169,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,188,"Disclosure as a Protective Task.Most participants, especially those outside of the HCI field, sketched form-based interactions situated close to the point of manuscript submission."
8170,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,189,Disclosure was fre- quently framed as a means of meeting publisher requirements and protecting oneself from potential scrutiny.
8171,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,190,"For these participants, disclosure had to be easy and minimally disruptive, with several explicitly noting that it “should not be another obstacle” (P5)."
8172,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,191,"Their sketches and written requirements sometimes located disclosure within the existing editorial systems, for example “in a form in the submission system” (P4)."
8173,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,192,"Several participants asked for guidance on what counts and what does not in terms of AI use for a statement, and for “a clear threshold” (P6) suggesting concern with drawing defensible boundaries."
8174,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,193,"Others raised questions about verification, for example asking whether disclosure should “explain how it will be checked if you are being truthful or not” (P2)."
8175,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,194,This framing was also visible in the sketches.
8176,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,195,"P7’s sketch showed a single submission box with a short checklist and a space to insert a disclosure text or link, while P4’s showed a simple form starting with a yes/no question about AI use followed by fixed options indicating affected parts of the work."
8177,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,196,"Several participants preferred to describe AI use in abstract terms, stating that they would “keep it high level” (P3) or “only say it if it was substantial” (P6), motivated by concerns about how disclosure would be perceived by the readers."
8178,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,197,"Disclosure as an Opportunity for Transparency.The speculative disclosure artefacts were also described as a potential way to sup- port transparency in research practices, a perspective raised primar- ily by participants with HCI backgrounds."
8179,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,198,"Their sketches reflected concern with the complexity of AI involvement and with helping authors articulate how and where AI was used across research and writing activities, often aiming to support more detailed disclosure statements."
8180,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,199,"A common concern was the difficulty of making sense CHIWORK ’26, June 22–25, 2026, Linz, Austria Ahmetoglu et al."
8181,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,200,Figure 3: The DAISY interface.
8182,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,201,"The left panel shows the default, unfilled form."
8183,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,202,"The right panel shows a completed form and the resulting AI disclosure statement, including the editable output reviewed and refined by the author prior to submission. of AI use after the fact, particularly when AI involvement was dis- tributed across time, AI tools and research activities."
8184,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,203,Three out of five HCI participants proposed system-level tools rather than single forms.
8185,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,204,Some participants proposed logging approaches that allow AI use to be noted as it occurs and later summarised for disclosure (P9).
8186,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,205,"In some cases, participants suggested checking these recorded interactions against the final manuscript to understand where and how AI may have shaped the work, with draft disclosure state- ments generated from this interaction history (P2)."
8187,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,206,"Others were more cautious about logging or quantification, questioning whether numerical representations of human-AI contribution meaningfully capture complex intellectual work, or whether such mechanisms risk shifting disclosure from a reflective practice to a monitoring one."
8188,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,207,"P10 noted that disclosure should remain a “trust space”. 3.3 Designing DAISY To explore how a digital tool could support AI disclosure, we drew on the findings reported above and created DAISY."
8189,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,208,DAISY was designed to operationalise AI disclosure as an author-facing in- teraction and to enable empirical investigation of how authors construct and experience disclosure statements [59].
8190,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,209,This decision to implement DAISY as a form-based interface reflects both exist- ing disclosure mechanisms and the preferences expressed during the co-design sessions.
8191,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,210,"More speculative approaches (e.g., design fiction) could explore alternative disclosure paradigms, but our aim was to study a format that could plausibly integrate with current practice."
8192,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,211,"DAISY was built as a web application using HTML for structure, CSS for layout and styling, and JavaScript for interaction and statement generation, and is hosted on GitHub Pages."
8193,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,212,"To address content requirements (R1), DAISY structures dis- closure around six activities: Ideation and brainstorming, Coding assistance, Analytical support, Writing and drafting, Figures and tables, and Language editing and proofreading."
8194,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,213,"These categories were adapted from the AI disclosure framework but consolidated to meet the needs for brief and easy presentation (e.g. multiple writing- related subcategories are captured under Writing and drafting, and analysis-related uses under Analytical support) [56]."
8195,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,214,"Authors in- dicate the level of AI support (none, low, medium, high) for each activity and can add short bracketed notes to specify what the AI did and where, allowing both high-level and more precise reporting in line with co-design findings."
8196,30,C030_P1_pdf.txt,215,"In addition to activities, DAISY includes open ended fields, such as tools used (including names and versions), input data shared with AI systems, safeguards ap- plied during use, human review steps, and authorship boundaries indicating that responsibility for the final content remains with the authors."
