8341,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,120,"When considering a balanced dataset of papers,Th e A I Sc i e n t i s t’s reviewing process achieves human-level accuracy (0.65% vs. 0.66%)."
8342,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,121,"Furthermore, the False Negative Rate (FNR) is much lower than the human baseline (0.39 vs. 0.52)."
8343,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,122,"Hence, the LLM-based review agent rejects fewer high-quality papers."
8344,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,123,"The False Positive Rate (FNR), on the other hand, is higher (0.31 vs. 0.17) highlighting room for potential future improvements."
8345,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,124,"To further validate the performance of the automated reviewer, we compare the consistency of the overall paper scores between anonymous OpenReview reviewers randomly sampled pairwise per paper (Figure 2, bottom-left) and between the average of all reviewers and the LLM score (Figure 2, bottom-middle)."
8346,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,125,"For the set of 500 ICLR 2022 papers, we find that the correlation between the score of two human reviewers is smaller (0.14) than the correlation between the LLM score and the average score across the reviewers (0.18)."
8347,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,126,"Overall, across all metrics, the results suggest that LLM-based reviews can not only provide valuable feedback (D’Arcy et al., 2024) but also align more closely with the average human reviewer score than individual human reviewers align with each other. 1Numbers are calculated based of the NeurIPS consistency experiment (Beygelzimer et al., 2021). 6 The AI Scientist: Towards Fully Automated Open-Ended Scientific Discovery Figure 2 | Evaluation of Th e A I Sc i e n t i s t’s paper reviewing process on ICLR 2022 OpenReview Data using GPT-4o."
8348,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,127,Adding Reflexion and one-shot prompting improves the accuracy of the LLM-Based Reviewing Process.
8349,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,128,"Review ensembling (5 reviews) and subsequent meta-aggregation, on the other hand, did not affect the reviewer’s performance, but can reduce variance."
8350,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,129,Each review is generated for $0.25 to $0.50 in API costs.
8351,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,130,We additionally compared the reviewing performance of various other foundation models.
8352,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,131,"While Claude Sonnet 3.5 (Anthropic, 2024) and GPT- 4o-mini provide a more cost-efficient approach, their performance was substantially worse (Table 1)."
8353,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,132,"Moreover, we had to threshold scores at 8 for Sonnet 3.5 to obtain calibrated results, due to persistent over-optimism bias."
8354,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,133,"Llama 3.1 405B (Llama Team, 2024) struggled to follow the reviewer output template consistently."
8355,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,134,"We open-source our code, providing a new and interesting LLM benchmark for the community."
8356,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,135,"LLM Reviewer Ablations.We compare various prompt configurations for GPT-4o and find that both Reflexion (+2%) and one-shot prompting (+2%) substantially help with performing more accurate reviewing (Figure 2, top and bottom-right)."
8357,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,136,"On the other hand, using review ensembling does not appear to improve the reviewer’s performance substantially but can reduce variance."
8358,32,C032_P1_pdf.txt,137,"In the following sections, we used our best overall reviewer: GPT-4o with 5 rounds of self-reflection, 5 ensembled reviews, a meta-aggregation step, and 1 few-shot example. 5."
