8618,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,80,"CS, Multi, Bio and Neu indicate Scholar-CS (computer science), Scholar-Multi, Scholar-Bio  (biomedicine) and Scholar-Neuro (neuroscience), which require multi-paper synthesis and long-form answer generations, respectively. ‘Acc.’ indicates the correctness metrics in single-paper  tasks (accuracy for PubMedQA and SciFact, ROUGE-L for QASA)."
8619,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,81,"Rubric accuracy (‘Rub.’) in Scholar-CS is used as the primary metric for correctness on multi-paper synthesis tasks. ‘Cite’  indicates citation F1. ‘LLM’ indicates the average score of organization, relevance and coverage as predicted by Prometheus44."
8620,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,82,PaperQA2 is based on GPT-4o and its pricing is dependent on  the number of PDF files used during inference.
8621,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,83,"For the 8B and 70B model costs, although evaluations were conducted on our local machines, we estimated costs based on Together AI pricing.  *We used Perplexity Pro (which requires a monthly subscription at US$20) and divided this cost by 9,000, which is the maximum number of queries allowed under the Pro subscription."
8622,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,84,"Because  the Perplexity user interface does not provide snippets for each citation, we were unable to evaluate its citation accuracy. 860 | Nature | Vol 650 | 26 February 2026 Article bi-encoders, cross-encoders and in-house models, OpenScholar-8B and  OpenScholar-GPT-4o achieve much lower costs—orders of magnitude  cheaper than PaperQA2—while maintaining high performance."
8623,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,85,"Limitations of parametric LMs On both single-paper and multi-paper tasks, we observe that non-  retrieval augmented baselines struggle—retrieval is almost always  conducive to achieving better performance—and models without any  retrieval often struggle to generate correct citations and show limited  coverage on multi-paper tasks."
8624,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,86,Table 2 presents statistics on the cited  papers in the outputs of four models.
8625,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,87,We report the number of fully  fabricated citations (‘No. of hallucinated’) by verifying whether the  cited paper titles exist using the Semantic Scholar API.
8626,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,88,"Across mod- els, the share of cited papers that actually exist is very low: despite  plausible-looking reference lists, 78–98% of titles are fabricated, with  the worst rates in biomedicine."
8627,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,89,"This mirrors previous findings that  LLMs hallucinate on long-tail, underrepresented knowledge2,19 and we  suggest that the effect is amplified in scientific areas undercovered  on the open web."
8628,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,90,"Repeating the analysis on GPT-5, which was released  in August 2025, lowers title-level hallucination to 39% but fabricated  citations remain common."
8629,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,91,"Examples of model responses, as well as a  list of paper titles, are available in Supplementary Tables 19 and 20."
8630,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,92,"We also noticed that, even when citations refer to real papers, most of  them are not substantiated by the corresponding abstracts, resulting  in near-zero citation accuracy."
8631,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,93,We also observe that such models generate responses with limited  coverage.
8632,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,94,"On Scholar-Multi, non-retrieval models (Llama 3.1 8B, 70B  and GPT-4o) consistently exhibit much lower average scores com - pared with retrieval-augmented models."
8633,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,95,"This discrepancy is primarily  driven by substantially lower coverage scores; for instance, Llama 3.1 8B  achieves a coverage score of 3.45, whereas Llama 3.1 8B + OSDS (a stand- ard RAG baseline) improves the coverage score to 4.01."
8634,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,96,"These results  suggest that relying on the parametric knowledge of models alone is  particularly difficult in scientific domains, especially for smaller LMs."
8635,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,97,Human performance on ScholarQABench We also analysed expert performance on this challenging literature  synthesis task.
8636,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,98,"Specifically, we evaluated human-written answers on the  two subsets of ScholarQABench with long-form human annotations:  Scholar-CS and Scholar-Multi."
8637,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,99,"For both, we applied the same evaluation  pipeline used for model-generated responses to assess rubric and cita- tion accuracy."
8638,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,100,"For Scholar-Multi, rubric evaluation is not available, but  we conducted expert evaluations on both human and model responses  and compare the results in the next section."
8639,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,101,"Table 3 compares human per- formance with OpenScholar-GPT-4o, OpenScholar-8B, PaperQA2 and  GPT-4o (no retrieval)."
8640,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,102,Our analysis shows that human-written answers  remain strong baselines for quality and relevance.
8641,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,103,"On rubric-based  evaluations, human responses outperform GPT-4o without retrieval by  9.6 points and OpenScholar-8B by 2.9 points."
8642,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,104,"PaperQA2 demonstrates  high citation accuracy but its scores for rubrics, organization, coverage,  and relevance are lower."
8643,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,105,"By contrast, OpenScholar-GPT-4o achieves  even higher rubric scores than human experts and OpenScholar-8B  matches expert-level citation accuracy."
8644,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,106,"We found that OpenScholar  tends to produce more comprehensive responses than humans  or other baseline systems, citing a greater number of papers, as  reflected in both answer length and citation count."
8645,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,107,"In Supplemen - tary Information Section 6, we present a detailed human analysis  of model-written and human-written answers and further examine  key factors for improving scientific literature synthesis."
8646,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,108,Ablations and analysis Ablations of inference components.
8647,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,109,We ablate inference com - ponents by removing: (1) reranking (use top N OSDS results only);  (2) feedback (generate once then attribute); and (3) citation verification  (omit the final check).
8648,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,110,"For OpenScholar-8B, we also ablate training by  swapping in off-the-shelf Llama 3.1 8B with the same inference pipeline  (as in OpenScholar-GPT-4o)."
8649,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,111,"Extended Data Table 2 shows notable  drops in both correctness and citation accuracy for all removals, with  the largest losses from removing reranking."
8650,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,112,Feedback removal hurts  GPT-4o more than our trained 8B (probably because the latter learned  feedback patterns during training) and skipping post-hoc attribu - tion reduces both citation accuracy and final correctness.
8651,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,113,The gap  between trained versus vanilla OpenScholar-8B underscores the value  of domain-specific training.
8652,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,114,"We also compare OSDS-only (dense retrieval),  S2-only (Semantic Scholar keyword API), web-only (You.com) and their  combination."
8653,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,115,"T o isolate retrieval, we use our 8B LM without self-feedback  or citation verification and rerank to the top 15 with OpenScholar  reranker."
8654,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,116,"On Scholar-CS (Extended Data Table 2), web-only performs  worst (45.9 correctness, 12.6 citation F1), S2-only improves especially  on citations (47.9/39.1) and the combined pipeline is best (49.6/47.6)."
8655,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,117,"Tailored, literature-focused retrieval (dense + API + reranking)  yields the strongest factuality and attribution."
8656,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,118,We analyse how the number of retrieved passages (top N) affects  performance.
8657,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,119,"We compare standard RAG and OpenScholar with our  trained 8B model and Llama 3.1 8B, evaluating generation and citation  accuracy on Scholar-CS."
8658,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,120,Extended Data Figs. 3 and 4 summarize the  results.
8659,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,121,"Although Llama 3.1 is trained to accept up to 128,000 tokens,  its performance degrades beyond a certain context size: increasing top  N from 5 to 10 improves correctness but larger N harms both correct- ness and citation accuracy."
8660,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,122,"This suggests that, despite long-context  capacity, smaller LMs may struggle to effectively use many passages  without specialized training."
8661,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,123,"By contrast, our trained 8B model remains  strong up to N = 20 and larger models (for example, Llama 3.1 70B) are  more robust to longer contexts."
8662,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,124,"Expert evaluation of OpenScholar’s effectiveness T o complement automatic metrics and examine the strengths and limits  of OpenScholar, we ran expert evaluations comparing human-written  answers with those generated by LLM systems."
8663,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,125,"This study involved more  than 100 literature review questions and more than 15 participants,  including PhD students, research scientists and university professors  with expertise in the relevant fields."
8664,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,126,"In total, we curated more than  400 fine-grained expert evaluations of expert and model answers."
8665,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,127,Table 2 | Statistics of hallucinated papers in the computer science and biomedicine domains Computer science Biomedicine Model Total no.
8666,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,128,No. of hallucinated (↓) Ratio (↓ ) Total no.
8667,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,129,"No. of hallucinated (↓) Ratio (↓ ) OpenScholar-8B 9.65 0 0 6.25 0 0 Llama 3.1 8B 5.20 4.79 92.1% 5.58 5.46 97.6% Llama 3.1 70B 6.14 4.78 78.1% 6.98 6.74 96.6% GPT-4o 5.74 4.52 78.7% 5.24 4.97 94.8% Our analysis revealed a substantial number of non-existent cited papers in predictions made by LLMs without retrieval, which is a problem not observed in OpenScholar."
8668,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,130,"Nature | Vol 650 | 26 February 2026 | 861   Evaluation design We use 108 question-answer (QA) pairs from Scholar-Multi, written  by experts (expert writers)."
8669,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,131,"We evaluated three set-ups on these ques- tions: GPT-4o (no external retrieval), OpenScholar with GPT-4o as the  generator (OpenScholar-GPT-4o) and OpenScholar with our trained  8B model (OpenScholar-8B), each producing answers with citations."
8670,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,132,We then recruited a separate group of PhD-level domain experts to  rate the model-generated answers against expert-written answers.
8671,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,133,"In particular, each evaluation involves presenting a question, a  model-generated answer and a human-written answer."
8672,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,134,Expert raters  then conduct fine-grained assessments of each answer and provide pair- wise preference judgements between the two.
8673,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,135,"For fine-grained evalu- ations, we use the five-scale evaluation criteria described in Methods  (coverage, relevance and organization), with annotators scoring both  model and human answers using the same rubrics."
8674,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,136,Detailed prompts  are presented in Supplementary Information Section 6.
8675,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,137,"For usefulness,  annotators assign scores on a scale from 1 to 5, which we convert into  three classes: not useful (1, 2), neutral (3) and useful (4, 5)."
8676,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,138,We then cal- culate the percentage of answers that fall into the useful category.
8677,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,139,"For  pairwise preference, annotators either choose one of the answers or  mark a ‘tie’ if they judge both answers to be of equal quality."
8678,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,140,"Optionally,  experts provide explanations on why one answer is better than the other."
8679,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,141,"Our expert writers for question and answer  writing are 12 PhD students and postdoctoral researchers from research  institutions across the USA, all of whom have at least three years of  research experience and have published several papers in journals or  conferences in their fields."
8680,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,142,"The expert areas covered by our writers  include the computer science (natural language processing, computer  vision, humancomputer interaction), physics (astrophysics, photon- ics/optics) and biomedical (neuroscience, bioimaging) domains and  we assign our expert annotators to questions in their expertise."
8681,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,143,"On  average, we paid US$35–40 per person."
8682,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,144,"Sixteen expert raters from the three fields  contributed to our evaluations, with 12 of them also participating in  answer generation."
8683,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,145,All expert raters meet the same qualifications as  those who composed the answers.
8684,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,146,"T o minimize potential biases, we  ensured that raters did not evaluate responses to their own questions by  assigning evaluation tasks to different groups of experts."
8685,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,147,"Each instance  was reviewed by one to three expert raters, depending on availability."
8686,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,148,"The inter-annotator agreement was 0.68 using pairwise comparison with  ties and 0.70 using a relaxed approach, in which ties were merged."
8687,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,149,"On  average, each expert rater spent five minutes per instance on evaluation  and received compensation ranging from US$25 to US$35."
8688,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,150,Expert evaluation results Overall result.
8689,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,151,"Table 4 presents the average scores for each evalua- tion aspect, alongside the relative win rates against human responses."
8690,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,152,"Extended Data Fig. 5 illustrates the score distributions for human,  GPT-4o and OpenScholar with Llama 3.1 8B and GPT-4o."
8691,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,153,"Notably,  both OpenScholar-GPT-4o and our OpenScholar-8B versions outper- form human answers in more than 50% of cases, with their advantage  primarily attributed to their ability to provide a greater breadth and  depth of information (coverage)."
8692,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,154,"By contrast, GPT-4o, which lacks  retrieval capabilities, demonstrates greatly limited coverage and wins  in fewer than 35% of cases, with its overall usefulness rated much lower  than responses from humans and the other two models."
8693,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,155,"These results  highlight that, even for state-of-the-art models, synthesizing and  answering scientific literature review questions remains a challeng- ing task, consistent with our findings on ScholarQABench."
8694,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,156,"Overall,  OpenScholar-GPT-4o and OpenScholar-8B are rated as useful in 80%  and 72% of the queries, respectively."
8695,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,157,"Although the performance of OpenScholar using an open 8B LM  already surpasses that of human experts, the output of the 8B model is  judged to be less organized or fluent than the present state-of-the-art  private LLM-based OpenScholar."
8696,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,158,"We found that GPT-4o incorporates  feedback more effectively and tends to generate longer and more fluent  outputs, leading to much higher organization scores compared with  both the OpenScholar-8B as well as human responses."
8697,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,159,Effects of length control on model responses.
8698,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,160,"Although we found  that model outputs are often preferred over expert-written outputs, one  potential confounding factor is the large difference in their output  length—OpenScholar-GPT-4o and OpenScholar-8B are 2.4 times and  2.0 times longer than expert-written answers, respectively, which  affects judgement20."
8699,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,161,"T o understand the effect of output length, we  conducted a controlled experiment."
8700,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,162,"For a random sample of 50 ques- tions, we generate abbreviated responses for OpenScholar-GPT-4o  by prompting GPT-4o to create summaries of responses that are less  than 300 words."
8701,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,163,"This led to OpenScholar answers that average around  333 words, which is close to the average length of human answers."
8702,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,164,"We  then repeat the human evaluation, considering both fine-grained and  overall responses."
8703,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,165,"On average, the shortened GPT-4o scores 4.5 for  organization, 4.6 for coverage and 4.6 for relevance."
8704,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,166,The shortened  OpenScholar-GPT-4o responses are preferred or tied with expert  answers in 75% of the queries.
8705,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,167,The experimental results show that the  superior performance of the model is not only because of the increased  length of the OpenScholar answers.
8706,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,168,"Moreover, the explanations of  human annotators often mention that both shortened OpenScholar and  human answers could be improved by incorporating more details, imp- lying that a 300-word restriction may limit the usefulness of answers."
8707,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,169,Analyses on human explanations for pairwise judgements.
8708,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,170,We ran- domly sampled 59 instances with free-form explanations of pairwise  preferences and conducted a manual analysis to identify factors that  influence overall preferences.
8709,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,171,"Specifically, we examined whether the  explanations referenced one or more of the following four catego- ries: organization, relevance, coverage and citations."
8710,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,172,"Although the  first three categories align with the fine-grained human evaluation  criteria, the citation category also considers the quality of the cited  Table 3 | Expert-written answer stats Scholar-CS Scholar-Multi Length No. of cit."
8711,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,173,"Human 424.3 7.1 54.0 43.2 40.1 44.4 41.5 – – – OpenScholar-GPT-4o 1,447.3 11.8 57.7 41.1 38.1 38.0 37.1 4.63 4.50 4.23 OpenScholar-8B 706.3 10.1 51.1 40.6 44.1 42.5 43.2 3.92 4.44 4.02 PaperQA2 288.7 2.7 45.6 45.9 48.0 53.1 42.2 3.67 3.46 4.20 GPT-4o 281.5 0.5 45.0 1.0 0.8 0.8 0.6 4.06 3.94 4.21 Models tend to generate longer responses and cite more papers than humans."
8712,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,174,"For reference, we include GPT-4o outputs without retrieval, evaluated on the human evaluation queries. ‘Length’  refers to the average length of the answers and ‘No. of cit.’ indicates the average number of cited papers in the final answers. ‘Prec.’ and ‘Rec.’ denote citation precision and recall and ‘Org.’, ‘Cov.’  and ‘Rel.’ represent organization, coverage and relevance, respectively, as evaluated by LLM-as-a-judge."
8713,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,175,"For the number of citations of GPT-4o, we only consider valid citations. 862 | Nature | Vol 650 | 26 February 2026 Article papers (for example, whether the system includes seminal papers in  the field)."
8714,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,176,"Our analysis (Supplementary Information Table 27) revealed  that 12%, 23%, 29% and 9% of the explanations cited organization, rel- evance, coverage and citation accuracy, respectively, as key factors in  pairwise decisions."
8715,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,177,"This suggests that coverage plays a crucial role in  how humans assess the quality of responses, with annotators largely  favouring model-generated answers for their greater coverage and  depth of information."
8716,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,178,"However, annotators also noted that the cita- tions provided by models could be improved, pointing out that the  suggested papers were occasionally outdated or less relevant compared  with more representative work."
8717,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,179,"Discussion T o further research on LM-based systems that can help scientists navi- gate the complex, ever-growing task of scientific literature review,  we introduce OpenScholar and ScholarQABench."
8718,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,180,"OpenScholar, the  first fully open retrieval-augmented system, uses open-weight LLMs  and trained retrieval models to iteratively refine scientific output,  addressing challenges such as hallucinations and citation accuracy."
8719,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,181,"Scholar QABench, a new large-scale benchmark, provides a standard- ized way to evaluate literature review automation across several sci- entific domains."
8720,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,182,"In evaluations using ScholarQABench, OpenScholar  demonstrates substantial improvements, outperforming existing sys- tems such as GPT-4o and the concurrent proprietary system PaperQA2."
8721,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,183,"Our expert evaluation across three scientific disciplines reveals that  OpenScholar generates answers that are more helpful than those pro- duced by expert annotators, who required an hour per annotation."
8722,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,184,"Specifically, OpenScholar, using our trained 8B and GPT-4o achieves a  51% and 70% win rate against human-generated answers, respectively."
8723,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,185,"We open-source the OpenScholar code, data, model checkpoints, data  stores and ScholarQABench, along with a public demo, to support and  accelerate future research efforts."
8724,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,186,"Our public demo has engaged more  than 30,000 users across diverse scientific disciplines."
8725,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,187,"Future work  can further improve OpenScholar by integrating user feedback from  this platform to enhance retrieval quality, improve citation accuracy  and optimize overall usability."
8726,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,188,Limitations We highlight several limitations of our work in this section.
8727,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,189,It is impor- tant to note that we do not claim that LM-based systems can fully auto- mate scientific literature synthesis.
8728,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,190,"T o further advance research in this  area, we are releasing both ScholarQABench and OpenScholar to the  community."
8729,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,191,"Limitations of ScholarQABench First, expert annotation is costly and time-consuming, so our human-  written evaluation sets are small (for example, 110 for computer  science long-form question answering; 108 expert answers), which  may introduce variance and annotator-expertise bias."
8730,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,192,We open-source  data and annotation pipelines to facilitate scaling.
8731,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,193,"Second, our automatic evaluation may not perfectly capture qual- ity."
8732,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,194,"In Scholar-CS, we combine length, excerpts and rubric items with  heuristic weights."
8733,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,195,"Annotators often requested ancillary elements  (background, elaborations, challenges) that are not strictly required  and LLMs tend to supply these, potentially inflating scores or enabling  exploitation of rubric style."
8734,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,196,"Despite good correlations with expert  judgements, scoring emphases and aggregation merit refinement."
8735,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,197,Our  citation precision/recall is sentence-level and can be overly strict when  adjacent sentences carry support.
8736,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,198,"Annotations reflect specific time  points ( July 2024 for Scholar-CS, September 2024 for Scholar-Multi);  for fair comparison, papers published after these dates should be  excluded."
8737,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,199,We recommend using the OSDS or restricting sources to  publications up to October 2024 for ScholarQABench v1 and we plan  regular updates.
8738,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,200,"Third, ScholarQABench is a static, public benchmark, raising future  contamination risks."
8739,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,201,"Although multi-paper synthesis data were newly  written by experts, public availability may expose it during training or  search21,22."
8740,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,202,We will continue updating the benchmark and monitoring  its use.
8741,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,203,"Last, ScholarQABench primarily focuses on computer science, bio- medicine and physics, with no instances from social sciences or other  engineering and scientific disciplines."
8742,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,204,"We recognize that our findings  may not fully generalize to other domains, particularly those with more  restricted access to paper data."
8743,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,205,"Limitations of OpenScholar Although OpenScholar demonstrates strong performance on Scholar- QABench and in human evaluations, as discussed in the relevant sec- tions, our expert annotators identified several limitations."
8744,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,206,"First, as highlighted by our expert annotators, OpenScholar does  not consistently retrieve the most representative or relevant papers  for certain queries."
8745,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,207,"Enhancing retrieval methodologies by incorpo - rating further information, such as citation networks or metadata  such as publication recency, could substantially improve its per - formance."
8746,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,208,"OpenScholar outputs may contain factual inaccuracies  or unsupported information, particularly in versions based on our  8B model, which has limited capacity for instruction-following and  scientific knowledge."
8747,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,209,Future work can explore training that fur - ther improves OpenScholar-8B.
8748,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,210,"In parallel, although competitive,  OpenScholar-GPT-4o relies on invoking the proprietary GPT-4o  through the OpenAI API, which may evolve over time, making  exact result replication a challenge."
8749,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,211,"Furthermore, note that Open - Scholar does not use license-protected papers at inference time."
8750,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,212,There are continuing discussions on how to ensure fair data use in  retrieval-augmented LMs and we leave the exploration of properly  incorporating copyright-protected content to future work.
8751,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,213,We encourage future research to address these limitations and con- tinue improving LM-based systems for scientific literature review.
8752,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,214,Limitations of our expert evaluation process.
8753,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,215,"In our human evalua- tions, annotators performed fine-grained assessments on aspects such  as coverage, relevance, organization and usefulness, whereas other  factors, such as citation precision and recall, were separately evalu- ated."
8754,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,216,"As a result, when assessing usefulness or pairwise preferences,  annotators may have focused more on the overall quality of writing  instead of carefully evaluating factual correctness or citation accuracy."
8755,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,217,"Table 4 | Expert rater evaluations of literature synthesis responses written by expert writers and LMs Fine-grained (1–5, average) Overall usefulness  (%) Relative to human (%) Organization Coverage Relevance Win Tie Lose GPT-4o 4.63 (+0.4) 4.06 (−0.2) 4.50 (−0.1) 69.7 (−13.9) 31.9 13.8 54.2 OpenScholar-8B 3.82 (−0.3) 4.30 (+0.7) 4.00 (−0.4) 72.1 (+8.7) 50.8 12.3 36.9 OpenScholar-GPT-4o 4.47 (+0.8) 4.38 (+0.9) 4.30 (0) 80.0 (+22.5) 70.0 6.8 23.2 Fine-grained aspect evaluations are conducted on a five-point scale across four aspects, following our detailed instructions and rubrics."
8756,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,218,"Values in parentheses denote relative performance  differences; positive values indicate that the model achieves higher average performance, whereas negative values indicate that expert writers achieve higher average performance."
8757,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,219,"Nature | Vol 650 | 26 February 2026 | 863 We leave a more detailed human analysis of citation accuracy, validity  and factuality for future work."
8758,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,220,Our evaluations were conducted by 16 PhD students and postdoc- toral professionals and we made an effort to align their expertise with  the evaluated topics.
8759,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,221,"However, because research often necessitates  deep domain knowledge, the annotators may not have captured more  nuanced differences for questions outside their immediate areas of  expertise."
8760,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,222,"Furthermore, these evaluations were based on 108 questions  that span three scientific disciplines, meaning that findings may not  fully generalize to other fields or domains."
8761,33,C033_S1_pdf.txt,223,"Online content Any methods, additional references, Nature Portfolio reporting summa- ries, source data, extended data, supplementary information, acknowl- edgements, peer review information; details of author contributions  and competing interests; and statements of data and code availability  are available at https://doi.org/10.1038/s41586-025-10072-4. 1."
