9089,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,0,"Journal of Further and Higher Education ISSN: 0309-877X (Print) 1469-9486 (Online) Journal homepage: www.tandfonline.com/journals/cjfh20 Use of artiﬁcial intelligence tools by doctoral students: a mixed-methods explanatory- sequential investigation Muhammad Naveed Akbar To cite this article: Muhammad Naveed Akbar (2025) Use of artiﬁcial intelligence tools by doctoral students: a mixed-methods explanatory-sequential investigation, Journal of Further and Higher Education, 49:7, 995-1013, DOI: 10.1080/0309877X.2025.2515135 To link to this article: https://doi.org/10.1080/0309877X.2025.2515135 © 2025 The Author(s)."
9090,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,1,"Published by Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group."
9091,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,2,Published online: 05 Jun 2025.
9092,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,3,"Submit your article to this journal  Article views: 5189 View related articles  View Crossmark data Citing articles: 5 View citing articles  Full Terms & Conditions of access and use can be found at Use of artificial intelligence tools by doctoral students: a  mixed-methods explanatory-sequential investigation Muhammad Naveed Akbar Interdisciplinary Science, Education, Technologies and Learning Research Group, School of Education,  University of Glasgow, Glasgow, UK ABSTRACT Increasing use of AI tools in higher education comes with a need to  develop a clear understanding of how students (by demography  and study discipline) employ them, for what purposes and in what  terms their use is evaluated."
9093,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,4,This will inform the development of  future guidelines and training for staff and students.
9094,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,5,"In the current  mixed-methods study, a cross-sectional survey was first adminis - tered to a convenience sample of 105 doctoral students (71  females, 34 males), followed by semi-structured interviews with  a subset of seven participants (four females, three males)."
9095,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,6,"This  had several aims; to identify patterns of AI tool use and its perceived  helpfulness; to explore AI use with regard to aspects of time man - agement, stress and study progress; to construct a predictive model  of AI tool use and to explore, in-depth, students’ views on beneficial  and problematic aspects of AI."
9096,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,7,Findings suggested AI was widely  used.
9097,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,8,"Males were more likely to use it for data analysis and research  planning, with greater use by students in non-scientific disciplines."
9098,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,9,Use was significantly related to stress and time management.
9099,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,10,Several potential benefits and problems were identified.
9100,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,11,"Benefits  included aiding research, for example, assisting and improving  coding/programming, use in proofreading and writing and as an  explanatory tool for rendering complex information accessible."
9101,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,12,"Potential problems included environmental cost, violation of intel - lectual property rights, provision of misleading and/or inaccurate  information and risks of plagiarism and hindered creativity."
9102,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,13,Limitations of the study are discussed alongside implications for  policy and training with suggestions for further work.
9103,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,14,"ARTICLE HISTORY  Received 29 January 2025  Accepted 29 May 2025  KEYWORDS  Postgraduates; AI; chatGPT;  benefits; problems Introduction In higher education it is recognised that staff and students benefit from competence in  information and communication technology (Almerich et al. 2020 ; Henderson, Finger, and  Selwyn 2016 ; Lee, Zawacki-Richter, and Cefa Sari 2024 )."
9104,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,15,"The higher education technolo - gical ecosystem is now facing novel challenges related to the development and introduc - tion of the latest generation of tools in artificial intelligence (AI), not least in relation to the  integrity of assessed work (Landers 2024 )."
9105,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,16,"The use of large language models, such as  CONTACT Muhammad Naveed Akbar   m.akbar.1@research.gla.ac.uk   Interdisciplinary Science, Education,  Technologies and Learning Research Group, School of Education, University of Glasgow, Glasgow, UK JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  2025, VOL. 49, NO. 7, 995–1013  © 2025 The Author(s)."
9106,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,17,"Published by Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group."
9107,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,18,"This is an Open Access article distributed under the terms of the Creative Commons Attribution License ( http://creativecommons.org/  licenses/by/4.0/ ), which permits unrestricted use, distribution, and reproduction in any medium, provided the original work is properly  cited."
9108,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,19,The terms on which this article has been published allow the posting of the Accepted Manuscript in a repository by the author(s) or  with their consent.
9109,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,20,"ChatGPT, which are based on principles of neurocomputation, has attracted interest and  concern in equal measure."
9110,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,21,"Despite this concern, an analysis of world leading universities  in several countries found that less than half had published guidelines for academics on  their use (Moorhouse, Yeo, and Wan 2023 )."
9111,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,22,"What is clear is that use of such AI tools in higher education is destined to increase, as  students become more aware of the potential benefits they offer in their discipline,  whether STEM or non-STEM based (Blease et al. 2021 ; Khanagar et al. 2021 ; Meron and  Araci 2023 ; Parviz 2024 ; Yilmaz et al. 2023 ; Yüzbaşıoğlu 2021 )."
9112,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,23,"Questionnaire and interview  studies with postgraduate students drawn from a wide range of countries – including  China (Xu et al. 2024 ), Ghana (Segbenya et al. 2023 ), Hungary (Tick et al. 2023 ), India  (Mohammed, Al-Ghazali, and Alqohfa 2023 ), Indonesia (Muslimin 2023 ), Morocco (A."
9113,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,24,"Bouzar, Idrissi, and Ghourdou 2024 ), Portugal (Costa, Costa, and Carvalho 2024 ) and  South Africa (Chauke et al. 2024 ) – suggest that ChatGPT is judged to be beneficial for  research planning, information searching, proofreading and academic writing."
9114,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,25,Work also  points to effects on research supervision ( Dai et al. 2023 ).
9115,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,26,"Current data suggest use of  ChatGPT is more favoured among high income groups (Baek, Tate, and Warschauer 2024 )."
9116,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,27,"Gender differences have also been observed in the manner in which AI is used, the ethical  concerns held towards its use (Møgelvang et al. 2024 ) and the frequency and amount of  time it is employed (A."
9117,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,28,Ghourdou 2024 ; Nyaaba et al. 2024 ).
9118,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,29,"Concerns over AI use: ethics, effects and performance The potential benefits of AI use aside, however, several concerns have been raised."
9119,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,30,"There  is evidence that ChatGPT use can be associated with delayed task initiation, thereby  affecting students’ customary time management practices (Bouzar, El Idrissi, and  Ghourdou 2024 )."
9120,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,31,"On this front, Abbas, Jam, and Khan ( 2024 ) have pointed to academic  workload and time pressure as factors precipitating students’ ChatGPT use."
9121,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,32,"Unease has  also been expressed about the potential for dependency, addiction and reduced creativity  in users (Das and Madhusudan 2024 ) as well as the ensuing problems of plagiarism and  plagiarism detection which may arise from its use (Bhullar, Joshi, and Chugh 2024 ; Hutson  2024 ; Landers 2024 ; Rasul et al. 2023 )."
9122,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,33,"In addition, the reliability and accuracy of output  generated by ChatGPT (Schei, Møgelvang, and Ludvigsen 2024 ; Vaishya et al. 2024 ; Xu  et al. 2024 ) has been questioned."
9123,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,34,These concerns are also shared by students (Shoufan 2023 ).
9124,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,35,Given the unsatis - factory ability of current assessment tools to detect plagiarism (Chaudhry et al.  2023 ) – and there is a steady growth in the availability of such tools (Wang et al.  2024 ) – data showing a high positive correlation between ChatGPT usage and  academic performance (e.g.
9125,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,36,"Khan and Fatima 2024 ), while inconclusive, do  little to allay concerns that the tools will be used inappropriately."
9126,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,37,This is evident in  recent work by Deng at al.
9127,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,38,"( 2024 ), the first systematic review and meta-analysis of  experimental studies ( N = 69) into the effect of ChatGPT on student learning."
9128,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,39,"This  reported evidence ChatGPT use was consistently associated with increased aca - demic performance, motivation and higher order thinking but reduced mental  effort, although these effects varied across subject areas."
9129,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,40,"The authors cautioned  that the documented improvements in academic performance may simply have  arisen as the direct result of ChatGPT’s role in producing higher quality work, as  996  M."
9130,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,41,AKBAR many of the studies included failed to exclude its use during the assessment of  academic performance.
9131,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,42,"Similarly, no objective tests of higher-order thinking were  used."
9132,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,43,It is also of note that the only study included in the analysis which assessed  originality (Niloy et al. 2023 ) found a detrimental effect.
9133,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,44,Rationale for current study If suitable guidelines and training for AI use are to be developed it will be helpful  to develop a broad picture of the various uses to which undergraduate and  postgraduate students are putting AI tools.
9134,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,45,"It will also be helpful to ascertain  which groups of students are using the tools, and for what specific purposes."
9135,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,46,"A recent survey indicates students’ use of AI has mushroomed, with the percen - tage reporting use of any AI tool jumping from 66% in 2024 to 92% in 2025."
9136,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,47,The  same survey reported that only 36% of students had received training in AI skills  from their institution (Freeman 2025 ).
9137,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,48,"It is clear that AI tools are being increasingly  adopted to assist with writing by scholars at all levels, adding to the ethical  concerns for educators and assessors (Segbenya et al. 2023 ) and lending weight  to the assertion that education has not kept pace with developments in AI (Razak,  Abdullah, and Ahmad 2024 )."
9138,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,49,"Given this widespread use, and the potential problems associated with it, it is impor - tant to understand students’ general perceptions of AI tool use, and the means by which  they evaluate it."
9139,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,50,"The current study, which was developed as part of a larger study into the  benefits and disadvantages of technology in doctoral education, therefore has several  specific aims."
9140,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,51,"(1) To identify patterns of AI tool use and perceived helpfulness of AI tools in doctoral  students by gender, age and study discipline."
9141,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,52,"(2) To explore AI use in relation to aspects of time management, stress and study  progress."
9142,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,53,(3) To develop a provisional predictive model of AI tool use.
9143,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,54,(4) To understand doctoral students’ perceptions of the advantages and disadvan - tages of AI tool use.
9144,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,55,Method Design An explanatory-sequential mixed-methods design was employed.
9145,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,56,"Initially, a cross-  sectional survey was administered to a convenience sample of 105 doctoral students  (71 females, 34 males)."
9146,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,57,This was hosted on the Online Survey platform (formerly BOS) and  organised in several sections.
9147,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,58,Data was gathered between June 2023 and May 2024.
9148,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,59,A more detailed description of the survey can be found in Akbar ( 2024 ).
9149,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,60,"This was followed  by a semi-structured interview with a subset of seven participants (four females, three  males)."
9150,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,61,"JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  997 Participants An opportunity sample of doctoral students was recruited by emails sent to the  Postgraduate Student Association in the Education Department of the University of the  author, and PhD supervisors and Heads of Department in departments of Education and  Psychology throughout the UK."
9151,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,62,These provided detailed information about the study and  requested recipients to forward the email to current PhD candidates.
9152,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,63,Each letter con - tained a live link to the survey.
9153,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,64,"Notices were also posted on Facebook, Twitter and  Instagram."
9154,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,65,"The sample for the present study ( N = 105; 71 females, mean age = 28.31, SD  = 4.60 and 34 males, mean age = 29.15, SD = 6.03) comprised those who responded  following the late addition to the survey of several questions about the use of AI tools  such as ChatGPT."
9155,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,66,"The majority of these were full-time ( N = 100, 95.2%)."
9156,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,67,"The largest group  of participants were Asian ( N = 34, 32.38%), followed by British ( N = 33, 31.4%) and  European ( N = 19, 18.09%)."
9157,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,68,"The majority were studying at UK universities ( N = 88,  83.81%) with a small percentage studying in universities based in Europe, the Americas  and Asia."
9158,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,69,A subset of participants who indicated their willingness to partake in further  study were recontacted and agreed to be interviewed in greater depth about their use of  technology.
9159,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,70,Details on these (with pseudonyms) are presented in Table 1 .
9160,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,71,"Materials and variables Demographic information collected comprised gender, age and academic discipline  studied."
9161,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,72,"The latter was recoded into a binary variable, science/non-science, in keeping  with Rockinson-Szapkiw et al’.s ( 2019 ) distinction between STEM and non-STEM subjects."
9162,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,73,"In addition to questions on general software use, data was collected on time manage - ment, perceived stress, perceived study progress and use of AI tools such as ChatGPT."
9163,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,74,Whether participants had ever used AI tools was assessed as a binary variable.
9164,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,75,"Assessment  of time management, perceived stress, perceived study progress and the perceived  helpfulness of AI tools were all measured on 5-point Likert scales by respondents’ level  of agreement with a series of statements (further details of the questions are given in  Akbar 2024 )."
9165,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,76,"For interviews, a semi-structured interview was first piloted and, following  modification, was used in the subsequent interviews."
9166,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,77,"Procedure and ethics On following the survey link, participants were presented with an initial information sheet  describing the study and its estimated completion time."
9167,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,78,They were then presented with  Table 1.
9168,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,79,Participants in the interview study.
9169,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,80,Participant Age Gender Field of Study S1 Frank 24 Male Chemistry S2 Helen 29 Female Psychology S3 Teng 24 Male Applied Linguistics S4 Nina 25 Female Psychology/Business S5 Diana 55 Female Music S6 Baris 42 Male Architecture S7 Cynthia 23 Female Aerospace Engineering 998  M.
9170,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,81,"After providing consent, they were directed to the survey."
9171,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,82,Estimated  completion time for this was approximately 45 minutes.
9172,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,83,A subset of participants who agreed to participate in further research were recontacted  following the survey and invited to take part in a semi-structured interview.
9173,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,84,Having  agreed to take part they were presented with a broad outline of potential topics to be  covered in the interview prior to its commencement.
9174,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,85,Interviews lasted between 45 and  90 minutes.
9175,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,86,Approval for the study was granted by the University Research Ethics Committee.
9176,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,87,"Consent to participate For both the survey and interview, respondents were informed that participation was  voluntary and that they could withdraw at any time, with any personal details supplied  being confidential."
9177,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,88,A digital consent form was provided for respondents to indicate they  had read and understood the information provided and agreed to take part.
9178,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,89,Quantitative analyses (1) Use of AI tools was cross-tabulated with gender and study discipline.
9179,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,90,The prob - ability of the observed results is given by Fisher’s exact p.
9180,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,91,"(2) Mann-Whitney U-tests were employed to assess differences in degree of help - fulness by use of AI tools, as well as by gender and study discipline (science v non-  science)."
9181,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,92,(3) Mann-Whitney U-tests assessed differences in perceived study progress by use of AI  tools.
9182,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,93,(4) AI use and degree of helpfulness of AI tools were correlated with age.
9183,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,94,"AI use was  also correlated with problems arising from spending time online (interferes with  exercise, interferes with social life, interferes with quality of sleep, interferes with  family life – these variables were assessed on a 5-point Likert scale)."
9184,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,95,"(5) A logistic regression was computed for use of AI tools, with gender, study disci - pline, perceived stress and several variables concerned with spending time online  (interferes with exercise, interferes with social life, interferes with quality of sleep  and interferes with family life) entered as predictor variables."
9185,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,96,Gender and study  discipline were entered as categorical variables.
9186,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,97,All analyses were conducted in SPSS v28.
9187,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,98,Thematic analysis of interview data Interview data was subjected to reflexive thematic analysis (Braun and Clarke 2006 ; Clarke  and Braun 2017 ).
9188,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,99,"The method’s pioneers, Braun and Clarke, consider it an accessible,  pragmatic form of data analysis which proceeds as an organic process which ‘happens at  the intersection of you and your data, and your reflexivity, your subjectivity, your dis - ciplinary and social context’ (Coxon, Clarke, and Braun 2022 , 41)."
9189,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,100,"Consequently, the  researcher brings to the analysis their own knowledge of the context in which participants  are located."
9190,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,101,"After transcribing the interviews, the researcher first familiarised themselves  JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  999 with the data, carefully reading and re-reading each transcript, creating notes and  a summary of the impressions from each interview."
9191,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,102,"Once an overview of an interview  had been obtained, data were assigned initial codes."
9192,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,103,Transcriptions were subject to both  descriptive coding – highlighting important aspects of participants’ experiences – as well  as linguistic coding – focusing on the lexicon and meaning of the language used.
9193,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,104,"Finally,  conceptual coding involved interpreting the data in context, with similar and related  codes clustered together to produce themes, leading to a deeper semantic understand - ing."
9194,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,105,Ideas and key words which were noted signalled the emergent themes and these  were written down.
9195,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,106,"This procedure was repeated for each transcript, with the researcher  then considering the transcripts as a whole, identifying common ideas and the connec - tions between them."
9196,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,107,"Key themes were then tabulated, with quotations and participants’  names (anonymised) recorded next to each theme."
9197,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,108,"For the current paper, only those  themes directly pertinent to the use of artificial intelligence are presented and discussed."
9198,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,109,"Results Almost two-thirds of the respondents (N = 69, 65.7%) reported having used AI tools."
9199,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,110,"The  proportions of males (N = 23, 67.6%) and females (N = 43, 64.8%) using them were similar."
9200,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,111,"Of these, a large majority (N = 56, 81.16%) indicated they found them to be helpful or very  helpful."
9201,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,112,Only four respondents (5.8%) reported it as very unhelpful.
9202,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,113,"The tools were most  frequently used for assistance with proofreading (N = 34, 49.28%), academic writing (N =  28, 40.58%), generation of ideas (N = 27, 39.13%) and literature reviews (N = 23, 33.33%),  with evidence of gender differences in their use (see Table 2 )."
9203,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,114,"Males were significantly  more likely than females (35.29% cf. 8.45%, Odds Ratio = 4.18, Fisher’s Exact p = .0015) to  employ it for data analysis and marginally significantly more likely to use it for research  planning (17.65% cf. 5.62%, Odds Ratio = 3.13, Fisher’s Exact p = 0.074)."
9204,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,115,Purpose for which AI tools were used by gender.
9205,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,116,N Males (N = 34) Females (N = 71) Literature Review 23 10 (29.41%) 13 (18.31) Data Analysis** 18 12 (35.29%) 6 (8.45%) Idea Generation 27 7 (20.59%) 20 (28.17%) Writing Research Proposals 10 2 (5.88%) 8 (11.27%) Academic Writing 28 8 (23.53%) 20 (28.17%) Proofreading 34 10 (29.41%) 24 (33.80%) Designing Questionnaire Items 5 3 (8.82%) 2 (2.81%) Research Planning* 10 6 (17.65%) 4 (5.63%) ** p < 0.01 * p < 0.10.
9206,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,117,Purpose for which AI tools were used by study discipline.
9207,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,118,N Science (N = 87) Non-Science (N = 17) Literature Review 23 17 (19.54%) 6 (35.3%) Data Analysis 18 16 (18.39%) 2 (11.76%) Idea Generation 27 21 (24.14%) 6 (35.29%) Writing Research Proposals 10 8 (9.19%) 2 (11.76%) Academic Writing 28 21 (24.13%) 7 (41.18%) Proofreading 34 26 (29.89%) 8 (47.06%) Designing Questionnaire Items 5 4 (4.60%) 1 (5.88%) Research Planning 10 8 (9.19%) 2 (11.76%) 1000  M.
9208,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,119,"AKBAR Age was not significantly related with use of AI tools (rho = −0.01, p = 0.96), nor with  how helpful they were judged to be (rho = −0.03, p = 0.81)."
9209,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,120,There was a suggestion of  differences in use by academic discipline (see Table 3 ).
9210,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,121,"For example, non-science students  (N = 14, 82.4%) were almost three times more likely to report their use than science  students (N = 55, 63.2%; Odds Ratio = 2.72, Fisher’s Exact p = 0.10)."
9211,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,122,These differences  appeared to pertain to non-science students being more likely to use the tools for  academic writing (42.18% cf. 24.13%) and proofreading (47.06% cf. 29.89%).
9212,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,123,"In terms of helpfulness, those using AI tools reported them as being significantly more  helpful than those who didn’t (3.93, cf. 3.00; Mann-Whitney U = 16,Z = −2.07, p = 0.039)."
9213,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,124,"In  addition, males gave higher ratings than females (4.17, cf. 3.76), though this difference  was not significant (Mann-Whitney U = 447, Z = −1.47, p = 0.14)."
9214,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,125,"There was no significant  difference between science and non-science students (3.96, cf. 3.64; Mann-Whitney U =  355, Z =−0.60, p = 0.55)."
9215,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,126,"Correlates of AI use Use of AI tools was significantly positively correlated with spending time online, interfering  with exercise (rho = 0.21, p = 0.037) and with social life (rho = 0.21, p = 0.037)."
9216,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,127,"The relation - ship with spending time online interferes with quality of sleep (rho = −0.18, p = 0.066) was  marginally significant – AI use being associated with less interference."
9217,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,128,"The relationship with  spending time online affects my family life was not significant (rho = 0.08, p = 0.41)."
9218,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,129,"In addition, AI tool use was negatively correlated with level of self-reported stress (rho  = −0.17, p = 0.09)."
9219,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,130,A clearer picture of this relationship comes from cross-tabulating  perceived stress with use of AI tools.
9220,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,131,Data from two participants who reported no stress  were excluded owing to low expected frequencies.
9221,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,132,This left a cross-tabulation between  low/high levels of stress and use of AI.
9222,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,133,This was highly significant (Fisher exact p = 0.0046).
9223,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,134,The relationship is shown in Figure 1 .
9224,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,135,"As can be seen, those using AI tools were more likely  to report moderate stress (71.6%, cf. 28.6%), with those not using AI tools more likely to  report high stress (71.4% cf. 28.4%)."
9225,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,136,"AI tool use was not significantly related to perceived  study progress (Mann-Whitney U = 1097, Z = −1.05, p = 0.30). 71.6 28.428.6 71.4 0 10 20 30 40 50 60 70 80 Yes No Percentage Use of AI Tools Moderate Stress High Stress Figure 1."
9226,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,137,Use of AI tools by level of stress.
9227,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,138,"JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  1001 Modelling AI use The logistic regression model was significant ( χ 2 (7) = 25.80 p < 0.001; Hosmer and  Lemeshow χ 2 (8) = 7.19, p = 0.52) explaining between 23.1% and 32.1% of the  variance in AI use (Cox and Snell R 2  = 0.231, Nagelkerke R 2 = 0.321)."
9228,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,139,"The model  correctly classified 78.6% of the cases (AI use, 87.7%, non-use, 60.6%)."
9229,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,140,"Study  discipline was significant (Wald χ 2  = 4.07, p = 0.044, Odds Ratio = 5.58; Figure 2 )."
9230,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,141,"Non-science students were over five times more likely to use AI than science  students, whilst lower perceived stress almost doubled the likelihood of using AI  (Wald χ 2  = 4.69, p = 0.03, Odds Ratio = 1.87, Figure 3 )."
9231,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,142,"Spending time online affects  my social life was also significant, each unit increase raising the likelihood of AI use  by a factor of 3 (Wald χ 2  = 6.61, p = 0.01, Odds Ratio = 3.07)."
9232,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,143,Two further variables  were marginally significant.
9233,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,144,"Spending time online affects my family life (Wald χ 2  =  3.35, p = 0.067, Odds Ratio = 0.54) and Spending time online interferes with my  sleep (Wald χ 2  = 3.35, p = 0.067, Odds Ratio = 0.57)."
9234,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,145,"For the latter variable, AI use  was associated with less disruption."
9235,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,146,"Spending time online interferes with exercise  was no longer significant (Wald χ 2  = 1.10, p = 0.29)."
9236,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,147,"Results of thematic analysis The interviews produced two contrasting themes concerning students’ use of ChatGPT,  one detailing its beneficial aspects, the other, a range of problems associated with its use."
9237,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,148,Probability of use of AI tools by study discipline. 1002  M.
9238,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,149,"AKBAR Artificial intelligence as beneficial Positive evaluations given were that ChatGPT could be employed to aid programming,  assist in the use of statistical tests and help with academic writing and the synthesis of  large quantities of information."
9239,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,150,Two respondents referred to aiding coding/programming.
9240,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,151,"One of them, Cynthia, described how she used the tool, first, for detecting errors (debug - ging) in her coding, I usually use ChatGPT, mostly . . ."
9241,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,152,I use it as an assistant for codes problems.
9242,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,153,"So say that there is  a there is a few lines of code that are causing me an error and I’ve tried to debug it, but I’m still not."
9243,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,154,I’m still getting the same errors.
9244,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,155,"Then I’m usually going to ask ChatGPT, or when it’s about tedious  formatting, perhaps shifting from coding results to latex for publications, I’m I usually ask ChatGPT  to create a table for me, or so, you know, tabulate data or check codes."
9245,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,156,"(Cynthia, lines 276–280) And, secondly, for generating code from mathematic notation."
9246,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,157,So I just go by math myself . . .
9247,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,158,"I explain the problem that I have to ChatGPT using, using math  language, and say, given that I want to formulate this, how would you do it?"
9248,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,159,"And then  sometimes it’ll give me, it will spit out the first iteration."
9249,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,160,"(Cynthia, lines 297–299) Another student, Teng, also enlisted ChatGPT for coding, as well as for helping him to  choose appropriate statistical tools for analysing data. . . . with ChatGPT, it will gave me some guidance, and also some clues to start and also, like  I said, also for coding, especially I don’t have any backgrounds for coding and stats, it gave me  lots of clues how to code and how."
9250,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,161,"(Teng, lines 306–308) In addition to these recognisably technical applications, he was enthusiastic about how it  could help him with academic writing as well as synthesising and summarising informa - tion from academic sources."
9251,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,162,"However, in his view, it still required human input to make  the most of it."
9252,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,163,Probability of use of AI tools by level of perceived stress.
9253,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,164,"JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  1003 And second is, it helped me a lot to, you know, revise my abstract writing, because English is  my second language, I inevitably write something that's not appropriate for academic  English."
9254,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,165,So it helped me to revise and change my language.
9255,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,166,"And sometimes, you know, the  word limits may be like 200 words, and I write 500 and I like let ChatGPT help me to shorten  my passage."
9256,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,167,"(Teng, lines 553–557) I still think chat GPT for now can only do some simple or baby step work, but for like reading  articles, synthesize and summarize tons of tons of references."
9257,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,168,It still needs human work to do.
9258,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,169,"(Teng, lines 806–808) These comments are consistent with reports in existing literature (Blease et al. 2021 ;  Khanagar et al. 2021 ; Parviz 2024 ; Yilmaz et al. 2023 ) of a variety of benefits that AI can  offer students."
9259,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,170,Artificial intelligence as problematic Doctoral students’ assessment of AI as potentially problematic was more extensive than  its ostensibly beneficial uses.
9260,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,171,There was a long list of potential problems which respon - dents either foresaw or had directly experienced themselves – many of which highlight  issues previously raised by researchers.
9261,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,172,"These were grouped into four broad sub-themes:  the production of inaccurate or misleading information (Schei, Møgelvang, and Ludvigsen  2024 ), detrimental effect on creativity (Das and Madhusudan 2024 ) with an attendant risk  of plagiarism (Hutson 2024 ), environmental cost and the violation of intellectual property  rights."
9262,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,173,Example comments from participants under each of these headings can be found  here.
9263,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,174,Inaccurate or misleading information The production of inaccurate references by ChatGPT was frequently mentioned by  participants.
9264,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,175,"The following comments from Cynthia, Nina and Frank are typical of the  problems encountered."
9265,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,176,"It’s not really the best idea to ask ChatGPT for guarantees, because it can make up sources."
9266,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,177,It  can make up papers that do not really exist.
9267,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,178,"It will even give you some unique things like DOIs  and ISBN, in case it’s books . . ."
9268,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,179,I don’t really believe too much what ChatGPT tells me.
9269,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,180,"(Cynthia,  lines 453–455, 473) I did run into some issues with ChatGPT."
9270,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,181,It happened once or twice to me that ChatGPT  invented references that I just couldn’t find.
9271,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,182,"(Nina, lines 296–297) I found that the answers that the ChatGPT gave me, they were not like, very scientific or yes or  I found that they like the references that ChatGPT, you said they were not like that good."
9272,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,183,"(Frank, lines 245–247) As can be seen, the questionable referencing supplied by ChatGPT led some to question  its usability if not to cease using it outright. 1004  M."
9273,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,184,AKBAR Detrimental effect on creativity and risk of plagiarism Helen was the most vocal of those interviewed when it came to views on the creative  limitations of AI and the potential problems for students seeking to do novel work.
9274,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,185,"Artificial intelligence cannot do . . . it cannot generate new knowledge, so artificial intelli - gence will replicate all the knowledge and all the arguments that are already existing out  there."
9275,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,186,"So if you’re doing something new and you’re trying to, let’s say, for example, say that  pitch iced tea is good for your eyesight, and there is no evidence around that you it."
9276,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,187,AI cannot  write an essay about that because it’s novel.
9277,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,188,"It hasn’t been done before, and it want to know  how to connect, or how to link the arguments, so you can see whatever the novel ideas in the  writing that actually this novel argument here belongs to the student, because AI cannot  synthesize it, because it doesn’t have this connection previously in the literature."
9278,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,189,"(Helen, lines  2473, 2480) In this she was supported by Nina, who considered not only the potential motivation  underpinning the sacrifice of one’s own thinking but also costs incurred when favouring  machine generated output."
9279,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,190,"I think that’s definitely a risk that comes with generative AI and then obviously independent  thinking, critical thinking, maybe sometimes it’s easier to ask ChatGPT for ideas than trying to  come up with your own . . ."
9280,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,191,"Maybe they’re not as good, they’re not as creative."
9281,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,192,"And  so I think it will probably, I could imagine that it reduces our patience a little bit in the long  run, and we’re just after a really quick response for something, so we fall back onto ChatGPT,  for example, rather than putting in our own cognitive efforts."
9282,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,193,"(Nina, lines 358–363) The issue of reduced self-reliance and thinking for oneself and potential self-harm result - ing from use of ChatGPT was also raised in moments of honest, self-criticism by Teng as  well as Diana."
9283,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,194,"Sometimes I feel myself very rely too much, rely on that software, like I cannot think by myself,  or sometimes I need to for think by myself, because, you know, you have a tool, very efficient,  and he can just pop up a question, they will give you an answer immediately, rather than  think by yourself and do more training by your own brain."
9284,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,195,"(Teng, lines 347–350) I’m still worried about using it as a shortcut for processes that actually are meant to be  difficult . . . worried it will deskill me . . ."
9285,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,196,I worry that it’s changing the way I think.
9286,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,197,"(Diana, lines  664–665, 704, 714) Diana went further and remarked how the issue of plagiarism surrounding use of ChatGPT  not only caused students a great deal of trouble but also risked the loss of something she  saw as fundamentally human in the quest for knowledge."
9287,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,198,"And I, you know, it’s causing lots of trouble for undergraduates, particular, particularly, it  seems to be causing lots of trouble."
9288,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,199,"(Diana, lines 2829–2830) But AI, as sophisticated and wonderful as it is, isn’t human thought."
9289,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,200,"And the ability to think  sideways without linear connections is a is a uniquely human thing, and I don’t ever want to  lose that."
9290,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,201,"(Diana, lines 767–768) Environmental cost Two respondents, Amanda and Cynthia, questioned the environmental burden of gen - erative artificial intelligence and with it the economic cost."
9291,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,202,"JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  1005 . . . there are serious problems with the information that you get by asking questions of  generative AI, also like the carbon impact . . . and ask a program like open AI or ChatGPT  a question is like, the greenhouse gas emissions from that are like a year’s worth of regular  server information generation."
9292,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,203,"(Amanda, lines 423–425) There is always a price to pay . . . even though the price may not be directly your like  money out of your pocket."
9293,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,204,"How are these websites still running where, where servers have  a cost, even, even assuming that they have their own servers, which is very unlikely, the  cost of electricity is still pretty expensive if you’re running a server."
9294,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,205,"(Cynthia, lines  1290–1292) These same two individuals were also vocal about the costs of generative AI with respect  to creative workers’ intellectual property rights."
9295,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,206,"Violation of intellectual property rights The ethical concerns of Amanda, who had previously voiced her unease about the  implications of generative AI for the climate, extended to the potential violation of  intellectual property rights."
9296,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,207,"At several points in the interview, she discussed this at  some length, covering issues of consent, the untraceable nature of data sources AI relies  upon and the legality of the means by which AI engines are trained."
9297,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,208,"I have concerns with, like, the training databases that OpenAI uses for their generative AI, and  that, like people did not consent for their intellectual property to be used in it."
9298,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,209,"(Amanda, lines  51–52) She went on to say, . . . and on top of that, the data that OpenAI uses, you can’t trace it back to its sources, and  they’re using the intellectual property of people like me, yeah, without our consent."
9299,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,210,"(Amanda,  lines 463–464) There are serious ethical concerns with like, you’re legally not entitled to just scrape anyone’s  information off of the internet and then use it for for-profit enterprises, like there are copy - right and intellectual property laws across the world that say that you’re not allowed to do  that, and the people in charge of OpenAI have admitted that they’re not able to verify that all  of the information used in their training databases, in their training sets, has been appro - priately sourced."
9300,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,211,"(Amanda, lines 478–482) Her final reflections in this area expanded on the potential unsanctioned use of her own  intellectual property."
9301,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,212,I have a website where I write about public health topics.
9302,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,213,"OpenAI can take that intellectual  property that I have created, is my ideas and my science and my learning and my words, and  they can use that in their training database, and they then use that to answer the questions or  respond to the queries, the generative queries that people are requesting."
9303,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,214,"I have not  consented to my data being used in that way, and that is fundamentally different than  what happens when someone Googles something, and one of the results for that search is an  article that I published."
9304,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,215,"(Amanda, lines, 503–508) Some of these worries were shared by Cynthia."
9305,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,216,She spoke about her understanding of the  different rights which exist in Europe and the United States for people whose work may  be appropriated for training AI models. 1006  M.
9306,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,217,"AKBAR And, and this is, this is a more like, these are comment about Meta."
9307,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,218,"I remember  when early June, they released that they were going to use whatever was published to train  their own the Meta AI model."
9308,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,219,"And, you know, in in the you’re in the Eurozone, it was possible  to opt out, but in the US, it was not really possible."
9309,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,220,"(Cynthia, lines 1306–1309) She described her own unsuccessful attempt to opt out from having her work used in  this way."
9310,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,221,"Because as soon as I found out that they were doing this, I wanted to try to opt out, but  I couldn’t."
9311,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,222,"(Amanda, lines 1315–1316) Discussion AI tools were used by a majority of survey respondents and for a variety of purposes."
9312,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,223,"These included proofreading, academic writing, idea generation, reviewing literature,  data analysis and research planning."
9313,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,224,This has some overlap with the uses documented  in several existing studies (e.g.
9314,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,225,Chauke et al. 2024 ; Segbenya et al. 2023 ).
9315,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,226,"The finding that  non-science-based students were more likely to report it was surprising, given that most  literature has been concerned with the application of AI in STEM subjects (e.g."
9316,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,227,"Khan and Fatima 2024 ; Deng et al., 2024 ), there was  no evidence in the current study that use of AI tools was associated with study progress."
9317,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,228,"Given the rapid appearance of the tools, however, this may well change, as students  become more familiar with them and more accomplished in their use."
9318,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,229,"Previous findings of  gender differences in AI use (Møgelvang et al. 2024 ) were supported, with the present  study finding that males were more likely to employ it for data analysis and research  planning."
9319,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,230,"Given the predominantly female orientation of the interview sample, further  research will be necessary to discover if any of the issues raised in the interviews reflect  genuine gender differences in how AI is evaluated."
9320,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,231,"Overall, doctoral students’ use of AI tools such as ChatGPT was associated with  reporting less stress and less disruption to sleep, both of which may be consistent with  the tools promoting better time management."
9321,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,232,"However, time spent online disrupting  social life was also associated with greater AI tool use and, together with A."
9322,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,233,"Ghourdou ( 2024 ), findings that ChatGPT use is associated with delaying  work is suggestive of negative effects on time management."
9323,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,234,Any putative benefits of AI  use on stress reduction therefore requires further replication.
9324,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,235,"Increased self-efficacy,  efficiency and motivation, as well as reduced time spent on assignments are just some  of the means through which this might be achieved."
9325,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,236,"Overall, the significant effects  observed in the regression point to increased AI use being associated with both favour - able and unfavourable factors operating in doctoral students’ lives."
9326,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,237,"This poses challenges  to any practical attempts to modify AI usage through stress reduction, though these may  be clarified by identifying what kinds of AI use, and its appropriateness, are associated  with both stress and time spent online being disruptive."
9327,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,238,Contrary to work which has shown a high positive correlation between ChatGPT  usage and academic performance (B.
9328,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,239,"Khan and Fatima 2024 ), the present study  found no significant relationship with study progress."
9329,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,240,"These contrasting findings  may reflect different patterns of AI use between undergraduate and postgraduate  students, as well as differences in the nature of undergraduate and postgraduate  JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  1007 assessment."
9330,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,241,"Overall use of AI appears to be moderately predictable, although  analysis with larger samples will be necessary to confirm the accuracy of the  current estimates."
9331,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,242,The interviews supplied additional evidence that AI may aid the conduct of  research.
9332,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,243,"Respondents mentioned help with coding, guidance in choosing statis - tical tests, assistance with both academic writing and the assimilation of large  amounts of information."
9333,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,244,All these may enable tasks to be completed more rapidly.
9334,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,245,"However, the interviews also provided evidence of student unease suggesting that  AI tools may potentially impede not only well-being, but also efficiency and under - standing."
9335,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,246,"The first of these concerns was connected to the risk of plagiarism  (Hutson 2024 ), followed by unhappiness about the unreliability of ChatGPT output  (Schei, Møgelvang, and Ludvigsen 2024 )."
9336,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,247,"Added to these were fears about the  effects of repeated use of AI on one’s own creative capacity, an issue which Das  and Madhusudan ( 2024 ) have reported and which Niloy et al."
9337,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,248,( 2023 ) have pro - duced experimental evidence to support.
9338,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,249,"To these were added consideration of the  potential violation of intellectual property rights, now that, as doctoral students,  their own work may be subject to the data sweeps of major tech companies."
9339,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,250,"These  latter two issues position doctoral students as participants in acts of reciprocal  exploitation – first of all in becoming dependent on AI to conduct one’s intellec - tual work and, secondly, having one’s own intellectual work exploited by AI  developers."
9340,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,251,A reminder perhaps that there is no such thing as an academic free  lunch.
9341,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,252,"Finally, the question of the environmental and energy footprint of AI use was raised by  some of the respondents."
9342,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,253,It has been estimated that the power consumption of  a ChatGPT enquiry is approximately 10 times greater than a traditional Google search  (de Vries 2023 ).
9343,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,254,This is clearly an issue which educational institutions must address as AI  use grows.
9344,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,255,"Limitations The relatively small sample size, together with the fact that most of the survey respon - dents were drawn from UK universities, may limit the generalisability of the findings."
9345,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,256,"However, with AI use in universities now a global phenomenon, it is likely that the issues  and motivations underlying it have much in common no matter where it is employed,  although the manner in which it is used is likely to vary with study discipline  (Schei et al. 2024 )."
9346,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,257,"Undoubtedly, further cross-cultural research is required to identify  any significant differences in the patterns of use."
9347,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,258,"As the current survey data is cross-sectional, the findings concerning stress are con - sistent both with use of AI tools acting to reduce academic stress and facilitate changes in  time management, and with the possibility that those who are less stressed to begin with  and who may already possess better time management skills are more likely to use AI  tools."
9348,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,259,"Again, further research of a longitudinal nature will be required to clarify the nature  of causal relationships. 1008  M."
9349,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,260,"AKBAR Conclusions Research In conclusion, this study provides some of the first available evidence on the use of  artificial intelligence by postgraduate students."
9350,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,261,This is consistent with work show - ing they hold positive views towards its use (Chan and Hu 2023 ) but also high - lights areas of concern which point to significant issues relevant to how higher  education institutions prepare current and future scholars for what is rapidly  becoming a very different academic world.
9351,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,262,"The picture emerging from the present  study points to a need for further work to firm up the existing evidence base, to  establish what patterns of use exist across demographic groups, to determine the  psychological and pedagogical consequences for students of this use and to apply  such knowledge to the development and evaluation of appropriate guidelines,  policy and training."
9352,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,263,Higher education policy on artificial intelligence Although Dempere et al.
9353,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,264,"( 2023 ) argue there is a pressing need for the regulation of  artificial intelligence in higher education institutions, no universally agreed guidelines  exist on how to deal with it."
9354,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,265,"( 2024 ) have suggested that policy must  encompass four main aspects – accepting the presence of generative AI, aligning this  with learning objectives, developing curriculum to prevent misuse and adopting a range  of evaluation strategies, alongside discipline-specific policies and guidelines."
9355,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,266,"Though  laudable, these aspirations remain vague with no clarity as to how they will be achieved."
9356,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,267,Reliable and consistent AI detection remains out of reach.
9357,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,268,"The present study suggests that  prospective students would benefit from being informed about the limitations of gen - erative AI, as well as the risks it poses to accuracy, originality, creativity and fostering  dependence."
9358,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,269,"It would also do no harm to outline the threat which training AI models  poses to intellectual property rights, as on current trends doctoral students’ own future  work is likely to be utilised by such models without their consent."
9359,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,270,"Finally, while sustainability is recognised as having strategic importance in higher  education (S."
9360,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,271,"Khan et al. 2025 ), there is as yet no clear evidence that the energy  consumption of large language models utilised by researchers – as well as by under - graduates – is being factored into institutional policies on sustainability, even as higher  education institutions develop guidelines and recommend its integration into existing  curricula (McDonald et al. 2024 )."
9361,35,C035_P1_pdf.txt,272,"It is difficult to disagree with Sok and Heng ( 2024 )  acknowledgement that, while there is a shortage of evidence regarding how best to  embed generative AI in higher education, it is perhaps best to proceed on the basis of  practice-and-learn, with appropriate reflection on how best to appraise students’ work  and limit its environmental impact."
