9589,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,0,"Predicting Field Experiments with Large Language Models Yaoyu Chen1 Yuheng Hu1 Yingda Lu1 1The Department of Information and Decision Sciences, College of Business Administration, University of Illinois at Chicago {ychen563, yuhenghu, yingdalu}@uic.com Abstract Large language models (LLMs) have demonstrated unprecedented emergent capabilities, including content generation, translation, and simulation of human behavior."
9590,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,1,"Field experiments, on the other hand, are widely employed in social studies to examine real-world human behavior through carefully designed manipulations and treatments."
9591,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,2,"However, field experiments are known to be expensive and time consuming."
9592,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,3,"Therefore, an interesting question is whether and how LLMs can be utilized for field experiments."
9593,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,4,"In this paper, we propose and evaluate an automated LLM-based framework to predict the outcomes of a field experiment."
9594,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,5,Applying this framework to 276 experiments about a wide range of human behaviors drawn from renowned economics literature yields a prediction accuracy of 78%.
9595,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,6,"Moreover, we find that the distributions of the results are either bimodal or highly skewed."
9596,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,7,"By investigating this abnormality further, we identify that field experiments related to complex social issues such as ethnicity, social norms, and ethical dilemmas can pose significant challenges to the prediction performance."
9597,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,8,CCS Concepts •Information systems → Collaborative and social computing systems and tools.
9598,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,9,"Keywords Large Language Models, Field Experiments 1 Introduction Field experiments allow researchers to manipulate variables of inter- est in a real-world setting, such as human behaviors like ad clicking or donation giving, establishing causal relationships between in- terventions and outcomes."
9599,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,10,"They typically begin by designing an intervention aligned with a specific research question, randomly assigning participants to treatment or control groups, and then measuring outcomes under natural conditions."
9600,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,11,The resulting data are collected and analyzed to evaluate the causal impact of the intervention [27].
9601,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,12,"It is adopted by a wide range of disciplines across academia and industry, such as finance [5, 14], marketing [17, 28], and organizational studies [ 23, 31]."
9602,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,13,"In recent years, online field experiments, also known as A/B testing, have revolutionized nu- merous online platform designs, advertising strategies, etc."
9603,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,14,"While effective, field experiments are also known to be expensive and time consuming."
9604,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,15,"For example, some experiments may take months or years to conduct [35]."
9605,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,16,"Moreover, recruiting high-quality partici- pants for the experiments is challenging and costly [3], potentially affecting the experiment’s outcomes."
9606,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,17,"In recent years, Large language models (LLMs) have demon- strated unprecedented emergent capabilities, including content generation, translation, and simulation of human behavior."
9607,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,18,"For example, existing studies have explored the alignments between simulated data generated by LLMs and real data collected from human participants across various aspects, including human re- sponses, traits [16], moral standards [13], preferences [36], and emo- tions [18]."
9608,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,19,"Therefore, it is becoming increasingly popular to lever- age LLMs for simulating human behaviors [19, 48]."
9609,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,20,"For example, there are a handful of studies in which scholars have successfully instructed LLMs to replicate existing lab experiments across several disciplines, including psychology [2, 11], sociology [22, 26, 34], and economics [2, 24]."
9610,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,21,Their aim is to replicate existing lab experiments by treating LLMs as participants in lab experiments.
9611,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,22,"However, directly applying these works to field experiment sim- ulations in our context has several challenges."
9612,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,23,"First, they mainly focused on lab experiment settings."
9613,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,24,"But field experiments are in- herently more challenging to conduct than laboratory experiments, due to diverse participant backgrounds, complex workflows, and multifaceted treatment designs."
9614,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,25,"Second, most of the previous stud- ies mainly relied on manual processes, and because of that, tested a handful of experiments with a limited scope of topics."
9615,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,26,"While some recent studies tested on relatively large data, the selected experiments were limited to Likert-based psychological or social surveys [11, 22]."
9616,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,27,"In order to explore LLMs’ capabilities, robustness, and generalizability in field experiment simulation, we need to test them on a much larger scale and broader range of experiments on different topics."
9617,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,28,"In this paper, we fill the literature gap by proposing an auto- mated LLM framework to predict the outcome of a wide range of field experiments."
9618,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,29,"Our framework has several major components, such as an information extraction module, a variant generation module, and a prediction module."
9619,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,30,"Specifically, the information ex- traction module extracts key experiment settings, while the variant generation module generates false variants as distractors to con- fuse LLMs."
9620,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,31,"Finally, the prediction modules leverage two prompt templates with a Chain-of-Thought design, prompting the LLM to predict the outcomes of a field experiment."
9621,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,32,We test this framework on 276 field experiments reported in premier academic journals from 2000 to 2024.
9622,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,33,"Those experiments contain a total of 1261 conclusions with a wide range of topics such as labor-market discrimination, educational incentives, house- hold finance behavior, and the impact of healthcare enrollment."
9623,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,34,"Without any alignment techniques or fine-tuning, our framework achieves an average prediction accuracy of 78%."
9624,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,35,"We also test for data memorization effects by examining prediction results on re- cent experiments that appeared in 2024, which would be less likely to be included in the training data of LLMs."
9625,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,36,"More interestingly, we also find that the prediction results are either bimodal or highly skewed."
9626,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,37,"For example, our framework achieves nearly 100% predic- tion accuracy on 71% of conclusions while it completely fails to arXiv:2504.01167v3 [cs.CY] 21 May 2025 SLW, August 6th, 2025, Toronto Yaoyu Chen1 Yuheng Hu1 Yingda Lu1 1The Department of Information and Decision Sciences, College of Business Administration, University of Illinois at Chicago {ychen563, yuhenghu, yingdalu}@uic.com predict 18% of the conclusions with close to 0% accuracy."
9627,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,38,"Further analyses reveal that our LLM-based framework has limitations in predicting experiments related to complex social issues such as ethnicity, social norms, and ethical dilemmas."
9628,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,39,Our research makes several contributions: 1 We extend the current literature on LLMs’ emergent capa- bilities by demonstrating that LLMs can simulate field ex- periments by predicting conclusions.
9629,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,40,"While using LLMs to simulate human behavior is well studied in recent years, to the best of our knowledge, this is the first work in the litera- ture to replicate large-scale field experiments that require a more complex environment setting and workflow design. 2 Our proposed framework enables the prediction of field ex- periment conclusions in a fully automated, large-scale fash- ion."
9630,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,41,"As a result, our framework is robust and can be gener- alized to a wider range of downstream applications in field experiments. 3 This paper examines the prediction performance and reveals the limitations of LLMs in field experiment simulations. 2 Literature Review Our study is related to the LLM literature on simulating human behavior, with a particular focus on experimental simulations by LLMs."
9631,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,42,"Here, we highlight our contributions by comparing and contrasting our work with existing studies."
9632,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,43,"While past literature mainly focused on agent-based social sim- ulation [9, 45, 49], there is an increasing trend to adopt LLMs as simulation tools."
9633,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,44,"Existing studies have found that LLMs’ ability to simulate human behavior stems from their possession of human- like reasoning skills and their adaptivity to personas of diverse characters [40, 43]."
9634,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,45,"Upon those features of LLMs, Aher et al. [ 2] proposed the concept of ""Turing Experiment"", in which LLMs are profiled as synthetic participants of experiments with integrated prompt of experimental settings and demographic information."
9635,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,46,"Similarly, Horton [24] demonstrated LLMs’ ability to simulate lab experiments and promoted it as a method of experimental pilot test- ing."
9636,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,47,"The usage of LLMs in Horton [24]’s work is similar to Aher et al. [2], consisting of two stages: prompting LLMs as synthetic exper- imental participants and collecting responses from conversations, reporting a few successful simulation cases of lab experiments."
9637,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,48,"Leng & Yuan [26] harnessed a three-phase procedure to complete the lab experimental simulation, which includes the initialization phase, interaction phase, and decision analysis phase."
9638,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,49,"In the initialization phase, separate conversations of GPT-4 are prompted as vanilla experimental participants without specifying demographic infor- mation."
9639,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,50,"Then, in the interaction stage, synthetic participants are prompted with the actions of other participants and asked to take actions and rationales according to the experiment design."
9640,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,51,"Last, agents’ actions and rationales are collected for analysis to conclude."
9641,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,52,"Leveraging this procedure, the study simulates five existing lab ex- periments."
9642,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,53,Manning et al. [34] proposed an automated framework for various lab experimental simulations.
9643,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,54,"Although the entire work- flow is divided into seven steps, it is essentially similar to the manual procedures of the three papers above."
9644,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,55,"However, the sole input is the backstory of the experiment."
9645,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,56,"Based on the input information and powered by an LLM, the framework continues with subsequent steps: identifying dependent and independent variables, generating treatment values, profiling agents, organizing the interaction of agents, collecting data, and establishing causal relationships and conclusions."
9646,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,57,The paper reports the results of four social scenarios.
9647,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,58,"Besides the aforementioned studies, which were tested only on a small scale of cases, there are extant papers that implemented large-scale testing on LLM-based experimental replication."
9648,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,59,Cui et al. [11] replicated 154 psychological experiments.
9649,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,60,"Specifically, they profiled LLMs as either students or adults, retrieving Likert-like responses from LLMs, which is oversimplified compared to most lab and field experiments."
9650,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,61,"By comparison, Ashokkumar et al. [22] extended such a massive replication to 70 more complex survey experiments, though their selected experiments were limited exclu- sively to US social surveys and did not include any field experiments in the primary tests."
9651,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,62,"In summary, while existing studies discussed above pioneered the application of Large Language Models (LLMs) to laboratory experi- ment simulations, several research gaps remain unaddressed."
9652,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,63,"For instance, existing methods are not tested on field experiments that are inherently more complex than laboratory experiments, encom- passing diverse participant backgrounds, more intricate workflows, and multifaceted treatment designs."
9653,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,64,"Besides, despite extensive dis- cussions on LLM bias [8, 15, 46] and the fact that recognized biases in LLMs—such as gender [ 25] and social norm bias [39]—can com- promise performance on downstream tasks [21], only one of these studies mentioned the impact of certain topics on the replication successful rate of psychological surveys [11]."
9654,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,65,It is still unclear how the joint effect of topics and sentiments would undermine the fi- delity of field experiment prediction.
9655,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,66,"Another limitation is that these studies tested their simulation strategies on only a small number of experiments, restricting generalizability."
9656,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,67,"To address these gaps, we evaluated our proposed framework at scale on field experiments from published papers, demonstrating not only that LLMs can ac- curately predict the outcomes of established experiments, but also clarifying boundary conditions under which they cannot provide reliable experimental predictions."
9657,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,68,"Furthermore, current automated simulation framework [11, 22, 34] are incompatible with scenarios involving complex treatments involving human-object interactions and limit only to lab experiments with Likert response or survey."
9658,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,69,"By contrast, our framework offers a broadly adaptable approach that supports experiments across a wide range of contexts. 3 Data Collection and Filtering To explore LLMs’ ability to predict field experiments in a large- scale fashion, we first need to collect existing field experiments."
9659,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,70,"Inspired by prior studies that focus on using LLMs to simulate human behaviors in lab experiments from existing psychology literature, we also consider field experiments studied in premier journals in economics, such as The Review of Economic Studies, American Economic Review, Journal of Political Economy, and The Quarterly Journal of Economics."
9660,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,71,It is worth noting that we focus on field experiments in economics because they are generally a larger scale in terms of participant size and robust in terms of careful design.
9661,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,72,Figure 1 shows the data collection and filtering workflow.
9662,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,73,"Ini- tially, 6544 papers containing keywords related to field experiments Predicting Field Experiments with Large Language Models SLW, August 6th, 2025, Toronto Figure 1: The Data Collection Workflow. published between 2000 and 2024 of these top journals were se- lected."
9663,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,74,"Then, we applied a two-layer verification process powered by Claude (Claude-3-opus-20240229)."
9664,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,75,"First, we prompted the title and abstract of each paper to Claude and asked it to judge if the paper designs and implements a field experiment."
9665,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,76,"Upon this, the second verification prompted the entire paper to Claude, asking the same question."
9666,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,77,"This strategy balances the accuracy of verification and the cost of calling Claude, as prompting the entire paper ex- ponentially increases the cost."
9667,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,78,A final rule-based manual check to ensure the fidelity of the automated selection and filter out 276 pa- pers for testing.
9668,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,79,More details about the manual check are available in Section 4.4.
9669,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,80,"It is also worth mentioning that using Claude as the verification tool, instead of GPT, prevents potential data leakage as GPTs are leveraged as the prediction tool in our framework."
9670,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,81,The distribution of the selected papers is shown in Figure 7 (In Appendix A). 4 Framework We present the details of our automated framework for predicting field experiments in this section.
9671,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,82,"Overall, our framework is divided into three stages: Extraction from Papers, Variant Generation, and Prediction."
9672,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,83,"Notably, Claude (Claude-3-opus-20240229) powers all preprocess tasks in the first two stages, whereas GPT completes the prediction at the last stage."
9673,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,84,"We use two different LLMs in different stages to prevent potential data leakage from one another. 4.1 Extraction Specifically, the framework uses Claude to extract information related to a field experiment from the selected paper."
9674,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,85,"To realize this, the framework leverages a manually crafted prefixed prompt, which has proven to be efficient for various downstream tasks [7]."
9675,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,86,"As shown in Figure 8 (In Appendix B.1), the prompt template con- tains a placeholder ""𝑃𝑎𝑝𝑒𝑟 "", an information form consisting of bullet points from ""A"" to ""G"", and clear instructions that ask the LLM to extract information according to the form from the paper."
9676,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,87,"As un- derscored in the prompt, the first six bullet points ""A"" to ""F"" are key experimental settings that shape the experiment context, whereas the last point ""G"" is about conclusions that are true outcomes in the prediction task."
9677,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,88,"Based on the response from Claude, the framework formulates ""Experiment Settings"" directly from bullet points ""A"" to ""F"", while it polishes point ""G"" to generate ""Experiment Conclusions""."
9678,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,89,"Specif- ically, the raw response regarding point ""G"" is a paragraph con- taining multiple conclusions of the field experiment."
9679,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,90,"To separate Figure 2: Prediction Framework. that paragraph into standalone conclusions, the framework calls a new Claude session, prompting the raw paragraph and related in- structions to it, finally getting ""Experiment Conclusions"" in return."
9680,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,91,"Breaking complex tasks into subtasks improves the performance of LLM-driven workflows [50], which is the main reason for complet- ing the extraction and separation of conclusions in different Claude sessions. 4.2 Variant Generation After the experiment settings and conclusions are extracted, the next step is to generate variants based on the true conclusion, since the goal is to see if the LLM could select the true one under distrac- tion."
9681,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,92,"Inspired by Luo et al. [33]’s prediction of neuroscience results by LLMs, for each conclusion from an experiment, our framework prompts the original conclusion and its two variants to GPT: a re- versed variant and an unrelated variant."
9682,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,93,"As a result, the framework will make the prediction by choosing one of three options."
9683,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,94,"Specifically, as shown in Figure 9 (In Appendix B.2), the frame- work initially prompts the original conclusion to Claude, which follows the instructions to generate the reversed variant of the original conclusion."
9684,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,95,The reversed variant means that the direction of the conclusion is inverted.
9685,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,96,"For example, if one conclusion is ""receiving housing vouchers reduces quarterly employment rates , "" its reversed variant will be "" receiving housing vouchers increases SLW, August 6th, 2025, Toronto Yaoyu Chen1 Yuheng Hu1 Yingda Lu1 1The Department of Information and Decision Sciences, College of Business Administration, University of Illinois at Chicago {ychen563, yuhenghu, yingdalu}@uic.com quarterly employment rates . "" Next, the framework prompts both the original and reversed conclusions to Claude to generate the unrelated variant, which typically indicates that there is no correla- tion between entities of interest."
9686,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,97,"Following the same example, the unrelated variant will be ""There is no relationship between receiving housing vouchers and quarterly employment rates . "" 4.3 Prediction In the final stage, our framework takes a field experiment’s ex- periment settings, conclusion, and its two variants as input and generates two parallel prediction prompts: basic prediction prompt and Chain-of-Thought (CoT) prompt, which are then prompted to GPT to get predictions by asking GPT to select one conclusion from three conclusions."
9687,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,98,We also rely on CoT as it has proven to be capa- ble of improving the general performance of LLMs on downstream tasks [47].
9688,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,99,"Specifically, the basic prediction prompt is shown in Figure 10 (In Appendix B.3)."
9689,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,100,"It consists of a background information section, a question section, and necessary instructions."
9690,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,101,"Specifically, the background information section contains the general goal of the ex- periment (such as exploring the impact of job training on income), treatments (such as receiving job training or not), experiment dura- tion (such as seven weeks), outcomes (such as income), participant information (such as people seeking jobs in New England), and experiment workflow (such as when and how training was given and outcomes were recorded)."
9691,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,102,"All of these were extracted from a target paper, which is the same as bullet points ""A"" to ""F"" from Figure 8 (In Appendix B.1)."
9692,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,103,"Following the background information, a question section is au- tomatically generated and entered into the templates."
9693,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,104,"Specifically, the original conclusion, its reversed variant, and its unrelated vari- ant are shuffled and substitute the placeholders ""option 1"", ""option 2"", and ""option 3""."
9694,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,105,"Meanwhile, instructions tell GPT that the predic- tion of conclusions is under the context of the field experimental settings, asking GPT to choose one option from the three options as it deems correct."
9695,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,106,"As we are also interested in how CoT would improve such pre- diction, Figure 11 (In Appendix B.3) shows the CoT Prediction Prompt, which follows a similar logic as the basic prediction but integrates CoT strategies to boost the performance [47]."
9696,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,107,"Initially, the framework prompts the experiment settings and three options for a conclusion to GPT, instructing it to think about decisive el- ements that help choose the correct option."
9697,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,108,"Upon receiving the decisive elements from GPT, the framework prompts GPT to make a selection among three options to get a predicted conclusion."
9698,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,109,It is worth noting that the entire process is within the same GPT session for a conclusion.
9699,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,110,"Although either prompt strategy generates a prediction for a given input, LLMs are stochastic models, meaning that their re- sponses may vary to the same prompt."
9700,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,111,"To handle such randomness in experiment simulations, Leng & Yuan [26] set the temperature to 0 and always get fixed responses from synthetic participants of lab experiments, which is a strategy to eliminate the stochasticity of LLMs totally."
9701,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,112,"By contrast, Brand et al. [ 6] repeated the same prompt 300 times and used the averaged number as the result of Willingness-to-Pay from customers role-played by LLMs."
9702,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,113,"Here, we take the latter approach by incorporating the stochasticity of LLM outputs since this stochasticity of LLMs is similar to how the same human participant might respond differently when presented with the same instruction [12]."
9703,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,114,"Specifically, we repeat the same predic- tion prompt several times and calculate an average accuracy as the final result."
9704,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,115,"For example, if the framework is running the basic prediction, a filled-out prompt based on Figure 10 (In Appendix B.3) will be repeated a given number of times to get a stable result."
9705,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,116,The determination of a proper repeat number will be further discussed in the Results section.
9706,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,117,"Parameter-wise, no fine-tuning is involved in any stage of the proposed framework, and all parameters of OpenAI API and An- thropic API are set to default."
9707,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,118,"Whereas Horton [ 24] harnessed fine-tuned LLMs in lab experimental simulation to better follow instructions, Coda-Forno et al. [10] simulated several human be- haviors by LLMs without fine-tuning."
9708,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,119,The use of fine-tuned LLMs complicates the reproduction attempts since other researchers don’t have access to the same model in the existing papers [4].
9709,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,120,"Addition- ally, avoiding fine-tuning LLMs saves computing resources and mitigates environmental impacts [ 38], especially when the pre- training of LLMs is enough to make them capable of downstream tasks [30]. 4.4 Robustness Checks Given that most steps in the proposed framework are automated, concerns naturally arise regarding the validity of these automated processes."
9710,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,121,"To address these concerns, we conduct three manual screenings to verify the results from extraction (Section 4.1) and variant generation (Section 4.2)."
9711,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,122,"First, we examine whether the ex- tracted experiment settings (Figure 8, Appendix B.1) inadvertently include genuine conclusions."
9712,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,123,"Second, we check whether the ex- tracted conclusions align with those reported in the original papers."
9713,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,124,"Finally, we assess whether the generated variants of the conclusions (Figure 9, Appendix B.2) match our expectations."
9714,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,125,The first and third screenings revealed no issues.
9715,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,126,"However, the second screening, which examined the alignment of extracted con- clusions, identified 377 conclusions as either incomprehensible or nonexistent in the original texts."
9716,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,127,"Consequently, after the three screenings, 1261 conclusions and 276 papers remained and were deemed valid for our purposes."
9717,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,128,"Additionally, 86 out of 1261 conclusions were dequantified, as existing studies suggest that predicting the magnitude of exper- imental outcomes remains challenging at this stage [ 34]."
9718,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,129,"Given our focus on predicting the direction of experimental conclusions rather than the magnitude, conclusions specifying precise numeri- cal treatment effects were reformulated in a dequantified manner."
9719,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,130,"For instance, a conclusion such as ""Job training increases income by 30%"" was revised to ""Job training increases income. "" 5 Results In this section, we test our framework on 276 field experiments that contain a total of 1261 conclusions and discuss the performance."
9720,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,131,We use Conclusion Accuracy and Paper Accuracy to evaluate the prediction performance under different settings.
9721,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,132,"As shown in Figure 2, the framework generates a prompt for each conclusion."
9722,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,133,"The generated prompt either follows the template in Figure 10 or 11 Predicting Field Experiments with Large Language Models SLW, August 6th, 2025, Toronto (In Appendix B.3), depending on which prompt strategy (basic or CoT) the framework applies."
9723,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,134,Each prompt instructs GPT to output a predicted conclusion.
9724,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,135,"If the predicted conclusion matches the true conclusion, that attempt is counted as correct."
9725,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,136,"As aforementioned, the framework repeats such an attempt for a set number of times for each conclusion to get a stable result."
9726,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,137,"Therefore, we define Conclusion Accuracy as the percentage of correct predictions among a set number of attempts (Equation 1)."
9727,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,138,"Given that a field experiment may contain multiple conclusions, Paper Accuracy is the average of all Conclusion Accuracy within a paper (Equation 2)."
9728,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,139,Conclusion Accuracy = Num of Correct Predictions Num of Predictions × 100% (1) Paper Accuracy = 1 𝑁 𝑁∑︁ 𝑖=1 Conclusion Accuracy𝑖 (2) 5.1 Prediction Performance Overview Table 1: Prediction Accuracy under Different Repeats GPT-4 Turbo Basic CoT Conclusion Acc.
9729,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,140,Repeat = 10 66% 66% 76% 76% Repeat = 20 66% 66% 76% 76% Repeat = 30 65% 66% 76% 76% Sample size: 1261 conclusions from 276 papers.
9730,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,141,"In the experiment we use gpt-3.5-turbo-0125, gpt-4-turbo-2024-04-09, and gpt-4o-2024-11-20."
9731,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,142,Table 2: Prediction Accuracy under 20 Repeats by GPT Models Model Basic CoT Conclusion Acc.
9732,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,143,GPT-3.5 Turbo 61% 61% 68% 67% GPT-4 Turbo 66% 66% 76% 76% GPT-4o 75% 75% 78% 78% Sample size: 1261 conclusions from 276 papers.
9733,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,144,"In the experiment we use gpt-3.5-turbo-0125, gpt-4-turbo-2024-04-09, and gpt-4o-2024-11-20."
9734,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,145,Table 1 reports two types of accuracy for both strategies un- der different repeats by GPT4-turbo.
9735,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,146,"The best results for the basic strategy are obtained under 10 repeats, which are 66% for both con- clusion accuracy and for paper accuracy."
9736,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,147,"By comparison, the CoT results are the same 76% for both strategies and different repeats, which are generally 10% points higher than basic results and aligns with prior literature on boosting LLM performance by CoT [ 47]."
9737,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,148,"Meanwhile, another key observation is that the results show a certain degree of invariability to repeat numbers."
9738,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,149,"Specifically, the results across different numbers of attempts don’t seem to change under either the basic or CoT strategy."
9739,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,150,"Given that more repeats result in higher time and monetary cost, we chose 20 repeats for further evaluation."
9740,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,151,Table 2 reports results by different GPT models with 20 attempts.
9741,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,152,"One key observation from Table 2 is that prediction performance steadily improves as LLMs iterate, though the rate of improvement decreases over time."
9742,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,153,"According to Table 2, the best result under 20 repeats is achieved by GPT4o under CoT prompt strategy, which is a conclusion accuracy of 78% and a paper accuracy of 78%."
9743,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,154,"Specifically, on average, GPT4o is able to predict a conclusion in 78% of the 20 repeated prediction attempts, and it also predicts 78% of the outcomes correctly for each paper."
9744,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,155,"While the conclusion accuracy of GPT4o under CoT strategy is 10 percentage points higher than the CoT result of GPT3-turbo, it is only two percentage points higher than the CoT result of GPT4-turbo, indicating the improvement from model iteration becomes harder for this task."
9745,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,156,Another interesting finding from Table 2 is the boosting effect of CoT on performance varies on models for the experiment con- clusion prediction task.
9746,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,157,"Specifically, the largest improvement is 10 percentage points on GPT4-turbo, while the least improvement is three percentage points on GPT4o."
9747,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,158,"However, it’s unsafe to conclude that CoT boosting is weaker on newer models since CoT improves the accuracy by seven percentage points on the oldest model tested, GPT3-turbo."
9748,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,159,"In summary, our findings indicate that incorporating a CoT strat- egy generally enhances predictive performance, whereas increas- ing the number of repetitions does not produce a significant effect."
9749,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,160,"Furthermore, iterative refinements to LLMs consistently improve performance, although the rate of improvement diminishes over time."
9750,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,161,"Finally, the performance gains attributable to CoT appear to be model-sensitive. 5.2 Data Memorization Figure 3: Paper Accuracy by Year."
9751,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,162,Data memorization is a common concern in simulating exper- iments with LLMs.
9752,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,163,"If the results given by the LLM are from its memory of training data instead of reasoning, the proposed idea has no instructional value as pilot testing for field experiments [24]."
9753,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,164,"As revealed in its documents, the training data cutoff of gpt-4o- 2024-11-20 is October 2023."
9754,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,165,"Therefore, it is reasonable to assume that the model would not have seen the field experiments papers appeared in 2024."
9755,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,166,"In other words, field experiments published after 2024 would be less likely to be included in the training data."
9756,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,167,"To text our framework’s robustness in light of data memoriza- tion, we split the papers by year."
9757,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,168,Figure 3 shows that the paper accuracy is actually higher on papers 2024 than any other years.
9758,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,169,"This is notable because if the prediction results are driven by LLMs’ SLW, August 6th, 2025, Toronto Yaoyu Chen1 Yuheng Hu1 Yingda Lu1 1The Department of Information and Decision Sciences, College of Business Administration, University of Illinois at Chicago {ychen563, yuhenghu, yingdalu}@uic.com (a) Basic Conclusion Prediction Accuracy (b) CoT Conclusion Prediction Accuracy Figure 4: Conclusion Prediction Accuracy Distribution memorization of its training data, the framework’s performance in unseen papers in 2024 would be poorer, indicating data memoriza- tion of less concern to our framework. 5.3 Examination of Distributions of Results To further examine the prediction performance of our proposed framework, we plot the distributions of accuracy results reported in Table 2, based on different GPT models and two prompt strategies under 20 repeats (Figure 4 and 5)."
9759,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,170,"As shown in Figure 4a, the conclusion accuracy of all three mod- els (gpt-3, gpt4-turbo and gpt-4o) exhibits bimodal patterns, with peaks concentrated toward both the lower and upper extremes (a U-shaped distribution)."
9760,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,171,"Specifically, there are significant concen- trations of samples in the 90%-100% accuracy range and another notable cluster in the 0%-10% accuracy range."
9761,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,172,"This indicates that the model’s performance is highly polarized, where certain con- clusions are predicted with near-perfect accuracy, while others are almost wrongly predicted entirely."
9762,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,173,"Interestingly, by applying CoT strategy (Figure 4b), the concentration in the 0%-10% accuracy range is mitigated, while the concentration in the 90%-100% accu- racy range deepens, resulting from the performance boosting by CoT."
9763,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,174,"Model-wise, the U-shaped distributions for the earlier model (gpt-3-turbo) are milder compared to recent models (gpt-4-turbo (a) Basic Paper Prediction Accuracy (b) CoT Paper Prediction Accuracy Figure 5: Paper Prediction Accuracy Distribution and gpt-4o), probably resulting from the performance limitation of earlier models."
9764,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,175,Similar patterns also exist in Figure 5 to show the paper’s ac- curacy.
9765,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,176,Distributions for all models are skewed.
9766,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,177,"Such a skewness is more pronounced in gpt-4-turbo and gpt-4o, with samples con- centrating in the upper extreme."
9767,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,178,This indicates that the frame- work correctly predicts all conclusions from certain tested experi- ments.
9768,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,179,"Additionally, CoT generally increases the degree of skew- ness(Figure 5b), aligning with its boosting effect on LLMs’ perfor- mance."
9769,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,180,"Inspired by the bimodal and skewed results (Section 5.3), we closely examined the topics of each conclusion based on its exper- imental context."
9770,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,181,"Leveraging LLMs’ ability in annotating [42], we prompted Claude to label topic components of each conclusion under the context of the experiment, as shown in Figure 12."
9771,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,182,"To en- sure selected topics could grasp the reason behind the abnomalities found previously (Figure 4 and Figure 5), we included topics where LLMs’ responses are biased [1, 20, 29, 32, 44], including gender, eth- nicity, social norms, ethical dilemmas, age, socioeconomic status, and other topics."
9772,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,183,"As a result, each conclusion was represented by a vector of percentages summing to 100%, where each percentage indicated the degree to which the context was associated with a particular topic."
9773,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,184,"Furthermore, as the sentiment bias also affects the generated content of LLMs on top of topics bias [37], we used Predicting Field Experiments with Large Language Models SLW, August 6th, 2025, Toronto Claude as the sentiment analysis tool to label each conclusion, de- ciding the sentiment of each conclusion, either positive, negative, or neutral (Figure 13, Appendix B.4)."
9774,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,185,"In addition to regular senti- ments, for gender-related conclusions, Claude also labeled each of them with a gender favorability tag, as LLMs may favor and tend to generate pro-female content [41]."
9775,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,186,"Specifically, if the context of a conclusion relates to gender, Claude would further judge if the con- text is favorable to females or detrimental to males, the opposite, or neutral, as shown in Figure 14."
9776,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,187,"Finally, all variables acquired from the labeling process are summarized in Table 4 (In Appendix C)."
9777,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,188,"To study the impact of topic components and sentiments on LLMs’ performance in experimental prediction, we constructed a regression model (Equation 3)."
9778,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,189,"Table 3 reports six regression re- sults by three GPT models and two prompt strategies under 20 repeats, which corresponds with the conclusion accuracy results in Table 2."
9779,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,190,"Notably, the sample size, which is the number of con- clusions, decreases from 1261 to 955 because the content filtering policy prevents Claude from generating labels in the labeling pro- cess (Figure 12, 13, 14, Appendix B.4)."
9780,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,191,Conclusion Accuracy = 𝛽0 + 𝛽1 (Gender) + 𝛽2 (Ethnicity) + 𝛽3 (Social norms) + 𝛽4 (Ethical dilemmas) + 𝛽5 (Age) + 𝛽6 (Socioeconomic status) + 𝛽7 (Other topics) + 𝛽8 (Gender × Favorability) + 𝛽9 (Ethnicity × Sentiment) + 𝛽10 (Social norms × Sentiment) + 𝛽11 (Ethical dilemmas × Sentiment) + 𝛽12 (Age × Sentiment) + 𝛽13 (Socioeconomic status × Sentiment) + 𝛽14 (Other topics × Sentiment) + 𝜖 (3) Figure 6: Full specification of the regression model used to examine the effect of topic–sentiment interactions on prediction accuracy.
9781,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,192,There are several key findings from regression results (Table 3).
9782,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,193,"First, the interaction effects between certain topics and sentiments significantly affect the performance, though there is no significant evidence that topic components alone may affect LLMs’ ability in predicting experimental conclusions."
9783,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,194,"Specifically, sentiment inter- actions with complex social issues such as ethnicity, social norms, age, and other topics are significantly positive, while sentiment interactions with ethical dilemmas is significantly negative."
9784,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,195,"For example, the regression of gpt4o and basic prompt (Table 3 (1)) shows that sentiment interactions with ethnicity and other topics are significantly positive, suggesting if the context of a conclusions is positive and relates to ethnicity, LLMs tend to predict it correctly, while sentiment interaction with ethical dilemmas is significantly negative, suggesting that if the context of a conclusion is negative and relates to ethical dilemmas, LLMs tend to avoid it, resulting in a wrong prediction."
9785,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,196,"Surprisingly, gender, which is a topic compo- nent widely perceived to be biased in LLMs [32, 41], seems not to be a biased topic in LLM-based experiment prediction."
9786,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,197,"Favorabil- ity interaction with gender is only significantly positive in gpt4o prediction under CoT, suggesting that gpt4o inclines to predict pro-female conclusions and avoid pro-male conclusions under CoT strategy only in one out of six scenarios."
9787,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,198,"This is also the case for the age topic, as the coefficient of its interaction is positive only in one regression."
9788,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,199,"Another interesting finding is that estimated coefficients of socioeconomic status and its interaction terms are never significant according to the regression results, suggesting that LLM prediction is unbiased to conclusions related to this topic."
9789,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,200,"Second, though the directions of estimated coefficients are sta- ble, the significant levels of the same interaction term vary across regressions due to the refinement from model iteration and prompt strategies."
9790,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,201,"Specifically, the estimated coefficients of the ethnicity’s interaction term are significant across all gpt models, suggesting that the iteration LLMs didn’t fix this bias."
9791,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,202,"By comparison, the coef- ficients of the interaction of social norms are no longer significant since gpt4-turbo, suggesting that this bias might have been fixed."
9792,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,203,"Third, applying CoT strategy might mitigate the impact of senti- ment interaction with certain topics."
9793,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,204,"According to the regression results in Table 3 (1) and Table 3 (2), implementing CoT turns some significant estimated coefficients of interaction terms into non- significant."
9794,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,205,"However, this is not the case for gpt3-turbo model, as CoT brings more significant coefficients. 6 Conclusion In this paper, we propose an LLM-powered framework that auto- matically extracts information from existing papers and predicts field experimental conclusions."
9795,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,206,"To the best of our knowledge, this is the first paper to provide an automated framework for predicting such conclusions for field experiments."
9796,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,207,"Rather than merely intro- ducing the framework, our work also examines its fidelity on a large scale of samples and achieves a considerable accuracy of 78%."
9797,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,208,"Furthermore, the paper discovers that incorporating a CoT strat- egy generally enhances predictive performance in this scenario, whereas the performance gains attributable to CoT appear to be model-dependent."
9798,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,209,"Furthermore, iterative refinements to LLMs con- sistently improve performance, although the rate of improvement diminishes over time."
9799,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,210,"Interestingly, the paper also finds that the distributions of pre- diction accuracy are either bimodal or negatively skewed, with a large number of samples concentrating on the two extremes."
9800,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,211,"To explore this phenomenon, the paper regresses conclusion predic- tion accuracy on topic components and sentiments, revealing that interaction effects between certain topics and sentiments could affect the LLMs’ prediction performance in this task."
9801,36,C036_P1_pdf.txt,212,"SLW, August 6th, 2025, Toronto Yaoyu Chen1 Yuheng Hu1 Yingda Lu1 1The Department of Information and Decision Sciences, College of Business Administration, University of Illinois at Chicago {ychen563, yuhenghu, yingdalu}@uic.com Taken together, these findings underscore the potential of the LLM-driven frameworks in advancing automated predictions for field experiments while also clarifying the practical constraints that guide their effective use."
