9850,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,2,Published online: 05 Jun 2025.
9851,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,3,"Submit your article to this journal  Article views: 5189 View related articles  View Crossmark data Citing articles: 5 View citing articles  Full Terms & Conditions of access and use can be found at Use of artificial intelligence tools by doctoral students: a  mixed-methods explanatory-sequential investigation Muhammad Naveed Akbar Interdisciplinary Science, Education, Technologies and Learning Research Group, School of Education,  University of Glasgow, Glasgow, UK ABSTRACT Increasing use of AI tools in higher education comes with a need to  develop a clear understanding of how students (by demography  and study discipline) employ them, for what purposes and in what  terms their use is evaluated."
9852,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,4,This will inform the development of  future guidelines and training for staff and students.
9853,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,5,"In the current  mixed-methods study, a cross-sectional survey was first adminis - tered to a convenience sample of 105 doctoral students (71  females, 34 males), followed by semi-structured interviews with  a subset of seven participants (four females, three males)."
9854,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,6,"This  had several aims; to identify patterns of AI tool use and its perceived  helpfulness; to explore AI use with regard to aspects of time man - agement, stress and study progress; to construct a predictive model  of AI tool use and to explore, in-depth, students’ views on beneficial  and problematic aspects of AI."
9855,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,7,Findings suggested AI was widely  used.
9856,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,8,"Males were more likely to use it for data analysis and research  planning, with greater use by students in non-scientific disciplines."
9857,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,9,Use was significantly related to stress and time management.
9858,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,10,Several potential benefits and problems were identified.
9859,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,11,"Benefits  included aiding research, for example, assisting and improving  coding/programming, use in proofreading and writing and as an  explanatory tool for rendering complex information accessible."
9860,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,12,"Potential problems included environmental cost, violation of intel - lectual property rights, provision of misleading and/or inaccurate  information and risks of plagiarism and hindered creativity."
9861,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,13,Limitations of the study are discussed alongside implications for  policy and training with suggestions for further work.
9862,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,14,"ARTICLE HISTORY  Received 29 January 2025  Accepted 29 May 2025  KEYWORDS  Postgraduates; AI; chatGPT;  benefits; problems Introduction In higher education it is recognised that staff and students benefit from competence in  information and communication technology (Almerich et al. 2020 ; Henderson, Finger, and  Selwyn 2016 ; Lee, Zawacki-Richter, and Cefa Sari 2024 )."
9863,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,15,"The higher education technolo - gical ecosystem is now facing novel challenges related to the development and introduc - tion of the latest generation of tools in artificial intelligence (AI), not least in relation to the  integrity of assessed work (Landers 2024 )."
9864,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,16,"The use of large language models, such as  CONTACT Muhammad Naveed Akbar   m.akbar.1@research.gla.ac.uk   Interdisciplinary Science, Education,  Technologies and Learning Research Group, School of Education, University of Glasgow, Glasgow, UK JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  2025, VOL. 49, NO. 7, 995–1013  © 2025 The Author(s)."
9865,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,17,"Published by Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group."
9866,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,18,"This is an Open Access article distributed under the terms of the Creative Commons Attribution License ( http://creativecommons.org/  licenses/by/4.0/ ), which permits unrestricted use, distribution, and reproduction in any medium, provided the original work is properly  cited."
9867,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,19,The terms on which this article has been published allow the posting of the Accepted Manuscript in a repository by the author(s) or  with their consent.
9868,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,20,"ChatGPT, which are based on principles of neurocomputation, has attracted interest and  concern in equal measure."
9869,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,21,"Despite this concern, an analysis of world leading universities  in several countries found that less than half had published guidelines for academics on  their use (Moorhouse, Yeo, and Wan 2023 )."
9870,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,22,"What is clear is that use of such AI tools in higher education is destined to increase, as  students become more aware of the potential benefits they offer in their discipline,  whether STEM or non-STEM based (Blease et al. 2021 ; Khanagar et al. 2021 ; Meron and  Araci 2023 ; Parviz 2024 ; Yilmaz et al. 2023 ; Yüzbaşıoğlu 2021 )."
9871,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,23,"Questionnaire and interview  studies with postgraduate students drawn from a wide range of countries – including  China (Xu et al. 2024 ), Ghana (Segbenya et al. 2023 ), Hungary (Tick et al. 2023 ), India  (Mohammed, Al-Ghazali, and Alqohfa 2023 ), Indonesia (Muslimin 2023 ), Morocco (A."
9872,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,24,"Bouzar, Idrissi, and Ghourdou 2024 ), Portugal (Costa, Costa, and Carvalho 2024 ) and  South Africa (Chauke et al. 2024 ) – suggest that ChatGPT is judged to be beneficial for  research planning, information searching, proofreading and academic writing."
9873,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,25,Work also  points to effects on research supervision ( Dai et al. 2023 ).
9874,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,26,"Current data suggest use of  ChatGPT is more favoured among high income groups (Baek, Tate, and Warschauer 2024 )."
9875,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,27,"Gender differences have also been observed in the manner in which AI is used, the ethical  concerns held towards its use (Møgelvang et al. 2024 ) and the frequency and amount of  time it is employed (A."
9876,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,28,Ghourdou 2024 ; Nyaaba et al. 2024 ).
9877,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,29,"Concerns over AI use: ethics, effects and performance The potential benefits of AI use aside, however, several concerns have been raised."
9878,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,30,"There  is evidence that ChatGPT use can be associated with delayed task initiation, thereby  affecting students’ customary time management practices (Bouzar, El Idrissi, and  Ghourdou 2024 )."
9879,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,31,"On this front, Abbas, Jam, and Khan ( 2024 ) have pointed to academic  workload and time pressure as factors precipitating students’ ChatGPT use."
9880,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,32,"Unease has  also been expressed about the potential for dependency, addiction and reduced creativity  in users (Das and Madhusudan 2024 ) as well as the ensuing problems of plagiarism and  plagiarism detection which may arise from its use (Bhullar, Joshi, and Chugh 2024 ; Hutson  2024 ; Landers 2024 ; Rasul et al. 2023 )."
9881,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,33,"In addition, the reliability and accuracy of output  generated by ChatGPT (Schei, Møgelvang, and Ludvigsen 2024 ; Vaishya et al. 2024 ; Xu  et al. 2024 ) has been questioned."
9882,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,34,These concerns are also shared by students (Shoufan 2023 ).
9883,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,35,Given the unsatis - factory ability of current assessment tools to detect plagiarism (Chaudhry et al.  2023 ) – and there is a steady growth in the availability of such tools (Wang et al.  2024 ) – data showing a high positive correlation between ChatGPT usage and  academic performance (e.g.
9884,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,36,"Khan and Fatima 2024 ), while inconclusive, do  little to allay concerns that the tools will be used inappropriately."
9885,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,37,This is evident in  recent work by Deng at al.
9886,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,38,"( 2024 ), the first systematic review and meta-analysis of  experimental studies ( N = 69) into the effect of ChatGPT on student learning."
9887,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,39,"This  reported evidence ChatGPT use was consistently associated with increased aca - demic performance, motivation and higher order thinking but reduced mental  effort, although these effects varied across subject areas."
9888,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,40,"The authors cautioned  that the documented improvements in academic performance may simply have  arisen as the direct result of ChatGPT’s role in producing higher quality work, as  996  M."
9889,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,41,AKBAR many of the studies included failed to exclude its use during the assessment of  academic performance.
9890,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,42,"Similarly, no objective tests of higher-order thinking were  used."
9891,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,43,It is also of note that the only study included in the analysis which assessed  originality (Niloy et al. 2023 ) found a detrimental effect.
9892,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,44,Rationale for current study If suitable guidelines and training for AI use are to be developed it will be helpful  to develop a broad picture of the various uses to which undergraduate and  postgraduate students are putting AI tools.
9893,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,45,"It will also be helpful to ascertain  which groups of students are using the tools, and for what specific purposes."
9894,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,46,"A recent survey indicates students’ use of AI has mushroomed, with the percen - tage reporting use of any AI tool jumping from 66% in 2024 to 92% in 2025."
9895,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,47,The  same survey reported that only 36% of students had received training in AI skills  from their institution (Freeman 2025 ).
9896,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,48,"It is clear that AI tools are being increasingly  adopted to assist with writing by scholars at all levels, adding to the ethical  concerns for educators and assessors (Segbenya et al. 2023 ) and lending weight  to the assertion that education has not kept pace with developments in AI (Razak,  Abdullah, and Ahmad 2024 )."
9897,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,49,"Given this widespread use, and the potential problems associated with it, it is impor - tant to understand students’ general perceptions of AI tool use, and the means by which  they evaluate it."
9898,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,50,"The current study, which was developed as part of a larger study into the  benefits and disadvantages of technology in doctoral education, therefore has several  specific aims."
9899,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,51,"(1) To identify patterns of AI tool use and perceived helpfulness of AI tools in doctoral  students by gender, age and study discipline."
9900,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,52,"(2) To explore AI use in relation to aspects of time management, stress and study  progress."
9901,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,53,(3) To develop a provisional predictive model of AI tool use.
9902,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,54,(4) To understand doctoral students’ perceptions of the advantages and disadvan - tages of AI tool use.
9903,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,55,Method Design An explanatory-sequential mixed-methods design was employed.
9904,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,56,"Initially, a cross-  sectional survey was administered to a convenience sample of 105 doctoral students  (71 females, 34 males)."
9905,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,57,This was hosted on the Online Survey platform (formerly BOS) and  organised in several sections.
9906,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,58,Data was gathered between June 2023 and May 2024.
9907,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,59,A more detailed description of the survey can be found in Akbar ( 2024 ).
9908,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,60,"This was followed  by a semi-structured interview with a subset of seven participants (four females, three  males)."
9909,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,61,"JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  997 Participants An opportunity sample of doctoral students was recruited by emails sent to the  Postgraduate Student Association in the Education Department of the University of the  author, and PhD supervisors and Heads of Department in departments of Education and  Psychology throughout the UK."
9910,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,62,These provided detailed information about the study and  requested recipients to forward the email to current PhD candidates.
9911,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,63,Each letter con - tained a live link to the survey.
9912,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,64,"Notices were also posted on Facebook, Twitter and  Instagram."
9913,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,65,"The sample for the present study ( N = 105; 71 females, mean age = 28.31, SD  = 4.60 and 34 males, mean age = 29.15, SD = 6.03) comprised those who responded  following the late addition to the survey of several questions about the use of AI tools  such as ChatGPT."
9914,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,66,"The majority of these were full-time ( N = 100, 95.2%)."
9915,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,67,"The largest group  of participants were Asian ( N = 34, 32.38%), followed by British ( N = 33, 31.4%) and  European ( N = 19, 18.09%)."
9916,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,68,"The majority were studying at UK universities ( N = 88,  83.81%) with a small percentage studying in universities based in Europe, the Americas  and Asia."
9917,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,69,A subset of participants who indicated their willingness to partake in further  study were recontacted and agreed to be interviewed in greater depth about their use of  technology.
9918,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,70,Details on these (with pseudonyms) are presented in Table 1 .
9919,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,71,"Materials and variables Demographic information collected comprised gender, age and academic discipline  studied."
9920,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,72,"The latter was recoded into a binary variable, science/non-science, in keeping  with Rockinson-Szapkiw et al’.s ( 2019 ) distinction between STEM and non-STEM subjects."
9921,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,73,"In addition to questions on general software use, data was collected on time manage - ment, perceived stress, perceived study progress and use of AI tools such as ChatGPT."
9922,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,74,Whether participants had ever used AI tools was assessed as a binary variable.
9923,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,75,"Assessment  of time management, perceived stress, perceived study progress and the perceived  helpfulness of AI tools were all measured on 5-point Likert scales by respondents’ level  of agreement with a series of statements (further details of the questions are given in  Akbar 2024 )."
9924,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,76,"For interviews, a semi-structured interview was first piloted and, following  modification, was used in the subsequent interviews."
9925,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,77,"Procedure and ethics On following the survey link, participants were presented with an initial information sheet  describing the study and its estimated completion time."
9926,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,78,They were then presented with  Table 1.
9927,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,79,Participants in the interview study.
9928,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,80,Participant Age Gender Field of Study S1 Frank 24 Male Chemistry S2 Helen 29 Female Psychology S3 Teng 24 Male Applied Linguistics S4 Nina 25 Female Psychology/Business S5 Diana 55 Female Music S6 Baris 42 Male Architecture S7 Cynthia 23 Female Aerospace Engineering 998  M.
9929,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,81,"After providing consent, they were directed to the survey."
9930,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,82,Estimated  completion time for this was approximately 45 minutes.
9931,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,83,A subset of participants who agreed to participate in further research were recontacted  following the survey and invited to take part in a semi-structured interview.
9932,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,84,Having  agreed to take part they were presented with a broad outline of potential topics to be  covered in the interview prior to its commencement.
9933,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,85,Interviews lasted between 45 and  90 minutes.
9934,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,86,Approval for the study was granted by the University Research Ethics Committee.
9935,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,87,"Consent to participate For both the survey and interview, respondents were informed that participation was  voluntary and that they could withdraw at any time, with any personal details supplied  being confidential."
9936,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,88,A digital consent form was provided for respondents to indicate they  had read and understood the information provided and agreed to take part.
9937,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,89,Quantitative analyses (1) Use of AI tools was cross-tabulated with gender and study discipline.
9938,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,90,The prob - ability of the observed results is given by Fisher’s exact p.
9939,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,91,"(2) Mann-Whitney U-tests were employed to assess differences in degree of help - fulness by use of AI tools, as well as by gender and study discipline (science v non-  science)."
9940,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,92,(3) Mann-Whitney U-tests assessed differences in perceived study progress by use of AI  tools.
9941,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,93,(4) AI use and degree of helpfulness of AI tools were correlated with age.
9942,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,94,"AI use was  also correlated with problems arising from spending time online (interferes with  exercise, interferes with social life, interferes with quality of sleep, interferes with  family life – these variables were assessed on a 5-point Likert scale)."
9943,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,95,"(5) A logistic regression was computed for use of AI tools, with gender, study disci - pline, perceived stress and several variables concerned with spending time online  (interferes with exercise, interferes with social life, interferes with quality of sleep  and interferes with family life) entered as predictor variables."
9944,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,96,Gender and study  discipline were entered as categorical variables.
9945,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,97,All analyses were conducted in SPSS v28.
9946,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,98,Thematic analysis of interview data Interview data was subjected to reflexive thematic analysis (Braun and Clarke 2006 ; Clarke  and Braun 2017 ).
9947,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,99,"The method’s pioneers, Braun and Clarke, consider it an accessible,  pragmatic form of data analysis which proceeds as an organic process which ‘happens at  the intersection of you and your data, and your reflexivity, your subjectivity, your dis - ciplinary and social context’ (Coxon, Clarke, and Braun 2022 , 41)."
9948,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,100,"Consequently, the  researcher brings to the analysis their own knowledge of the context in which participants  are located."
9949,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,101,"After transcribing the interviews, the researcher first familiarised themselves  JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  999 with the data, carefully reading and re-reading each transcript, creating notes and  a summary of the impressions from each interview."
9950,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,102,"Once an overview of an interview  had been obtained, data were assigned initial codes."
9951,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,103,Transcriptions were subject to both  descriptive coding – highlighting important aspects of participants’ experiences – as well  as linguistic coding – focusing on the lexicon and meaning of the language used.
9952,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,104,"Finally,  conceptual coding involved interpreting the data in context, with similar and related  codes clustered together to produce themes, leading to a deeper semantic understand - ing."
9953,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,105,Ideas and key words which were noted signalled the emergent themes and these  were written down.
9954,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,106,"This procedure was repeated for each transcript, with the researcher  then considering the transcripts as a whole, identifying common ideas and the connec - tions between them."
9955,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,107,"Key themes were then tabulated, with quotations and participants’  names (anonymised) recorded next to each theme."
9956,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,108,"For the current paper, only those  themes directly pertinent to the use of artificial intelligence are presented and discussed."
9957,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,109,"Results Almost two-thirds of the respondents (N = 69, 65.7%) reported having used AI tools."
9958,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,110,"The  proportions of males (N = 23, 67.6%) and females (N = 43, 64.8%) using them were similar."
9959,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,111,"Of these, a large majority (N = 56, 81.16%) indicated they found them to be helpful or very  helpful."
9960,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,112,Only four respondents (5.8%) reported it as very unhelpful.
9961,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,113,"The tools were most  frequently used for assistance with proofreading (N = 34, 49.28%), academic writing (N =  28, 40.58%), generation of ideas (N = 27, 39.13%) and literature reviews (N = 23, 33.33%),  with evidence of gender differences in their use (see Table 2 )."
9962,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,114,"Males were significantly  more likely than females (35.29% cf. 8.45%, Odds Ratio = 4.18, Fisher’s Exact p = .0015) to  employ it for data analysis and marginally significantly more likely to use it for research  planning (17.65% cf. 5.62%, Odds Ratio = 3.13, Fisher’s Exact p = 0.074)."
9963,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,115,Purpose for which AI tools were used by gender.
9964,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,116,N Males (N = 34) Females (N = 71) Literature Review 23 10 (29.41%) 13 (18.31) Data Analysis** 18 12 (35.29%) 6 (8.45%) Idea Generation 27 7 (20.59%) 20 (28.17%) Writing Research Proposals 10 2 (5.88%) 8 (11.27%) Academic Writing 28 8 (23.53%) 20 (28.17%) Proofreading 34 10 (29.41%) 24 (33.80%) Designing Questionnaire Items 5 3 (8.82%) 2 (2.81%) Research Planning* 10 6 (17.65%) 4 (5.63%) ** p < 0.01 * p < 0.10.
9965,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,117,Purpose for which AI tools were used by study discipline.
9966,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,118,N Science (N = 87) Non-Science (N = 17) Literature Review 23 17 (19.54%) 6 (35.3%) Data Analysis 18 16 (18.39%) 2 (11.76%) Idea Generation 27 21 (24.14%) 6 (35.29%) Writing Research Proposals 10 8 (9.19%) 2 (11.76%) Academic Writing 28 21 (24.13%) 7 (41.18%) Proofreading 34 26 (29.89%) 8 (47.06%) Designing Questionnaire Items 5 4 (4.60%) 1 (5.88%) Research Planning 10 8 (9.19%) 2 (11.76%) 1000  M.
9967,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,119,"AKBAR Age was not significantly related with use of AI tools (rho = −0.01, p = 0.96), nor with  how helpful they were judged to be (rho = −0.03, p = 0.81)."
9968,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,120,There was a suggestion of  differences in use by academic discipline (see Table 3 ).
9969,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,121,"For example, non-science students  (N = 14, 82.4%) were almost three times more likely to report their use than science  students (N = 55, 63.2%; Odds Ratio = 2.72, Fisher’s Exact p = 0.10)."
9970,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,122,These differences  appeared to pertain to non-science students being more likely to use the tools for  academic writing (42.18% cf. 24.13%) and proofreading (47.06% cf. 29.89%).
9971,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,123,"In terms of helpfulness, those using AI tools reported them as being significantly more  helpful than those who didn’t (3.93, cf. 3.00; Mann-Whitney U = 16,Z = −2.07, p = 0.039)."
9972,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,124,"In  addition, males gave higher ratings than females (4.17, cf. 3.76), though this difference  was not significant (Mann-Whitney U = 447, Z = −1.47, p = 0.14)."
9973,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,125,"There was no significant  difference between science and non-science students (3.96, cf. 3.64; Mann-Whitney U =  355, Z =−0.60, p = 0.55)."
9974,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,126,"Correlates of AI use Use of AI tools was significantly positively correlated with spending time online, interfering  with exercise (rho = 0.21, p = 0.037) and with social life (rho = 0.21, p = 0.037)."
9975,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,127,"The relation - ship with spending time online interferes with quality of sleep (rho = −0.18, p = 0.066) was  marginally significant – AI use being associated with less interference."
9976,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,128,"The relationship with  spending time online affects my family life was not significant (rho = 0.08, p = 0.41)."
9977,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,129,"In addition, AI tool use was negatively correlated with level of self-reported stress (rho  = −0.17, p = 0.09)."
9978,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,130,A clearer picture of this relationship comes from cross-tabulating  perceived stress with use of AI tools.
9979,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,131,Data from two participants who reported no stress  were excluded owing to low expected frequencies.
9980,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,132,This left a cross-tabulation between  low/high levels of stress and use of AI.
9981,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,133,This was highly significant (Fisher exact p = 0.0046).
9982,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,134,The relationship is shown in Figure 1 .
9983,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,135,"As can be seen, those using AI tools were more likely  to report moderate stress (71.6%, cf. 28.6%), with those not using AI tools more likely to  report high stress (71.4% cf. 28.4%)."
9984,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,136,"AI tool use was not significantly related to perceived  study progress (Mann-Whitney U = 1097, Z = −1.05, p = 0.30). 71.6 28.428.6 71.4 0 10 20 30 40 50 60 70 80 Yes No Percentage Use of AI Tools Moderate Stress High Stress Figure 1."
9985,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,137,Use of AI tools by level of stress.
9986,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,138,"JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  1001 Modelling AI use The logistic regression model was significant ( χ 2 (7) = 25.80 p < 0.001; Hosmer and  Lemeshow χ 2 (8) = 7.19, p = 0.52) explaining between 23.1% and 32.1% of the  variance in AI use (Cox and Snell R 2  = 0.231, Nagelkerke R 2 = 0.321)."
9987,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,139,"The model  correctly classified 78.6% of the cases (AI use, 87.7%, non-use, 60.6%)."
9988,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,140,"Study  discipline was significant (Wald χ 2  = 4.07, p = 0.044, Odds Ratio = 5.58; Figure 2 )."
9989,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,141,"Non-science students were over five times more likely to use AI than science  students, whilst lower perceived stress almost doubled the likelihood of using AI  (Wald χ 2  = 4.69, p = 0.03, Odds Ratio = 1.87, Figure 3 )."
9990,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,142,"Spending time online affects  my social life was also significant, each unit increase raising the likelihood of AI use  by a factor of 3 (Wald χ 2  = 6.61, p = 0.01, Odds Ratio = 3.07)."
9991,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,143,Two further variables  were marginally significant.
9992,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,144,"Spending time online affects my family life (Wald χ 2  =  3.35, p = 0.067, Odds Ratio = 0.54) and Spending time online interferes with my  sleep (Wald χ 2  = 3.35, p = 0.067, Odds Ratio = 0.57)."
9993,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,145,"For the latter variable, AI use  was associated with less disruption."
9994,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,146,"Spending time online interferes with exercise  was no longer significant (Wald χ 2  = 1.10, p = 0.29)."
9995,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,147,"Results of thematic analysis The interviews produced two contrasting themes concerning students’ use of ChatGPT,  one detailing its beneficial aspects, the other, a range of problems associated with its use."
9996,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,148,Probability of use of AI tools by study discipline. 1002  M.
9997,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,149,"AKBAR Artificial intelligence as beneficial Positive evaluations given were that ChatGPT could be employed to aid programming,  assist in the use of statistical tests and help with academic writing and the synthesis of  large quantities of information."
9998,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,150,Two respondents referred to aiding coding/programming.
9999,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,151,"One of them, Cynthia, described how she used the tool, first, for detecting errors (debug - ging) in her coding, I usually use ChatGPT, mostly . . ."
10000,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,152,I use it as an assistant for codes problems.
10001,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,153,"So say that there is  a there is a few lines of code that are causing me an error and I’ve tried to debug it, but I’m still not."
10002,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,154,I’m still getting the same errors.
