10017,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,169,"(Teng, lines 806–808) These comments are consistent with reports in existing literature (Blease et al. 2021 ;  Khanagar et al. 2021 ; Parviz 2024 ; Yilmaz et al. 2023 ) of a variety of benefits that AI can  offer students."
10018,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,170,Artificial intelligence as problematic Doctoral students’ assessment of AI as potentially problematic was more extensive than  its ostensibly beneficial uses.
10019,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,171,There was a long list of potential problems which respon - dents either foresaw or had directly experienced themselves – many of which highlight  issues previously raised by researchers.
10020,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,172,"These were grouped into four broad sub-themes:  the production of inaccurate or misleading information (Schei, Møgelvang, and Ludvigsen  2024 ), detrimental effect on creativity (Das and Madhusudan 2024 ) with an attendant risk  of plagiarism (Hutson 2024 ), environmental cost and the violation of intellectual property  rights."
10021,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,173,Example comments from participants under each of these headings can be found  here.
10022,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,174,Inaccurate or misleading information The production of inaccurate references by ChatGPT was frequently mentioned by  participants.
10023,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,175,"The following comments from Cynthia, Nina and Frank are typical of the  problems encountered."
10024,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,176,"It’s not really the best idea to ask ChatGPT for guarantees, because it can make up sources."
10025,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,177,It  can make up papers that do not really exist.
10026,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,178,"It will even give you some unique things like DOIs  and ISBN, in case it’s books . . ."
10027,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,179,I don’t really believe too much what ChatGPT tells me.
10028,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,180,"(Cynthia,  lines 453–455, 473) I did run into some issues with ChatGPT."
10029,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,181,It happened once or twice to me that ChatGPT  invented references that I just couldn’t find.
10030,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,182,"(Nina, lines 296–297) I found that the answers that the ChatGPT gave me, they were not like, very scientific or yes or  I found that they like the references that ChatGPT, you said they were not like that good."
10031,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,183,"(Frank, lines 245–247) As can be seen, the questionable referencing supplied by ChatGPT led some to question  its usability if not to cease using it outright. 1004  M."
10032,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,184,AKBAR Detrimental effect on creativity and risk of plagiarism Helen was the most vocal of those interviewed when it came to views on the creative  limitations of AI and the potential problems for students seeking to do novel work.
10033,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,185,"Artificial intelligence cannot do . . . it cannot generate new knowledge, so artificial intelli - gence will replicate all the knowledge and all the arguments that are already existing out  there."
10034,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,186,"So if you’re doing something new and you’re trying to, let’s say, for example, say that  pitch iced tea is good for your eyesight, and there is no evidence around that you it."
10035,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,187,AI cannot  write an essay about that because it’s novel.
10036,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,188,"It hasn’t been done before, and it want to know  how to connect, or how to link the arguments, so you can see whatever the novel ideas in the  writing that actually this novel argument here belongs to the student, because AI cannot  synthesize it, because it doesn’t have this connection previously in the literature."
10037,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,189,"(Helen, lines  2473, 2480) In this she was supported by Nina, who considered not only the potential motivation  underpinning the sacrifice of one’s own thinking but also costs incurred when favouring  machine generated output."
10038,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,190,"I think that’s definitely a risk that comes with generative AI and then obviously independent  thinking, critical thinking, maybe sometimes it’s easier to ask ChatGPT for ideas than trying to  come up with your own . . ."
10039,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,191,"Maybe they’re not as good, they’re not as creative."
10040,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,192,"And  so I think it will probably, I could imagine that it reduces our patience a little bit in the long  run, and we’re just after a really quick response for something, so we fall back onto ChatGPT,  for example, rather than putting in our own cognitive efforts."
10041,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,193,"(Nina, lines 358–363) The issue of reduced self-reliance and thinking for oneself and potential self-harm result - ing from use of ChatGPT was also raised in moments of honest, self-criticism by Teng as  well as Diana."
10042,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,194,"Sometimes I feel myself very rely too much, rely on that software, like I cannot think by myself,  or sometimes I need to for think by myself, because, you know, you have a tool, very efficient,  and he can just pop up a question, they will give you an answer immediately, rather than  think by yourself and do more training by your own brain."
10043,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,195,"(Teng, lines 347–350) I’m still worried about using it as a shortcut for processes that actually are meant to be  difficult . . . worried it will deskill me . . ."
10044,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,196,I worry that it’s changing the way I think.
10045,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,197,"(Diana, lines  664–665, 704, 714) Diana went further and remarked how the issue of plagiarism surrounding use of ChatGPT  not only caused students a great deal of trouble but also risked the loss of something she  saw as fundamentally human in the quest for knowledge."
10046,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,198,"And I, you know, it’s causing lots of trouble for undergraduates, particular, particularly, it  seems to be causing lots of trouble."
10047,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,199,"(Diana, lines 2829–2830) But AI, as sophisticated and wonderful as it is, isn’t human thought."
10048,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,200,"And the ability to think  sideways without linear connections is a is a uniquely human thing, and I don’t ever want to  lose that."
10049,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,201,"(Diana, lines 767–768) Environmental cost Two respondents, Amanda and Cynthia, questioned the environmental burden of gen - erative artificial intelligence and with it the economic cost."
10050,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,202,"JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  1005 . . . there are serious problems with the information that you get by asking questions of  generative AI, also like the carbon impact . . . and ask a program like open AI or ChatGPT  a question is like, the greenhouse gas emissions from that are like a year’s worth of regular  server information generation."
10051,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,203,"(Amanda, lines 423–425) There is always a price to pay . . . even though the price may not be directly your like  money out of your pocket."
10052,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,204,"How are these websites still running where, where servers have  a cost, even, even assuming that they have their own servers, which is very unlikely, the  cost of electricity is still pretty expensive if you’re running a server."
10053,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,205,"(Cynthia, lines  1290–1292) These same two individuals were also vocal about the costs of generative AI with respect  to creative workers’ intellectual property rights."
10054,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,206,"Violation of intellectual property rights The ethical concerns of Amanda, who had previously voiced her unease about the  implications of generative AI for the climate, extended to the potential violation of  intellectual property rights."
10055,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,207,"At several points in the interview, she discussed this at  some length, covering issues of consent, the untraceable nature of data sources AI relies  upon and the legality of the means by which AI engines are trained."
10056,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,208,"I have concerns with, like, the training databases that OpenAI uses for their generative AI, and  that, like people did not consent for their intellectual property to be used in it."
10057,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,209,"(Amanda, lines  51–52) She went on to say, . . . and on top of that, the data that OpenAI uses, you can’t trace it back to its sources, and  they’re using the intellectual property of people like me, yeah, without our consent."
10058,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,210,"(Amanda,  lines 463–464) There are serious ethical concerns with like, you’re legally not entitled to just scrape anyone’s  information off of the internet and then use it for for-profit enterprises, like there are copy - right and intellectual property laws across the world that say that you’re not allowed to do  that, and the people in charge of OpenAI have admitted that they’re not able to verify that all  of the information used in their training databases, in their training sets, has been appro - priately sourced."
10059,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,211,"(Amanda, lines 478–482) Her final reflections in this area expanded on the potential unsanctioned use of her own  intellectual property."
10060,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,212,I have a website where I write about public health topics.
10061,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,213,"OpenAI can take that intellectual  property that I have created, is my ideas and my science and my learning and my words, and  they can use that in their training database, and they then use that to answer the questions or  respond to the queries, the generative queries that people are requesting."
10062,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,214,"I have not  consented to my data being used in that way, and that is fundamentally different than  what happens when someone Googles something, and one of the results for that search is an  article that I published."
10063,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,215,"(Amanda, lines, 503–508) Some of these worries were shared by Cynthia."
10064,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,216,She spoke about her understanding of the  different rights which exist in Europe and the United States for people whose work may  be appropriated for training AI models. 1006  M.
10065,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,217,"AKBAR And, and this is, this is a more like, these are comment about Meta."
10066,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,218,"I remember  when early June, they released that they were going to use whatever was published to train  their own the Meta AI model."
10067,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,219,"And, you know, in in the you’re in the Eurozone, it was possible  to opt out, but in the US, it was not really possible."
10068,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,220,"(Cynthia, lines 1306–1309) She described her own unsuccessful attempt to opt out from having her work used in  this way."
10069,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,221,"Because as soon as I found out that they were doing this, I wanted to try to opt out, but  I couldn’t."
10070,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,222,"(Amanda, lines 1315–1316) Discussion AI tools were used by a majority of survey respondents and for a variety of purposes."
10071,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,223,"These included proofreading, academic writing, idea generation, reviewing literature,  data analysis and research planning."
10072,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,224,This has some overlap with the uses documented  in several existing studies (e.g.
10073,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,225,Chauke et al. 2024 ; Segbenya et al. 2023 ).
10074,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,226,"The finding that  non-science-based students were more likely to report it was surprising, given that most  literature has been concerned with the application of AI in STEM subjects (e.g."
10075,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,227,"Khan and Fatima 2024 ; Deng et al., 2024 ), there was  no evidence in the current study that use of AI tools was associated with study progress."
10076,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,228,"Given the rapid appearance of the tools, however, this may well change, as students  become more familiar with them and more accomplished in their use."
10077,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,229,"Previous findings of  gender differences in AI use (Møgelvang et al. 2024 ) were supported, with the present  study finding that males were more likely to employ it for data analysis and research  planning."
10078,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,230,"Given the predominantly female orientation of the interview sample, further  research will be necessary to discover if any of the issues raised in the interviews reflect  genuine gender differences in how AI is evaluated."
10079,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,231,"Overall, doctoral students’ use of AI tools such as ChatGPT was associated with  reporting less stress and less disruption to sleep, both of which may be consistent with  the tools promoting better time management."
10080,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,232,"However, time spent online disrupting  social life was also associated with greater AI tool use and, together with A."
10081,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,233,"Ghourdou ( 2024 ), findings that ChatGPT use is associated with delaying  work is suggestive of negative effects on time management."
10082,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,234,Any putative benefits of AI  use on stress reduction therefore requires further replication.
10083,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,235,"Increased self-efficacy,  efficiency and motivation, as well as reduced time spent on assignments are just some  of the means through which this might be achieved."
10084,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,236,"Overall, the significant effects  observed in the regression point to increased AI use being associated with both favour - able and unfavourable factors operating in doctoral students’ lives."
10085,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,237,"This poses challenges  to any practical attempts to modify AI usage through stress reduction, though these may  be clarified by identifying what kinds of AI use, and its appropriateness, are associated  with both stress and time spent online being disruptive."
10086,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,238,Contrary to work which has shown a high positive correlation between ChatGPT  usage and academic performance (B.
10087,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,239,"Khan and Fatima 2024 ), the present study  found no significant relationship with study progress."
10088,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,240,"These contrasting findings  may reflect different patterns of AI use between undergraduate and postgraduate  students, as well as differences in the nature of undergraduate and postgraduate  JOURNAL OF FURTHER AND HIGHER EDUCATION  1007 assessment."
10089,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,241,"Overall use of AI appears to be moderately predictable, although  analysis with larger samples will be necessary to confirm the accuracy of the  current estimates."
10090,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,242,The interviews supplied additional evidence that AI may aid the conduct of  research.
10091,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,243,"Respondents mentioned help with coding, guidance in choosing statis - tical tests, assistance with both academic writing and the assimilation of large  amounts of information."
10092,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,244,All these may enable tasks to be completed more rapidly.
10093,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,245,"However, the interviews also provided evidence of student unease suggesting that  AI tools may potentially impede not only well-being, but also efficiency and under - standing."
10094,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,246,"The first of these concerns was connected to the risk of plagiarism  (Hutson 2024 ), followed by unhappiness about the unreliability of ChatGPT output  (Schei, Møgelvang, and Ludvigsen 2024 )."
10095,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,247,"Added to these were fears about the  effects of repeated use of AI on one’s own creative capacity, an issue which Das  and Madhusudan ( 2024 ) have reported and which Niloy et al."
10096,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,248,( 2023 ) have pro - duced experimental evidence to support.
10097,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,249,"To these were added consideration of the  potential violation of intellectual property rights, now that, as doctoral students,  their own work may be subject to the data sweeps of major tech companies."
10098,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,250,"These  latter two issues position doctoral students as participants in acts of reciprocal  exploitation – first of all in becoming dependent on AI to conduct one’s intellec - tual work and, secondly, having one’s own intellectual work exploited by AI  developers."
10099,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,251,A reminder perhaps that there is no such thing as an academic free  lunch.
10100,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,252,"Finally, the question of the environmental and energy footprint of AI use was raised by  some of the respondents."
10101,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,253,It has been estimated that the power consumption of  a ChatGPT enquiry is approximately 10 times greater than a traditional Google search  (de Vries 2023 ).
10102,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,254,This is clearly an issue which educational institutions must address as AI  use grows.
10103,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,255,"Limitations The relatively small sample size, together with the fact that most of the survey respon - dents were drawn from UK universities, may limit the generalisability of the findings."
10104,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,256,"However, with AI use in universities now a global phenomenon, it is likely that the issues  and motivations underlying it have much in common no matter where it is employed,  although the manner in which it is used is likely to vary with study discipline  (Schei et al. 2024 )."
10105,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,257,"Undoubtedly, further cross-cultural research is required to identify  any significant differences in the patterns of use."
10106,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,258,"As the current survey data is cross-sectional, the findings concerning stress are con - sistent both with use of AI tools acting to reduce academic stress and facilitate changes in  time management, and with the possibility that those who are less stressed to begin with  and who may already possess better time management skills are more likely to use AI  tools."
10107,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,259,"Again, further research of a longitudinal nature will be required to clarify the nature  of causal relationships. 1008  M."
10108,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,260,"AKBAR Conclusions Research In conclusion, this study provides some of the first available evidence on the use of  artificial intelligence by postgraduate students."
10109,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,261,This is consistent with work show - ing they hold positive views towards its use (Chan and Hu 2023 ) but also high - lights areas of concern which point to significant issues relevant to how higher  education institutions prepare current and future scholars for what is rapidly  becoming a very different academic world.
10110,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,262,"The picture emerging from the present  study points to a need for further work to firm up the existing evidence base, to  establish what patterns of use exist across demographic groups, to determine the  psychological and pedagogical consequences for students of this use and to apply  such knowledge to the development and evaluation of appropriate guidelines,  policy and training."
10111,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,263,Higher education policy on artificial intelligence Although Dempere et al.
10112,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,264,"( 2023 ) argue there is a pressing need for the regulation of  artificial intelligence in higher education institutions, no universally agreed guidelines  exist on how to deal with it."
10113,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,265,"( 2024 ) have suggested that policy must  encompass four main aspects – accepting the presence of generative AI, aligning this  with learning objectives, developing curriculum to prevent misuse and adopting a range  of evaluation strategies, alongside discipline-specific policies and guidelines."
10114,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,266,"Though  laudable, these aspirations remain vague with no clarity as to how they will be achieved."
10115,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,267,Reliable and consistent AI detection remains out of reach.
10116,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,268,"The present study suggests that  prospective students would benefit from being informed about the limitations of gen - erative AI, as well as the risks it poses to accuracy, originality, creativity and fostering  dependence."
10117,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,269,"It would also do no harm to outline the threat which training AI models  poses to intellectual property rights, as on current trends doctoral students’ own future  work is likely to be utilised by such models without their consent."
10118,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,270,"Finally, while sustainability is recognised as having strategic importance in higher  education (S."
10119,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,271,"Khan et al. 2025 ), there is as yet no clear evidence that the energy  consumption of large language models utilised by researchers – as well as by under - graduates – is being factored into institutional policies on sustainability, even as higher  education institutions develop guidelines and recommend its integration into existing  curricula (McDonald et al. 2024 )."
10120,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,272,"It is difficult to disagree with Sok and Heng ( 2024 )  acknowledgement that, while there is a shortage of evidence regarding how best to  embed generative AI in higher education, it is perhaps best to proceed on the basis of  practice-and-learn, with appropriate reflection on how best to appraise students’ work  and limit its environmental impact."
10121,36,C036_S1_pdf.txt,273,Disclosure statement No potential conflict of interest was reported by the authors.
